<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-CARDS28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Braves stop McGwire as streak hits 8
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS _ The best pennant race met the great home run chase
as the Braves and Mark McGwire converged Friday night at Busch
Stadium to open a three-game series.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately for the sellout crowd of 46,723, this one had a
lot more of a Braves feel to it. They outlasted the Cardinals 2-1
as Bret Boone drove in Brian Jordan with the winning run in the top
of the ninth inning.
</P>
<P>
   With that stroke, the Braves extended their season-high winning
streak to eight games and are a win shy of matching their best
winning streak of last season. Greg Myers started the rally with a
single to right off Juan Acevedo, Gerald Williams prolonged it with
an infield hit and Boone sealed the deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're at the point now where we just need wins,'' Boone said.
``This team is starting to get excited about things. We're in a
great pennant race. The last two, three weeks, I've been feeling
good at the plate, started swinging the bat the way I should be
swinging.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Acevedo) came right at me with all fastballs. I got a pitch
out away, didn't try to do too much. It's nice when you can be a
big part of a win. ''
</P>
<P>
   The Braves kept McGwire stuck on 51 homers as he went 1-for-4
with a single and three strikeouts.
</P>
<P>
   With Greg Maddux missing his first start in more than two years
because of a chipped bone in his wrist, Terry Mulholland filled in
valiantly. He limited the Cardinals to a run over six innings, but
it was Russ Springer who got the win after working a perfect
eighth.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're 3-1 in my starts and I'll take that,'' Mulholland said.
``Things are snowballing a little bit. Confidence is really up.
It's tough to beat a team when they're feeling that good
mentally.''
</P>
<P>
   Mulholland struck out a season-high seven and the bullpen added
seven as Mike Remlinger, Springer and John Rocker struck out seven
of the nine batters they faced.
</P>
<P>
   ``Greg (Myers) did a great job calling the game,'' Mulholland
said. ``He worked all my stuff, making really good pitch selection
in key situations.''
</P>
<P>
   Mulholland dodged eight singles and stranded seven while holding
a 1-1 tie through four. He retired the heart of the Cardinal order
with two runners on in the first inning and did some nifty work
with the bases loaded in the third, holding the Cardinals to a run
on Fernando Tatis' liner.
</P>
<P>
   Garrett Stephenson, who spent most of the season in Class AAA,
was making his fifth start ever for the Cardinals and sixth against
the Braves, dating to his days with the Phillies.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
