<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-DOLPHINS-MARTIN28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Dolphins' deep threat: They will throw long
 &HT;    By Mark Woods
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAVIE, Fla. _ You can call it the bomb. Or the deep pass. Or the
``go'' pattern.
</P>
<P>
   In NFL meeting rooms, it often is called the ``9-route,'' a
reference to its place on the passing tree. The 0-route is a hitch.
The 1-route is a quick out. And so on, until you get to last stop
on the football map, the 9-route.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my professional opinion, it's the lowest percentage route
in the game,'' Dolphins receivers coach Robert Ford said. ``If you
throw eight of them and get two of them, you're actually beating
the odds.''
</P>
<P>
   The thing is, in recent years the Dolphins rarely tried to beat
those odds. The 9-route became the nein-route.
</P>
<P>
   And for that matter, the 7-route (a post pattern) and 8-route (a
corner pattern) weren't getting much use either.
</P>
<P>
   Last season the Dolphins had only three completions for more
than 50 yards, the lowest amount in the AFC.
</P>
<P>
   And it was for lack of trying.
</P>
<P>
   Jimmy Johnson admitted as much at the start of training camp
when he said, ``One thing we're trying to emphasize is our deep
passing game. We were last in the league last year with the number
of deep passes attempted. We are trying to stress that. We're
charting it and looking at a lot of different things.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, Johnson admitted as much when he spent the off-season
searching for a deep threat and ended up taking a chance on
free-agent receiver Tony Martin, who was released by Atlanta
because of the impending federal money-laundering trial.
</P>
<P>
   Ever since the Dolphins first let go of Martin _ trading him to
San Diego for a fourth-round pick in 1994 _ Martin has been one of
the NFL's top deep threats. In his first season in San Diego, he
became the seventh player in NFL history to catch a 99-yard
touchdown pass.
</P>
<P>
   Last season he averaged 17.9 yards a catch, fourth-best among
NFL players with at least 50 receptions.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, the Dolphins got the news that Martin will be in
uniform this season. He was found innocent of all five charges he
faced.
</P>
<P>
   It remains to be seen whether Martin, who expects to be on the
field for most of tonight's exhibition game against Detroit, will
be the playmaker the Dolphins hope he is. Or whether Yatil Green,
the 1997 first-round pick who has yet to play a regular-season
down, will stay healthy. Or whether Lamar Thomas, who has a torn
labrum in his left shoulder, will be effective.
</P>
<P>
   But this much is certain: Johnson seems intent on making the
deep pass more a part of the offense in '99.
</P>
<P>
   Just ask the Dolphins' defensive backs.
</P>
<P>
   This year's training camp has been filled with more deep passing
drills, which means more running for the receivers and defensive
backs.
</P>
<P>
   ``You see more deep balls this camp,'' cornerback Sam Madison
said. ``And you see more being caught. I'm not saying they're
beating us up and down the field. We're right on them, but they
come down with the big play. ... Now we have guys that can stretch
the defense.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the receivers love the idea of going deep, they haven't
exactly been thrilled with the way it has changed training camp.
They have spent many an hour in the August heat, running up and
down the field.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard on them, especially when we go two-minute offense,''
Ford said. ``They look at me like I'm nuts.''
</P>
<P>
   That especially was clear after one practice in San Diego last
week. Thomas got hurt running a deep route. And the receivers who
were healthy were weary.
</P>
<P>
   As O.J. McDuffie trudged down the sideline after trying to chase
down one deep pass, he muttered: ``It's like a track meet out
here.''
</P>
<P>
   Although four receivers will miss tonight's game _ Thomas,
Oronde Gadsden (back), Nate Jacquet (toe) and McDuffie (thumb) _
Dolphins coaches don't buy the idea that the rash of injuries can
be traced to the practices.
</P>
<P>
   And they also believe that when the season opens Sept. 13 in
Denver, they will be ready to test Dan Marino's arm.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not just because of Tony,'' Johnson said. ``Oronde Gadsden is
as good as we have with the deep pass. Obviously, Yatil is one of
the better players we have with the deep pass. Larry Shannon maybe
gets open better than anybody, including Tony. ... In the San Diego
game we had an opportunity for four or five big plays if we just
make the catch. I think we're on schedule to make some of those
plays.''
</P>
<P>
   That schedule got a boost Friday when Martin showed up for his
first post-verdict practice.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has been an unusual training camp for the receivers with
the injuries and having all this uncertainty,'' Ford said. ``And
it's all behind us now. The only way can go now is up.''
</P>
<P>
   Up and, they hope, deep.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
