<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-MORTON-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MORTON'S HEALTH IS KEY FOR USC
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ If one player is considered invaluable to the USC
football team, it has to be quarterback Carson Palmer.
</P>
<P>
   But even if the unthinkable happened and the sophomore (begin
ital)wunderkind(end ital) got injured, USC would not be completely
devastated. Backup quarterback Mike Van Raaphorst has started 10
games while senior John Fox has nine career starts.
</P>
<P>
   Tailback is another situation. If senior Chad Morton gets
injured, the Trojans are in trouble. They only have an
inexperienced cast of replacements behind him.
</P>
<P>
   Below Morton on the depth chart are redshirt freshman Sultan
McCullough (0 career carries), sophomore Frank Strong (37 carries,
three fumbles) and senior Jabari Jackson (13 carries). There is
also sophomore Malaefou MacKenzie, who is still recovering from
knee surgery.
</P>
<P>
   Palmer is clearly USC's most valuable player, but the most
irreplaceable Trojan is Morton.
</P>
<P>
   It's not a comforting predicament, considering Morton has missed
games each of the past three seasons because of injuries.
Basically, Morton can't afford to get injured this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's critical for us,'' Palmer said. ``Chad is our No. 1 guy.
He's our leader. Hopefully, he's not going to get dinged up.''
</P>
<P>
   The emphasis here is on ``hopefully.'' Morton missed two games
last season with a bruised back, saw limited playing time in
several other games and fell 15 yards short of reaching the magical
1,000-yard figure.
</P>
<P>
   Sensitive to criticism about his ability to remain injury-free,
Morton is trying harder than ever to stay on the field this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even in practice, if I get a nick it's hard to come out,''
Morton said. ``People will say, `OK, he's hurt again.' If I'm hurt,
I'm going to have to play with it. I don't even like coming out of
practice anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Morton missed most of USC's first scrimmage with a tender
hamstring but returned Tuesday and gained 25 yards in six carries.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could have gone more,'' Morton said after the scrimmage. ``I
feel great right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Surprisingly, that view was not shared by USC coach Paul
Hackett.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Chad Morton is behind where he was a year ago,''
Hackett said. ``He's tired. He's not running with the same zip.''
</P>
<P>
   These comments might be part psychological ploy, just to make
sure Morton plays through any minor aches and pains and realizes he
is indispensable.
</P>
<P>
   Because in the next breath, Hackett defended his star tailback
for being fatigued during training camp.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are exhausted this time of year. I think he extended
himself more this year in the role that he's in,'' Hackett said.
``This year, he is the man. He's got to get himself rested. He
will.''
</P>
<P>
   There's no other choice and Morton knows it. This is his senior
season, and it still angers him that he finished with 985 yards
rushing last year.
</P>
<P>
   Morton entered the Sun Bowl needing just 33 yards to gain 1,000.
He ended up with 18 yards in 11 carries against Texas Christian
University.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was very disappointing. It hurt really bad,'' Morton said.
``A lot of people came up to me and said, `You're going to get it
this game.' Does it make me less of a back because I didn't get 15
yards?''
</P>
<P>
   Although Morton desperately wants to be USC's first back to gain
1,000 yards since 1995, he has tried to alter his goals this
season. If he can just stay healthy, he figures there is no way he
will be denied.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I go 13 games healthy, I'm going to break 1,000 yards,''
Morton said. ``That's my only goal this year, to play in every
game.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, almost his only goal.
</P>
<P>
   ``This year, I just want to go to a good bowl game,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   This summer, in addition to his regular workouts at USC, he
spent his mornings working out with his brother, Detroit Lions wide
receiver Johnnie Morton.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to running, he learned pass routes from his brother,
because he will occasionally line up at wide receiver for the
Trojans.
</P>
<P>
   USC would like to get Morton into the open field without taking
so many hits. It's one way for him to avoid, you guessed it,
injuries.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I'm going to be a little more conscious of the
durability issue because I have grown to admire his ability in
space,'' Hackett said. ``I think he will be able to do more things
than just get in the I-formation and run the ball.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
