<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-GALAXY-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GALAXY'S PENA A FAVORITE TARGET
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRED J. ROBLEDO  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA -- Danny Pena might not be the most famous player in
Major League Soccer, but you'll know when he's on the field.
</P>
<P>
   He's one of the league's favorite targets, accumulating more
penalty points (36) than anyone while sharing the league lead in
cautions (8) with New England's Ivan McKinley. He's missed two
games this season because of yellow-card accumulation and has been
kicked out twice in his three-year tenure.
</P>
<P>
   When he joined the Galaxy in 1996, his rough tackles quickly
earned him the reputation as one of the dirtiest players in the
league, yet Pena has never seriously injured anyone.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll never understand that (reputation),'' said Pena,
preparing for the Galaxy's Western Conference match at Dallas this
evening. ``I've never been in a situation where I've severely hurt
someone, thrown an elbow at somebody or head-butted somebody. But
if you go by the league and disciplinary committee, they will say
I'm a player to watch out for. It's just crazy.''
</P>
<P>
   His demeanor may be the most misleading.
</P>
<P>
   During practice he's painfully vocal, screaming obscenities at
fellow players for making mistakes while cursing himself if he does
the same.
</P>
<P>
   During matches he's as intense as they come, causing attacking
midfielders to wince when Pena comes full-speed their way.
</P>
<P>
   But he's also one of Los Angeles' most important pieces, a
prized defensive midfield specialist who rarely loses 50-50 balls
and closes space as well as anyone.
</P>
<P>
   All in all, he's just a rare package of determination and skill.
</P>
<P>
   ``That quality comes from being a great competitor,'' said
Galaxy coach Sigi Schmid. ``His number one goal is to compete and
win games and he really doesn't care if he offends anyone. He's an
older player who has been through wars and you can count on him in
the big games.
</P>
<P>
   ``And as far as players, they all have Danny's respect. When you
have his kind of dedication and tenacity, you earn that respect.''
</P>
<P>
   Galaxy goalkeeper Kevin Hartman explained how tough it is for
newcomers adjusting to Pena's personality.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're a new player to the Galaxy and you take Danny Pena
seriously, he can scare you,'' said Hartman. ``But he just has a
unique sense about him. Whenever you see him get really mad, you
kind of take it with a grain of salt because he takes the game
very, very seriously. If he makes a mistake, he's the first to
raise his hand and say, `I messed up.' And he expects you to do the
same.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite his aggressive play and sometimes volatile nature, Pena
is loved and respected by his teammates and those who know him
personally.
</P>
<P>
   At 31, he's not a rah-rah guy who seeks personal gratification.
In 1997 he turned down an invitation from then-coach Steve Sampson
to join the U.S. National Team in preparation for the 1998 World
Cup in France.
</P>
<P>
   The Galaxy was in a playoff drive at the time and Pena didn't
want to leave the Galaxy for a substitute role on the U.S. team.
More importantly, Pena wasn't going to show up at the last minute
after the national team had overlooked him his entire career.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a big week with the Galaxy but people need to
understand I've been playing in America for 12 years as a
professional. I just didn't fall out of a tree,'' Pena said of his
1997 decision. ``I was invited at the last second. If I had been
invited to camp from day one (to prepare for that game) like the
other players, it may have been a different story.''
</P>
<P>
   Pena claims he was invited as a substitute, but after he turned
down Sampson's invitation, he was upset to learn later that Sampson
said he would have been a starter in the friendly against Ecuador.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was completely uncalled for, for him (Sampson) to say,''
said Pena. ``He never spoke to me. He never took two minutes of his
time to call and explain why he wanted to bring me in. He had his
secretary call me. I told her, `Listen, I want you to thank him,
I'm grateful for the opportunity but now is not the best time for
me to come.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Pena admits that part of the reason he may not have been invited
to the national team sooner is because of his vocal demeanor.
</P>
<P>
   It's a reputation that carried over to the MLS when he joined
the league in 1997. And in Pena's mind, MLS has singled him out
because of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been completely and unfairly treated by this league,''
says Pena, who earned most of his yellow cards this season for
dissent. ``When I came into this league I had a reputation during
my days in other outdoor professional leagues I played in as well
as my days in indoor soccer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of my problems have been with referees and being very
vocal; that's where I get my reputation. But I've never been a
player looked at as a dirty player or a player who hurts players.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
