u a BC-HURRICANE-DENNIS-1STL     08-28 0768
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HURRICANE-DENNIS-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOUTHEAST COAST PREPARES FOR HURRICANE DENNIS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (SUBS to update location of storm in 3rd graf.) 
(ATTN: S.C., N.C., Ga., Fla. )  (ART ADV: A photo is being sent. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By EMILY YELLIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHARLESTON, S.C. _ Carrying a potential to strengthen
significantly, Hurricane Dennis moved toward the Southeast coast
Friday as residents from Florida to North Carolina prepared and
simply waited.
</P>
<P>
   The National Weather Service issued a hurricane watch for the
east coast of Florida, from Sebastian Inlet northward to Fernandina
Beach, and warned residents from central Florida through North
Carolina to ``closely monitor the progress'' of the hurricane.
</P>
<P>
   Late Friday night, the hurricane was 290 miles southeast of Cape
Canaveral, Fla., and 40 miles east-northeast of Harbour Island in
the Bahamas, The Associated Press reported. With winds of 80 mph,
the storm was moving west-northwest at 7 mph, the news agency said.
</P>
<P>
   Predictions Friday afternoon said the storm might travel along
the Florida coast and either turn inland or gather force and hit
land anywhere from Georgia to North Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   Jerry Jarrell, director of the National Hurricane Center in
Miami, said, ``We think it does have the potential to intensify and
perhaps even become a major hurricane before landfall.''
</P>
<P>
   For that to happen, the storm would have to stay over the water
and not touch the Florida coast as it heads north, Jarrell said,
adding, ``My best guess is that it probably won't come ashore until
it gets up around either Georgia or South Carolina, and South
Carolina is the most likely.''
</P>
<P>
   That is not good news in this city, which was hit hard in
September 1989 by Hurricane Hugo, a Category 4 hurricane that
killed 504 people in the Caribbean and the Carolinas.
</P>
<P>
   Anthony Stich, chief of the Fire and Rescue Department on
Sullivan's Island, a barrier island near Charleston, said: ``During
Hugo, we were wiped out. Much of the island had to be rebuilt. We
learned a lot from that, and I think a lot of people here don't
want to go through anything like that again.''
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Jim Hodges of South Carolina ordered 1,000 National Guard
troops and 500 state troopers to prepare for storm duty Friday. In
Georgia and North Carolina, emergency planners were also on alert.
</P>
<P>
   Officials in Georgia and the Carolinas said decisions about
possible evacuations would not be made until Saturday morning.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now it's pretty much a waiting game,'' said Pamela
Swanson, a spokeswoman for the Georgia Emergency Management Agency.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Hegele of the North Carolina Division of Emergency
Management said; ``When and if the storm decides to come in, we'll
be ready for it. We're concerned about the whole coast. The storm
can swing 100 miles either way on impact.''
</P>
<P>
   Farther south, in Daytona Beach, Fla., workers cleared the beach
of life guard towers and trash cans as surfers in brightly colored
shorts rode eight-foot waves. ``It's absolutely surfer heaven,''
said Joe Wooden, the beach chief for Volusia County.
</P>
<P>
   But here along the South Carolina coast, which has been
evacuated three times in the last few years since Hurricane Hugo _
for Hurricanes Fran and Bertha in 1996 and Hurricane Bonnie last
year _ the mood was more serious.
</P>
<P>
   At Bert's Bar on Sullivan's Island here, Brooke Hawkins, a
29-year-old bartender, served patrons this afternoon as the weather
channel played in the background. Talk of neighbors who had already
begun boarding up their homes mixed with discussions of what
everyone planned to do.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Hawkins remembered Hurricane Hugo well, and took the threats
seriously.
</P>
<P>
   She said she planned to leave on Saturday if it looked as if the
hurricane was coming this way. ``I live one block from the beach,
and the biggest danger for me is flooding,'' she said. ``I'm trying
to figure out where to put my furniture _ up on cinder blocks, or
my upstairs neighbor said I could put it up there.''
</P>
<P>
   Mary Tate, 42, a real estate agent on Sullivan's Island, moved
here after Hurricane Hugo and said she did not plan to board up her
house, but did plan to leave on Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've boarded up the windows and moved all the furniture up
against the wall a few times before, and nothing, nothing,
nothing,'' Ms. Tate said. ``So I'm not going to do it this time. I
don't have the energy, and I have insurance. I can't do anything
about the hurricane coming, so I'm not going to worry about it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
