<HEADLINE>
RANGERS, HELLING MASTER BLUE JAYS
</HEADLINE>
 JAYSG-TEX (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHNNY PAUL 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TORONTO _ Right-hander Rick Helling put himself on target to
start Game 1 of the 1999 Division Series provided the Rangers
secure their near-certain playoff berth.
</P>
<P>
   Helling's complete-game effort in the Rangers' 8-2 victory last
night against the Toronto Blue Jays only strengthened his position.
</P>
<P>
   ``He threw like a No. 1 starter,'' manager Johnny Oates said.
``He threw breaking pitches from behind. He was in total command,
and he showed it. Body language says a lot, and I didn't need an
interpreter to know what I was seeing out there. I'm excited.''
</P>
<P>
   Oates identified his potential postseason rotation indirectly
yesterday afternoon by proclaiming that Helling and right-handers
Aaron Sele and Esteban Loaiza _ the unit's most effective members _
will pitch every fifth day.
</P>
<P>
   Helling, Sele and Loaiza have combined for 18 victories through
19 decisions since the All-Star break, and the Rangers improved to
22-3 in games started by those three during that period.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, it's a confidence booster to have the manager want
you to pitch every five days,'' said Helling, who surrendered only
six hits and two walks during his 131-pitch appearance. ``It makes
you feel confident to know that he wants you out on the mound. I'll
pitch whenever he wants me to pitch. I'll pitch on three days rest.
I'll pitch on six days rest. It doesn't matter to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Among Oates' plans could be that Helling _ the rotation's most
effective and consistent performer _ starts Game 1 of the Division
Series. Helling won for the 11th time through 18 decisions and
improved his rotation-best earned-run average to 4.19.
</P>
<P>
   Helling pitched four innings of no-hit ball, and the Rangers did
not squander that effort, scoring five runs early. Designated
hitter Lee Stevens gave SkyDome's visitors a 2-0 lead with his
two-run, second-inning home run off right-hander Chris Carpenter
(9-8), and the Rangers' advantage grew during their next at-bat.
</P>
<P>
   Right fielder Juan Gonzalez delivered a bases-loaded single that
scored second baseman Mark McLemore, and designated hitter Rafael
Palmeiro and third baseman Todd Zeile produced consecutive
sacrifice flies that scored catcher Ivan Rodriguez and left fielder
Rusty Greer.
</P>
<P>
   Palmeiro also led off the sixth inning with his 40th home run.
</P>
<P>
   Helling's only encounter with trouble occurred during the Blue
Jays' fifth inning. First baseman Carlos Delgado hit his 38th home
run to lead off the inning before third baseman Tony Fernandez and
catcher Darrin Fletcher reached with consecutive doubles.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're going to face three or four situations in every game
where the game could be decided,'' Helling said. ``That was
definitely one of them. That was the first time they had a chance
to break out.''
</P>
<P>
   Helling, though, responded with consecutive strikeouts of
shortstop Tony Batista and designated hitter Willie Greene before
inducing an inning-ending ground ball from second baseman Homer
Bush.
</P>
<P>
   ``I made a bad pitch to Carlos and didn't get it in on him
enough, but I thought I threw a lot of good pitches that inning,''
Helling said. ``You can't let two, three or four hits in a row
bother you. Big-league hitters are going to get three or four hits
in a row sometimes. I realized I was making good pitches, and I
knew I would be fine if I kept making good pitches.''
</P>
<P>
   Helling did, and the display included eight strikeouts. Many of
those were the product of a nasty slider.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my mind,'' Oates said, ``that might be as well as he's
pitched all year.''
</P>
<P>
   The target remains within Helling's sights. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
