<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-TEXAS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LONGHORNS OPEN WITH A NEW RICKY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIMMY BURCH 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN _ During the summer, members of the Texas football team
were surveyed on a variety of subjects. Some were silly
(worst-dressed teammate), some serious (best leader).
</P>
<P>
   With all precincts reporting, Longhorns fans might be surprised
to learn which player received the most votes from peers as ``The
First Guy I Would Pick For My Team.''
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't quarterback Major Applewhite, Texas' top returning
offensive weapon. Nor was it defensive end Aaron Humphrey, the
emotional leader of an experienced defense.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, it was a guy whose college career has been marked by
more head butts than headlines. A bullish blocker who touched the
ball just 18 times last season: fullback Ricky Brown.
</P>
<P>
   Those who find the election returns surprising, said Applewhite,
fail to appreciate what the Arlington High School graduate does for
the 17th-ranked Longhorns, who open the season tonight at 7:30 at
Royal-Memorial Stadium against North Carolina State.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no way to really describe how much he means to us,''
said Applewhite, who ticked off a laundry list of attributes, most
of them related to dependability and dedication. ``I think he's the
most underrated player in the Big 12.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown soon might lose that title. After two years as an
afterthought in weekly game plans, he'll have a much higher profile
in the Texas offense this season. That could lead to recognition
from someone other than Texas offensive coordinator Greg Davis, who
calls Brown ``the fullback of the future'' because he is equally
adept at running, blocking and receiving.
</P>
<P>
   Consider: Brown carried the ball 10 times in 11 games last
season while serving as the lead blocker for Heisman Trophy winner
Ricky Williams. Brown might top that total tonight.
</P>
<P>
   ``He could get 11 carries against North Carolina State,'' Davis
said. ``He could get three. It just depends on how the game
unfolds. The good thing about Ricky is, he really doesn't care.
It's very unusual for a skill-position player to be that unselfish.
He's taken to his role as well as anybody I've ever seen.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet Brown admits, somewhat grudgingly, that he's happy his role
is about to change. Although quick to acknowledge tailbacks Hodges
Mitchell and Victor Ike as the primary ball carriers in the Texas
arsenal, Brown likes the idea of touching the ball 10 times a game
_ maybe more _ as a rusher and receiver in the Longhorns'
post-Williams attack.
</P>
<P>
   ``Heading into this game, the excitement is there a little
more,'' said Brown, a fifth-year senior who has logged 49 carries
in 34 games during his college career. ``I've waited a long time
for this opportunity. I'm ready to go out and surprise some
people.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown (6-foot, 225 pounds) might catch opponents off-guard with
his quick bursts through holes and his soft hands. But he will not
surprise teammates who watched him average 5.5 yards during his
infrequent excursions last season (10 carries, 55 yards, 1
touchdown). Among the top seven returning rushers in the Big 12,
only Nebraska tailback Correll Buckhalter averaged more yards per
carry last season (5.6) than Brown.
</P>
<P>
   Texas coach Mack Brown said the fullback's versatility makes him
indispensable. In addition to his primary role as the battering ram
for Texas' tailbacks, the Arlington native is expected to line up
in one-back sets and as a slot receiver. Brown grabbed a
career-high eight passes last season and figures he could top 30
this year. The idea, said Texas coaches, is to keep opponents
guessing about Brown's impending role on each snap.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see myself getting a lot of catches. I'll probably get an
equal number of catches as runs,'' said Brown, who rushed for 1,939
yards and 31 touchdowns in leading Arlington to the Class 5A
semifinals in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ricky is the consummate professional. The thing he does is
exactly what he's supposed to do, and he does it on every play,''
Mack Brown said. ``You never hear from him, but he leads by
example. He's known as a great blocker, but every time you give it
to him, he makes yards. He'll be much more involved in the game
plans this season.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to being named the Texas player peers would prefer
to build a team around, Brown also won in three other categories:
class act, team leader and _ in a landslide _ the ever-popular
``Doesn't Get the Recognition He Deserves.''
</P>
<P>
   Starting tonight against North Carolina State, that could
change. Brown said he's ready to make the necessary adjustment from
a one-carry-per-game back to a vital cog in a revamped offense.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year, when I heard a play called for me, my eyes would
get big and I'd think, `I'm getting the ball. Now, try and do your
best,''' Brown said. ``I was always surprised when I heard my name
called. I don't think there will be so many surprises this year.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the ones caught off-guard will be opponents who
underestimate the versatility of a fullback teammates consider a
cornerstone of Texas' revamped offense. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-28-99 0026EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990828.0012 </DOCNO>
