r a BC-GROWING-AZR &LR;      08-28 0513
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GROWING-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GROWING SMARTER COMMITTEE LOOKS TO COMPROMISE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DENNIS WAGNER  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   A state panel assigned to solve rampant growth problems in
Arizona decided Friday . . .
</P>
<P>
   Well, it didn't decide anything. Instead, the Growing Smarter
Commission argued about land-use planning for two days, then
decided to try for a compromise next week.
</P>
<P>
   Commissioners have spent most of the past year conducting
statewide meetings, gathering data and writing proposals to
preserve open space, reform local zoning and encourage citizen
involvement with community planning.
</P>
<P>
   That campaign is scheduled to end Tuesday. In the meantime,
however, members don't even agree on whether they're accomplishing
anything.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Betts, a Phoenix land-use attorney, said the 15-member
committee is on the brink of proposing dramatic changes in the way
development occurs in Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's truly significant stuff that is going to make a big
difference in the way we grow,'' Betts added.
</P>
<P>
   But Rep. Jake Flake, R-Snowflake, said there are so many
irreconcilable differences among the members that very little has
been achieved.
</P>
<P>
   The commission is debating a laundry list of recommendations
that would discourage leap-frog development, reform local planning
methods, preserve open spaces and encourage citizen participation.
Many of the measures under consideration would require amendments
to the Arizona Constitution and federal law, or approval by voters.
One example: a plan to set aside up to 10 percent of the state's
9.4 million acres of trust land for conservation purposes.
</P>
<P>
   By law, proceeds from trust land are used to help finance public
education. During Friday's session, commissioners could not agree
on how much property should be preserved, whether schools should be
compensated for the loss of revenues or who should decide which
properties should be set aside.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Gail Griffin, R-Sierra Vista, said she could not support
any plan that involves ``stealing'' money from schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're taking education dollars away for preservation; I'm
opposed to it,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   After hours of discussion, commission chairman Jack Pfister
ended the meeting and asked members to draw up a compromise.
</P>
<P>
   Growing Smarter commissioners are gathering recommendations from
subcommittees. The work is supposed to produce a package that can
compete with the Citizens Growth Management Initiative, an
environmentalist measure that will appear on statewide ballots this
fall.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, Sierra Club lobbyist Sandy Bahr condemned the Growing
Smarter options even before any had been formally adopted.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no substance as far as growth management goes,'' she
said. ``If anything, they (commissioners) could be making things
worse.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Her schtick is to downplay anything we do as insignificant,''
Betts said. ``If this process succeeds, her initiative doesn't have
any momentum.'' &QL; 
Dennis Wagner can be reached at (602) 444-8874 or at
dennis.wagner(at)pni.com. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
