<SLUG> BC-BBA-REEVES-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GRABBING FASSERO A NO-BRAINER FOR RANGERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM REEVES 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TORONTO _ Jeff Fassero may be the worst pitcher in the American
League this season, bar none.
</P>
<P>
   Yep, that takes in a lot of territory, but then, so have the
Yellowstone Park-sized home runs the one-time Mariners' ace has
surrendered this year, 31 of them to right-handed hitters alone.
</P>
<P>
   That's just a fraction, however, of the 188 hits in 139 innings
he's given up. Or the 123 runs, tops in the league, he's allowed.
Then there are those 14 losses, tying him for the most in that
category, too.
</P>
<P>
   This is downright grisly.
</P>
<P>
   Right-handed hitters are tanning the 36-year-old left-hander's
hide at a .341 clip with a slugging percentage of .631.
</P>
<P>
   There have been reports that even his dog growls at him when he
comes home after the game.
</P>
<P>
   So let me be the first to say that Rangers' general manager Doug
Melvin has pulled off yet another brilliant move.
</P>
<P>
   Seriously.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers' general manager has done it again. This is your
basic risk-free, money-back guaranteed deal. Try him out for 30
days and if you don't like what you see, send him on his merry way.
</P>
<P>
   Well, not exactly money back, but you get the idea.
</P>
<P>
   This is a no-brainer. This is the Rangers trying to catch
lightning in the Gatorade jug. This is Melvin plunking down a mere
million of Tom Hicks' bucks on the ``pass'' line and looking for 7
or 11.
</P>
<P>
   Just one time, baby, seven from heaven.
</P>
<P>
   Hey, what's a million bucks between friends.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a little bit of a roll of the dice,'' Melvin admitted
after trading a borderline minor-league prospect to Seattle for the
beleaguered Fassero. ``I can't say his numbers are good. He won't
say that either.''
</P>
<P>
   That's a relief. At least we know he's not delusional as well as
horrid.
</P>
<P>
   Melvin had a choice this week. He could have put in a waiver
claim for Baltimore right-hander Scott Erickson, who will have
about $26 million and four years left on his contract after this
season.
</P>
<P>
   Or he could opt for Fassero and the just-under $1 million left
on his contract this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a hunch the Orioles weren't really serious about trading
Erickson,'' Melvin said. ``You would have had to overwhelm them. It
would have been expensive, picking up his contract, plus giving up
a ton of players. You're not going to get him for some kid at
Savannah.''
</P>
<P>
   The Indians found that out. When the Rangers passed on Erickson,
Cleveland, desperate for a starter, claimed him on waivers and
tried to work out a deal with the Orioles. Those negotiations fell
through yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, Erickson has been pitching superbly (8-2) since the
All-Star break.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a horse,'' said Rangers first baseman Rafael Palmeiro, a
teammate of Erickson's at Baltimore the last five years. ``Forget
his \Rfirst half\S record. He can give you seven, eight, nine
innings and keep you in the game. He'd fit in nicely here.''
</P>
<P>
   But it's Fassero and his season-to-forget who's coming.
</P>
<P>
   ``If can get the old Fassero he could be a great pickup for
us,'' Palmeiro conceded. ``A couple of years ago he was dealing.
Maybe a change of scenery, put him in a pennant race, surround him
with good players ... He was once a great pitcher. We just have to
get him back to where he was.''
</P>
<P>
   Scouting reports say the velocity on Fassero's fastball is still
88-90 miles per hour. There are no reports of injury, though he had
arthroscopic surgery to clean out some bone chips out of his elbow
in the off-season. It's his command that has seemingly deserted
him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year he had a pretty good year \R13-12, 3.87 earned-run
average\S,'' Melvin pointed out. ``People keep asking, `How could
he go so bad in so short a time?'
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a lot of confidence in putting him out in the bullpen
to work with John Wetteland and Larry Hardy. Maybe we can get him
turned around.''
</P>
<P>
   Hicks, Melvin said, never flinched when he was called to OK the
deal. And if it had been Erickson and his $26 million?
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't even bring it up,'' Melvin said, ``but he probably
would have said, `Whatever you think. If you think he can make the
difference, do it.'''
</P>
<P>
   My kind of owner.
</P>
<P>
   September will be an audition for Fassero, who is said to be
delighted with the trade. The Rangers can use a left-handed starter
or long reliever to help neutralize the strong left-handed hitting
lineups featured by Oakland, New York and Cleveland.
</P>
<P>
   It could be one of the youngsters _ Matt Perisho, Corey Lee or
Doug Davis _ due up from Oklahoma.
</P>
<P>
   Or it could be Fassero.
</P>
<P>
   He's a lightweight, million-dollar gamble having a butt-ugly
season.
</P>
<P>
   What a great deal.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
