<HEADLINE>
WARREN UPBEAT ON INJURY STATUS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CLARENCE E. HILL JR. 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING _ Cowboys running back Chris Warren says he feels better
than at any point in the 1998 season, when he missed seven games
and was hobbled in several others by a severe groin strain.
</P>
<P>
   However, he also admitted that the groin strain is still not
fully healed and will likely linger all season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel better, and I don't have any limitations,'' said
Warren, who will play against the Denver Broncos tomorrow (7 p.m.
at Texas Stadium) after missing the Cowboys' preseason game last
Saturday against the New England Patriots.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm used to playing pain-free without having to worry about
injuries. I just have to realize it's going to be there, and it's
something I'm going to have to play with.''
</P>
<P>
   Warren, who took a leave from training camp last week to get
therapy from a specialist in Colorado, said he has had no problems
in practice the past few days. He said he is looking forward to
tomorrow's game.
</P>
<P>
   Cowboys owner Jerry Jones said he's all for Warren doing
whatever it took to care for his injury.
</P>
<P>
   Jones said he has no problem if Warren flies to Colorado every
Monday following a Sunday game and gets treatment on Tuesday, the
players' day off, and returns to Dallas for practice Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Warren is slated to be the Cowboys' third-down running back and
the primary backup to starter Emmitt Smith. TWO-WAY THOMAS
</P>
<P>
   Just call Cowboys second-year man Robert Thomas a fullbacker.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of simply moving from linebacker to fullback, as Cowboys
coach Chan Gailey announced a few days ago, Thomas has moved back
and forth between the positions in practice this week, learning
fullback and playing linebacker in the Cowboys' first-team short
yardage defense. He will do both in tomorrow's preseason matchup
with the Broncos.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas has no problems with the dual role.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fullback is almost like linebacker,'' Thomas said. ``You read
and react, and they want you to be real physical. The difference is
I'm not tackling, I'm blocking.''
</P>
<P>
   Thomas said fullback is actually not that new of a position for
him; he played in high school and as a freshman in college at
Henderson State before concentrating on linebacker.
</P>
<P>
   He said his experience on defense will also help him at
fullback.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like I have an advantage almost because I know exactly
what a defensive player is thinking,'' Thomas said. ``It enables me
to get my block and get better leverage because whatever they are
thinking about doing I've been there and done that.'' QUINN TO GET
ANOTHER LOOK
</P>
<P>
   Third-string quarterback Mike Quinn will get the nod ahead of
backup Jason Garrett to start the second half tomorrow night.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys want to evaluate Quinn with better people around
him, so he will play when the second-team offense takes the field
in the third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Quinn's game should go better than his previous game, when he
didn't complete a pass and was sacked three times against the
Oakland Raiders. This time, the backup offensive line should be
better, thanks to the return of Tony Hutson and Everett McIver.
</P>
<P>
   Hutson, who will play left tackle behind starter Flozell Adams,
is expected to bolster the second unit. McIver's return to the
starting lineup at right guard enables rookie second-round pick
Solomon Page to move to the second group as well. UN-LUCKY BREAK
</P>
<P>
   The rash of preseason injuries continued for the Cowboys
yesterday when rookie tight end Mike Lucky, a seventh-round draft
pick, suffered a sprained left foot in practice.
</P>
<P>
   The results of X-rays taken last night won't be known until
today.
</P>
<P>
   Lucky's situation puts the Cowboys in a bind at tight end,
considering that Hayward Clay was sidelined by a sprained knee a
couple of weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   Clay will have exploratory surgery Wednesday to determine the
seriousness of his injury, which is feared to be season-ending.
</P>
<P>
   Lucky was being looked upon to fill the backup tight-end spot,
behind starter David LaFleur, after Clay's injury.
</P>
<P>
   All that might have changed yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   What's certain is that his injury will result in more playing
time for rookie free agent Brian Waters of North Texas against
Denver tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys have already lost three players to season-ending
injuries _ receiver James McKnight, linebacker Brandon Tolbert and
guard/center Mike Kiselak. COWBOYS SCHEME FOR BRONCOS
</P>
<P>
   Chan Gailey acknowledged that the Cowboys have done some
offensive scheming in preparation for the Broncos.
</P>
<P>
   Gailey, who usually shuns the idea of doing a lot of game
planning for preseason games, said the Broncos' unusual defensive
style made it a necessity.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are so unusual defensively,'' Gailey said. ``We've spent
a lot more time on them than anyone else.''
</P>
<P>
   Gailey said he has also spent a little time mentally preparing
for the first two games of the regular season, Sept. 12 against the
Washington Redskins and Sept. 20 against the Atlanta Falcons. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
