<SLUG> BC-RAILS-MURDER-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RAILS SENTENCED TO LIFE IN PRISON IN PENNSYLVANIA WOMAN'S DEATH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TONY RIZZO  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Moments before he was sentenced to life in prison for strangling
a Pennsylvania woman, Carl Dean Rails assured the woman's parents
that their daughter did ``absolutely nothing wrong'' on the night
she died.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish I could tell you what really happened,'' Rails said
after turning and facing Vic and Claire Monti at his sentencing
Friday in Johnson County District Court.
</P>
<P>
   Rails made a standing offer to provide the Montis with what he
claimed to be the truth of what happened in the Lenexa hotel room
where Claire-Marie Monti was killed April 26, 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Rails avoided trial and a possible death sentence by pleading
guilty on Aug. 12 to capital murder, rape and aggravated sodomy.
</P>
<P>
   He would have to live to be well over 100 before being
considered for parole under the terms of the plea agreement and
sentence imposed by District Judge Peter Ruddick.
</P>
<P>
   While saying Rails deserved the death penalty, Vic Monti said he
and his wife supported the plea agreement as a ``reasonable
alternative'' that ensured Rails would spend the rest of his life
in prison.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Rails will never be a free man,'' he said. ``It's
important to take vicious criminals off the street.''
</P>
<P>
   Claire Monti told Rails, 36, that forfeiting his freedom for the
rest of his life was a small price to pay for taking her daughter's
life.
</P>
<P>
   ``He gave the death sentence to Claire-Marie,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   A co-defendant, Rodney Wayne Henry, previously went to trial and
was convicted of first-degree murder, rape and aggravated sodomy.
He also was sentenced to life in prison and is appealing his
conviction.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the information about Claire-Marie Monti's last hours
that has been made public came from the confession Henry gave to
police in which he claimed Rails savagely beat and strangled Monti
and defiled her body after she died.
</P>
<P>
   Henry admitted helping Rails restrain her as she struggled for
her life but said he did so out of fear that Rails would also harm
him.
</P>
<P>
   Rails told the Montis on Friday that many of the details they
heard in court about their daughter's death were not true.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not saying it was not a bad thing or not a horrible
thing,'' Rails said.
</P>
<P>
   Claire-Marie Monti, 32, was in the Kansas City, Mo., area to
give computer software training to employees of a Lenexa company
that spring.
</P>
<P>
   She met Rails and Henry, who were co-workers for a Kansas City
remodeling company, in the Westport area the night before she was
found dead, according to testimony.
</P>
<P>
   Vic Monti said after the sentencing that he could never forgive
Rails but said that at least Rails took responsibility for what he
did.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's more than we can say for Rodney Henry,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Monti said he doubted he would ever take Rails up on his offer
to talk about the crime.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't look at either one of them as a reliable source,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Rails is the third person in Johnson County to be charged with
capital murder since Kansas reinstated the death penalty in 1994.
All three have avoided a death sentence by pleading guilty or no
contest and have been sentenced to life in prison.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson County District Attorney Paul Morrison said the case was
an example of the power of the death penalty.
</P>
<P>
   ``It brought the defendant to his knees,'' Morrison said. ``Carl
Rails is going to waste away and die an old man in some
maximum-security prison.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
