<DOCNO> NYT19990828.0017 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-28 00:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2550 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e BC-TV-GOODY-AZR &LR;      08-28 0937
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-GOODY-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SLICK REPLAY THOMAS-HILL SAGA LACKS CONVICTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL GOODYKOONTZ  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   In October 1991, the real-life saga of race, sex and politics
playing out before their eyes on national television gripped
millions of Americans.
</P>
<P>
   ``Strange Justice'' likely won't be so lucky.
</P>
<P>
   The movie, which dramatizes the Clarence Thomas-Anita Hill saga,
includes some great performances, stylish direction, and one of
those stories so bizarre it could happen only in real life, because
no one would think to invent it.
</P>
<P>
   What it lacks is conviction.
</P>
<P>
   Delroy Lindo is outstanding as Thomas. Regina Taylor makes a
convincing, if understated, Anita Hill. Mandy Patinkin gives, for
him, an understated performance as spin doctor Kenneth Duberstein _
not only does he refrain from breaking into a show tune, he never
even looks like he wants to. Emmy nominations all around, no doubt.
</P>
<P>
   Yet aside from a truly bizarre _ and inspired _ take on Thomas'
and Hill's testimony before a Senate committee, ``Strange
Justice,'' based on the book of the same name, doesn't give us much
more than what we already knew. The movie never takes a stand as to
who might have been telling the truth, who was lying. It's
admirably evenhanded in that regard, I suppose, but the drama
suffers because of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were never trying to make a straightforward docudrama about
these events,'' Jacob Epstein, the movie's writer, said from his
home last week. ``We were trying to go for what was the meaning of
all this.''
</P>
<P>
   When Thurgood Marshall retired, then-President Bush nominated
Thomas to the Supreme Court. A conservative Black and a Republican,
Thomas opposed quota systems and the like. Although he had a
relatively thin record as a judge, his nomination seemed set to
sail through the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Until Anita Hill came along.
</P>
<P>
   Hill worked for Thomas a decade earlier, and claimed that he
sexually harassed her. The nation was treated to tales of
legendarily endowed porn stars and pubic hairs left on Coke cans.
(We survived. Today, Monica Lewinsky and Bill Clinton's Oval Office
exploits make all this seem almost quaint.)
</P>
<P>
   ``Strange Justice'' opens with Thomas' confirmation, then
flashes back to Marshall's retirement. The White House enlists
Duberstein, who helped get David Souter confirmed to the bench, to
shepherd Thomas through Senate hearings.
</P>
<P>
   Duberstein, in the cliched manner of Washington types, plays
hardball, warning Thomas never to say anything off the cuff without
clearing it with him first.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our job is the same as if we were selling a product in the
marketplace,'' he tells the surprised judge. Later he warns Thomas,
``Don't get mad. Don't get even. Get confirmed.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, in Oklahoma, Hill is watching Bush nominate Thomas.
(Much like the trickery in ``Forrest Gump,'' Lindo and Taylor are
placed digitally into actual news footage.) The president calls
Thomas the ``best qualified'' candidate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah,'' a friend of Hill tells her, ``best qualified to grab
your ass.''
</P>
<P>
   The early scenes with Hill drag as she agonizes over whether to
come forward. Meanwhile, Duberstein preps Thomas, repeatedly asking
him if there are any skeletons in his closet. Not a one, Thomas
assures him.
</P>
<P>
   Hill's decision to go public changes all that, of course.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rules of fiasco,'' Duberstein muses. ``The higher the stakes,
the bigger the disaster.''
</P>
<P>
   The White House, of course, attempts to stonewall Hill, as well
as other women who want to come forward with damning testimony.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we get through with Anita Hill, there's not going to be
enough left to mop the floor,'' an oily White House operative
gloats.
</P>
<P>
   Then come the hearings _ and the best part of the movie. They
begin simply enough, with the well-remembered sight of Thomas
sitting at a green-topped table in front of a bank of senators.
Then, oddly, Thomas takes off his jacket and rolls up his sleeves.
</P>
<P>
   Wait a second! you think. He didn't do that. No, he didn't. Nor
did Hill erupt during her testimony. Director Ernest Dickerson
shows not just what they are saying, but how they feel while saying
it. The effect is, at first, more interesting than effective.
</P>
<P>
   Then Thomas begins his famous ``high-tech lynching'' rebuttal.
</P>
<P>
   He removes his shirt and, at one point, hangs himself with his
tie. Lindo is wonderful here. The rage, the humiliation, the
wounded pride all boil to the top. The device succeeds flawlessly.
</P>
<P>
   ``We saw this as an existential crisis for both of them,'' movie
writer Epstein said. ``They were really speaking to save their
lives. What could be more dramatic than that?''
</P>
<P>
   Nothing in ``Strange Justice,'' certainly.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, after the speeches, there is still some movie
left, more tortured scheduling and maneuvering, until Thomas
finally is confirmed. Immediately afterward, the president calls
Duberstein to congratulate him _ and to ask for his help for
re-election.
</P>
<P>
   ``Undertakers and spin doctors,'' Duberstein laughs. ``We're
never out of luck.''
</P>
<P>
   In the end, ``Strange Justice'' is a depressing story of
manipulation _ manipulation of Thomas, of Hill and, most
importantly, the American people.
</P>
<P>
   We never may find out who was telling the truth. We certainly
won't find out here.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody can know what happened . . . between those people
except the two people involved,'' Epstein said. ``It would be
impossible for anybody to say, `I know who was right and who was
lying.' I think that's the achievement of the movie.''
</P>
<P>
   It's also its downfall. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
