<SLUG> BC-FBC-UCLA-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MANNING IS HIGH ON TOLEDO'S LIST
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ As his players turned their gaze to Boise State,
Bruins coach Bob Toledo offered final thoughts on training camp.
</P>
<P>
   Best freshmen: Tight end Mike Seidman, linebackers Marcus Reese
and Asi Faoa and cornerback Ricky Manning Jr.
</P>
<P>
   Especially Manning.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like he's a 25-year-old playing his freshman year,''
Toledo said. ``He's mature beyond belief. He's so aware of what's
happening. I'm really, really pleased with him.''
</P>
<P>
   Most improved: Tight end Bryan Fletcher and defensive tackle Ken
Kocher. Kocher has secured a starting spot, while Fletcher will
rotate with tight ends Gabe Crecion and Seidman.
</P>
<P>
   Most opportunistic: Several players took advantage of the
disabled parking suspensions.
</P>
<P>
   Defensive end Rusty Williams is replacing Santi Hall, who is
replacing the suspended linebackers.
</P>
<P>
   Cornerback Joe Hunter has replaced Marques Anderson, who is out
for the season.
</P>
<P>
   Walk-on fullback Matt Stanley will start in place of Durell
Price. (Walk-on Adam Geitner is the No. 2 fullback until Price
returns.)
</P>
<P>
   ``The fullbacks are doing a good job,'' Toledo said. ``We'll be
fine with those two guys. They're two walk-ons who could eventually
earn scholarships.''
</P>
<P>
   Best finish: In the final days of training camp, no one was more
impressive than senior defensive end Travor Turner, a pass-rush
specialist whose run defense has improved. Turner is the No. 2
weakside end, behind Williams.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's playing as well as he ever has,'' Toledo said. ``Rusty
has played really well. He just plays so hard. But Travor has put
himself in a position so that we can play him and not drop off at
all.''
</P>
<P>
   Suspended in scout colors: Toledo is making optimum use of the
11 suspended players: After a lethargic training camp, they're on
the scout team, which replicates Boise State's attack.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of the suspended guys didn't put in as much effort
(during training camp) as they possibly could, and some have,''
Toledo said. ``Maybe it's a natural instinct when you know you're
not going to play.''
</P>
<P>
   Receiver rotation: Danny Farmer's sprained ankle is threatening
Toledo's plan to redshirt sophomore Jon Dubravac.
</P>
<P>
   UCLA's offense requires four healthy receivers. If Farmer can't
play against Boise State _ he's doubtful _ the Bruins might need
Dubravac to relieve Brian Poli-Dixon, Freddie Mitchell and Brad
Melsby.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to redshirt him, but I've told him he has to be
ready,'' Toledo said.
</P>
<P>
   Cody Joyce, Ryan Wilkins and Devon Reese also are competing for
Dubravac's spot.
</P>
<P>
   In and out: Next week, the Bruins will refine their substitution
patterns to prepare for two new rules: Teams cannot break the
huddle with 12 players, and teams cannot have anyone within 10
yards of the huddle.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if coaches placed 12 or 13 players in huddles to confuse
opponents, Toledo said: ``You bet. The intent was to deceive.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
