<SLUG> BC-Y2K-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BANK STRIVES TO QUELL Y2K FEARS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID HAYES and FINN BULLERS  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Technology and theology have once again
intersected, this time courtesy of the American Bankers
Association.
</P>
<P>
   The nation's bankers have gone into the sermon-writing business
in an effort to calm beliefs in some religious circles that the
Year 2000 will bring an apocalypse, without ATM machines and
electronic checking. Reaction to the bankers' sermon has been less
than charitable.
</P>
<P>
   The four-page homily, being distributed nationwide to bankers to
give to local ministers, priests and rabbis, includes these words:
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to go into the new millennium with hope, eagerness and
faith in this new century of promise. We don't want to be crouched
in our basements with candles, matches and guns.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are, after all, two ways to cross the Red Sea. With
Moses, who with God's help, led the children of Israel into a
bright, hopeful future. Or with Pharaoh, who in trying to preserve
the old, hurled his chariots, his officers and his army into the
sea.''
</P>
<P>
   Episcopal priest Paul Goodland of Fountain Hills, Ariz., was not
impressed. ``They're treading where angels fear to tread,'' he
said, adding that problems with his ATM card had made him skeptical
of banks' Year 2000 readiness.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're trying to tell us we're safe in the bosom of the
banks,'' Goodland told us this week. ``But we're safe in the bosom
of the Lord.''
</P>
<P>
   Evangelical Steve Hewitt, a Raytown preacher and publisher of
Christian Computing magazine, agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't care if this was the best sermon since `Sinners in the
Hands of an Angry God,' '' he said, it's hard to hear the word of
the Lord channeled through the mouth of a banker.
</P>
<P>
   Spokesmen with the American Anglican Council and the U.S.
Catholic Conference declined to discuss the sermon. But in the end,
Hewitt said, the bankers may be giving organized religion a dose of
what it deserves.
</P>
<P>
   ``We grabbed (Y2K) and made it a Biblical issue, and now it's
hard to condemn secular society for trying to set us straight,''
said Hewitt, who travels the country speaking out against Year 2000
alarmism.
</P>
<P>
   ``Y2K was never a Biblical issue and we're the ones who strayed
first. We drew first blood.'' Don't believe it
</P>
<P>
   We debunk yet another e-mail hoax this week.
</P>
<P>
   If you receive one of the more than 2 billion e-mail messages
sent each day, chances are you've seen this message in your
mailbox: ``You are not Y2K ready unless you've done this to your
computer
</P>
<P>
   1. Click on ``My Computer.''
</P>
<P>
   2. Click on ``Control Panel.''
</P>
<P>
   3. Click on ``Regional Settings.''
</P>
<P>
   4. Click on the ``Date'' tab. Where it says ``Short Date
Sample,'' look and see if it shows a ``two digit'' year. Of course
it does. That's the default setting for Windows 95, 98 and NT. This
date is the one that feeds application software and will not
rollover in the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
   5. Click on the button across from ``Short Date Style'' and
select the option that shows mm/dd/yyyy.
</P>
<P>
   6. Click ``Apply'' and then click on ``OK.'' Easy enough to fix.
However, every single installation of Windows worldwide is
defaulted to fail Y2K rollover.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If you believe it,'' says The Star's own newsroom systems
manager Rob Perschau, ``all you're doing is tricking yourself into
thinking your Windows 95 computer is ready for 2000.'' It may not
be unless you do a more comprehensive check.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft says the short date setting is for display purposes
only. Dates are stored and processed by Windows in a four-digit
format.
</P>
<P>
   If you want to check it out for yourself, Perschau recommends
these sites:
</P>
<P>
   - Urban legends and folklore: http://urbanlegends.miningco.com
</P>
<P>
   - Virus Hoax Center:
www.nai.com/asp_set/anti_virus/library/hoaxes.asp
</P>
<P>
   - Anti Virus Research Center:
www.symantec.com/avcenter/hoax.html
</P>
<P>
   - Microsoft Corp.: www.microsoft.com/y2k/hoax/y2khoax.htm Y2K
bomb plot
</P>
<P>
   One of the biggest threats looming at the end of year comes from
those who want something bad to happen, experts say. Case in point:
Alfred Reumayr of New Westminster, British Columbia.
</P>
<P>
   The 50-year-old Canadian is suspected in an alleged Y2K bomb
plot. He is charged with attempting to hire a U.S. citizen to blow
up energy supply systems in the United States and Canada.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not any sort of terrorist activity. It's not a political
thing. He's not some sort of ideological nut,'' Cpl. Frank Henley
of the Royal Canadian Mounted Police told Reuters news agency. ``It
was a carefully planned-out fraud.''
</P>
<P>
   Authorities in both countries said the man planned to have
explosives detonate at the end of the year to cover his tracks and
throw suspicion on the Y2K bug. They did not say what systems were
chosen as targets or how the man planned to extort funds.
</P>
<P>
   No arrests have been made. Sheriff's plan scrapped
</P>
<P>
   In Orange City, Iowa, some people think the sheriff would have
done better to call upon church elders rather than people holding
permits for concealed weapons to mobilize a special Y2K reserve
force.
</P>
<P>
   Sheriff Jim Schwiesow recently sent letters to the county's 396
registered concealed weapon permit-holders, asking them to help his
department in case of any Y2K emergencies. ``This would be strictly
a volunteer pool of trustworthy people that I could summon in dire
times,'' he wrote.
</P>
<P>
   The Sioux County Board of Supervisors nixed the idea, saying the
county would be liable for the actions of any reserve force. Under
Iowa law, a reserve peace officer force must be approved by the
board and officers must attend a minimum training course of 150
hours plus weapons training.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Jeff Sajdak, pastor of Immanuel Christian Reformed
Church, said the sheriff could have called on Sioux County CARES, a
coalition of people in education, law enforcement and social
services. Sioux County CARES would be ``a better and perhaps more
effective way than to find everybody with a weapons permit,'' he
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
