<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-AIKMAN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOW YOU'RE COOKING: AIKMAN WOWS YOUNG CROWD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RICHIE WHITT 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ Warning: The following true account of a Dallas
Cowboys player's off-field activity contains no drugs or dancers,
no speed or weed or even a hint of prima-donna sneers, excessive
beers or barber shears. Hold on to your jurisprudence, it's a nice
story about a nice guy helping nice kids. It's probably been a
while so, please, proceed with caution:
</P>
<P>
   Troy Aikman hasn't thrown a pass that counts this season, but he
might have already made his most important completion.
</P>
<P>
   While many of you were still sleeping yesterday morning, the
Cowboys quarterback, who has enough money to buy the Mavericks and
enough popularity to run against Gov. George W. Bush, crawled out
of bed and drove himself to Texas Stadium in search of 100 smiles.
When he arrived around 6:30 a.m., he was met by producers from
ABC's ``Good Morning America'', black-belt chef Emeril Lagasse and
a school-bus worth of stopped hearts, dropped jaws and fixated eyes
enamored by the sight of a superstar sight doubling as a
sympathetic civilian.
</P>
<P>
   Touchdown, Aikman-to-Caring.
</P>
<P>
   Turning heads faster than Michael Johnson and seizing attention
spans stronger than Pokemon, Aikman instantly melted the stress of
100 children staring at fourth-down-and-life. The students _ from
Happy Hill Farm Academy/Home in Granbury _ suddenly weren't
burdened by their troubled pasts of abuse, neglect or simply being
dumped at the doorstep with no note and no hope.
</P>
<P>
   For 45 precious minutes, Aikman reminded the children that
apparently it's still safe to have your Heroes be Cowboys.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's great, like a dream,'' said Heather, a 17-year-old senior
at Happy Hill. ``We're in Texas Stadium, we're meeting Troy and
we're on TV. Plus, we don't have to go back to class today.''
</P>
<P>
   While an additional 200 fans provided a ``GMA'' backdrop of
Aikman jerseys, cardboard cutouts and signs that ranged from
``Marry Me Troy'' (obviously in denial) to ``Pork Fat Rules''
(obviously insane), Aikman switched gears from Chan Gailey's
playbook to the ``Dallas Cowboys Family Cookbook''. Dressed in a
golf shirt and holding _ surprise _ a football (''The only prop
they feel I can handle,'' he joked), Aikman talked to millions of
viewers about his zest for charity and the desperate need of funds
created from sales of the cookbooks.
</P>
<P>
   Proceeds from the cookbook _ started in 1979 by former Cowboys
linebacker Bob Breunig and this year featuring recipes from
renowned Fort Worth chef Grady Spears _ benefit Happy Hill.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a special opportunity to be able to help these kids,''
said Aikman, who wasn't paid for his appearance but did claim to
receive an immeasurable gift. ``Hopefully, with events like this
and others, we can give them another chance in life. That's what
it's all about to me. It's the rewarding part.''
</P>
<P>
   During his live 10-minute segment, Aikman feigned knowing nods
as Lagasse prepared ``Troy Aikman's Chicken Breasts Alfredo'' (page
22).
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm into eating much more than the cooking,'' Aikman joked.
``I ran out of recipes after the first year of the cookbook.''
</P>
<P>
   While the chicken soaked in white sauce and the children soaked
in unforgettable memories, Aikman gave a thumbs-up taste test
despite grimacing when Lagasse lopped an entire stick of butter
into the concoction.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a little heavy for a pregame meal,'' Aikman said before
presenting Lagasse with a No. 8 Cowboys jersey. ``But it would
probably taste pretty good after a victory.''
</P>
<P>
   After the show, which was also open to the public, the children
and fans engorged themselves with T-shirts, souvenir footballs and,
most important, leftovers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Outstanding,'' said Navy recruiter Mike Raley, who made the
trip with three co-workers from the Naval Air Station north of Fort
Worth. ``The food is good, but the best thing is how Troy is still
down-to-earth. You hear a lot of bad things about athletes these
days, but here's proof they're not all bad. There's some good ones
still out there.''
</P>
<P>
   With the sun rising but a full moon still peeking through the
stadium's roof, Aikman _ the one sometimes criticized for being too
stoic _ unhinged his jerky-tough exterior long enough to give
further glimpse of his soft underbelly. By shaking hands, signing
autographs, exchanging smiles or simply patting a head, he planted
seeds for a new generation of fans seeking positive role models.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's easy to spot someone's big talent,'' Lagasse said. ``But
when you see an athlete give his time and be genuinely excited like
Troy was, you get to see his big heart. He really sent a spark into
those kids. And vice versa.''
</P>
<P>
   When the Cowboys are host to the Denver Broncos tomorrow night,
Aikman will resume being the quarterback. But somewhere at Happy
Hill, 100 youngsters will never be the same.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
