<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STAR-JOURNAL-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BASEBALL HALL OF FAMER'S RELATIVES REMEMBER A MAN DIFFERENT FROM
MANY OF TODAY'S STARS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOE POPPER  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Kansas City, Mo. _ Recently, as hundreds of Kansas Citians
descended upon Cooperstown, N.Y., to celebrate George Brett's
induction into the National Baseball Hall of Fame, one family with
deep Kansas City roots made the journey for a different reason.
</P>
<P>
   ``We went for a reunion marking the 50th anniversary of our
great-grandfather's election to the Hall,'' said Sharon Everett,
who grew up in Kansas City and now teaches in San Diego, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Her great-grandfather was Charles ``Kid'' Nichols, a legend in
early baseball and one of the first Kansas Citians elected to the
Hall of Fame.
</P>
<P>
   His 15-year major-league record was impressive. His plaque at
Cooperstown credits him with 360 victories and 202 losses.
</P>
<P>
   His other achievements included seven seasons with 30 or more
wins; 48 shutouts; 532 complete games. (He was almost never taken
out of a game for a relief pitcher.)
</P>
<P>
   Ty Cobb called him ``one of the greatest pitchers of all
time...''
</P>
<P>
   Christy Mathewson said he was ``the greatest pitcher'' he'd ever
faced.
</P>
<P>
   Although Nichols played for the old Boston Nationals, later
renamed the Braves, he lived in Kansas City from 1880 until his
death in 1953.
</P>
<P>
   ``But who remembers him now?'' said his great-granddaughter Ann
Everett, a nun and teacher who lives in Fairway.
</P>
<P>
   ``Almost no one,'' said her sister, Sharon Everett. ``And that
certainly makes you think twice when you read all the sportswriter
hype about `immortal fame' and `enshrinement' in the hall.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1949, the year of Nichols' induction, entering the Hall of
Fame was a simpler affair than it is now.
</P>
<P>
   That year Nichols traveled alone to Cooperstown for the
ceremony. He could not afford to take his family with him.
</P>
<P>
   ``He never made more than $3,000 a year in baseball,'' said
Sharon Everett.
</P>
<P>
   In his later years he did not trade upon his fame to hobnob with
the wealthy and powerful. Instead he used his lifetime baseball
pass to take children to games at old Blues Stadium in Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   ``He taught us to love baseball as a game for all the people,''
said Ann Everett. ``We were in awe of him, but we didn't know how
great he had been. He never talked about that.''
In his playing years, Nichols was slender and handsome and, at 5
feet 10 inches tall and 160 pounds, was considered small for a
major leaguer.
</P>
<P>
   Although he smoked cigars and moved through the world with
confidence, he had a baby face that led teammates to tab him the
``Kid.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite his appearance, he was a hard man on the ball field.
</P>
<P>
   In a 1902 game, a bat slipped from a player's hands and smashed
Nichols' head, causing a long gash. He was rushed to a doctor, who
stitched the gash.
</P>
<P>
   ``I returned to the park with my head so swathed in bandages I
was unable to wear my cap,'' Nichols wrote later.
</P>
<P>
   He was woozy and half asleep, but when his team's pitcher was
ejected for arguing with an umpire, Nichols, looking like a mummy,
walked to the mound and pitched three near-perfect innings.
</P>
<P>
   The Kansas City Star called him an ``iron man.'' The paper paid
special attention to his career because Nichols, although born in
Wisconsin, always called Kansas City his hometown, having moved
here when he was 11.
</P>
<P>
   ``I began playing baseball on (Kansas City's) corner lots,'' he
wrote. He joined organized baseball when he was 18, playing first
for the old Kansas City Western League club and winning the first
five games he pitched.
</P>
<P>
   At the time he weighed only 135 pounds, but his fastball was
blazing, his curve a sweeping blur.
</P>
<P>
   He joined the major league Boston club in 1890. That year he won
27 games, the next year 30, the year after that 35.
</P>
<P>
   In 1892 he won three consecutive games on three consecutive days
in three different cities, a feat Ty Cobb later called
``remarkable.''
</P>
<P>
   His delivery was straightaway. He never broke eye contact with
the batter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I faced the best batters of my time, but I did not dread
them,'' he wrote.
</P>
<P>
   He played his last game in 1906. He then returned to Kansas City
and held a series of jobs. He managed bowling alleys, sold
insurance and men's furnishings. He devoted his free time to youth
baseball.
</P>
<P>
   ``He always thought of himself as just a common person who had
been given a great talent,'' said Sharon Everett. ``And he wanted
to share it with everybody.''
When Nichols' descendants returned to Cooperstown this year, what
they encountered outside the museum surprised them.
</P>
<P>
   ``We saw Pete Rose and other old ballplayers set up booths and
charge $25 for each autograph they signed,'' said Sharon Everett.
</P>
<P>
   ``It disgusted me. One of the things I hate most is seeing
little kids begging ballplayers for autographs as the players walk
by without a second glance. It breaks my heart.''
</P>
<P>
   She recalls that when children wrote asking for her
great-grandfather's autograph, he always sent one by return mail.
After his death at 83, his daughter, Alice, continued the
tradition, cutting Nichols' signatures off old canceled checks,
pasting them on postcards and sending them out with notes of
thanks.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot has changed since then,'' said Ann Everett.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now at the ballpark I see tiers of fancy corporate boxes, and
the lower level filled with people who have paid a fortune for
tickets and aren't even watching the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``And then I wonder, why can't we be down there instead, people
like us who may not be rich but who really love the game?''
</P>
<P>
   Every Memorial Day, Ann Everett takes flowers to her
great-grandfather's grave at Mount Moriah Cemetery in south Kansas
City.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, as she was cleaning the floral urn in front of the
grave, a baseball rolled out and fell onto the grass.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ball was very old and brown and cracked,'' she said. ``But
I could see it was signed in several places. I was so happy that
somebody remembered him and wanted to honor him with a ball from
his own era.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, filled with curiosity, she took the ball to autograph
experts to find out who had signed it. But the signatures were so
faint that no one could read them. They had faded away like the
forgotten past.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
