<HEADLINE>
MCCAIN COURTS VOTES IN NAVAJO COUNTRY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By KRIS MAYES  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WINDOW ROCK, Ariz. _ Sen. John McCain on Friday became the first
presidential candidate to take his campaign to Navajo country,
where he is hoping to convert a long record of political favors
into votes.
</P>
<P>
   McCain, who still is running behind Texas Gov. George W. Bush,
told residents of the Navajo Nation that he would make their issues
a priority in the White House.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I am elected president of the United States, after the
election I will come back here to Window Rock, and we will meet,''
McCain told 71 members of the Tribal Council gathered for a special
session to work on the tribe's budget. ``And we will formulate new
policies for the Navajo Nation and Indian Country.''
</P>
<P>
   With more than 55,000 registered voters, Navajos represent an
undeniably attractive block of votes to any presidential candidate.
In 1996, Republican presidential hopeful Steve Forbes, who
eventually won Arizona's primary, set up shop here.
</P>
<P>
   In his Senate campaigns in Arizona, McCain has done well among
the Navajo and during his last two Senate bids secured the tribe's
official endorsement.
</P>
<P>
   At a press conference at tribal headquarters, McCain told
reporters that the Indian vote could become critical if the
Republican race tightens.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are tens of thousands of (Native American) votes in
Arizona,'' he said. ``And it's not just the reservation, and it's
not just this tribe. In a close race, every vote counts.''
</P>
<P>
   In one of the day's biggest surprises, former Navajo President
Peterson Zah publicly switched his voter registration from Democrat
to Republican at a press conference. McCain hopes it's the
beginning of a campaign to convert the Navajo into a tribe of
Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many of you out there are Democrats, but you know there is a
way you can help this man,'' Zah told about 150 people. ``If you
are a Democrat, you can change over during the primary and vote for
this man, and, if you want, you can change back during the
general.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain spent the day meeting with tribal leaders and the
council, followed by a rally thrown by Navajo military veterans.
</P>
<P>
   Small groups of veterans, many of whom expressed their affinity
for McCain, a former prisoner of war in Vietnam, gathered to hear
the senator speak under a hot afternoon sun.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a Democrat, but I still wish McCain a lot of luck,'' said
Oscar House, a former Marine from Window Rock who served in Korea.
``Because he's a veteran and I'm a veteran, I have a lot of respect
for the man and what he went through.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, House noted that McCain's challenge will be in bringing
Native Americans to the polls.
</P>
<P>
   ``Out here, he can get a lot of support if he gets people who
will push for him,'' House said. ``The Navajo are voters in tribal
elections. They just don't go out and vote in national elections.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain, a former member of the Senate Native American Affairs
subcommittee, has spent years wooing Arizona Indians. Repeatedly on
Friday, he sought to highlight his record on Indian issues. In his
speech before the Tribal Council, McCain vowed to help eradicate
poverty on the reservation and resolve a long-standing dispute over
Indian trust funds.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a public disgrace, $2.4 billion in revenues that belong
to tribal governments,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   To land the Native American vote, McCain will be relying in part
on the efforts of Arizona House Speaker Jeff Groscost, R-Mesa, who
has made recent inroads with Navajo voters on behalf of the GOP.
Groscost, who has been traveling between Phoenix and Window Rock
for McCain, promised to deliver the vote.
</P>
<P>
   ``They (the Navajo) understand that he needs help, and I think
people would be surprised how willing they are to help,'' Groscost
said. ``They are extremely loyal people.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
