<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKL-LIBERTY-STING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.Y.)  
 CHARLOTTE BEATS LIBERTY IN GAME 1, 78-67 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By STEVE POPPER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHARLOTTE, N.C. _ As she walked from the bench to the scorer's
table with just over six minutes left in the game, Teresa
Weatherspoon barked at the official standing nearby, ``Let me
play!'' The official didn't look her way, the argument already
lost. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   With Weatherspoon spending most of the game's most crucial
moments on the bench in foul trouble, her Charlotte Sting
counterpart, Dawn Staley, took over the game, guiding the Sting to
a 78-67 victory in Game 1 of the two-of-3-games Eastern Conference
finals. The Liberty goes home for Sunday night's Game 2 with the
very real prospect of elimination just 40 minutes away. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Just as the Houston Comets found themselves on the losing end on
the underdog's home court in the Western Conference playoffs on
Thursday night, the Liberty now can forget about the 18-14 record
and its first-place finish in the conference. The Liberty must now
use the home court advantage that it gained throughout the regular
season to pull off two straight victories over the Sting, which has
beaten the Liberty in the teams' last three meetings. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Staley finished the game with 16 points and nine assists, while
Weatherspoon had five points and eight assists. But it was what
Staley did when Weatherspoon was forced to the bench that made the
difference. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Weatherspoon drew a pair of fouls in a four-second span in the
opening minutes of the second half, sending her to the sideline
with four fouls. When Becky Hammon took her place, Staley
immediately attacked, and with 16 minutes 52 seconds to play, she
hit from beyond the arc to tie the score at 42-42. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Robinson led the Liberty in Weatherspoon's absence, continuing
her run that had begun in the final minutes of the first half,
scoring seven of the Liberty's first 15 points.
</P>
<P>
   But it wasn't enough to keep the Sting from pushing to its first
lead since early in the first half.
</P>
<P>
   Staley gave Charlotte a 49-47 lead by finishing a 3-on-1 fast
break after a missed 3-pointer by Hammon. That forced Liberty coach
Richie Adubato to put Weatherspoon back into the game, but she
stayed off Staley and the Liberty paid for that. With the shot
clock winding down minutes later, Staley drained a 3-pointer over
Vickie Johnson to give Charlotte a 62-55 lead. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Then, with 7:48 to play, Weatherspoon drew her fifth foul and
was back on the bench, the damage already done. Staley had scored
nine points in the those first 12 minutes of the second half, and
the Sting was pulling away. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Robinson had kept the Liberty alive through the first half after
starting miserably from the floor, missing four consecutive shots
after starting the game with a 3-point field goal. But she missed
three straight 3-pointers and then misfired on a long jumper.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   So Robinson went inside, just the way any coach would beg even
the best of shooters to do, passing up a 3-pointer and giving the
ball to Weatherspoon, who found Robinson cutting down the lane.
Robinson dropped in a reverse layup with 2:50 left in the first
half and then she was off. The next trip downcourt, she took a pass
on the left sideline on a break and delivered a 3-pointer. After a
pair of free throws by Weatherspoon, Robinson converted a pretty
turnaround jumper just outside the lane, finishing the half with 10
points and helping the Liberty to a 36-33 halftime advantage.
</P>
<P>
   ``Defenses are looking for her and they're not going to give her
the jump shot,'' Adubato said before the game. ``She's going to
have to do that, use the pump fake, drive around people, or look
for the open man.
</P>
<P>
   ``This team, the Sting, is so concerned with her. She was six
for 12 from 3-point range in one game against them, that's my No. 1
concern.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
