<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-28 00:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2566 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a BC-ABORTION-SIDE-AZR &LR;      08-28 0737
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ABORTION-SIDE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AID OFFERS ABOUND FOR 14-YEAR-OLD WHO WANTS ABORTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By KARINA BLAND  
 and KRIS MAYES  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Lawmakers in Arizona want to send her to college.
</P>
<P>
   Parents as far way as Oklahoma want to adopt her.
</P>
<P>
   And strangers from around the country are offering her money,
clothing and a place to live.
</P>
<P>
   But only if she keeps her baby.
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of people want to help a 14-year-old girl who last week
received a judge's permission to have a late-term abortion.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the girl decides to have the baby, there will be a
scholarship waiting for her,'' Rep. Matt Salmon, R-Ariz., said
Friday during a campaign stop on the Navajo Reservation in Window
Rock.
</P>
<P>
   He pledged $25,000. His offer was matched by former state
Attorney General Grant Woods.
</P>
<P>
   Salmon later called former gubernatorial candidate and local
businessman Eddie Basha who, along with his son, promised an
unspecified amount of money. KFYI radio talk show host Barry Young
pledged $10,000 for the care of the young mother through the time
of delivery.
</P>
<P>
   ``It sounds like coercion to me,'' Bruce Miller, director of
Arizona Right to Choose, an abortion rights advocacy group, said of
all the offers. ``This is nothing more than trying to bribe a young
woman into continuing a pregnancy she doesn't want by throwing a
handful of coins in front of her.''
</P>
<P>
   He asked whether the men were going to give that much money to
every pregnant 14-year-old girl in Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   House Speaker Jeff Groscost, R-Mesa, bristled at the suggestion
that the offers are bribes, saying such characterizations are
cynical.
</P>
<P>
   He said his office at the state Capitol has been deluged with
more than 600 telephone calls, including 300 from people who have
offered to either adopt the girl's yet-unborn baby or give her
money if she chooses to continue the pregnancy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It really was just a groundswell of people saying, `We want to
put our money where our mouths are,' '' Groscost said.
</P>
<P>
   Brian Finkel, a doctor at Metro Phoenix Women's Center and a
strong abortion rights advocate, said lawmakers are unduly
influencing not only this girl but the judge.
</P>
<P>
   ``If this girl does not get her abortion because of the
strong-arming of lawmakers, she is going to become Arizona's next
multimillionaire,'' he said, alluding that lawyers would line up
behind her to sue the state for forcing her to continue her
pregnancy.
</P>
<P>
   Miller says he's been in contact with the National Abortion
Rights Action League about the possibility of hiring an attorney
for the girl if the judge reverses his decision to allow the
abortion.
</P>
<P>
   The Governor's Office has been flooded with calls as have the
court and the state Department of Economic Security.
</P>
<P>
   Tamra Burnett, a foster mother from the small farming community
of Lamont, Okla., is offering to adopt both the girl and her baby.
</P>
<P>
   A Flagstaff family, too, is offering her a home.
</P>
<P>
   Burnett read about the girl in her local newspaper. She has had
eight foster children since 1996 and two kids of her own, ages 7
and 11 months.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know a lot of times that these kids feel that nobody cares,
and I'm sure she feels that way,'' Burnett said. ``They lose
hope.''
</P>
<P>
   The Flagstaff home of Scott and Kelli Waxman, a finance manager
and math teacher, is licensed as a foster home. The couple also
want to care for the girl. They live on an Arabian horse ranch and
have already adopted one girl from state care.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can provide the best schools, constant supervision,
spiritual guidance and modeling of effective parenting,'' they
wrote in a letter to the court. ``We would be glad to have the
court consider us for immediate placement of this young lady and/or
her baby.''
</P>
<P>
   John Jakubczyk, an attorney who represents Arizona Right to
Life, the state's largest anti-abortion group, said he, too, has
received dozens of calls from people from across the country who
want to adopt the yet-unborn baby. Others said they want to give
her money, baby clothes and other items.
</P>
<P>
   The girl's situation has even attracted the attention of
presidential candidates, including Arizona's Republican Sen. John
McCain.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a terrible tragedy,'' he said. ``I hope that she
would be assured that thousands of families would adopt her
child.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Republic reporter Chris Moeser contributed to this article. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
