<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL NOTEBOOK: THE URBAN UN-JUNGLE  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By ELEANOR RANDOLPH  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Saturday, Aug. 28:
</P>
<P>
   To the ordinary ear, the rules on keeping animals in New York
City always seemed perfectly clear. Pets must not be ``wild,
ferocious, fierce, dangerous or naturally inclined to do harm,''
the Health Department code advised for decades. Over time, however,
some residents found such language soft and fuzzy enough to allow
creatures that were undomesticated even for the streets of New
York. Six adult alligators, for example, once were found living in
a Brooklyn brownstone. One renter left behind a python in her
apartment bathtub. Then officials nabbed an illegal rooster in the
Bronx that might well have escaped detection had it not also broken
the city's noise ordinance every morning at dawn.
</P>
<P>
   Faced with so many ferocious arguments about which creatures are
fierce, the city recently banned 150 specific animals. Some of
those named have not been a big problem historically in the city,
but health officials decided not to let any more unwanted life
forms slip, slither or fly through their loopholes. So they banned,
among others, armadillos, polar bears, bees, iguanas, vultures,
prairie dogs, black widow spiders, Tasmanian devils, kangaroos,
pythons, whales _ yes, whales _ and ``all non-human primates.''
</P>
<P>
   So far the noisiest complaints have come not from sleazy dealers
in contraband animals but from tenacious supporters of the equally
tenacious ferret. Ferret owners believe their pets are sweet and
lovable. They shrug off veterinary warnings that ferrets have been
known to bite babies, and they were outraged when Mayor Rudolph
Giuliani suggested that a ferret advocate needed psychiatric help
for ``devoting your life to weasels.'' In truth, many of these
ferrets are actually European stoats, but in the city, stoats are
taboo as well.
</P>
<P>
   The Health Department, after listing range animals that even
Donald Trump could not hide in his apartment, has decided against
any ``animal dragnets.'' This makes sense given that the department
has more pressing issues. With passions running high, the City
Council is expected to reconsider the city's illegal pet list. If
experience to date offers any guidance, the Council's hearing on
this issue could be a zoo.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-28-99 0100EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990828.0031 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-28 01:01 </DATE_TIME>
