<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-NY-CHARTER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: REVISING CHARTER REVISION 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Saturday, Aug. 28:
</P>
<P>
   Finally, New York City's Charter Revision Commission offers a
flicker of good news. The commission chairman, Randy Mastro,
indicated Friday that it might be time to douse the political
firestorm his group ignited this summer by proposing to change the
way the city replaces a mayor who leaves office early. His move
could end suspicions that a commission loaded with Mayor Rudolph
Giuliani's supporters has one overriding purpose _ to limit the
powers of one of Giuliani's least favorite politicians, Public
Advocate Mark Green.
</P>
<P>
   The way the charter works now, a mayor who leaves office early
is replaced by the public advocate. Thus if Giuliani wins the race
for Senate against Hillary Rodham Clinton next year, he will have
to give Green the keys to his City Hall office for a year, until
the next mayoral election in 2001. So this Charter Commission was
considering a referendum asking voters to approve a mayoral
election 60 days after the public advocate becomes mayor.
</P>
<P>
   Mastro hopes to persuade the commission next Wednesday to word
the item on succession so that it would not take effect until after
the mayoral vote in 2001. Fpom the start, this commission has been
a hasty and ill-conceived political exercise. Its hearings have
been held in the dead of August, and the election in November has
no citywide races to attract a cross-section of voters. But if the
commission changes the date on its succession item, at least those
voters who make it to the polls can decide more rationally on
issues, not personalities.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
