u a BC-FIRES-SPI &LR;      08-28 0648
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FIRES-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIRE DANGERS BEFORE HOLIDAY WEEKEND WORRY FOREST, PARK OFFICIALS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JUDD SLIVKA  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   A forecast of warm, dry days leading into next week's long Labor
Day weekend has park and forest rangers in Washington state worried
that a careless hiker or camper could ignite the dry underbrush and
start a forest fire.
</P>
<P>
   Campfire restrictions already are in place at three state
campgrounds, including one in the popular San Juan Islands, and may
be expanded into the busiest camping week of the year.
</P>
<P>
   The fire danger west of the Cascades is ``moderate,'' but east
of the mountains, where temperatures have soared into the high 90s,
the risk is approaching ``very high.''
</P>
<P>
   Even the grass along the freeways is tinder dry. Firefighters in
Pierce County were called out twice this week to fight brush fires.
</P>
<P>
   One fire, at Interstate 5 and Pacific Highway South, briefly
shut down southbound lanes of the freeway Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our concern is man-caused fires. Someone throwing a cigarette
butt out the window. ... People need to be aware if they're going
camping or outdoors that it's getting dry out there,'' said John
Werth, a fire-weather forecaster with the National Park Service in
Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   More than 10,000 firefighters equipped with at least 700 fire
engines battled Western wildfires on Friday, assisted by scores of
helicopters and air tankers. Several of the fires were sparked by
lightning, and some have been burning since last weekend.
</P>
<P>
   The Colville Indian Reservation in Eastern Washington had two
fires this week, a 350-acre fire believed to have been caused by a
car and a 2,000-acre fire believed to be caused by a power surge in
a transformer. Neither fire caused much damage.
</P>
<P>
   The weather forecast for the next 10 days calls for
higher-than-normal temperatures coupled with little precipitation,
a combination that makes the twigs, grasses and fallen tree limbs
more flammable, Werth said.
</P>
<P>
   Aware of the growing fire hazard, Spencer Spit State Park on
Lopez Island is allowing only small fires in designated fire pits.
Lyons Ferry State Park near Starbuck in Eastern Washington has
banned fires and charcoal briquets, and Steamboat Rock State Park
near Grand Coulee Dam has banned fires in its primitive
campgrounds.
</P>
<P>
   Washington's dry spell comes at a time when regional
firefighting resources are beginning to be taxed. The federal
government Wednesday authorized National Guard troops to fight
fires if needed.
</P>
<P>
   While Washington has so far been spared large fires, Oregon and
California have not.
</P>
<P>
   In Oregon's Sheldon-Hart National Wildlife Refuge, 30,000 acres
_ much of it antelope habitat _ were on fire Friday. Authorities
expect to have it contained by Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   In California, the situation is worse. Authorities are fighting
19 fires from lightning strikes 22 miles north of Redding in the
Shasta-Trinity National Forest.
</P>
<P>
   Named the High Complex fire, only 5 percent of the 8,000-acre
fire was contained Friday, and nearly 900 structures were
threatened by the flames.
</P>
<P>
   In California' Modoc National Forest, nearly 18,000 acres south
of Tulelake are on fire. Only 25 percent of the fire had been
contained, and the fire was moving into areas where goshawks were
nesting.
</P>
<P>
   Still, firefighters have been gaining ground.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've been able to handle the new starts and get a better
handle on what they're already fighting. Things are looking better
today,'' said Janelle Smith of the National Interagency Fire Center
in Boise, Idaho.
</P>
<P>
   Wildfires temporarily chased hundreds of residents from their
homes in California and Nevada early this week but have burned few
homes. There were no mandatory evacuations in effect Friday.
</P>
<P>
   This report includes information from The Associated Press.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
