<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-28 01:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2573 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-EDIT-MIDEAST-NYT &LR;      08-28 0502
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-MIDEAST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: MIDEAST PEACE PROSPECTS  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Saturday, August 28:
</P>
<P>
   Israel and the Palestinians are close to agreement on a
timetable for carrying out last year's Wye River peace agreement.
Similar progress is now needed in reviving talks between Israel and
Syria, which have been suspended for more than three years. Since
Israel's prime minister, Ehud Barak, took office in early July,
Israel and Syria have been talking through intermediaries like
Jordan and the United States. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright
should use her visits to Jerusalem and Damascus next week to speed
the resumption of face-to-face talks.
</P>
<P>
   After a summer of upbeat statements by Barak and Syria's
president, Hafez al-Assad, it is time for the two countries to
begin narrowing their differences on the main issues. These include
the extent of Israeli withdrawals from the Golan Heights, the
precise nature of the diplomatic and economic relations Syria
offers in return and arrangements for assuring Israeli security and
access to water resources after a Golan withdrawal.
</P>
<P>
   One issue holding up direct talks was Syria's insistence that
negotiations resume at the point they broke off in 1996. Damascus
claims Israel was prepared at the time to withdraw from the entire
Golan Heights if agreement was reached on all other issues. Israel
has a different view on how much progress was made then. But the
Barak government suggested last month that it was willing to pick
up from where the 1996 talks left off.
</P>
<P>
   If Syria is ready to make a full peace, it may be able to regain
legal sovereignty over the entire Golan. But it will have to accept
security provisions like demilitarized zones and monitoring
stations to assure that Israel's northern towns are not exposed to
surprise attack as they were before 1967. Some Israeli officials
have suggested that an Israeli withdrawal to the internationally
recognized boundary line, which would leave the entire eastern
shore of the Sea of Galilee in Israeli hands, could serve as the
basis for a settlement of water and other issues. It is up to Barak
to decide whether this proposal should be part of an overall
settlement.
</P>
<P>
   If agreement can be reached on Golan issues, arranging an
Israeli withdrawal from southern Lebanon should be relatively
straightforward. Barak has already declared that he wants to
withdraw all Israeli troops from Lebanon. But he will do so only if
he can be sure that Lebanese Hezbollah guerrillas will not use the
border area to launch rocket attacks on northern Israel.
</P>
<P>
   Assad, who is the real power in Lebanon, can rein in Hezbollah,
but will not do so until he reaches a deal on the Golan. If the
Syrian peace track is going to move forward, Assad must do more
than just sit and listen when Ms. Albright comes calling. He will
have to offer compromise proposals of his own that can lead to
direct talks between Syria and Israel.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
