<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-GUNCONTROL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: GUN CONTROL GAINS IN CALIFORNIA  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Saturday, August 28:
</P>
<P>
   California, the scene of the latest shooting spree by a deranged
gunman, continues to move far out ahead of Washington and the rest
of the country on the issue of gun control. The gun safety measures
that Gov. Gray Davis signed into law Friday were the latest in a
series of initiatives that can only shame _ and with any luck will
inspire _ an indifferent Congress that is nowhere near agreement on
a far more modest package of reforms.
</P>
<P>
   California's progress this summer has been nothing short of
remarkable. Just last month the state enacted the country's
toughest ban on assault weapons and large-capacity ammunition
clips. It also cracked down on gun trafficking by limiting
individual handgun purchases to one a month _ a sensible idea that
has gone nowhere in Washington. Then last week Davis directed all
state agencies to destroy confiscated and other out-of-service
firearms instead of selling them.
</P>
<P>
   Friday's measures include the nation's most comprehensive ban on
so-called Saturday night specials, the cheap, poorly made handguns
commonly used in criminal activity. For the first time all handguns
manufactured or sold in California will have to meet minimum
quality and safety standards. This is a major breakthrough. About
80 percent of all Saturday night specials are manufactured in
southern California, and a similar measure was vetoed by the
previous governor, Pete Wilson. Like Massachusetts, California will
now require that handguns be tested to make sure they do not break
apart or fire when dropped _ a precaution to avoid the accidental
shootings that claimed the lives of 675 children in California
alone last year.
</P>
<P>
   Another new California safety measure will require that all guns
sold in the state after Dec. 31, 2001, be equipped with a
state-approved child-safety lock. This provision stops short of
requiring personalized handguns, those that can be fired only by
the authorized owner. But unlike the weak safety-lock provision
that is now languishing in Congress, California's version at least
requires that firearm safety devices meet reasonable standards of
effectiveness.
</P>
<P>
   Friday's signing ceremony was held at the Los Angeles hospital
where, just 18 days ago, wounded victims of Buford Furrow's assault
on a Jewish community center were brought for emergency treatment.
California's strong action on gun control will save lives. But no
matter how severe its laws, California cannot prevent criminals and
disturbed individuals from obtaining weapons in other states with
much looser gun laws. Gun violence is a national problem. For that
reason the vast majority of Americans, according to every poll, are
demanding national solutions.
</P>
<P>
   When Congress returns to work after Labor Day, it will be
interesting to see how much it has learned from the Furrow rampage,
and from California's brave efforts to stop the violence.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-28-99 0105EDT &QL; 
