u a BC-BOEING-SPI &LR;      08-28 1354
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOEING-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOEING, MACHINISTS HUDDLE AS DEADLINE FOR FINAL OFFER NEARS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JAMES WALLACE  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Weary negotiating teams from The Boeing Co. and its
largest union raced against the clock at a Sea-Tac hotel Friday
night grasping for a new labor agreement that might avert a strike
at the world's largest aerospace company.
</P>
<P>
   Offers and counteroffers were flying across the bargaining
table.
</P>
<P>
   But as a midnight deadline neared Friday night for Boeing to
present the union with its best and final offer, the union's leader
said the two sides remained far apart.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've seen some improvement in the day, but we are far apart.
... I'm still not optimistic we are going to avert a labor
dispute,'' said Bill Johnson, president of the Machinists union
that represents 44,000 of Boeing's 207,000 employees.
</P>
<P>
   But Boeing Chairman Phil Condit, who visited with his
negotiating team at the hotel in midafternoon, told reporters
afterward that he thought an agreement acceptable to the company
and the Machinists would be reached.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we can reach an agreement that is good for our
employees,'' Condit said.
</P>
<P>
   Condit said he believed chances ``are reasonably good'' a strike
can be averted.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing planned to post its final offer on its Web site
(www.boeing.com) immediately after presenting it to the union late
Friday night. The union said it would respond by the weekend on its
Web site (www.iam751.org).
</P>
<P>
   Following a recommendation from union leadership, the Machinists
will vote on the contract Wednesday. The current contract expires
at 12:01 a.m. Thursday and a strike could begin immediately if
two-thirds of the Machinists vote to authorize it.
</P>
<P>
   Asked at the news conference what he would like to say to the
men and women of his company who could be on strike early Thursday
morning if the agreement is rejected, Condit said:
</P>
<P>
   ``I would ask them to look at it with great care. Look for what
is important to them, think about what is important to them and the
company and then vote. ... They are going to need to look at it and
say, `This is a fair offer or no it's not.' I believe if they look
at it they will discover its fair.''
</P>
<P>
   Boeing's Machinists have gone on strike after rejecting two of
the past three contracts. They last struck for 69 days in 1995. But
Boeing has never had back-to back strikes by its Machinists.
</P>
<P>
   Tim Flinn, a spokesman for the International Association of
Machinists and Aerospace Workers, said Boeing gave the union a
``complete offer'' around noon Friday, but it was not the company's
final offer.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a compilation of everything,'' Flinn said. That
document served as the basis for negotiations the rest of the
afternoon and into the evening, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The two sides would meet for a while, then break to caucus, and
then head back to the hotel bargaining room to continue the talks.
</P>
<P>
   Neither side last night was willing to talk about details of the
negotiations until the company's final offer was on the table.
</P>
<P>
   But a union member familiar with the complete proposal the
company had presented to the union around noon told the Seattle
Post-Intelligencer it fell well short of what the Machinists need
to see.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was nothing good in that proposal. We are on strike if
that's the best the company can do,'' the union member said. ``They
are playing hardball. Boeing obviously doesn't want to deliver 620
airplanes this year.''
</P>
<P>
   But Johnson, when interviewed in the early evening, cautioned
that talks would continue into the night until the company made its
final offer.
</P>
<P>
   ``The company still has time,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Sources said Boeing, in its complete offer at noon, did not
insist on a flexible work week, one of the key issues that Johnson
had said could result in a strike.
</P>
<P>
   Asked at the news conference how important the flexible work
week is to Boeing, Condit said, ``A lot of people worry about that.
But where we get to in this contract, I don't think is critical at
this point. But it is something that is certainly of interest to
us.''
</P>
<P>
   Boeing has argued that to become more efficient, it must have
the authority to scatter five-day shifts throughout the week,
including weekends.
</P>
<P>
   The company must now pay overtime for weekend work.
</P>
<P>
   The other key issues are:
</P>
<P>
   _Job security. The union wants a say in work that is outsourced.
Boeing wants the final say.
</P>
<P>
   _Health benefits. Boeing wants union members to begin partial
payment for their health care benefits. The union wants the current
plan left alone. Workers now don't pay anything.
</P>
<P>
   _Pensions. The union wants control over the pension plan and it
wants Boeing to contribute. The company wants to keep control, and
does not want to make payments at this time.
</P>
<P>
   Although not one of the so-called four major strike issues,
wages in the new contract were still considered by union leaders to
be critically important in getting Machinists a contract they could
approve.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson said the initial wage proposal made by the company
Friday was inadequate. ``It was far from where we need to be,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   The average Boeing Machinist earns about $44,000 a year, not
counting benefits or overtime.
</P>
<P>
   In an e-mail sent to Boeing managers Friday, Jerry Calhoun,
leader of the Boeing negotiating team, said the company's hourly
pay scale is one of the highest in the industry.
</P>
<P>
   The Post-Intelligencer obtained a copy of the e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the realities is that we have to judge our proposal
against the labor agreements at our competitors and in related
industries,'' wrote Calhoun, the company's vice president of
employee and union relations.
</P>
<P>
   He noted that AlliedSignal, Lockheed Martin and Northwest
Airlines this year negotiated new contracts with Machinists that
called for wage increases of around 3 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Asked how damaging a strike would be for Boeing, Condit said:
</P>
<P>
   ``No strike that I have ever seen is good for anybody, not the
company and not the employees. ...
</P>
<P>
   ``But if you don't reach an agreement, that's the situation you
face. Then it becomes an issue of how long (a strike). ... The
company is in good financial condition. The fact is, we are a much
better balanced company today. We have a lot of other business.''
</P>
<P>
   Since the last strike in 1995, Boeing has greatly expanded its
military and space business by acquiring McDonnell Douglas in 1997
and the aerospace business of Rockwell in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   But Boeing is supposed to deliver a record 620 airplanes this
year. A strike would certainly impede production efforts.
</P>
<P>
   Alan Mulally, president of Boeing Commercial Airplanes, was
asked by reporters Wednesday during the rollout ceremony at the
Everett plant for Boeing's new 767-400 if the company could
continue to build airplanes if the Machinists struck.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course you can't keep building airplanes when you don't
have the team that's here. ... ''
</P>
<P>
   Friday, Boeing's second-largest labor union that represents
about 25,000 engineers said it would support the Machinists if they
strike.
</P>
<P>
   Members of the Seattle Professional Engineering Employees
Association, or SPEEA, cannot walk off the job, but they can
decline management requests to perform Machinist' work, said
Charles Bofferding, executive director of SPEEA.
</P>
<P>
   It is generally assumed that Boeing, given its horrible
financial performance the past two years, cannot afford to have its
airplane production disrupted by a strike.
</P>
<P>
   That perception is wrong, according to several industry analysts
interviewed Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``The union has done its best to make it look like they are in
the catbird's seat and Boeing is behind the eight-ball,'' said Paul
Nisbet, analyst with JSA Research. ``Quite the contrary.''
</P>
<P>
   He said Boeing could defer lost earnings until next year and
easily make up for undelivered planes, since the company only
expects to deliver 480 planes in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you are in a build-down mode as Boeing is, it is very
easy after a strike to make up for delinquent deliveries.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-28-99 0108EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
