<DOCNO> NYT19990828.0037 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-28 01:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2581 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r f BC-RANCH-DEVELOP-LADN     08-28 0677
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RANCH-DEVELOP-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEWHALL LAND TO OVERSEE CITY RANCH DEVELOPMENT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY CHARLES F. BOSTWICK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- The Newhall Land and Farming Company, which
created Valencia and is planning to build 21,000 more homes on the
Ventura County line, announced it will help develop Kaufman and
Broad's massive City Ranch master-planned development.
</P>
<P>
   Through a joint venture with a Kaufman and Broad subsidiary,
Newhall Land acquired a 50.1 percent interest in the 1,900-acre
parcel in west Palmdale and will act as the master developer, with
day-to-day responsibility to build 4,200 houses, 300 apartment
units and 260,000 square feet of commercial space.
</P>
<P>
   ``This project allows us to diversify our income and asset base
into a nearby, complementary and strengthening housing market, and
establishes a model that could be used in other markets with other
builders, as well,'' said Newhall Land Chairman Thomas L. Lee in
the announcement Friday.
</P>
<P>
   A Newhall Land spokeswoman said construction of streets, sewers,
water lines and other infrastructure will probably begin early next
year on the acreage in the Ana Verde Valley, where cattle now
graze. The company expects to begin selling lots to builders in
late 2000.
</P>
<P>
   As it did in Valencia, Newhall Land will install the
infrastructure and grade the housing pads, then sell lots to
developers who will actually build the homes.
</P>
<P>
   The company expects the last of the lots to be sold within eight
years, if present real estate market trends continue.
</P>
<P>
   Newhall Land officials say the Palmdale development will be
complementary, not competitive, with their Valencia projects
because it will offer homes aimed at first-time and first move-up
home buyers who are priced out of closer-in communities, such as
Valencia.
</P>
<P>
   New home prices average about $153,000 in Palmdale, compared
with $302,000 in Santa Clarita.
</P>
<P>
   City Ranch home prices have not been set, but Newhall Land
spokeswoman Marlee Lauffer said they will be competitive with other
new homes in the Antelope Valley.
</P>
<P>
   Palmdale Mayor Jim Ledford said Newhall Land's interest in the
Antelope Valley is an indication of the growing strength of the
local housing market, and he expects the company to do a good job
of developing City Ranch, one of several large master-planned
communities proposed in the late 1980s in the Antelope Valley but
the only one now moving forward.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Newhall Land has done an exceptional job in the
Valencia area,'' Ledford said. ``They build real value into the
community.''
</P>
<P>
   City Ranch also will help boost the value of existing homes by
providing new-home prices to which existing homes can be compared
and by drawing in out-of-town buyers, the mayor said.
</P>
<P>
   Approved in 1993 after much debate on the development's impact
on roads and city finances, City Ranch will cover what has been
mostly farm and cattle land in an area south of Elizabeth Lake Road
and about a mile west of Tierra Subida Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   City Ranch will comprise approximately 5,000 homes, neighborhood
shopping centers, schools, a lake, parks, riding and hiking trails,
and a public golf course.
</P>
<P>
   Newhall Land's venture does not include some parts of the City
Ranch development, including a 200-home subdivision under
construction by Kaufman and Broad adjacent to Elizabeth Lake Road
near 25th Street West.
</P>
<P>
   Newhall Land's portion will include approximately 4,200
single-family homes, 300 apartment units and 260,000 square feet of
store space.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement comes as Newhall Land is engaged in a legal
battle over its Newhall Ranch mini-city, planned on a 12,000-acre
tract along the Santa Clara River just east of the Ventura County
line and west of Valencia.
</P>
<P>
   Newhall Ranch won approval by the Los Angeles County Board of
Supervisors in April, but Ventura County filed suit seeking joint
approval authority over the project and a declaration that its
environmental impact report is inadequate.
</P>
<P>
   X X X &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
