<HEADER>
A2588 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-FBC-KICKOFFWEEKEND-TE     08-28 0722
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-KICKOFFWEEKEND-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GAMES FIT THE CLASSIC NAME TO START 1999 SEASON
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By Wendell Barnhouse 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   These are, for once, games deserving Classic with a capital
``C.''
</P>
<P>
   By tomorrow evening, the winners of the Pigskin and Kickoff
classics will be aglow with the hopes that this season could be
special. Rarely has a college football season started off with such
a double-barreled bang.
</P>
<P>
   It kicks off with two ``preseason'' games of national
significance. Today, No. 4 Arizona is at No. 3 Penn State in the
Pigskin Classic. Tomorrow, No. 9 Ohio State plays No. 12 Miami
(Fla.) in the Kickoff Classic in East Rutherford, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   Also on tap today is North Carolina State at No. 17 Texas in the
Black Coaches Association Football Classic, and Kansas at No. 18
Notre Dame in the Eddie Robinson Classic. Louisiana Tech, which
replaced Auburn, plays at No. 1 Florida State in a game set up by
ESPN and which airs on ESPN2.
</P>
<P>
   Today's Arizona-Penn State game is only the second time a
preseason game has matched top five teams.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes you might play a patsy in one of these games, but
that's not the case in these two games,'' Ohio State coach John
Cooper said. ``It should be a pretty interesting weekend.''
</P>
<P>
   The Kickoff Classic has been played since 1983; the Pigskin
Classic since 1990. ``Preseason'' games are exempt from the NCAA
limit of 11 regular-season games and are designed as showcase games
to start the season. Historically, though, the games have had
little impact.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 25 Kickoff and Pigskin classics, two winners have gone on
to win national championships _ Florida State in 1993 and Nebraska
in 1994 from the Kickoff. Colorado won a share of the '90 title
after tying Tennessee in the Pigskin. Nebraska (1994) is the only
team to finish undefeated after playing in a preseason game, and
just five others have finished with one loss.
</P>
<P>
   Today's Arizona-Penn State game matches two teams that are bona
fide national championship contenders. The Wildcats are coming off
the best season (12-1) in school history and return 15 starters.
The Nittany Lions were 9-3 last season and have perhaps the
nation's best defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, we're a talented team,'' Penn State middle
linebacker Brandon Short said. ``And we'll see how good we are
right off the bat.`
</P>
<P>
   Arizona coach Dick Tomey, whose team plays at TCU on Sunday
night, Sept. 5, sought the trip to Penn State for today's game to
challenge his team for the upcoming season. The Wildcats might be
thinking ``national title,'' but they're not talking about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think there's any way any team in America can talk
about being national champions,'' said Arizona senior Keith Smith,
who shares the team's two-quarterback system with junior Ortege
Jenkins. ``There are so many big games to be played every week.
Shoot, we've got Penn State to start with right off the bat.''
</P>
<P>
   Ohio State and Miami are probably a notch below Arizona and Penn
State. The Buckeyes have major holes to fill at quarterback and
linebacker a season after finishing 11-1. The Hurricanes, favored
to win the Big East Conference, are still recovering from the
effects of NCAA-mandated scholarship limitations.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can really measure your program when you challenge the
team and play somebody good instead of playing a team you're going
to beat 55-0 where the starters will be sitting down after the
first or second quarter,'' said Miami coach Butch Davis, who is
31-15 in four seasons. ``The Kickoff Classic adds a lot to the
program, it's national exposure and it's already helped our
recruiting.''
</P>
<P>
   Noting that Miami also has games with Penn State (Sept. 18) and
Florida State (Oct. 9), Davis joked that ``they're trying to get
the coach fired.'' Ohio State also has a challenging schedule, with
UCLA visiting on Sept. 11 and Big Ten Conference games at Penn
State and Michigan.
</P>
<P>
   This weekend's losers, though, won't give up hope of a national
title.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're going to lose, you better lose early,'' said Cooper,
whose team lost late, to Michigan State the first weekend in
November, last season and was painted out of the national
championship picture. ``Then you better win the rest of your games
then hope that you get some help from some other teams.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
