<HEADLINE>
MCIVER BEATS ODDS TO PLAY FOR COWBOYS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JEFF CAPLAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WICHITA FALLS, Texas _ Everett McIver shouldn't even be in the
NFL. Anyone else and his alma mater, Elizabeth City State
University, would have done what it does best: send him out into
the world as a hard-working teacher, not a professional football
player.
</P>
<P>
   Odds, however, have always been outmatched against the 6-foot-5,
330-pound sixth-year pro. Like when he went undrafted, soon to be
followed by being signed and cut by the Chargers, signed and cut by
the Cowboys, and then signed a third time to the Jets' practice
squad, all in an eight-month period.
</P>
<P>
   He experienced tragedy when his 3-month-old daughter, Morquisha,
died during heart surgery in an attempt to reverse a sudden
irregular heartbeat.
</P>
<P>
   Last season McIver was stabbed in the neck with a pair of
scissors during training camp, then suffered torn ligaments in both
knees on separate occasions.
</P>
<P>
   But McIver has overcome those injuries.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's not too much out there that can deter me,'' said
McIver, who explained that his drive to succeed is fueled by his
daughter's death. ``She went into heart surgery and didn't make it
out again. My heart, my focus, my career right now is her. She
didn't know what was going on, of course, but if she can do that, I
can overcome anything out here.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been hard work getting here,'' McIver said Tuesday, the
day after returning to practice for the first time since undergoing
major knee surgery Nov. 25. ``I'm not going to leave that easy.''
</P>
<P>
   He came to Dallas after playing two seasons in Miami. McIver has
found a home at right guard and is regarded as a potential
cornerstone on the offensive line.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would say that potentially, and that's a dangerous word many
times, that he is a player of that caliber,'' offensive line coach
Hudson Houck said. ``I am very excited about his future.''
</P>
<P>
   McIver is expected to see his first exhibition action tomorrow
at home against the Denver Broncos. It's unlikely he will play the
entire first half. But it will mark the first time he's played in a
game since Nov. 22 against Seattle when he tore ligaments in his
left knee.
</P>
<P>
   In typical McIver pile-on-the-odds fashion, the ACL injury
occurred during his anticipated return to the lineup following torn
ligaments in his right knee in Week 5. That injury kept him out six
weeks and interrupted a fast start in which he had begun to emerge
as a dominant presence. The injuries limited him to six starts.
However, McIver quickly won over coach Chan Gailey and Houck with
his powerful run-blocking ability and his agility as a pass
blocker.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he was just getting comfortable when he got hurt,''
Houck said. ``I think he has only touched the tip of the iceberg.''
</P>
<P>
   McIver said he is far from 100 percent, but that his knees feel
well enough to play. He said he will start in the Sept. 12 season
opener at Washington with ``expectations of playing the entire
game.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He has looked pretty good,'' Gailey said. ``I've been
impressed with how he's moved and hit.''
</P>
<P>
   McIver is expected to be a major part of a retooled offensive
line that dropped left guard Nate Newton and added Mark Stepnoski
at center and moved second-year player Flozell Adams from guard to
tackle.
</P>
<P>
   Rookie tackle Solomon Page has been forced to play guard during
McIver's absence. Gailey said Page will remain there as a backup.
</P>
<P>
   Left guard Larry Allen and right tackle Erik Williams are the
other remaining regulars in their usual positions. McIver's return
upgrades the unit to full strength. Two more preseason games,
against AFC playoff teams Denver and Jacksonville, plus two more
practices, will provide time to meld before heading into game-week
preparation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any time you lose time on the field it hurts,'' McIver said.
``It bothers me because I want to get a feel for the guys next to
me. My timing is off, but I don't feel like I'm way off. I'm just
happy to be where I'm at.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
