<HEADLINE>
STARS CAP SEASON TICKET SALES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE HEIKA 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING _ Stars fans will have to battle harder than ever to get
tickets this season as the defending Stanley Cup champions have
capped season ticket sales for the first time in franchise history
and have raised ticket prices at almost every level.
</P>
<P>
   Stars season tickets have reached 14,500, and the Stars have
started a waiting list for season ticket purchases. Individual game
tickets _ now the only way to buy tickets for a Stars game this
season _ go on sale tomorrow for home games in September
(preseason) and October.
</P>
<P>
   Individual game tickets are available at $42, $32 and $20 levels
_ up from $32.50, $22.50 and $14 last season. Ticket prices for
season-ticket renewals were raised 8 to 12 percent and ticket
prices for new season tickets were raised 20 to 30 percent, said
Jeff Cogen, vice president of marketing and promotion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Have we had some complaints? Sure,'' Cogen said. ``But for the
most part, season ticket holders were not offended, and new season
ticket buyers were lining up.''
</P>
<P>
   The Stars had the third-highest payroll in the NHL last season
at $40 million, and owner Tom Hicks said the franchise did not make
money, despite playing host to 12 home playoff dates. Raising
ticket prices with the heavy demand was expected, Cogen said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We put a lot of thought into every change,'' Cogen said. ``But
there are some issues of supply and demand.''
</P>
<P>
   The Stars sold out all but three of their 53 home dates last
season and expect to sell out every home game this season. With a
capacity of 17,001, the Stars will make available for sale 2,501
individual seats per home game. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
