<SLUG> BC-BKN-MAVERICKS-NOTES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NELSON CAUTIOUS ON FORWARD PROGRESS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DWAIN PRICE 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ As expected, the Mavericks signed free-agent forwards
Gary Trent and Cedric Ceballos yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   Trent signed a one-year, $2 million contract with an option for
a second year that _ because of the NBA's salary cap rules _ could
pay him more than $2.2 million during the 2000-2001 season.
Ceballos signed a two-year contract for $8.2 million.
</P>
<P>
   Now that the Mavericks have made their big off-season moves, one
question comes into play: Has this team been improved for the
1999-2000 season?
</P>
<P>
   Asked for his thoughts, Mavericks coach/general manager Don
Nelson said: ``I ain't saying nothing. You got me last year, you
ain't getting me this year. You can be dumb, but you can only be
dumb one time.''
</P>
<P>
   Nelson was referring to his bold comments before last season
when he predicted that the Mavericks were good enough to make the
playoffs, or be in the race during the final week of the season.
</P>
<P>
   The Mavericks did win eight of their final 14 games last season.
The only problem is they won only 11 of their opening 36 games.
</P>
<P>
   ``Actually, they played about like how I'd hope they would play
at the end of the year,'' Nelson said. ``I was hoping we'd play
that way all year.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's better than not having it happen at all. But it was
still too late for us to make any noise.''
</P>
<P>
   Trent was busy house-hunting in North Dallas yesterday and
didn't stick around to explain how this deal made financial sense
for him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am very excited to be back with the Mavericks,'' were
Trent's words on a Mavericks press release. ``I had a taste of
success last season and I want to continue to have success.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully we can get a jump-start on things and make a good
run this year. Anytime you are part of success it sticks in your
mind.''
</P>
<P>
   Mark Termini, Trent's agent,, said the 6-foot-8 forward turned
down several offers from other teams to remain with the Mavericks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can say the entire situation that Gary started in Dallas
last season outweighed other situations that were presented to
us,'' Termini said. ``There's a lot of value put to how you're
being used, and the known factors that exist in a situation where
you're enjoying personal success, and where you see room and
potential for team success.
</P>
<P>
   ``That cannot be discounted, and that weighed heavily in the
decision to reject other situations in order to return to the
Mavericks. But there were a number of elements, and all the
elements that Dallas presented resulted in him making that decision
to return here.''
</P>
<P>
   Forward Samaki Walker's decision to leave is another matter.
Walker, who signed a free-agent contract Wednesday with San Antonio
Spurs, is the only lottery pick in the last seven drafts to leave
his team without that team getting something in return.
</P>
<P>
   The last lottery pick to do so was Shaquille O'Neal _ Orlando's
top pick in 1992 who bolted to the Los Angeles Lakers in 1996. The
Mavericks drafted Walker ninth in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would all hoped that would happen, but you can't predict
the future,'' Don Nelson said. ``I don't want you to make a big
issue out of that. That will take care of itself once the time
comes. Nobody's worried about that.'' ANSTEY ALMOST FREE
</P>
<P>
   Don Nelson said he will not offer Chris Anstey a contract
extension before this season.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, he will let the 7-footer play out his third season and
become a free agent next summer.
</P>
<P>
   Anstey, the 18th pick of the 1997 draft, averaged just 2.8
points and 2.3 rebounds last season while shooting a team-low 29
percent from the field. He averaged 5.9 points and 3.8 rebounds
while shooting 39.8 percent from the floor as a rookie. GREEN
UPDATE
</P>
<P>
   Don Nelson contacted A.C. Green's agent, Mark Fleisher,
yesterday to inform him of the team's interest in signing the
free-agent forward.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're a little light in depth upfront, and it'll be nice to
have another bigger player, a veteran,'' Nelson said. ``It looks
like \RGreen's\S got some other offers that he's going to take, but
we just let him know we still love him, and if it doesn't work out
that he should call us.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
