<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-FASSERO-TEX </SLUG>
 
FASSERO OBTAINED FOR MINOR-LEAGUER AS STARTER OPTION (For use by
NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHNNY PAUL 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TORONTO _ The Rangers, hoping to catch lightning in a bottle for
their left-handed-starved pitching rotation, acquired left-hander
Jeff Fassero from the Seattle Mariners yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   They parted with a minor-league player who will be identified in
October. The Rangers accepted responsibility for the remaining
$997,238 of the struggling pitcher's $4.75 million contract this
season.
</P>
<P>
   Fassero, 36, went 4-14 with a 7.38 earned-run average in 30
appearances (24 starts) for the Mariners this season and entered
last night's game leading all American League pitchers in runs
(123) and home runs (34) allowed.
</P>
<P>
   Fassero also shares the league lead in losses with Detroit's
Brian Moehler and ranked among the worst 10 in hits allowed (188)
and walks issued (73).
</P>
<P>
   Fassero will begin his stint with the Rangers in their bullpen,
with an opportunity to join the rotation.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's one of the reasons for this move,'' manager Johnny
Oates said.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers wanted a left-handed starter for their potential
postseason rotation because possible opponents New York, Cleveland,
Toronto and Oakland have a number of quality left-handed hitters in
their lineups. Left-handed batters have hit only .252 (32-for-127)
against Fassero.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's had a lot of success against left-handers this year,''
Oates said. ``That's the reason we got him. A change of scenery
sometimes does a veteran guy good. I know it's been a rough year
for him.''
</P>
<P>
   The origin of Fassero's abysmal season might be traced to minor
surgery to remove bone chips from his left elbow after the 1998
season.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's healthy, but I think it took something out of him,''
Seattle manager Lou Piniella said, ``and it might be a year before
his arm comes back entirely. As a starter, we went with him as long
as we possibly could. I felt we gave him every opportunity. We were
hoping he would turn his fortunes around because he's a good guy
and he works hard.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers made room for Fassero on their 40-man roster by
transferring left-hander Eric Gunderson (torn labrum/rotator cuff,
left shoulder) from the 15-day to 60-day disabled list. The Rangers
probably will option left-hander Corey Lee to Triple-A Oklahoma
before this afternoon's game to make room for Fassero on the 25-man
roster.
</P>
<P>
   Fassero, who can become a free agent after this season, provides
the Rangers a left-handed long reliever and an option to
right-hander Mike Morgan for the rotation. Morgan has not pitched
more than five innings in any of his past five starts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've talked to Mike,'' Oates said. ``Mike knows what's going
on. We'll make our decisions after the Detroit series based on
need.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers claimed Fassero on waivers Wednesday and completed
the trade after reaching an agreement on the minor-league player
involved yesterday morning.
</P>
<P>
   ``This gives us some versatility,'' Melvin said of obtaining
Fassero. ``He's got experience. He knows the league. He knows the
hitters.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-28-99 0136EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
