<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-DIAMONDBACKS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOTEL BOUNCES BACK AS METS DOWN DIAMONDBACKS
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By JUDY BATTISTA   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ The seesaw was due to be up for Octavio Dotel, to
bounce the rookie pitcher up high after a troubled start. By Bobby
Valentine's theory, a young pitcher who throws adeptly in one game
is likely to be awful in the next. Emotion and adrenaline combine
with the physical and mental toll that a sterling outing can exact
on those too inexperienced to know how to cope, and Dotel's recent
history proved Valentine's premise.
</P>
<P>
   After taking a no-hitter into the seventh inning two starts ago,
Dotel was knocked around for eight hits and four runs in five
innings in his most recent start. If he had been at the bottom of
the seesaw then, his knees scraping in the dirt, this was _ for the
Mets _ a fortuitous night for his rebound. Dotel, making just his
11th major league start, sprung up and held the Arizona
Diamondbacks, the top team in the National League West, to just
four hits in eight innings en route to a 6-3 victory. The victory
in the first game of a six-game road trip keeps the Mets 1 1/2
games out of first place in the National League East behind the
Braves, who beat St. Louis Friday night, 2-1.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's physical,'' Valentine said of Dotel's struggles
after good starts. ``When you start out guys like that and they
have an emotional game, I think it's tough to recover for the next
start.''
</P>
<P>
   Dotel's hangover from the near-miss no-hitter lasted for just
one game. The Mets had been 1-5 against Arizona this season, but
Dotel _ who could lose his spot in the starting rotation when
either Rick Reed or Bobby Jones comes off the disabled list _ was
making his first career start against the Diamondbacks. He
effectively mixed speeds with a curveball, dazzling Arizona with a
sizzling fastball that was clocked as high as 93 mph. In the first
five innings, only one runner _ the first of the game, Tony Womack
_ got to third base and only one other, Andy Fox in the third, got
to second.
</P>
<P>
   Dotel did not give up a run until the sixth inning, and by then
the Mets had already given him a four-run lead and his fastball had
not failed him. On his 102nd pitch, which he used to strike out Fox
in the eighth, Dotel threw 90 mph. He retired the side in that
inning, and as it ended on his 110th _ and final _ pitch, he
pounded the grass in glee. He had thrown 76 strikes and just 34
balls, had walked one and struck out six.
</P>
<P>
   Valentine will not discuss what he will do with his rotation
when Reed and Jones are healthy, and Dotel's inexperience surely
hurts his chances of pitching in the final month of the season. But
the victory _ which Armando Benitez finished after Billy Taylor
failed to retire any of the three batters he faced in the ninth _
improved Dotel's record to 5-1.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets' offense gave Dotel all the support he needed early in
the game. Arizona starter Omar Daal, who had won his last three
decisions and had already won two this season, against the Mets,
was touched quickly when Rickey Henderson led off the game with a
double to left field and Edgardo Alfonzo, who would finish 3 for 4
with a walk, batted him in with a single.
</P>
<P>
   In the second inning, with one out, Shawon Dunston singled and
went to third on Benny Agbayani's double, then scored when Rey
Ordonez grounded out. In the sixth inning, the Diamondbacks
intentionally walked Agbayani to load the bases and Ordonez hit a
two-run single to short left center field in the sixth inning,
Daal's last, to give the Mets a 4-0 lead. Ordonez's three runs
batted in tied a career high. After Arizona got a run back in its
half of the sixth, the Mets added runs in the seventh and the
ninth.
</P>
<P>
   But by that time, Dotel could afford to watch Benitez work while
Dotel bounced against the dugout railing and wondered which way the
seesaw would swing for him next time _ or whether he would still be
perched on it at all.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
