<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOSA SILENT AS DODGERS WIN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ For the Dodgers, the good thing about hosting the
dangerous Sammy Sosa is that he comes attached to pitcher Steve
Trachsel every fifth day.
</P>
<P>
   Sosa's assault on Mark McGwire's home run record stalled Friday
night during a 9-0 rout of the Chicago Cubs in front of 44,230 at
Dodger Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   But there was no stopping the slide of Trachsel, who was
hammered again in his sad run to become baseball's first 20-game
loser since Oakland's Brian Kingman 22 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   While every Sosa at-bat brought cheers and a procession of
flashbulbs from the fans, the most impressive part of the night was
the Dodgers offense, which battered Trachsel (4-16) for seven
earned runs and a season-high 11 hits.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers strung together five consecutive base hits during a
four-run fifth inning that put the game away.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps because it has been missing most of the season, the
offense overshadowed an impressive performance by Dodgers
right-hander Ismael Valdes (9-11), who went the distance for his
first victory since July 16 at Anaheim.
</P>
<P>
   Valdes deserved more attention, but he was pitching against the
last-place Cubs, who are 5-21 in August.
</P>
<P>
   Not even Sosa's 53 homers, which put him eight games ahead of
last year's pace when he hit 66, could pull this team out of its
funk.
</P>
<P>
   In the first inning, Sosa struck out on a 3-2 fastball up around
his eyes.
</P>
<P>
   He tapped to short on the first pitch in the fourth inning and
grounded out in the sixth.
</P>
<P>
   And with Mark Grace aboard with no outs in the ninth, Valdes got
Sosa to ground into a double play.
</P>
<P>
   Valdes, who has battled blisters, a bruised pitching hand and
lower back pain this season, allowed the Cubs just seven hits and
did not walk a batter.
</P>
<P>
   Chicago leadoff hitter Lance Johnson was the only Cub to figure
out Valdes, getting three hits.
</P>
<P>
   He was the only runner to reach third all night, after doubling
with one out in the second and advancing on a fly ball by second
baseman Chad Meyers.
</P>
<P>
   Valdes, who needed just 106 pitches for his second complete game
and first shutout of the season, sailed after Johnson's double.
</P>
<P>
   He retired 12 of the next 13 batters and benefited from two
Dodgers double plays that ended the eighth and ninth.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers got to Trachsel in the second inning when third
baseman Adrian Beltre hit an opposite-field two-run homer into the
lower right-field stands. It was his 15th of the season.
</P>
<P>
   In the fourth, Eric Young opened with a double and Mark
Grudzielanek, Gary Sheffield, Raul Mondesi and Todd Hollandsworth
followed with singles.
</P>
<P>
   Trachsel stayed in the game but lasted just four batters into
the sixth when the Dodgers scored two more.
</P>
<P>
   Despite a winless streak that included four losses and three
no-decisions, Valdes has been one of the Dodgers' most consistent
pitchers.
</P>
<P>
   He followed his victory over the Angels by getting battered
against Colorado. But since then, Valdes has allowed just 16 runs
in his last 491/3 innings with an ERA of 2.92.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
