<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VECSEY-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIG UNIT MAKING BID TO RECLAIM HIS HALL SPACE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LAURA VECSEY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ The Mariners can pat themselves on the back. Ten of
Randy Johnson's record-setting 301 strikeouts in his first 29
starts this season were notched during the Big Unit's 6-0 shutout
back on July 20.
</P>
<P>
   Safeco Field was Johnson's personal strikeout palace for one
night.
</P>
<P>
   So, in a way, Seattle can still consider itself a bit player in
Johnson's still-rising career.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, Johnson set a record for posting the quickest 300
K's in one season. He nudged past Pedro Martinez's 1997 mark of 300
strikeouts in 31 games. He also joined Nolan Ryan and Sandy Koufax
as the only three pitchers to reach the 300 mark in three different
seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Here's guessing that being in the company of such Hall of Famers
is giving Johnson a sense of baseball immortality. Though it's a
tall order, maybe now he'll bear down on Ryan's 1979 single-season
record of 383 strikeouts. After all, Johnson knows about tall.
</P>
<P>
   Although it took years for Johnson to harness his power and
channel his ornery edge into the psyche of a dominating pitcher, he
is putting an undeniably impressive finish to his career _ although
he would probably glower at the mere inference that his time is
anywhere close to being over.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe Johnson can keep this up for the length of his $53 million
contract with the Diamondbacks. (He'll be hard-pressed to match
Ryan's seven 300-strikeout seasons, but you never know.)
</P>
<P>
   Goodness knows the Big Unit can motivate himself like none
other, and certainly just thinking back to how the Mariners refused
to believe big money was a worthwhile investment for a 6-foot-10
power pitcher coming off back surgery is plenty of fuel for
Johnson's fire.
</P>
<P>
   At 35 years old, Johnson has told people this is his best season
ever. Who would doubt him?
</P>
<P>
   If he had gotten run support during those five overpowering
outings that the D-backs lost, Johnson would be one win away from
that coveted 20-win plateau.
</P>
<P>
   While Johnson's 1995 Cy Young season with the Mariners was the
undeniable emergence of the game's premier left-hand power pitcher,
Johnson has since found his career and his reputation in the
hamper.
</P>
<P>
   There was back surgery in '96 that limited his action. In '97,
he was again impressive, but the Mariners were driven out of the
American League Division Series by the Orioles _ with Johnson
losing twice to Mike Mussina.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, Johnson let his contract status and the Mariners'
fumbling diminish his concentration. He pitched good enough in
Seattle only on the occasions when he was attempting to bolster his
trade value so that the Mariners could move him.
</P>
<P>
   And while he won games and struck out 300 after moving to
Houston, the Astros, too, lost in the first round of the playoffs,
and Johnson turned out to be a rent-a-pitcher who cost the Astros
three very good players in Freddy Garcia, John Halama and Carlos
Guillen.
</P>
<P>
   Then, after signing with the D-backs, Johnson suffered the
accusations that he was merely taking the money and the convenience
of playing near his family's new Scottsdale palace.
</P>
<P>
   Now, though, Johnson is cruising. The D-backs are winning. This
is his best season ever, so he says.
</P>
<P>
   In Seattle, it is difficult to not pay attention to what Johnson
is up to. Even as the success of Halama and Garcia help erase doubt
that good deals can be made for rare, one-of-a-kind players,
Johnson's ability and accomplishments can not be overlooked.
</P>
<P>
   However, Johnson's declaration that this is his best season ever
will only become fact if his Diamondbacks make it not only to the
postseason, but to the National League Championship Series or,
better yet, the World Series.
</P>
<P>
   It is his time to provide further proof of his dominance.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, when Johnson's accomplishments cause Mariner fans pain
instead of good-natured curiosity, he can take pride in
substantiating his true market value, not to mention staking his
claim for some sort of baseball immortality.
</P>
<P>
   WHAT SPORTS IS REALLY ABOUT: Those Nike ads featuring Tiger
Woods bouncing a golf ball off the face of a club for 27 seconds
before belting it a la Ken Griffey Jr. into the distance have
caused more than just a buzz among TV watchers.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, Titleist has filed a lawsuit charging false
advertising and contract interference. Nike admits the young Master
Woods uses Titleist golf balls in the Nike ad, although a new Nike
deal estimated at $80 million could have Tiger solely under
contract to Nike. Indeed, as Nike promised, Woods is changing the
world.
</P>
<P>
   ALL-CENTURY TEAM REVISION: OK, thanks for all the input and
friendly reprisals. Willie Mays was a ludicrous omission, and, yes,
Pete Rose was really a third baseman, but he was listed as an
outfielder. I'm still guessing The Banned One will be on the field
at the World Series, now that commissioner Bud Selig has said Rose
will be invited to attend if he is voted onto the All-Century Team.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-28-99 0214EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
