<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-28 02:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2618 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s BC-BBA-MARINERS-NOTEBOOK     08-28 0653
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-NOTEBOOK-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VANCOUVER PRODUCT MAKES BIG-LEAGUE DEBUT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TYLER KEPNER  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Robert Ramsay pitched Friday night in the third major
league game he ever attended.
</P>
<P>
   Growing up in Vancouver, Wash., the Mariners left-hander made
just two trips to the Kingdome, once when he was 14 and again in
1995, when the Minnesota Twins invited him to watch them play in
Seattle after drafting him.
</P>
<P>
   Friday at Yankee Stadium, the 25-year-old left-hander worked
22/3 innings in relief of starter Gil Meche in the Mariners' 8-0
loss to New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``Words can't describe it,'' said Ramsay, after finding his
locker Friday afternoon. ``I've been looking forward to this moment
ever since I was a kid, and to have my first big-league experience
in Yankee Stadium, it's like a dream.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm trying to stay down-to-earth, trying to not get caught up
in the moment too much. I've got a job to do.''
</P>
<P>
   For now, that job is middle to long relief, although Ramsay was
a starter at Class AAA Tacoma, where he went 4-1 with a 1.08 earned
run average after coming over from Boston for Butch Huskey on July
26. With Class AAA Pawtucket in the Red Sox's system, he was 6-6,
5.35.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really can't explain it,'' Ramsay said. ``I don't know if it
was the change of scenery or if going from the East Coast to the
West Coast motivated me a little bit. But my last few starts in
Pawtucket were pretty good, and maybe it just carried over into
Tacoma.''
</P>
<P>
   Ramsay, a Washington State alumnus, entered Frida's game in the
fourth inning, with runners at first and third and the Mariners
trailing 4-0. He got ahead of Paul O'Neill, 1-and-2, but his next
two curveballs missed high and a low fastball bounced just past the
plate for ball four, loading the bases.
</P>
<P>
   With Bernie Williams batting, Ramsay uncorked a wild pitch with
the curveball, bringing in a run. After an intentional walk, he
recovered to strike out Tino Martinez, throwing two sharp curves.
Chili Davis singled in two runs, but Ramsay recovered to pitch a
scoreless fifth and sixth.
</P>
<P>
   ``My release point on (the curveball) early wasn't where I
wanted it to be at all,'' Ramsay said. ``I got ahead on the
hitters; I just couldn't put them away. ... (But) it was a dream of
mine. You live for that, coming in in a tough situation. I wish I
could have had better results in that first inning, but hopefully
I'll learn from it.''
</P>
<P>
   ROSTER SHUFFLE: The Mariners considered promoting outfielder
Charles Gipson instead of Ramsay, because with Jay Buhner suspended
until Sunday, the club has just three reserve position players. But
with a doubleheader on Monday in Chicago, manager Lou Piniella went
with another pitcher.
</P>
<P>
   Frankie Rodriguez is the most likely candidate for a spot start
against the White Sox, although Piniella said there is a ``good
possibility'' Ramsay will get a chance to start in September.
</P>
<P>
   EXTRA BASES: Second baseman David Bell was back in the lineup
after leaving Wednesday's game with a migraine headache. Bell took
medication Wednesday and did not travel with the team. The pain
stayed with him overnight, but by Thursday morning it was gone. ...
With Yankees left-hander Andy Pettitte pitching Sunday, Piniella
said Bell will make his season debut at first base that day, with
Rafael Bournigal starting at second. Bell will be the seventh
Mariner to play first since David Segui was traded July 28. Catcher
Dan Wilson became the sixth when he played the eighth inning there
Friday for the first time in his career. ... Yankees bench coach
Don Zimmer was admitted to Columbia Presbyterian Medical Center on
Thursday night for neck pain and evaluation of a minor cardiac
abnormality. The Yankees said Zimmer, 68, has been treated for the
heart condition in the past. ... Saturday is Piniella's 56th
birthday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
