<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARINERS CAN'T GET OVER THEIR `HICCUPS' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TYLER KEPNER  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It's not that the Mariners have been inconsistent
this season. More than anything, they've been streaky, and whether
they're on a winning or losing streak has come down to the same
thing.
</P>
<P>
   When they play also-rans, they win. When they play contenders,
they don't. It's why the Mariners have been at .500, or a few games
below, for almost two months. And it's why a series like the one
that began in the Bronx Friday night tells so much about where the
team stands.
</P>
<P>
   As manager Lou Piniella put it, referring to games with
contenders, ``We can't afford any hiccups.''
</P>
<P>
   In that case, maybe the Mariners should hold their breath, chug
some water or breathe into a bag. They lost 8-0 to Roger Clemens
and the New York Yankees Friday, and hiccupped all the while.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners trailed by seven runs after four innings as the
defending World Series champions took advantage of a pair of
rookies who had never visited Yankee Stadium before. Gil Meche gave
up six runs in 31/3 innings, dropping his record to 4-4, and
newcomer Robert Ramsay allowed a walk and a wild pitch before
recording his first major league out.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every pitch I threw I thought I'd like to have back,'' said
Meche. ``I didn't feel like I made any good, key pitches out
there.''
</P>
<P>
   His counterpart encountered trouble of his own early on. In the
first inning, the M's had runners at second and third with one out.
Alex Rodriguez swung at a low Clemens breaking ball, burying it
into the ground. Brian Hunter dashed from third, but Clemens rushed
in, barehanded the ball and made a tumbling flip to catcher Joe
Girardi, who was waiting when Hunter slid head-first into home.
</P>
<P>
   ``He made the perfect play,'' Hunter said. ``If he doesn't make
the perfect play, it's 1-0 in the first.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, after a walk that loaded the bases, Clemens got Tom
Lampkin to fly out, ending the inning. The M's never got another
runner to third against the five-time Cy Young Award winner, who
limited Seattle to three singles over the next seven innings.
Clemens (12-6) worked eight innings in all, striking out nine and
walking three.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to get him early, and we didn't,'' said hitting coach
Jesse Barfield. ``That first inning told the story of the ballgame.
We had him on the ropes and didn't capitalize. When you get chances
against a guy like Roger Clemens, you can't let him off the
ropes.''
</P>
<P>
   But lately, the Mariners have been making a habit of that.
They've won three of their last seven games, but have hit .210 and
averaged 2.86 runs per game in that span. Several players have
struggled _ David Bell is 4-for-26, Ryan Jackson 0-for-13 and Dan
Wilson 1-for-15. Russ Davis has one extra-base hit since Aug. 9.
Raul Ibanez is batting .156 in the second half.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens pitched well Friday, Rodriguez said. But the shortstop
was careful not to give too much praise.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have our own problems to deal with right now,'' Rodriguez
said. ``We're not swinging the bats particularly well. You have to
give (Clemens) some credit, but at the same time, we're not
swinging the bats well.''
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez singled and stole second in the fourth, but was thrown
out at third by Bernie Williams while trying to tag up on a fly to
center. The Mariners' other double play was equally crushing: in
the sixth, Ken Griffey Jr. swung at a high pitch for strike three
on a hit-and-run that ended with Bell getting thrown out at second.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees got to Meche early, scoring once in the first on a
ground out and twice in the second on a Derek Jeter single. Meche
worked a scoreless third, but three of the first four Yankees got
hits in the fourth, knocking him out.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the bullpen, I kind of realized I was throwing my fastball
up,'' Meche said. ``I couldn't throw it down in the zone. I figured
once I got out on the mound, I'd make adjustments. From the get-go,
I couldn't do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither could Ramsay, at least at first. Ramsay, who allowed two
inherited runners to score and also allowed a run of his own before
throwing two scoreless innings, is the 14th rookie pitcher the M's
have used this season. He is Seattle's 27th pitcher overall,
extending a franchise record.
</P>
<P>
   The loss dropped the Mariners to 8-19 against the American
League's first-place teams, and put them a game under .500 overall.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
