<SLUG> BC-ABORTION-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARIZONA JUDGE GIVES NOD TO LATE-TERM ABORTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By KARINA BLAND AND CHRIS MOESER  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ A judge on Friday affirmed his decision to allow a
14-year-old girl to have a controversial late-term abortion,
sources said.
</P>
<P>
   The girl is to go to Kansas for the abortion unless an appeal by
the Arizona Attorney General's Office is successful, sources close
to the case said. No date has been set, but child welfare officials
say they won't take her until all appeals have been resolved.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Jane Hull first said there was little the state could do to
stop the abortion but changed direction Thursday and asked that the
girl's competency be re-evaluated.
</P>
<P>
   Friday's decision had the Governor's Office working late into
the night planning a second appeal, sources said. The appeal was
expected to be filed late Friday or early Saturday, most likely in
Maricopa County Superior Court.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney General Janet Napolitano, a Democrat, initially refused
to file an appeal, sources said. But she changed her mind after
Hull threatened to hire former Attorney General Grant Woods and
former attorney general candidate Tom McGovern, both Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   Napolitano declined to comment Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   The Governor's Office on Thursday askedJudge William Sargeant of
Maricopa County Superior Court to reconsider his ruling after
receiving an onslaught of criticism about the decision that would
allow the girl to leave the state to have an abortion, sources
said.
</P>
<P>
   With every day that passes, it becomes less likely that the girl
will get the abortion she wants. Fewer doctors will perform the
procedure the later she goes into her pregnancy.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the political stalling has forced this young woman to
continue a pregnancy against her will, I think we've all lost, this
girl more than anyone else,'' said Bruce Miller, director of
Arizona Right to Choose, an abortion rights group.
</P>
<P>
   Already, at 24 weeks along, the girl faces a difficult and
taxing procedure.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney John Jakubczyk, who represents Arizona Right to Life,
the state's largest anti-abortion group, said public outcry will be
deafening if the girl is allowed to have the late-term abortion
because the fetus, if born now, has a 50 percent chance of
survival.
</P>
<P>
   ``Talk about backlash,'' he said. ``The people will go nuts.''
</P>
<P>
   Generally, abortions are not performed in Arizona much after the
first trimester because state law prohibits the procedure once the
fetus is considered ``viable,'' although what constitutes
``viability'' varies from state to state and doctor to doctor.
</P>
<P>
   But experts agree that a 24-week-old fetus would have roughly a
50 percent chance of survival if born prematurely, though it likely
would have some sort of disability at this stage. A fetus born
before 24 weeks has no chance of survival.
</P>
<P>
   Each week, a fetus' chance of survival improves. For example,
babies born at 26 weeks stand a 95 percent chance of survival in
the nursery at Good Samaritan Regional Medical Center, said a
Phoenix doctor who asked not to be identified.
</P>
<P>
   State officials have the option of sending the girl to either
California or Kansas, the only states that routinely perform
late-term abortions.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas law is the most liberal, allowing abortions well into the
third trimester under certain circumstances, including danger to
the life of the mother and possible impairment to physical and/or
mental health.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are all very dreadful procedures,'' Dr. Carolyn Gerster,
chairwoman of Arizona Right to Life, said of late-term abortions.
``It's really infanticide. It's a living, moving baby right up
until that moment.''
</P>
<P>
   The procedure, Gerster said, could cause long-term physical
problems for the girl, including sterility or complications in
later pregnancies. Gerster also worries the already troubled girl
might face deep depression, drug or alcohol abuse or suicide.
</P>
<P>
   But Beth Weber, director of medical services for Planned Parent
hood of Central and Northern Arizona, said that abortion is no more
risky than childbirth and that the girl faces the same emotional
aftermath if she is forced to give birth to a child she does not
want.
</P>
<P>
   ``This young lady has become a pawn, and we seemed to have
forgotten her,'' Weber said.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors said the girl likely would be given pain medication and
a general anesthesia during the abortion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just because you're a minor child doesn't mean you're not
covered under the Constitution and the Bill of Rights,'' said Dr.
Brian Finkel of Metro Phoenix Women's Center and an abortion-rights
advocate.
</P>
<P>
   The girl's attorney called him last week, asking if he could
perform the procedure.
</P>
<P>
   Finkel does not perform late-term abortions because of what he
calls the ``criminal activities'' of abortion foes. Hospitals are
hesitant to allow doctors to use their facilities for such
procedures for fear they will be picketed, their staff stalked or
their buildings bombed, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have personally seen to it that her life is irreparably
damaged, whether she gets the abortion or not,'' Finkel said.
</P>
<P>
   Even if he had access to the needed facility, he would not
perform an abortion at 24 weeks because the fetus has a solid
chance of survival.
</P>
<P>
   The safest way to abort a fetus in the later stages of pregnancy
is to open the cervix and remove the amniotic fluid, placenta and
fetus. The fetus is removed in sections.
</P>
<P>
   The fetus also can be allowed to die without the medical
intervention it would need to survive.
</P>
<P>
   In another procedure, doctors begin delivery, insert an
instrument into the base of the baby's head and suction out the
brain.
</P>
<P>
   There are doctors in Arizona who will perform late-term
abortions but only because of complications that threaten the
mother's life or if the baby is not expected to survive anyway. In
those cases, that doctor's decision must be approved by three other
board-certified physicians.
</P>
<P>
   Also, in Arizona, any doctor performing an abortion after 20
weeks must submit a report to the state Department of Health
Services explaining the circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Rusty Bowers, R-Mesa, has asked state Senate staffers to
explore the possibility of the state's appointing a guardian to
represent the interests of the 14-year-old's unborn baby.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would like to see if a guardian can be appointed for the
baby and push it right to the Supreme Court for an expedited
appeal,'' Bowers said.
</P>
<P>
   Miller called the idea of assigning a guardian to the fetus
``ridiculous.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Arizona Legislature doesn't care about babies after they
are born, only before they are born,'' Miller said. ``It's just
another idea to force this girl into continuing a pregnancy that
she wishes to terminate.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
