<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-WRITETHRU-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOSA SILENT AS DODGERS WIN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ He was three outs from his first shutout in 14
months, but the cheers were not for Ismael Valdes.
</P>
<P>
   Sammy Sosa commands the stage in every at-bat these days,
especially in Friday's otherwise meaningless 9-0 Dodgers rout of
the Chicago Cubs in front of 44,230 at Dodger Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Valdes didn't mind that the roar of the crowd was not for him.
It was better to win for the first time since July 16. When Valdes
got Sosa to ground into a double play, he knew he had shut down one
of his baseball gods.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody loves Sammy,'' Valdes said. ``How often do you face
someone that can hit a home run every time up? What he has done for
baseball the past two years is incredible.''
</P>
<P>
   What Sosa has done this season is hit a major-league-leading 53
home runs, a pace that puts him eight games ahead of last year's 66
and keeps him head-to-head with Mark McGwire as the premier power
hitters in the game.
</P>
<P>
   Although Sosa says he has been humbled by his accomplishments,
he admitted he wasn't surprised to have the crowd on his side at
the end of Friday's game.
</P>
<P>
   ``It happens everywhere I go now,'' Sosa said. ``When you do
this over a period of time, the fans respond. They clap for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Little did the crowd realize that Sosa would go 0 for 4 against
Valdes, who last pitched a shutout on June 27, 1998, at Pittsburgh.
</P>
<P>
   His performance also was obscured by the Dodgers offense, which
strung together five consecutive base hits against the Cubs'
beleaguered right-hander, Steve Trachsel (4-16), in a four-run
fifth inning that put the game away.
</P>
<P>
   Valdes deserved more attention, but he was pitching against the
last-place Cubs, who are 5-21 in August.
</P>
<P>
   During that time, no one has looked worse than Trachsel, who was
hammered again in his sad run to become the majors' first 20-game
loser since Oakland's Brian Kingman 19 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers got to Trachsel in the second inning when third
baseman Adrian Beltre hit an opposite-field, two-run homer into the
lower right field. It was his 15th of the season.
</P>
<P>
   In the fourth, Eric Young opened with a double, the second of
his three hits, and Mark Grudzielanek, Gary Sheffield, Raul Mondesi
and Todd Hollandsworth followed with singles.
</P>
<P>
   Trachsel stayed in the game but lasted just four batters into
the sixth when the Dodgers scored two more runs.
</P>
<P>
   And how often do the home fans cheer the visiting star?
</P>
<P>
   ``We couldn't do anything against Valdes,'' Sosa said. ``He was
inside and outside all night. I tip my cap.''
</P>
<P>
   In the first inning, Sosa struck out on a 3-2 fastball up around
his eyes.
</P>
<P>
   He tapped to short on the first pitch in the fourth and grounded
out in the sixth.
</P>
<P>
   Valdes, who has battled blisters, a bruised pitching hand and
lower back pain this season, allowed the Cubs just seven hits and
did not walk a batter.
</P>
<P>
   Despite a winless streak that included four losses and three
no-decisions, Valdes has been one of the Dodgers' most consistent
pitchers.
</P>
<P>
   In his last six starts, Valdes has allowed just 16 runs in his
last 491/3 innings, with an ERA of 2.92.
</P>
<P>
   ``With Sammy, you want to keep the ball up and I did that,''
Valdes said. ``I got some runs and I made my pitches. I feel very
good right now.''
</P>
</TEXT>
