<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-28 09:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2646 &Cx1f; tib-z
u k BC-DOWD-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      08-28 0764
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOWD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
  
 COMMENTARY: THE McCAIN MUTINY  
(jt) 
 By MAUREEN DOWD    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN JOSE, Calif. _ I went up to my hotel room after watching
John McCain make a speech here to 300 high-tech corporate types. I
flipped on the TV.
</P>
<P>
   There was Regis Philbin, quizzing some guy on ``Who Wants to Be
a Millionaire?'' I had never seen the game show before and the
questions seemed pretty silly _ multiple choices on which famous
Washington building has the address 1600 Pennsylvania Avenue, and
what sort of work was done by the father of Loretta Lynn, who sang
``Coal Miner's Daughter.''
</P>
<P>
   The contestant sailed up to $32,000 before he got bumped off
with this one: ``What was the shared occupation of the group of men
referred to as the Keating Five?'' Possible answers were
``Musicians,'' ``Bankers,'' ``Senators'' and ``Writers.''
</P>
<P>
   He chose ``Bankers.'' A surprised Regis told him that until the
answer ``senators'' flashed on his screen, he had assumed the
Keating Five were bankers, too.
</P>
<P>
   Too bad McCain, who has been here campaigning for the California
primary, was on a plane back to Arizona. He would have loved to
know that on a game show that is generating more excitement than
the presidential race, no one remembered the most painful episode
of his life.
</P>
<P>
   McCain has said being locked in solitary and savagely beaten as
a POW in Hanoi for five and a half years was a less scalding
experience than the fracas over his role meeting with regulators on
behalf of Charles H. Keating Jr., a savings and loan operator later
convicted of fraud. The Senate Ethics Committee faulted the Arizona
senator only for bad judgment, but he felt ashamed that he had
embarrassed his father and grandfather.
</P>
<P>
   The 2000 race could have been written by Arthur Miller. Never
have so many men wanted to run, not only to win the Oval Office,
but to prove they are worthy to larger-than-life dads and
granddads.
</P>
<P>
   Explaining over coffee why he is never afraid to mutiny against
party leaders, McCain says he doesn't seek their approval: ``My
father's and grandfather's approving of me is my lasting
ambition.''
</P>
<P>
   The same could be said for George W. Bush, who belatedly began
trying to leapfrog into the footsteps of his father, the president,
and his grandfather, Prescott, the craggy senator from Connecticut.
And for Al Gore, whose father was the principled senator from
Tennessee. And for Steve Forbes, whose flamboyant father, Malcolm,
made the publishing fortune that Steve has spent prodigally on his
vanity campaign _ even putting the family island in Fiji up for
sale.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Faith of My Fathers,'' his new memoir, McCain recounts his
searing experiences as a Navy flier, and tells the saga of his
father and his grandfather, both Navy admirals. ``It was a family
tradition: boozing on shore, heroics in uniform,'' he writes. ``My
father, like his father, was famous for both.'' As commander of the
Pacific Fleet, his dad had to approve the decision to bomb Hanoi in
1972 while his son was in prison there.
</P>
<P>
   McCain, who turns 63 Sunday, still feels he let his family down
and rejects the appellation of hero, because after being horribly
beaten he gave in and read a statement prepared by his captors that
he was ``a black criminal.''
</P>
<P>
   Before it happened, he made a couple of ``feeble'' suicide
attempts, looping his shirt through the shutter of his cell and
wrapping it around his neck. ``I'm not sure I could have gone all
the way through with it,'' he says. ``I knew I was going to break.
I didn't want to do that. I did and I failed.''
</P>
<P>
   He watched the presidential campaigns of John Glenn and Bob
Kerrey and Bob Dole collapse, and he knows that a heroic life story
is not a ticket to the White House. In fact, it can make the
candidate seem smaller than his own biography.
</P>
<P>
   Americans crave heroes. But they would still rather hear what a
candidate plans for their future than relive his past. Voters want
a president with character, but in the wake of Bill Clinton, they
define character differently. More weight on values shown in public
life and less on values shown _ or not shown _ in private life.
</P>
<P>
   That's fine with McCain, who says he has made lots of mistakes.
He did not criticize W. about his waffly answers on cocaine, only
observing that if he had not been in the Hanoi Hilton, he might
also have had a swell time in the Age of Aquarius.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was nobody selling cocaine in prison,'' he says, with a
rueful laugh. ``When I left to go to Vietnam, Haight-Ashbury was
still just a street corner.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
