<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-SEASON-800(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEISMAN HOPEFULS AND OTHER FACES IN THE NEWS 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By JOE DRAPE    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Not Him Again
</P>
<P>
   If, as in politics, Heisman Trophy campaigns were helped by name
recognition, Ricky Williams might be this year's front-runner to
win college football's most coveted award. Like last year's winner
of the same name, he is a talented running back from the Lone Star
State. But this Williams carries the ball at Texas Tech _ not Texas
_ and sports neither braided hair nor the its-his-to-lose portfolio
that helped the Longhorns' Williams to win last year.
</P>
<P>
   In short, this year's Heisman contest is wide open. Here are the
contenders and their odds of taking home the trophy. &QL; 
 &QL; 
1. PETER WARRICK, senior receiver, Florida State
</P>
<P>
   He passed on the National Football League draft, when he
certainly would have been a top 10 pick, to return to Tallahassee
and take another run at the national title. In 1998, the acrobatic
Warrick averaged 20.2 yards a catch and 102.7 yards a game _
numbers that should be even better with the return to action of
quarterback Chris Weinke, who missed the final two and a half games
of last season due to injury. Warrick will also be aided by weekly
national exposure because his team is the nation's top-ranked team.
Still, only three full-time wide receivers have pulled down the
trophy: Johnny Rodgers, Tim Brown and Desmond Howard.
</P>
<P>
   Odds: 2-1
</P>
<P>
   2. RON DAYNE, senior, running back, Wisconsin
</P>
<P>
   This 5-foot-10-inch, 285-pound pile driver also passed on the
NFL. Dayne needs 1,717 yards to break the Division I-A career
rushing record (6,279 yards) that Ricky Williams of Texas set last
year. Dayne was the most valuable player of the Rose Bowl after
rolling for 246 yards in Wisconsin's 38-31 victory against UCLA.
For Dayne to crush the Heisman competition, he needs to grind out
big numbers in back-to-back games against Michigan and at Ohio
State, and the Badgers need a repeat of 1998's 11-1 season.
</P>
<P>
   Odds: 2-1
</P>
<P>
   3. RICKY WILLIAMS, junior, running back, Texas Tech
</P>
<P>
   At 5-9, 195 pounds, he starts, stops and explodes a la Barry
Sanders, which means exhilarating footage for the highlight reel.
Williams was the nation's fourth-leading rusher in 1998 with 1,667
yards and might just flirt with 2,000 this time around.
Unfortunately, he needs publicity and the Red Raiders are famous
only in West Texas despite being in bowl games in five of the last
six years.
</P>
<P>
   Odds: 5-2
</P>
<P>
   4. DREW BREES, junior, quarterback, Purdue
</P>
<P>
   Like Tim Couch last year, Brees will be the quarterback with
eye-popping statistics because of the Boilermakers' airborne
offense. He completed 63.4 percent of his throws last year and set
Big Ten records for yardage (3,983), touchdowns (39), attempts
(569) and completions (361). Big home games against Notre Dame,
Penn State and Wisconsin will showcase his talents, but he may be a
year away from the Heisman.
</P>
<P>
   Odds: 4-1
</P>
<P>
   5. LaVAR ARRINGTON, junior, linebacker, Penn State
</P>
<P>
   He is more likely to become the first choice in this spring's
NFL draft than to win the Heisman from the defensive side of the
ball _ Charles Woodson had to return kicks and catch passes to woo
Heisman voters in 1997. But it helps that the nation's premier
defensive player (65 tackles, 17 for a loss) is the cornerstone of
``Linebacker U.'' in a year the Nittany Lions play a national title
caliber schedule that includes Arizona, Miami, Ohio State and
Michigan.
</P>
<P>
   Odds: 10-1
</P>
<P>
   THE FIELD (Odds: 15-1)
</P>
<P>
   JOE HAMILTON, senior, quarterback, Georgia Tech: An explosive
offensive maestro, he has 5,800 career passing yards, 36
touchdowns, more than 1,000 rushing yards. If the Yellow Jackets
upset Florida State in their second game, he vaults into the top
three.
</P>
<P>
   TRUNG CANIDATE, senior, running back, Arizona: He has the right
name for a clever publicist, plays on a national title contender
and rushed for 1,321 yards in an injury-plagued '98.
</P>
<P>
   TEE MARTIN, senior, quarterback and JAMAL LEWIS, junior, running
back, Tennessee: Martin led the Vols to a 13-0 record and the
national title last season. If he does it again? One handicap is
that he might share votes with Lewis, who is back from a midseason
knee injury. Lewis gained 1,364 yards as a freshman.
</P>
<P>
   CHRIS REDMAN, senior, quarterback, Louisville: He threw for
4,378 yards and 30 touchdowns in '98 to lead the Cardinals to a 7-5
record. Best thing to happen to Louisville football since Johnny
Unitas.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Locked Longhorns
</P>
<P>
   One has a famous name, the other has a catchy one. Both are
talented quarterbacks vying for the starter's job at Texas. For
now, Major Applewhite has held off the freshman Chris Simms, whose
father, Phil, led the Giants to a Super Bowl victory.
</P>
<P>
   However, the 6-foot-5-inch, 218-pound Simms has lived up to his
high school honors and earned the backup position. At Ramapo High
School in Franklin Lakes, N.J., Simms threw for 7,055 yards and 63
touchdowns. In three scrimmages at Texas, he completed 19 of 40
passes for 403 yards and a touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chris is certainly one of the best I've ever been around as a
true freshman,'' said the Longhorns' offensive coordinator, Greg
Davis.
</P>
<P>
   But Applewhite is the top returning passer in the Big 12 and was
sixth in the nation as a redshirt freshman last season when he
threw for 18 touchdowns. He has also proved more efficient than
Simms this summer, completing 18 of 23 passes for 264 yards and 3
touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   The pair have become friends despite what may develop into a
week-to-week, year-to-year quarterback controversy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Major is the starter; that is not a question,'' Longhorns
Coach Mack Brown said. ``Chris, as the second-team quarterback,
will play some. He will get a series now and then, but right know
I'd hate to throw him into the fire if Major got hurt.''
</P>
<P>
   Coaches' Carousel
</P>
<P>
   The moving vans were busy this summer shuttling head coaches _
30 in all _ to fresh sidelines and new teams.
</P>
<P>
   Several of the names are familiar: Rick Neuheisel bolted
Colorado for Washington; Gary Barnett left Northwestern to replace
him in Boulder; and the former Southern Cal and Los Angeles Rams
coach, John Robinson, landed at Nevada-Las Vegas, where the Rebels
didn't win a game last year.
</P>
<P>
   But two of the most famous names in coaching are resurfacing in
the troubled football state of South Carolina: Lou Holtz at South
Carolina and Tommy (Bobby's boy) Bowden at Clemson.
</P>
<P>
   If Notre Dame is the Vatican of college football, Holtz, the
former Irish coach, left the CBS broadcast booth for the gridiron
version of a corner ministry _ one that unfortunately has zero
toehold in the brutal Southeastern Conference. The Gamecocks were
1-10 last season, have won more than eight games only once in their
history and own but a single bowl game victory.
</P>
<P>
   Holtz brought in his son Skip from UConn as his offensive
coordinator and probably as his eventual successor. But what Holtz
says his new team needs immediately is to believe in the gospel
according to Lou.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is probably the most difficult situation I've ever taken
over due to the schedule that we will play and the lack of football
tradition at South Carolina,'' Holtz said. ``Every place has
something you can build on, no matter how successful it may already
be. We must be convinced we can win. I am convinced we can win.''
</P>
<P>
   The younger Bowden, on the other hand, sounds downright morose
about the prospects of the 3-8 team that he inherited just weeks
after orchestrating the Bourbon Street Miracle of leading Tulane to
a 12-0 season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got the fewest returning starters in the ACC,'' Bowden
said. ``We have an offense that was second to last in every single
category except one, the most important one _ we were last in
turnovers. We lost all five offensive line starters. We probably
have the smallest line in Division I-A. We don't have a
difference-maker at tailback, and we lost six guys off our defense
to the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have five home games and play seven bowl teams _ we ought
to be playing seven home games and five bowl teams. We're the
opposite. Then we don't have a kicker that has kicked in a game.
I'm afraid they're going to wet their drawers, kicking in a game in
front of 85,000 fans. So there's tremendous question marks in every
area.''
</P>
<P>
   To make it worse _ or better, deciding on what side of the
Bowden dinner table you're sitting on _ Tommy's Tigers face
Atlantic Coast Conference rival Bobby's Seminoles on Oct. 23.
</P>
<P>
   If the preseason polls are correct, Florida State will be 7-0
and the older Bowden will be after a career win No. 300 _ a
milestone reached by only six others, including Joe Paterno last
year.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only number I want is 304,'' said Bowden, referring to a
number that would reflect a perfect 1999 season and give him his
second national title. ``I'm just glad Tommy is down there having
to face my old friend Lou and not me.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-28-99 1025EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
