<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-28 10:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2658 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-FBC-FLORIDA-COLLEGES-     08-28 0887
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-FLORIDA-COLLEGES-ART-800(3TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOME GROWN AND READY FOR THE PICKING 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(jt) 
 By JOE DRAPE    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   He can barely bend his legs, and he shuffles them along as if
they were stilts. His neck hurts, too. He holds it with one hand,
rubs a grimace off his face with the other. It's 98 degrees, he's
just been hit for the first time at practice this summer, and Peter
Warrick isn't feeling well.
</P>
<P>
   He plops into a couch in the lobby of Florida State's Moore
Athletic Center in Tallahassee _ a room ringed with plaques and
retired jerseys. Fred Biletnikoff. Charlie Ward. All the Seminole
greats. As he sits down, the back of his head bangs against the
concrete wall. Crack!
</P>
<P>
   Meet your Heisman Trophy front-runner. The usually nimble wide
receiver laughs it off, but he can't hide a wince. Then he tries to
explain a day last January when National Football League
executives, agents, even some of his coaches, thought he must have
fallen and hit his head. He had called a news conference in this
building to announce . . . what?
</P>
<P>
   That he was entering the NFL draft? He was a certain top-10 pick
and would most likely be the first receiver selected. He had a
2-year-old daughter, A'Lyric, who was growing out of her clothes
more and more frequently. He was fourth in career receptions at
Florida State and his jersey was destined for the wall of fame.
</P>
<P>
   But Warrick had no idea what he would actually announce. He
paced a hallway. He said a prayer with the strength coach, Dave Van
Halanger. Ten minutes late, he waltzed into a packed room and was
asked, ``Well?''
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't know what I would do until it came out of my mouth,''
Warrick recalled. ``Once I said I was going to stay, a peace came
over me.''
</P>
<P>
   Warrick, who is a native of Bradenton, Fla., added: ``This state
is my home. This place is my family. I don't know what it is, but
Florida State has a powerful pull on me. I figured I could delay
sitting in a hotel room in Cleveland or Detroit for another year.''
</P>
<P>
   It was an impulsive decision that means the Seminoles begin this
year's college football season as the prohibitive favorite to win
the national title. Its logic, however, means much more and is
reflected beneath the ``hometown'' category on the rosters for the
Sunshine State's three football powers.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 272 players listed on this season's programs for Florida
State, Florida and Miami, 175 _ nearly two-thirds _ come from
within the state. They grew up near its South beaches, on its Gulf
Coast, in the central horse country or along the Panhandle. They
played football under palm trees or near swamps. They are talented,
and they win.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's see, you got the weather, the outdoors to run in,''
reasoned Florida State Coach Bobby Bowden, who is an Alabaman.
``This state's so dadgum big, so there's a lot of boys. They have
passion for football and mostly, I don't think they like to leave
their mamas. I don't know how scientific you need to get. We got a
lot of good football players in this state and we try to keep them
here.''
</P>
<P>
   If Pennsylvania forged its football tradition from the sons of
coal miners and steelworkers, and Texas honors its history beneath
the Friday night lights of high school football, Floridians
celebrate their football blessings each week when the national
college rankings are released.
</P>
<P>
   By keeping Florida's ample talent at home in the nation's
fourth-most populous state, the Seminoles, Gators and Hurricanes
have combined to win 273 football games in the 1990s. Each school
has won a national title during that period. Year in and year out,
the teams play rigorous schedules that insure they will have a say
in who plays for the national championship.
</P>
<P>
   This year is no different. The Seminoles are the consensus pick
to reach the national title game in the Sugar Bowl on Jan. 4. To do
so, they will have to beat the hated Gators on the road and the
Hurricanes at home.
</P>
<P>
   Florida also is thinking about New Orleans and the title game.
The Gators get Tennessee, the defending national champion, at home
in the third week of the season and might very well be unbeaten
when they face Florida State on the last weekend of the regular
season.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, there is Miami. In the 1980s the Hurricanes captured
three national titles, but they spent the last three years on
probation for major violations that took place while Jimmy Johnson
and Dennis Erickson were coaching them. The sanctions cost the team
24 scholarships in 1996 and '97, but now that the Hurricanes are
back at full strength they are intent on recapturing their form.
They want to win the Big East Championship.
</P>
<P>
   If they don't make it to the Sugar Bowl, they want to handpick
the team that does. They have that opportunity Saturday in the
Kickoff Classic against Ohio State, on Sept. 18 against Penn State
and again on Oct. 9 against Florida State.
</P>
<P>
   When the road to a national championship winds annually through
Florida, it tends to make its coaches and home-grown players
alternately good, bad and ugly, but always downright cocky.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Florida State: A Certain Air Of Invincibility
</P>
<P>
   The Seminoles have won 10 or more games in 12 consecutive
seasons, have posted a 10-2 bowl record and have never finished the
season ranked lower than No. 4 in the Associated Press poll during
that span. But Florida State has brought only one national
championship back to Tallahassee, in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Bowden, Warrick _ the whole team had banked on winning their
second last year in the Fiesta Bowl against Tennessee. Even with
his team down by 23-9 with six minutes left and the backup
quarterback Marcus Outzen having a miserable night in just his
third career start, Bowden was certain his team was going to win.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's got to break open for us sooner or later,'' Bowden
remembered thinking. He explained, ``It's the way we believe around
here.''
</P>
<P>
   It never did break open, though, and, afterward in the locker
room, Warrick doubted for the first time all season that his
Florida State career was over. After catching one touchdown pass
and throwing another in a 23-12 victory over Florida in the last
game of the regular season, he was sure he was going to the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   ``I figured I had done everything there was to do here and that
I could leave a champion,'' Warrick said.
</P>
<P>
   He had caught 61 passes for 1,232 yards and averaged 20.2 yards
a catch and 102.7 yards a game in the regular season. But in the
Fiesta Bowl, he brought down just one pass for 7 yards and was
frustrated by Tennessee's double teams. Worse, he was upstaged by
the Volunteers' Peerless Price, who caught four passes for 199
yards, including one for a 79-yard touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   Warrick fiercely denies that being outplayed in the Fiesta Bowl
figured in his decision. ``If I hadn't caught a ball and we won,
I'd be the happiest guy in the locker room,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Nor, Warrick said, was he moved to stay to win the Heisman. In
the moments before his announcement, the Seminoles' Chris Weinke
was summoned to the hallway to calm his stressed-out receiver.
Weinke is 27, a former minor league baseball player and, until
sustaining a frightening neck injury in Florida State's 10th game,
the Seminoles' quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   ``He couldn't talk,'' Weinke said. ``He was panicked. He really
didn't know what he was going to do. I told him if he came back he
could win the Heisman and every other award. I told him to do what
was in his heart, but I promised this was going to be a special
year.''
</P>
<P>
   Warrick's eyes flickered. He didn't know it until he said it,
but Warrick now knows why he stayed: ``I've waited my whole life to
turn pro. I can be poor for another year if it means that I'll take
a national championship there with me.''
</P>
<P>
   There is an air of invincibility surrounding the Seminoles,
partly because of Warrick, partly because 14 starters from the
Fiesta Bowl return and mostly because of Weinke. The quarterback
was an inch from being paralyzed against Virginia. He underwent
surgery in November, spent two months trying to survive
debilitating headaches caused by leaking spinal fluid, then had to
hit the weight room to reclaim the 25 pounds he had lost.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought I was lucky to have a second chance when I came here
as a 24-year-old freshman,'' Weinke said. ``I can't believe I'm
blessed to have a third chance. Something really special is going
to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Bowden also believes this is a team like none of his others. He
looks at Weinke the leader, Warrick the playmaker, the best front
four in the nation and finally to his all-America kicker, Sebastian
Janikowski.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm almost too yellow to say it,'' Bowden said. ``But I think
this is the best team I've ever had.'
</P>
<P>
   Florida: Second Best, And Not Liking It
</P>
<P>
   Yes, his visor and his headphones are often hurled to the
ground. Yes, on the field his Gators run up the score. Yes, Florida
Coach Steve Spurrier likes to agitate. He tells it like it is _ the
more upset opposing coaches and fans get, the better. Spurrier's
needle is sharp and thrust often. A sampling:
</P>
<P>
   _ Last year, after the Gators won at Vanderbilt in front of a
half-filled stadium, Spurrier was asked if he was surprised at the
turnout. ``It's Vandy,'' he said. ``There must have been something
good on TV.''
</P>
<P>
   _ When Kentucky Coach Hal Mumme tried several onside kicks
during a 1997 Florida victory, Spurrier remarked, ``If I had a
defense like Hal Mumme has, I'd be trying them on every kickoff.''
</P>
<P>
   _ After his Gators handled their rival Tennessee in 1996 in
Knoxville, the coach dead-panned: ``They said it was going to be
real loud and I admit it was _ during pregame warm-ups.''
</P>
<P>
   But Spurrier's comments can be just as unforgiving when directed
at his own team. The Gators won 10 games last year, but lost the
two most important: to Tennessee and Florida State. Heading into
this season, the coach has let his team know that was unacceptable.
</P>
<P>
   Still, despite losing nine players on defense _ five of them
taken in the first three rounds of the NFL draft _ as well his
defensive coordinator, Spurrier is not worried.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look at the books,'' he said. ``I'm not worried. Look at the
last nine years and where Florida has been. With the exception of
Alabama in '92 and the chance that there could be a surprise team
to jump up this year, I expect the usual _ greatness.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Florida is one of only two teams _ Florida State is the
other _ to finish in the top 10 in each of the last eight seasons.
The Gators certainly are not rebuilding, but this is a season of
transition as the new defensive coordinator, Jon Hoke, replaces Bob
Stoops _ now the head coach at Oklahoma _ and Spurrier tries to put
some punch back into an offense that scored the fewest points of
any Gator team since 1992.
</P>
<P>
   ``The title of underdog shouldn't belong to us,'' defensive end
Derrick Chambers said. ``We are a great team that had a little
trouble last year. Tennessee got lucky. I am sure of our team
chemistry, and I know what we can do. We want to go into games and
prove through our playing that we are a great team. The only way to
get rid of the title `underdog' is to prove on the field that we
are great, and we are.''
</P>
<P>
   Spurrier has put a great deal of emphasis on camaraderie for
this year's team. Last spring, seven since-departed members of the
1998 defense were implicated in a scandal that revolved around
accepting improper inducements from an agent. To many, it explained
why some Florida players looked distracted and selfish.
</P>
<P>
   The coach? When asked what the difference was between this
year's defense and last year's star-studded bunch, Spurrier said,
``We don't have as many fancy cars being driven around this year.''
</P>
<P>
   The offense is in the hands of the senior quarterback Doug
Johnson, who finally escaped Spurrier's doghouse by remaining in
Gainesville over the summer to concentrate on football instead of
playing minor league baseball, as he had done in the past. Johnson
has started only 12 games in a Gator career that is notable more
for its low lights than its achievements. He has been suspended for
breaking curfew, missed the beginning of last season with a
shoulder injury and broke his left leg in last season's Orange
Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Worse than any tongue-lashing their coach could give them was
the torture the Gators had to endure last Jan. 4 when they watched
two teams that beat them, Tennessee and Florida State, play for the
title.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish they both could have lost, but in the end I pulled for
Florida State, because at least they were from Florida _ have to
keep it in the state,'' wide receiver Travis Taylor said. But
Taylor, sounding like his coach, promises never to do it again _
Florida plays host to both teams at home in The Swamp.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tee Martin has no idea what he is in for,'' Taylor said of the
Volunteers' quarterback. ``Eighty-five thousand fans screaming and
11 guys wanting and trying to rip your head off is not the
atmosphere I think he understands.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Miami: Steady Progress, Not Trash-Talking
</P>
<P>
   The Miami Hurricanes were the team of the 1980s. Three titles
were won under three different coaches: Howard Schnellenberger,
Johnson and Erickson. Vinny Testaverde won the Heisman Trophy in
1986. They added one more of each at the turn into the 1990s _ a
national championship in 1991 behind the Heisman quarterback Gino
Torretta.
</P>
<P>
   While the Hurricanes were compiling a 107-13 record from 1983 to
1992, they also developed an outlaw reputation enhanced by
on-field, helmet-off-in-your-face trash talking as well as
off-field player cameos on the police blotter. No one cried when
the Hurricanes were handed those sanctions _ except Coach Butch
Davis.
</P>
<P>
   When he returned to South Florida in 1995, the former Dallas
Cowboys defensive coordinator's mission was simply to tread water.
For the first three years, he not only had to contend with reduced
scholarships, but also with the raising of academic standards by
the university. The Hurricanes managed 8-3 and 9-3 records his
first two seasons, but in his third, 1997, Miami drowned with a 5-6
record because 34 freshmen were on the squad.
</P>
<P>
   When the Hurricanes rebounded to 9-3 last year _ including a
thrilling season-ending upset of UCLA that knocked the
then-undefeated Bruins out of the national title game _ the South
Florida message seemed to be that the Canes were back.
</P>
<P>
   Not so fast, Davis said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This isn't the fifth year of our rebuilding,'' he said. ``It's
more like our second. For my first three years, we were like a
junior college team. More players were graduating or going out
early than we could recruit.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though Miami is near its full scholarship base of 85 for
the first time in Davis' reign, the program's atrophy will show _
especially with an ambitious schedule in which Miami faces Ohio
State, Penn State and Florida State within its first five games.
</P>
<P>
   To replace fullback Nick Williams, Mondriel Fulcher was moved
from tight end and Wilbur Valdez was plucked from the linebacking
corps. The rest of the backfield also is brand new.
</P>
<P>
   The sophomore Kenny Kelly will play quarterback and the redshirt
junior James Jackson replaces the two-time 1,000-yard rusher
Edgerrin James. It is the voluble Jackson who best combines the
Hurricane aura of old with Davis' mandate that today's Canes be
about class and classes. He's itching to trash-talk a bit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm no punk, but if someone wants to lip at me he's going to
hear back from me,'' said Jackson, who averaged 6.6 yards a carry
last year. ``So far, people have just hit me and walked back to the
huddle. They better just keep doing that because they don't want to
motivate me any more than I already am. I'm telling you there are
some teams out there that need to start paying attention to us
because we're going to terrify them, just terrify them.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson, who was also recruited by Notre Dame, spent a year in
prep school at Fork Union Military Academy to prepare for college
courses. He will graduate in December with a degree in sociology.
It was during his year in Virginia that the Belle Glades native
decided that South Bend, or anywhere else besides his beloved home
state, was not where he wanted to run or study.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look,'' he said. ``I'm a Florida boy. My family's here. We got
three of the best football programs in the country. There are great
rivalries and we play in big games. I mean  &UR; big games &LR;  played on
national television. Why would I go anywhere else?''
</P>
<P>
   Why, indeed, when surf and sand, palm trees and swamps, are
pleasant enough diversions in January between bowl and national
title games? &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
