<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-TOP20-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`WE'RE NUMBER ONE!' WELL, MAYBE NOT 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By JOE DRAPE    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   No. 1
</P>
<P>
   Florida State
</P>
<P>
   Last season's record: 11-2
</P>
<P>
   Last season's final New York Times computer ranking: 3
</P>
<P>
   Chris Weinke is an unflappable 27-year-old quarterback and the
senior wide receiver Peter Warrick is the Heisman Trophy
front-runner. The All-American defensive tackle Corey Simon is one
of seven returning starters from the nation's top-ranked defense.
Bottom line: Weinke rehabilitated a neck injury for 10 months and
Warrick passed up the National Football League to try to win the
national title. The season-ending game against Florida is the main
obstacle to a national championship rematch with ...
</P>
<P>
   No. 2
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee
</P>
<P>
   13-0
</P>
<P>
   Final NYT ranking last season: 2
</P>
<P>
   Quarterback Tee Martin was not allowed to run the full offense
until late in the Volunteers' national championship season. Still,
the Vols averaged 398.8 yards of offense and Martin threw only 2
interceptions in his last 179 attempts. With the return of tailback
Jamal Lewis, who averaged 6.8 yards a carry over the first four
games before sustaining a knee injury, Martin will trigger a
yardage-gobbling machine. Bottom line: The Vols will beat Florida
in Gainesville on Sept. 18 for the first time since 1971, then
square off for the title with the Seminoles again, this time in the
Sugar Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   No. 3
</P>
<P>
   Nebraska
</P>
<P>
   9-4
</P>
<P>
   Final NYT ranking last season: 22
</P>
<P>
   Injuries spoiled Coach Frank Solich's debut last year: nine
starters missed a combined 45 games, and there were three different
starters at both quarterback and I-back. Now Nebraska returns 16
starters, and another 8 got seasoning replacing the wounded. If
quarterback Bobby Newcombe and I-back DeAngelo Evans stay healthy,
they will dominate the Saturday highlight reels. Bottom line:
Beware! Nebraska will avenge losses to Kansas State, Texas A&AMP;M and
Texas and could bring a perfect record into the Sugar Bowl should
Florida State or Tennessee falter.
</P>
<P>
   No. 4
</P>
<P>
   Michigan
</P>
<P>
   10-3
</P>
<P>
   Final NYT ranking last season: 10
</P>
<P>
   Left guard Steve Hutchinson (6 feet 5 inches, 296 pounds) leads
a talented offensive line that will blossom into the best in the
nation. Michigan rolled over the vaunted Penn State defense in a
27-0 victory and finished 10-1 after an 0-2 start. Tom Brady is a
replica of the mistake-free quarterback of the 1997 co-national
champions, Brian Griese. Bottom line: The Wolverines are not as
hyped as Penn State or as sexy as Ohio State, but they are the best
team in a deep Big Ten.
</P>
<P>
   No. 5
</P>
<P>
   Arizona
</P>
<P>
   12-1
</P>
<P>
   Final NYT ranking last season: 8
</P>
<P>
   Tailback Trung Canidate gained 1,220 yards. Quarterback Keith
Smith completed 69 percent of his passes for 1,732 yards. Both are
back, along with 14 other starters, from a team that averaged 35
points a game. Bottom line: The Wildcats are the best of the West
and, if they get past Penn State in the opener, may have undefeated
bona fides for the Bowl Coalition to compute come title time.
</P>
<P>
   No. 6
</P>
<P>
   Virginia Tech
</P>
<P>
   9-3
</P>
<P>
   Final NYT ranking last season: 19
</P>
<P>
   Led by defensive end Corey Moore, an All-America candidate, the
Hokies return the entire front seven from the nation's
seventh-stingiest defense. The redshirt freshman quarterback
Michael Vick is a super talent, and Coach Frank Beamer can bring
him along slowly because of the defense and the flawless special
teams: the Hokies blocked eight punts and punter Jimmy Kibble and
place-kicker Shayne Graham were All-Big East. Bottom line: They've
beaten their Big East rival Miami four straight times and get them
at home this year.
</P>
<P>
   No. 7
</P>
<P>
   Texas A&AMP;M
</P>
<P>
   11-3
</P>
<P>
   Final NYT ranking last season: 14
</P>
<P>
   Coach R.C. Slocum brings back 16 starters, including the
1,000-yard rusher Dante Hall and quarterback Randy McCown, who was
6-1 before breaking his collarbone. The Aggies must replace their
leading career tackler, Dat Nguyen, but their swarming scheme
should allow them to duplicate their No. 10 rank in scoring
defense. Bottom line: This is a gritty bunch that wins ugly. Still,
they must beat Nebraska twice, in Lincoln and in the Big 12
championship game.
</P>
<P>
   No. 8
</P>
<P>
   Florida
</P>
<P>
   10-2
</P>
<P>
   Final NYT ranking last season: 4 (tie)
</P>
<P>
   The senior Doug Johnson threw for 19 touchdowns; the junior
Jesse Palmer threw for 14. Who gets more snaps? It doesn't matter _
Air Spurrier (358 yards a game) will take flight. It must, because
the defense lost its coordinator, Bob Stoops (now head coach at
Oklahoma), as well as its front seven. Bottom line: Anywhere else
this would be a rebuilding year, but the Gators and Florida State
are the only teams to finish in the top 10 the last eight seasons.
</P>
<P>
   No. 9
</P>
<P>
   Penn State
</P>
<P>
   9-3
</P>
<P>
   Final NYT ranking last season: 11
</P>
<P>
   LaVar Arrington, the front-runner for the Butkus Award as the
nation's top linebacker, is the monster among nine returnees from a
defense that did not let any running back gain 100 yards. Defensive
end Courtney Brown, linebacker Brandon Short and cornerback David
Macklin join him as future first-round draft selections. The
offense is not as distinguished; the senior quarterback Kevin
Thompson threw six touchdown passes against eight interceptions.
Bottom line: The grueling schedule includes Arizona, Miami, Ohio
State and Michigan. Win them all and the Nittany Lions are title
bound, though that's asking a lot.
</P>
<P>
   No. 10
</P>
<P>
   Ohio State
</P>
<P>
   11-1
</P>
<P>
   Final NYT ranking last season: 2
</P>
<P>
   The Buckeyes lost eight starters to the pros, so expectations
are low. They do return a pair of All-America candidates on either
side of the ball: linebacker Na'il Diggs had six sacks for the
nation's second-best defense, and running back Michael Wiley gained
1,147 yards and averaged 6.3 yards a carry. Bottom line: If either
Austin Moherman or Steve Bellisari can effectively replace Joe
Germaine at quarterback, Ohio State can quietly pursue its first
national title since 1968.
</P>
<P>
   nn$taf-z &QL; 
u sxxnt22 nt26 nt06 nt11 nt33 &QL; 
usxx &QL; 
 &UR; BC-SLUG-2NDTAKE-NYT &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; UNDATED: since 1968. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   No. 11
</P>
<P>
   Miami
</P>
<P>
   9-3
</P>
<P>
   Final NYT ranking last season: 16
</P>
<P>
   Seventeen starters return from a team that kept previously
undefeated UCLA out of the 1998 title game. But it's two
replacements, Kenny Kelly at quarterback and James Jackson at
tailback, who will determine whether the Hurricanes can survive a
big-time schedule. Bottom line: Three of their first five games are
with Ohio State, Penn State and Florida State. The Hurricanes are
potential giant-killers.
</P>
<P>
   No. 12
</P>
<P>
   Georgia Tech
</P>
<P>
   10-2
</P>
<P>
   Final NYT ranking last season: 7
</P>
<P>
   The senior Joe Hamilton is the most exciting quarterback in the
nation. His quick feet and accurate arm (2,166 yards passing, 56
percent completions) led the Yellow Jackets to a 35.5-point scoring
average. Unfortunately, Tech's defense gave up 397.5 yards and 24.3
points a game. Bottom line: Hamilton's highlights will pop him into
the forefront among Heisman candidates. But the shaky defense will
make most games adventures and at least one of them _ against
Florida State _ a loss.
</P>
<P>
   No. 13
</P>
<P>
   Wisconsin
</P>
<P>
   11-1
</P>
<P>
   Final NYT ranking last season: 4 (tie)
</P>
<P>
   Running back Ron Dayne needs 1,717 yards to break the career
rushing record Ricky Williams of Texas set last year. He will
probably get them, along with the Heisman. Nine returning starters
from the nation's fourth-best defense will insure Badgers games go
something like this: Dayne 31, Opponents 10. Bottom line: They play
in this year's most competitive conference and must face Michigan
and Ohio State back to back to open the league season.
</P>
<P>
   No. 14
</P>
<P>
   UCLA
</P>
<P>
   10-2
</P>
<P>
   Final NYT ranking last season: 15
</P>
<P>
   Drew Bennett takes over for Cade McNown and will hand off to
DeShaun Foster and Jermaine Lewis, who managed to combine for 1,100
yards rushing in the Bruins' pass-happy offense. But the
All-America candidate Danny Farmer leads one of the nation's best
corps of receivers, and Bennett, sooner or later, will get the ball
to them. Bottom line: Seven starters return from the nation's
99th-ranked defense. Is that good or bad? UCLA will find out in its
second game of the season against Ohio State.
</P>
<P>
   No. 15
</P>
<P>
   Notre Dame
</P>
<P>
   9-3
</P>
<P>
   Final NYT ranking last season: 28
</P>
<P>
   Jarious Jackson finished 13th in the country in passing
efficiency and his 2,181 yards of total offense was the fourth-best
ever among Irish quarterbacks. The Syracuse offensive coordinator
Kevin Rogers takes over that job in South Bend. Both need to
perform: only center John Merandi and the All-America tight end
Jabari Holloway return on a rebuilt offensive line. Bottom line:
Games at Michigan in Week 2 and at Tennessee in Week 9 will
determine whether the Irish are back in Bowl Coalition form.
</P>
<P>
   No. 16
</P>
<P>
   Arkansas
</P>
<P>
   9-3
</P>
<P>
   Final NYT ranking last season: 30
</P>
<P>
   Quarterback Clint Stoerner threw for a school-record 2,629 yards
and 26 touchdowns, Chrys Chukwuma rushed for 870 yards and free
safety Kenoy Kennedy had 95 tackles. All are back and determined to
forget Stoerner's last-minute stumble and fumble that gave
Tennessee its perfect season. Bottom line: The Razorbacks have two
chances to redeem themselves against Tennessee _ at home on Nov. 13
and in the Southeastern Conference championship game.
</P>
<P>
   No. 17
</P>
<P>
   Georgia
</P>
<P>
   9-3
</P>
<P>
   Final NYT ranking last season: 21
</P>
<P>
   Last season Quincy Carter was the Southeastern Conference's
freshman of the year; now he is a Heisman contender. The
21-year-old former minor league baseball player threw for 2,484
yards and completed 61 percent of his passes. He also scrambled for
284 yards and 4 touchdowns. The Bulldogs' defense is thin, but
boasts the Butkus Award contender Orantes Grant. Bottom line:
Unfortunately, the talented Bulldogs need to beat Tennessee and
Florida to reach the SEC championship game. Not this year.
</P>
<P>
   No. 18
</P>
<P>
   Texas
</P>
<P>
   9-3
</P>
<P>
   Final NYT ranking last season: 12
</P>
<P>
   Ricky Williams is gone, but Major Applewhite is not. As a
red-shirt freshman last year, Applewhite reeled off 10 straight
games of 200-plus passing yards. He will often look for Kwame Cavil
(51 catches for 775 yards). Coach Mack Brown lured the nation's
best recruiting class to Austin; one freshman, linebacker Cory
Redding, may have an immediate impact. Bottom line: The Longhorns
will be entertaining on their way to becoming national title
contenders in 2001.
</P>
<P>
   No. 19
</P>
<P>
   Alabama
</P>
<P>
   7-5
</P>
<P>
   Final NYT ranking last season: 39
</P>
<P>
   The Crimson Tide will roll again out of the backfield, where
tailback Shaun Alexander will use his final year of eligibility
after graduating and deciding to pass up the NFL. Four of the five
linemen who helped him gain 1,178 yards in '98 return. Among the
eight returning starters on defense, tackle Cornelius Griffith is
an All-America candidate. Bottom line: The Tide will press Arkansas
for the SEC West crown.
</P>
<P>
   No. 20
</P>
<P>
   Kansas State
</P>
<P>
   11-2
</P>
<P>
   Final NYT ranking last season: 13
</P>
<P>
   The All-America linebacker Mark Simoneau and six other veterans
of the nation's third-best defense will make the Wildcats tough to
score on. But how will Kansas State replace the Heisman runner-up,
Michael Bishop, at quarterback and the school's career leading
rusher, Eric Hickson? Until a late collapse against Texas A&AMP;M, the
Wildcats were national title contenders. Aaron Lockett, a
sophomore, returns after a sizzling 44-catch, 928-yard debut. But
the offense will not match last year's 48-point scoring average.
Bottom line: They lose at Texas and at Nebraska and finish 9-2.
</P>
