<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-28 11:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2684 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-PERU-REVOLUTION-ART-2     08-28 1011
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PERU-REVOLUTION-ART-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FROM A SAVAGE WAR, PERU'S INDIANS SALVAGE HOPE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A locator map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(js) 
 By CLIFFORD KRAUSS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NUNHUAYCCO, Peru _ At the entrance to this village of
Quechua-speaking Indians high in the Andes, residents have built a
children's playground beside six concrete tombs for 40 people slain
by Shining Path rebels eight years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The sight chills the soul. But villagers say they want to show
their children that life goes on despite the horrors of a war that
is still winding down.
</P>
<P>
   Adobe bricks are stacked everywhere as militiamen who first
mobilized to fight the Maoist rebels rebuild the village house by
house. The women have organized to plant a communal garden and
prepare hearty stews of cabbage, carrots and onions for their
neighbors. And at the recently rebuilt school, the children sing a
new Quechua song that goes, ``Happily we are not going to see any
more terrorists and our people will progress.''
</P>
<P>
   Ayacucho province, a land of soaring Andean peaks, aromatic
eucalyptus forests, ancient Indian ruins and desperate poverty that
was long ignored by the government in Lima, was the cradle and
epicenter of the Shining Path uprising. But the social and
political changes the rebels tried to impose backfired. As the
villagers organized to drive them out, a different kind of
revolution took place.
</P>
<P>
   Women, who took the lead in protecting their sons from being
drafted by the rebels, are becoming more assertive. Villagers were
emboldened to demand services from the central government, and in
the process village governments are becoming more democratic. Once
isolated Indian villages are developing local banks and building
roads and bridges to become more fully integrated into the national
economy.
</P>
<P>
   Anthropologists and local leaders say the villagers' resistance
to Shining Path's violent tactics and bizarre ideas bred new
attitudes and behavior.
</P>
<P>
   ``The war had many cultural and sociological impacts, and many
were positive,'' said Jaime Urrutia Ceruti, an anthropologist who
has studied the aftermath of the war in Ayacucho. ``The peasants
who resisted Shining Path came out of the war with a new sense of
confidence. And while the primitive methods of production and lack
of investment remain big problems, people learned the benefits of
organizing.''
</P>
<P>
   The Shining Path rebellion was born in a university in the
provincial capital in 1980 and spread across scores of impoverished
villages, pitting peasants against peasants, before it began
petering out when the rebel leadership was arrested in 1992. A
total of 30,000 people died and 600,000 more were displaced
nationwide. More than half of the victims came from Ayacucho.
</P>
<P>
   A few hundred Shining Path rebels barely hang on in the
mountains and jungles and attack sporadically, but the Maoist
cultural revolution they tried to install here at gunpoint failed
to take root.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONALL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   In an attempt to create a new society, the rebels banned Indian
and Christian holidays. They stoned communal leaders and replaced
them with rebel officers. To break down traditional family life,
the rebels banned the words ``mama'' and ``papa'' and forced
children to call their parents ``camarada.''
</P>
<P>
   And in many villages like Nunhuaycco that organized self-defense
militias called rondas _ either at the instigation of the Peruvian
army or independently _ Shining Path massacred thousands of people.
Often they used knives and machetes to save bullets.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The cultural change wrought by Shining Path in this province has
turned out to be very different from the upheaval the rebels
intended.
</P>
<P>
   Former militia organizations have become local police forces in
scores of villages, with chiefs elected by villagers, and they have
formed labor pools to rebuild schools, churches and homes set afire
by the guerrillas. They also farm communal plots to feed widows,
orphans and the disabled.
</P>
<P>
   Catholic ceremonies banned by the rebels have made a robust
comeback, with villagers dusting off statues of patron saints they
hid from the rebels and parading them down dirt streets during
frequent fiestas. Evangelical churches, declared enemies of the
people by the rebels, have mushroomed across the province as
stalwarts of conservative politics and of institutions that combat
family violence and alcoholism.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the war's impact was indirect. The guerrilla violence
accelerated migration to the cities, where Indians acquired a taste
for modern luxuries like electricity and potable running water. Now
that thousands have returned to their villages, Indians are making
increasing demands on the government for such services so they can
watch television and their children can do their homework at night.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   In the village of Vicus, where Shining Path attacked 15 times
and slashed and shot 18 people to death during the war, residents
repeatedly went to government officials demanding services as a
token of appreciation for their capture of 30 terrorists. They
received potable water and an electric generator for the first
time, as well as the materials and equipment to build a road and
concrete bridge.
</P>
<P>
   The new infrastructure has brought wholesale buyers from nearby
towns, creating profitable markets for produce from Vicus. Now
residents are demanding the government help them patch up a
crumbling schoolhouse.
</P>
<P>
   Before the war, farmers in Patahuasi, like those in many
villages, lived in huts so scattered neighbors needed to hike half
an hour to see each other. Now the former militia organization is
reconstructing adobe homes in a tightly organized grid that makes
it easier for residents to organize rebuilding efforts and for the
government to deliver education, health and sanitation services.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   All told, the central government complied with local demands by
building schools in 95 Ayacucho villages and potable water systems
in 66 villages between 1995 and 1998, according to a government
report. All or part of 137 villages destroyed during the war were
also rebuilt.
</P>
<P>
   In many villages, it was the women who first rose up against
Shining Path by hiding their sons from forced recruitment into the
guerrilla ranks. And with so many men killed, women became the
heads of thousands of families. Women also took charge of
cultivating the fields and took a leadership role in communal
assemblies.
</P>
<P>
   So-called mothers' clubs arose in hundreds of villages to plant
communal plots and distribute food donated by the government and
charitable groups. The clubs have recently begun forming village
banks with foreign aid to offer small loans to farmers, mostly
women, and to small entrepreneurs. The clubs also refer women to
government clinics, where many are receiving counseling for the
first time on how to plan their families.
</P>
<P>
   ``The old system of local and communal authority broke down
during the war and has been replaced by the militias and mothers'
clubs,'' said Jaime Marquez Calvo, a human rights lawyer. ``In the
past women were subordinated, but now they play a central role and
local services are delivered much more democratically.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   In the town of Vischongo, for instance, two of the five elected
members of the municipal council are now women. The two are using
their power to set up a center to teach women business skills and
give them credit and health advice. When government officials come
to town, the councilwomen lobby for tougher laws against family
violence and for job opportunities for women.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before the war, men didn't listen to our opinions,'' said
Councilwoman Francisca Medrano, 35, who was elected to the council
after serving as president of the mothers' club in the village of
Masinga. ``But it was the women who most resisted the terrorists
and that changed everything.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, seven years after the chief Shining Path leaders
were captured and the war began to wind down, poverty and lingering
trauma continue to plague this region. Per capita income for this
province of 550,000 people is only $600, and almost two-thirds of
the children are malnourished.
</P>
<P>
   Such poverty helped fuel the revolution in Ayacucho in the first
place _ before the excess of rebel cruelty became widely known _
and few economic indicators are much higher today than before the
war.
</P>
<P>
   With more than 10,000 Ayacucho women widowed and thousands more
children orphaned by both guerrilla and army massacres, the war
made lives worse for many families. The estimated $40 million of
government and international aid that arrived here between 1996 and
1998 does not nearly meet villagers' needs.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   One Indian woman who has benefited from the changes is
Maximiliana Nahui Sanchez, 43, who was widowed nine years ago when
rebels pulled her husband out of their hut and took him away. He
was never seen again. Forced to fend for her four children, she
could barely get by making the equivalent of $30 a month as a day
laborer working for other peasants.
</P>
<P>
   But last year her life took a small turn for the better. The
communal bank run by the mothers' club in her native village of
Osno gave her a four-month low-interest loan of $50 to buy seeds
for a variety of vegetables. Now she and her children grow their
own food and earn $200 a month.
</P>
<P>
   Sitting on a pile of her onions near a roadside, huddled under
blankets to protect her against the mountain cold, she sells
produce to merchants from nearby towns.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now that I cultivate my own crops,'' Mrs. Sanchez said, ``all
I need is some rain.''
</P>
</TEXT>
