<HEADLINE>
CONTENDERS, PRETENDERS AND LONG SHOTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By FRANK LITSKY    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; Atlantic Coast &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CONTENDERS &LR;  Only Florida State, which has it all _ dynamic
offense, polished defense, a deeper bench than ever and a winning
tradition. As usual, this is a potential national champion.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; LONG SHOTS &LR;  Virginia despite quarterback worries. Georgia Tech,
with a top quarterback in Joe Hamilton, but defensive worries.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; KEY PLAYERS &LR;  TB Travis Minor, WR Peter Warrick, DE Roland
Seymour, DR Corey Simon, DT Jerry Johnson and K Sebastian
Janikowski, Florida State; QB Joe Hamilton and WR Dez White,
Georgia Tech; TB Thomas Jones, Virginia; CB Lloyd Harrison, North
Carolina State; DE Chris Combs, Duke.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PIVOTAL GAMES &LR;  Georgia Tech at Florida State Sept. 11, Miami at
Florida State Oct. 9, Florida State at Clemson Oct. 23 (the rival
coaches are Bobby Bowden and his son Tommy), Florida State at
Florida Nov. 20.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; KEY QUESTION &LR;  Has Chris Weinke, Florida State's 27-year-old
quarterback, fully recovered from surgery for a rupture disk in the
neck?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Atlantic 10 &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CONTENDERS &LR;  Massachusetts, the defending national champion in
Division I-AA, is ranked first or second in every preseason
national poll. It averaged 37 points and 471 yards a game, and that
high-powered offense returns. Delaware will create its usual chaos
from an old-fashioned winged-T.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; LONG SHOT &LR;  Connecticut if its new coach, Randy Edsall, can
repair a leaky defense to complement a potent offense.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; KEY PLAYERS &LR;  QB Todd Bankhead and TB Marcel Shipp,
Massachusetts; QB Matt Nagy, Delaware; QB Chris Boden and LB Shaun
Lyons, Villanova; LB Paris Lenon, Richmond; DE Jojo Oliphant,
Maine; WR Daver Klemic, Northeastern; DT Raheem Walker, William and
Mary.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PIVOTAL GAMES &LR;  Massachusetts at Villanova Sept. 18,
Massachusetts at Delaware Oct. 23, Delaware at Villanova and
Connecticut at Massachusetts Nov. 20.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; KEY QUESTION &LR;  Can Villanova become a contender despite the
medical-redshirt loss of Brian Westbrook, the first college player
to gain 1,000 yards rushing and 1,000 in receptions in the same
season?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Big East &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CONTENDERS &LR;  Expectations are high for Miami despite a new
defensive scheme and a killer schedule. Virginia Tech, with its
special-teams magic, has quietly climbed into the elite ranks.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; LONG SHOT &LR;  Syracuse, but only if its sophomore quarterback,
Madei Williams, can occasionally do a good Donovan McNabb
imitation.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; KEY PLAYERS &LR;  RB James Jackson, TE Daniel Franks, OG Richard
Mercier, DT Damione Lewis and LB Dan Morgan, Miami; QB Michael
Vick, DE Corey Moore and DE John Engelberger, Virginia Tech; QB
Mark Bulger, West Virginia; OT Chris Hovan, Boston College; QB Mike
McMahon, Rutgers.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PIVOTAL GAMES &LR;  Miami vs. Ohio State in the Kickoff Classic
August 28, Penn State at Miami Sept. 18, Miami at Florida State
Oct. 9, Syracuse at Virginia Tech Oct. 16, Miami at Virginia Tech
Nov. 13.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; KEY QUESTION &LR;  Does Miami, still recovering from NCAA-mandated
scholarship losses, have the maturity to survive against all those
national powers and get through its league schedule?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Big Ten &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CONTENDERS &LR;  Penn State is a powerhouse, with a defense good
enough to carry the offense. Ohio State sent eight starters to the
pros and will still be tough if its young quarterbacks mature. If
Michigan can run the ball and develop a secondary, it will be
tough.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; LONG SHOT &LR;  Wisconsin, if only because Ron Dayne is a faster
version of Jerome Bettis. Dayne needs 1,717 yards, no big deal for
him, to become history's leading major-college rusher.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; KEY PLAYERS &LR;  DE Courtney Brown, LB LaVar Arrington, LB Brandon
Short and CB David Macklin, Penn State; TB Michael Wiley, OG Rob
Murphy, LB Na'il Diggs and CB Ahmed Plummer, Ohio State; OG Steve
Hutchinson and LB James Hall, Michigan; TB Ron Dayne, OT Chris
McIntosh, C Casey Rabach and CB Jamar Fletcher, Wisconsin; QB Drew
Brees, Purdue; S Tyrone Carter, Minnesota; DE Adewale Ogunyele,
Indiana.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PIVOTAL GAMES &LR;  Michigan at Wisconsin Sept. 25, Wisconsin at
Ohio State Oct. 2, Penn State at Ohio State Oct. 16, Michigan at
Penn State Nov. 13, Ohio State at Michigan Nov. 20.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; KEY QUESTION &LR;  Can Penn State give Joe Paterno, its old coach,
his third national championship? ``There is all kinds of potential
there,'' Paterno said, ``but we need more than potential.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Big 12 &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CONTENDERS &LR;  Texas A&AMP;M, a perennial defensive power, should be
better than ever. Nebraska, which actually lost four games last
season, gets quarterback Bobby Newcombe and I-back DeAngelo Evans
back from injuries. Texas seems on the way up, Kansas State on the
way down.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; LONG SHOT &LR;  Colorado, but only if quarterback Mike Moschetti
doesn't get battered trying to escape the pass rush.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; KEY PLAYERS &LR;  QB Randy McCown, OG Semisi Heimuli and P Shane
Lechler, Texas A&AMP;M; QB Bobby Newcombe, TB DeAngelo Evans and CB
Ralph Brown, Nebraska; DT Damian McIntosh, LB Mark Simoneau and S
Jamad Cooper, Kansas State; QB Mike Moschetti and CB Ben Kelly,
Colorado; C Rob Riti, Missouri; LB Kenyatta Wright, Oklahoma State;
TB Ricky Williams (the other Ricky Williams), Texas Tech.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PIVOTAL GAMES &LR;  Kansas State at Texas Oct. 2, Nebraska at Texas
Oct. 23, Texas A&AMP;M at Nebraska Nov. 6, Nebraska at Colorado and
Texas at Texas A&AMP;M Nov. 26.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; KEY QUESTION &LR;  Can Texas A&AMP;M make a permanent leap to the level
of Florida State, Florida, Penn State, Ohio State and Michigan?
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Ivy League &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CONTENDERS &LR;  Perhaps four of the eight teams could win the
title. Start with Penn, the defender, which must replace its
quarterback and key runner. Next is Brown, whose quarterback, James
Perry, is about to become the top passer in Ivy history. Yale (good
offense, young defense) could contend.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; LONG SHOT &LR;  Harvard, with the Ivy's premier runner in Chris
Menick, but there are holes on defense.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; KEY PLAYERS &LR;  QB James Perry and WR Steve Campbell, Brown; TB
Chris Menick and LB Isaiah Kacyvenski, Harvard; DE David Ferrara,
Princeton; TB Johnathan Reese, Columbia; WR Joe Splendorio,
Cornell.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PIVOTAL GAMES &LR;  Brown at Yale Sept. 18, Princeton at Brown Oct.
9, Brown at Penn Oct. 30, Penn at Yale Oct. 30, Harvard at Brown
Nov. 6, Penn at Harvard Nov. 13.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; KEY QUESTION &LR;  Will Gavin Hoffman, a quarterback transfer from
Northwestern, make Penn fans forget about the graduation loss of
Jim Finn, last season's Ivy player of the year?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Pacific 10 &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CONTENDERS &LR;  Arizona, 12-1 last season, may be even better now.
UCLA, unsettled at quarterback and defense, has fine receivers and
will improve this year or next. Arizona State's improved defense
will make it dangerous.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; LONG SHOT &LR;  Southern California if its productive offense can
keep an uncertain defense off the field.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; KEY PLAYERS &LR;  TB Trung Canidate and LB Marcus Bell, Arizona; WR
Danny Farmer, UCLA; TB J.R. Redmond, Arizona State; QB Carson
Palmer, WR R. Jay Soward and DT Ennis Davis, Southern California; C
Mike McLaughlin, Stanford; S Lamont Thompson, Washington State; C
John Romero and LB Sekou Sanyika, California.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PIVOTAL GAMES &LR;  Arizona at Penn State August 28, UCLA at Ohio
State Sept. 11, UCLA at Arizona State Oct. 2, Southern California
at Arizona Oct. 9, Arizona at UCLA Oct. 30, UCLA at Southern
California Nov. 20, Arizona at Arizona State Nov. 27.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; KEY QUESTION &LR;  Can Drew Bennett, a seldom-used backup to the
departed All-America quarterback, Cade McNown, keep UCLA in the
running in a conference laden with powerful offenses?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Southeastern &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CONTENDERS &LR;  Tennessee, the defending national champion, has a
monster offense with Tee Martin at quarterback and Jamal Lewis and
his reconstructed knee at tailback. Florida should be good although
its quarterback, Doug Johnson, is returning from a broken leg and
the ground game is suspect.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; LONG SHOTS &LR;  There are many _ Georgia (must rebuild offense),
Alabama (deep defense, good offense), Arkansas (four new starters
on offensive line), Mississippi State (tough defense) and
Mississippi (plenty of talent).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; KEY PLAYERS &LR;  QB Tee Martin, TB Jamal Lewis, OG Casey Colman, DT
Darwin Walker, LB Raynoch Thompson and CB Dwayne Goodrich,
Tennessee; QB Doug Johnson and C Zac Zedalis, Florida; QB Quincy
Carter and LB Orantes Grant, Georgia; DT Cornelius Griffith,
Alabama; WR Anthony Lucas, Arkansas.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PIVOTAL GAMES &LR;  Tennessee at Florida Sept. 18, Alabama at
Florida Oct. 2, Georgia at Tennessee Oct. 9, Tennessee at Alabama
Oct. 23, Georgia vs. Florida Oct. 30, Tennessee at Arkansas Nov.
13, Florida State at Florida Nov. 20, Mississippi at Mississippi
State Nov. 25, Georgia at Georgia Tech Nov. 27.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; KEY QUESTION &LR;  How long will it take for 62-year-old Lou Holtz
to turn around a South Carolina team that went 1-10 last season?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Independents and Others &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CONTENDERS &LR;  Notre Dame (independent) can run the ball and has a
good running quarterback in Jarious Jackson. Its defense is sound.
Other bowl contenders are Marshall and Miami (Ohio) from the
Mid-American Conference. Brigham Young and Air Force from the
Mountain West Conference, Fresno State from the Western Athletic
Conference and Louisville from Conference USA.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; LONG SHOTS &LR;  Southern Mississippi (Conference USA) if its junior
quarterback, Cable Davis, does the job. Brigham Young (Mountain
West) if its new shotgun offense revives a slumbering passing game.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; KEY PLAYERS &LR;  QB Jarious Jackson, TE Jabari Holloway and C John
Merandi, Notre Dame; QB Chad Pennington, Marshall; TB Travis
Prentice, Miami (Ohio); LB Rob Morris, Brigham Young; QB Billy
Volek, Fresno State; QB Chris Redman and TE Ibn Green, Louisville;
QB Tim Rattay, Louisiana Tech; OT Bernard Robertson, Tulane; QB Tim
Lester, Western Michigan; S Brian Urlacher, New Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PIVOTAL GAMES &LR;  Notre Dame at Michigan and Marshall at Clemson
Sept. 4, Marshall at Miami (Ohio) and Texas Christian at Fresno
State Oct. 2, Air Force at Brigham Young Oct. 30, Notre Dame at
Tennessee Nov. 6, Southern Mississippi at Louisville Nov. 20, Army
vs. Navy Dec. 4.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; KEY QUESTION &LR;  Does 64-year-old John Robinson, a success in
college and the pros, really need his new job coaching Nevada-Las
Vegas, which has lost 16 straight?  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
