<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-VIRGINIA-TECH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOORE LEADS VIRGINIA TECH ON ROAD TO RESPECT _ AND TO THE TOP 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By JOE DRAPE    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   He is the best defensive player in the nation that nobody knows,
and if Corey Moore has his way, he will become the best lawyer that
nobody knows. Huh? Moore, last year's Big East defensive player of
the year, does not think about playing professional football.
</P>
<P>
   He did not while he was the class president for three years
running at Haywood High School in Brownsville, Tenn., and he did
not while studying enough to graduate from Virginia Tech last May
with a 3.1 grade point average in finance. Now there are graduate
courses to concentrate on and a third Big East title to shoot for.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it happens, great, but there's other things I want to do so
it really has never driven me,'' Moore said.
</P>
<P>
   But he does foresee a future in football, sort of. What he
really wants to do is become a sports agent. National Football
League scouts, however, won't be coming to Blacksburg on Saturdays
to grade forensic ability and talk torts. In 1998, the little-known
defensive end attracted their notice, as well as all-America honors
in his first year as a starter, with 67 tackles and 13.5 sacks to
lead the seventh-stingiest defense in the nation.
</P>
<P>
   Those numbers were all the more impressive because, at 6 feet
and 212 pounds, Moore often gave away 100 pounds to offensive
linemen. Fortunately, his feet are as agile as his mind. If he
decides to delay law school and deal making, the undersized
defensive lineman will probably become a linebacker in the N.F.L. a
la his boyhood idol, Lawrence Taylor.
</P>
<P>
   ``He goes around people and in between them,'' Virginia Tech
Coach Frank Beamer said. ``He's as quick as anyone we've ever
had.''
</P>
<P>
   While Syracuse learns about life without Donovan McNabb and
Miami embarks on a prime-time schedule, the Hokies may not only
dominate the Big East _ but they may also raise the profile of one
of the most overlooked Eastern powers.
</P>
<P>
   Virginia Tech has gone to six straight bowl games and whipped
Alabama of the Southeastern Conference, 38-7, in last year's Music
City Bowl. The Hokies have also beaten Miami four straight years _
a fact that nettles the resurgent Hurricanes, whom many have picked
to win the Big East.
</P>
<P>
   ``It really eats at me,'' said Matt Sweeney of Miami, a senior
defensive tackle who will face the Hokies one last time on Nov. 13.
``I can't live life, graduate and say I never beat them. That game
is circled.''
</P>
<P>
   By finding players like Moore, Beamer has built a program that
so far only Hokies fans can appreciate. Those in the 51,000-seat
Lane Stadium get on their feet when the defense takes the field and
treat special teams play like scoring opportunities. They should.
</P>
<P>
   Last year Virginia Tech blocked eight punts and kicker Shayne
Graham and punter Jimmy Kibble were all-Big East selections for the
second time.
</P>
<P>
   ``We spend a lot of time on those units because any time a kick
is involved there's big yardage at stake,'' said Beamer, whose son,
Shane, is a long snapper.
</P>
<P>
   In what was supposed to be a rebuilding year, the Hokies went
9-3 in 1998 _ including final-seconds losses to Temple and
Syracuse. With seven starters back on defense, Virginia Tech is
unknown no more and has made its way into many top-10 lists.
</P>
<P>
   Moore not only believes the Hokies deserve the recognition, but
he says the defense may lead them to a Big East title and beyond.
He is not only the leader of the unit, but its most forceful
advocate.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a great defense, the kind that can carry a team,'' he
said. ``I believe we can go undefeated.''
</P>
<P>
   The facts he argues are correct. In truth, he is only half of
the best end tandem in the nation; the senior John Engelberger, a
6-4 former walk-on, has transformed himself into a 269-pound
all-Big East defensive end. The Hokies are solid in the middle,
too. The senior tackles Nat Williams and Carl Bradley and
linebacker Jamel Smith threaten to turn the all-conference team
into a Hokies-dominated unit.
</P>
<P>
   That unit will make it impossible for teams to key on Moore,
though the defensive end anticipates it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We get after it,'' he said. ``If you try to stop me,
Engelberger will kill your quarterback. Carl, Nat and Jamel will
take open shots at your running back. I just don't think it would
be too smart.''
</P>
<P>
   He rests his case.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
