<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-28 11:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2698 &Cx1f; var-z
u a BC-LUTHERAN-EPISCOPAL-RE     08-28 0888
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LUTHERAN-EPISCOPAL-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A RELIGIOUS UNION MAY BEGET OTHERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
 (NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact Olivia Vasquez in Los
Angeles (Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089)  
 (bl)  
 By GUSTAV NIEBUHR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   It has not been difficult to find Protestants who believed that
the ecumenical movement among their churches had entered a season
of winter, where new initiatives for formal cooperation among
denominations were frozen like ice in January. But that idea waned
a few days ago when the nation's largest group of Lutherans
approved an agreement for full communion with the Episcopal Church.
</P>
<P>
   The plan, which is subject to approval by the Episcopalians next
year, is no merger; each church would keep its structure and ways
of worshiping. But it is remarkable for allying two major
Protestant denominations, the 5.2 million-member Evangelical
Lutheran Church in America and the 2.4 million-member Episcopal
Church. Fully accepting each other's members and sacraments, the
two could hold joint worship services, exchange clergy members
where needed and collaborate on social service projects.
</P>
<P>
   An obvious question is why it happened. Does the Lutheran vote
simply represent something from the past, the last of the
church-to-church agreements of the 20th century? Or does it point
to a new era of formal Christian cooperation in the 21st?
</P>
<P>
   The answer could be argued either way. On one hand, the
Lutheran-Episcopalian agreement has its roots in the 1960s, a more
optimistic era for this sort of venture, when discussions between
theologians on both sides started.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, there are reasons to think the future could
produce more pacts of this kind, given the needs of local
congregations, pressure for cooperation from Christian groups
overseas (globalization is an important concept in religion, too)
and the desire for a common front in the face of a somewhat
aggressive secular culture.
</P>
<P>
   The United States has provided rich soil for a multitude of
religious denominations. But along with the divisions, there has
long been a push toward unity. Supporters cite the prayer of Jesus
in the Gospel of John 17:11 that all his followers ``may be one.''
</P>
<P>
   The Evangelical Lutheran Church was itself formed 11 years ago
through the merger of three smaller Lutheran denominations. In
1991, it adopted a policy to move in ``multiple directions'' toward
agreements with churches in different traditions. That policy bore
fruit in 1997, when the Lutherans' biennial Churchwide Assembly
voted for full communion with three churches in Protestantism's
Reformed tradition _ the Presbyterian Church (U.S.A.), the United
Church of Christ and the Reformed Church in America.
</P>
<P>
   But the Lutherans narrowly rejected a pact with Episcopalians,
after a number of voting members voiced concern about a provision
requiring their denomination to embrace the Episcopalian belief
that bishops possess an unbroken line of spiritual authority
extending back to Christianity's earliest days.
</P>
<P>
   What followed was two years of debate on whether this idea gave
bishops too much power at the expense of laypeople and pastors. On
Aug. 19, as the assembly met in Denver, proponents of the agreement
won out, 69 percent to 31.
</P>
<P>
   Although the process leading to the decision was long and
complex, at least three ideas involved in it seem important for the
ecumenical movement as a whole.
</P>
<P>
   It makes sense for some congregations to pool their resources
across denominational lines. Financially hard-pressed congregations
in rural areas and inner cities could share a full-time pastor as
well as collaborate on good works, making their dollars and
energies go farther.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement was also spurred by international pressures, said
the Rev. Daniel Martensen, the Lutherans' chief ecumenical officer.
Many American Protestant denominations belong to global
associations of churches that share theological and historical
traditions.
</P>
<P>
   The Episcopal Church, for example, belongs to Worldwide Anglican
Communion. The Evangelical Lutheran Church is a member (the
second-largest) of the Lutheran World Federation, an association of
churches with a total membership of nearly 60 million.
</P>
<P>
   Attending the Denver assembly, the federation's general
secretary, the Rev. Ishmael Noko of Zimbabwe, told voting members
that although the decision on full communion was theirs, whatever
they did would be felt in ``sister churches'' worldwide. He said he
expected full communion agreements between Lutherans and Anglicans
in Africa within five years.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, too, there is the incentive of bringing similar faiths
together in a common stand, or ``witness,'' in the face of an
increasingly secular American culture.
</P>
<P>
   This point was made by the Rev. John Thomas, president-elect of
the United Church of Christ, an observer at the assembly.
``Certainly, among Christians, there's less and less legitimacy in
our mission to cling to competitive and isolationist models,'' he
said. ``I think unity itself is a kind of witness and a kind of
mission.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-28-99 1143EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990828.0090 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-28 11:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2291 &Cx1f; var-z
u a BC-LUTHERAN-EPISCOPAL-RE     08-28 0888
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LUTHERAN-EPISCOPAL-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A RELIGIOUS UNION MAY BEGET OTHERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
 (NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact Olivia Vasquez in Los
Angeles (Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089)  
 (bl)  
 By GUSTAV NIEBUHR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
