<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-28 11:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2703 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-GORE-BUSH-TOBACCO-2TA     08-28 0969
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-BUSH-TOBACCO-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAMPAIGNS SEEK TO WEAKEN TOBACCO TIES 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By DON VAN NATTA Jr. and JILL ABRAMSON    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The presidential campaigns of Al Gore and George W.
Bush have this much in common: Both are trying to wean themselves
from the money and influence of the tobacco industry, long one of
the most generous of political donors.
</P>
<P>
   But neither campaign, nor either of the parties the candidates
seek to lead, has managed entirely to kick the political tobacco
habit.
</P>
<P>
   Gore hired a media consultant who had worked for the tobacco
industry, and was promptly denounced for doing so by such health
groups as the American Lung Association. His campaign sometimes
returns contributions from individuals with ties to tobacco, but
not always.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's top political strategist was a consultant to Philip
Morris from 1991 to 1996, and his presidential campaign has
accepted at least $50,000 in individual contributions from tobacco
executives. Although Texas sued tobacco companies during Bush's
first term as governor, he never publicly supported the litigation,
and he is a champion of legislation in Texas that would limit
damages in liability suits against industries. The legislation is
strongly favored by the tobacco industry.
</P>
<P>
   Matthew Myers, executive vice president of the National Center
for Tobacco Free Kids, said that health groups were certain to make
tobacco's contributions an issue in the 2000 presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``The tobacco industry has been exposed for being different in
terms of its product and wrongful behavior,'' Myers said.
``Association with the industry and its money creates a taint.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the criticism, Bush, Gore and several other presidential
candidates are trying to come up with approaches that allow them to
benefit from some tobacco contributions, but that also insulate
them from accusations that they are beholden to the industry's
interests. Other candidates have also received contributions from
tobacco executives. The maximum campaign gift for an individual is
$1,000.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, contributions from the tobacco industry and individuals
linked to it have been a tiny portion of the money the presidential
candidates have received.
</P>
<P>
   As various states sued the industry to recover money they spent
on smoking-related illnesses, the dominant role of tobacco's money
in politics has become much more closely scrutinized in recent
years.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995 and 1996, the tobacco industry contributed $5.8 million
in soft money, on which there are no limits, to the Republican
Party and $1.1 million to the Democratic Party. Lobbyists predict
that the industry's support for Republican candidates and the
Republican Party will be even more lopsided in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Democratic National Committee refuses to accept
soft money from the tobacco industry, other Democrat committees,
like the House and Senate and state party committees, have accepted
such contributions in the past.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has decided not to accept contributions from tobacco
political action committees, and he returned a $5,000 PAC donation
to his presidential campaign from Brown &AMP; Williamson Tobacco Corp.
It is a clear sign that the Bush campaign is sensitive to attacks
that the governor is too cozy with tobacco interests.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a decision he made in his gubernatorial re-election
campaign because the state was involved in a lawsuit with tobacco
companies in Texas,'' said Mindy Tucker, a spokeswoman for Bush's
presidential campaign. ``He has carried it over to the presidential
campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, that decision has hardly stopped the flow of
contributions from tobacco industry executives and lobbyists to
Bush's presidential campaign. Several tobacco executives and
lobbyists say Bush is viewed as a popular candidate by the industry
because of his stand on limiting liability damages.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   According to Federal Election Commission records, the Bush
campaign has received at least $50,000 from individuals affiliated
with tobacco concerns, more than any other presidential contender.
Among those who have contributed $1,000 to his campaign are
Geoffrey Bible, president of Philip Morris; Murray Bring, another
top Philip Morris executive, and more than a dozen executives of
United States Tobacco Co.
</P>
<P>
   While Bush refused to accept contributions from tobacco
interests in his two campaigns for governor, before his re-election
in 1998 a public policy group in Austin, Texas, accused him of
accepting contributions from lobbyists who were hired by Philip
Morris and the tobacco industry. ``Accepting money from tobacco
lobbyists raises thorny ethical questions,'' said Craig McDonald,
the director for Texans for Public Justice, a nonprofit advocacy
group.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Bush's chief political strategist, Karl Rove, and Haley
Barbour, the former chairman of the Republican National Committee
and now a lobbyist, have significant tobacco ties.
</P>
<P>
   Barbour has earned large lobbying fees from the tobacco
industry. And Rove was a $3,000-a-month consultant to Philip Morris
in Texas beginning in 1991. He ended his affiliation with Philip
Morris in December 1996, in part to avoid bringing controversy to
Bush. But from January 1995 to December 1996, Rove worked both as a
political consultant to Bush and as a paid consultant for Philip
Morris.
</P>
<P>
   Rove declined to comment for this article. Rove has said he
ended his affiliation with Philip Morris because he ``felt
awkward'' about working for the tobacco company at the same time he
was Bush's chief political strategist. He also said that Bush told
him specifically not to discuss tobacco issues with him while he
was a consultant for Philip Morris.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   In March 1996, Dan Morales, then attorney general of Texas,
filed a lawsuit against the tobacco industry, seeking reimbursement
for billions of dollars the state had spent on smoking-related
illnesses.
</P>
<P>
   In January 1998, the industry settled the lawsuit with Texas for
$15 billion, a figure that was eventually increased to $17.3
billion, including $2.3 billion in fees to the five lawyers and
firms for the plaintiffs.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, who had not commented on the case until then, called the
lawyers' fees ``unreasonable'' and tried to block them, prompting
complaints that he was taking the side of the tobacco industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm disappointed that we did not receive active public support
from the governor,'' Morales said. ``And I was troubled from the
outset about Rove's close relationship with Philip Morris and the
governor. My concern was there was a prospect for the sabotage of
our lawsuit.''
</P>
<P>
   But Bush's spokeswoman, Ms. Tucker, said that the governor
simply ``did not want the taxpayers to be on the hook for $2.3
billion in legal fees that Dan Morales negotiated with five
attorneys.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Gore, who has been a vocal critic of the tobacco industry and
delivered an emotional speech at the 1996 Democratic Convention
about his sister's death from lung cancer, does not accept
contributions from the tobacco industry and has returned some
individual contributions this year from tobacco executives.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our policy is that we do not accept contributions from tobacco
PACs, nor do we accept them from tobacco corporate entities,'' said
Roger Salazar, a spokesman for the Gore campaign. ``It would be
impossible to check individuals and their portfolios.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the other presidential candidates who have received
contributions from tobacco executives are Bill Bradley, the
Democratic candidate and former New Jersey senator, who received a
few thousand dollars. A spokesman said that Bradley had a strong
anti-smoking record and championed higher cigarette taxes.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   In January, the Gore campaign and its compliance fund, for
covering the legal costs of a campaign, received $2,000 each from
Bennett S. LeBow, the chairman and chief executive of Brooke Group
Ltd., which owns the Liggett Group, and LeBow's wife and a business
associate. The campaign returned the checks of LeBow and his
business associate, but kept Mrs. LeBow's money because she is not
employed the tobacco industry, Salazar said.
</P>
<P>
   Even Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., who is viewed as an enemy of the
tobacco industry because he was the author of federal anti-smoking
legislation, received a $1,000 contribution from another member of
LeBow's group.
</P>
<P>
   For the campaigns, the policy of not accepting contributions
from tobacco company PAC's neatly dovetails with the practices of
some tobacco firms. ``Our PAC, as a matter of policy, does not make
contributions to presidential candidates,'' said Peggy Roberts,
director of corporate communications for Philip Morris.
``Individuals are free to give to whomever they like.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, Gore denounced the Republican National Committee as
``just about a wholly owned subsidiary of the tobacco industry,''
because of millions of dollars in soft money that it received from
tobacco companies, including $2.5 million from Philip Morris. In
the last presidential election, Philip Morris was the Republican
Party's largest donor.
</P>
<P>
   But at the same time, tobacco companies, including R.J.
Reynolds, were directed by Democratic find-raisers to make
soft-money contributions to state Democratic Party organizations,
despite the Democratic National Committee's policy to refuse
tobacco money. Some of the state parties sent these contributions
back to the national committee, according to state and federal
election records.
</P>
<P>
   While he hones Gore's campaign message, Carter Eskew, the
campaign's top media adviser, maintains an affiliation with his
advertising and consulting firm, Bozell/Eskew. Salazar said that
Eskew must have all his client work approved by the campaign and
was prohibited from taking on tobacco work or ``drawing any profits
from any of the firm's tobacco clients.''
</P>
<P>
   Eskew helped design a $40 million advertising blitz for the big
tobacco companies during the congressional fight over federal
anti-tobacco legislation. The legislation was eventually defeated.
Eskew declined to be interviewed.
</P>
<P>
   He is not the only member of the Gore team with tobacco ties.
Tina Flournoy, Gore's finance director, is a former Philip Morris
executive, and Jonathan Tisch, one of his top fund-raisers in New
York, is a top executive at Loews Corp., the parent company of
Lorillard Tobacco. The Gore campaign takes pains to point out that
Tisch heads Loews' hotel unit.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
