<HEADLINE>
BASEBALL NOTES AND NEWS 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By MURRAY CHASS    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   From Out of Nowhere
</P>
<P>
   In his first season as a starting pitcher with the Houston
Astros last season, Jose Lima gained a career-high 16 victories.
With a month of starts remaining in his second season, Lima has 17
victories, not only the most in his career but also the most in the
National League.
</P>
<P>
   ``To think any of us are smart enough to take a player who has
been picked over by many clubs and see him become an All-Star the
next year ... ,'' Gerry Hunsicker, the Astros' general manager,
said without finishing the sentence but also without taking credit
for the discovery of Lima.
</P>
<P>
   The right-hander came to the Astros from Detroit in a 10-player
trade in December 1996 after having spent the second half of each
of the preceding two seasons with the Tigers. As a starter in 1995,
Lima had a 3-9 record and 6.11 earned run average. Primarily a
reliever in '96, he had a 5-6 record and 5.70 ERA.
</P>
<P>
   In Hunsicker's opinion, Lima was ``a kid who was initially
rushed to the big leagues before he was ready, put in a negative
environment, put on a bad club in a hitters' ball park.'' He had a
good arm and a good changeup, Hunsicker added, but ``the
environment he was in wasn't conducive to his development.''
</P>
<P>
   The trade, the general manager said, put Lima in a pitchers'
park and gave him a manager and a pitching coach who are good
teachers. Lima obviously was a good student, though the Astros
almost didn't find out how good.
</P>
<P>
   ``We almost released him last spring,'' Hunsicker said, speaking
of March 1998. ``He was horrible last spring. He made our rotation
by default. The week before the season started we called him into
the office and told him we were taking him out of the rotation to
start the season and outlined a list of things he had to do to get
better.'' Two days before the season began, Pete Schourek went down
with an elbow injury. ``We had to put Schourek on the disabled list
and Lima took his place in the rotation by default,'' Hunsicker
said. ``That's how smart we are.''
</P>
<P>
   Winning by Avoiding Slumps
</P>
<P>
   When Atlanta swept a three-game series from Cincinnati last
week, it marked the first time since the second week of June that
the Reds had lost three in a row. The Mets have had only one
three-game losing streak since they reached the nadir of their
season with an eight-game losing streak in late May and early June.
</P>
<P>
   But for impressive records, no one can beat the Braves, who
despite a seemingly ceaseless rash of injuries have the best
won-lost record in the majors.
</P>
<P>
   How the Rangers Got Their Man
</P>
<P>
   Even with their sights set on Albert Belle last November, the
Baltimore Orioles wanted to keep Rafael Palmeiro, their owner says.
``Belle was not selected over Raffy,'' Peter Angelos said. ``They
were looked upon as a team, lefty and righty.''
</P>
<P>
   And why not? Palmeiro had blasted his way through the five most
productive years in the Orioles' hit-filled history and had shown
no signs of easing his onslaught. But the Orioles did not pursue
Palmeiro with the same urgency, not to mention dollars, with which
they sought Belle.
</P>
<P>
   The result: Belle is having a below-average season for the
Orioles, and Palmeiro is having another remarkable season for the
Texas Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   Palmeiro entered Saturday's schedule with 40 home runs, 124
RBIs, a .341 batting average and a league-leading .659 slugging
percentage.
</P>
<P>
   These numbers could have been the Orioles but for an initially
lukewarm courtship and ultimately a quirk of timing. After offering
three years for $7.5 million a year, then inching up to four years
and finally five _ ``It took forever to get to five years and move
the money up,'' Jim Bronner, Palmeiro's agent, said _ the Orioles
finally got the first baseman's attention with a five-year, $50
million offer, though it was still $3 million a year below the
Belle terms.
</P>
<P>
   ``We basically had an agreement on what the terms would be,''
Bronner said. ``But there was one issue Raffy and Peter had to talk
about. They straightened that out, and Raffy called me and said it
was OK. I called Peter at his law offices at about 10:30 at night,
but I missed him. I called his house, but he wasn't there. By the
time he got home, he thought it was too late to call me.''
</P>
<P>
   Bronner and Angelos missed each other the next morning, too.
``If I had been able to get Peter that night or the next morning,
we would have had a deal,'' the agent said.
</P>
<P>
   But as he waited, Palmeiro, who had played in Texas before going
to the Orioles as a free agent in 1994, decided to try the Rangers
again. He and his wife had built a large house in Texas and would
have been happy if he had never left.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers had put Palmeiro off this time while they chased
Randy Johnson. Pitching was their No. 1 priority. But Johnson
shunned the Rangers so their general manager, Doug Melvin, agreed
to meet Palmeiro that morning.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told Raffy the other day I'm sure glad I took that half hour
to meet you at the hotel,'' Melvin said. ``He said he was, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Angelos was calling Bronner, but Bronner didn't take the calls
because he was waiting to hear from his client. Once he did and
learned that Palmeiro had his mind set on returning to the Rangers,
they had to wait for Melvin to get clearance from the team's owner,
Tom Hicks, to give Palmeiro $45 million for five years, and Hicks
was on a plane somewhere. ``We knew Angelos was getting antsy; he
was calling every 10 or 15 minutes,'' Bronner said. ``We didn't
want to lose that deal. We called the Rangers and gave them five
minutes.''
</P>
<P>
   More than five minutes elapsed, but the Rangers did the deal.
</P>
<P>
   Bronner said it was important for Palmeiro to get five years.
``He has some personal goals that will take some time to achieve,''
the agent said. ``He thinks he has a shot at 500 home runs and
3,000 hits. He needs five, five and a half years to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Palmeiro went into Saturday's game with 354 home runs and 2,131
hits.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
