<SLUG> BC-LADN-BUDGET </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Los Angeles Daily News plans to move the following general
stories for use by NYTimes News Service clients, AMs and PMs of
Sunday, Aug. 29 and thereafter. For questions about stories, please
contact Stew Slavin at the Daily News, (818) 713-3701.
</P>
<P>
   POKEMON-MOVIE (Los Angeles) _ If you haven't hung around
8-year-old boys lately, you probably don't know the next wave of
globalization has already arrived in the form of Pikachu, Raichu
and 149 other animated Pokemon characters. Pokemon _ the Japanese
name for ``pocket monster'' _ is becoming more prominent each day
in the United States with a mind-boggling array of video games,
trading cards, clothing and toys along with its own TV show. And in
a stunning reversal of the usual practice of American hit films
going to foreign markets, a made-in-Japan Pokemon movie will arrive
at U.S. multiplexes on Nov. 12. By Dave McNary. (Will move in the
``f'' financial and ``n'' California news file.)
</P>
<P>
   LA-PITBULL (Los Angeles) _ A white pit bull named L.A. was
seized by police checking out a dogfight in Los Angeles in 1996. He
had his ears nearly shredded off and was terrified of other dogs.
He is among the maimed and mangled pitbull, dog-fight veterans that
help make up 40 percent of stray dogs found wandering the San
Fernando Valley and across the city, a population fed by backyard
breeders who trade in dogs for fighting. By Robert Monroe. (Will
move in the ``n'' California news file.)
</P>
<P>
   X X X &QL;
</P>
