u a BC-FOIE-GRAS-TEXT-REVIEW     08-28 0913
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOIE-GRAS-TEXT-REVIEW-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOIE GRAS: THE FOOD FROM THE GOOSE THAT GETS UP THE DANDER 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review) 
(NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact Olivia Vasquez in Los
Angeles (Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089)  
 (Eds: text that should be italicized is marked with (BEGIN ITALICS
HERE) and (END ITALICS HERE)  
 (bl)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Smithsonian Institution in Washington last week canceled a
celebration of foie gras, a delicacy produced by the forced feeding
of ducks and geese, after protests from animal rights advocates,
including the actors Sir John Gielgud and Bea Arthur. A Smithsonian
spokesman said officials were worried that ``something untoward''
might happen at the gathering.
</P>
<P>
   The episode has a very '90s feel, pitting the prosperously
indulgent and those who cater to them against often censorious
defenders of humankind's lesser brethren, edible and otherwise.
Let's look at quotations outlining the controversy.
</P>
<P>
   _ By TOM KUNTZ
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN ITALICS HERE) The new popularity of foie gras in the
United States was noted last year by Forbes magazine, which said,
``Ten years ago, most Americans didn't know foie gras from a faux
pas.'' It profiled Michael Ginor, the food's top promoter: (END
ITALICS HERE)
</P>
<P>
   ``A delicacy once prized by the ancient Egyptians and Romans,
the force-fed foie gras (literally, fatty liver) has in France
achieved the kind of reverence usually reserved for Victor Hugo and
sex. But it was little known in the U.S. until Ginor, a beefy
34-year-old, began peddling it to fashionable restaurants in the
'90s.
</P>
<P>
   Now Ginor and his partner, Izzy Yanay, can't meet the demand
they've created. In eight years they have turned a bankrupt poultry
farm in Ferndale, N.Y., into Hudson Valley Foie Gras, a $9 million
(sales) company earning close to 22 percent pretax. Hudson Valley
virtually owns the U.S. market. Along with a small California
rival, Ginor is responsible for the 50,000 portions of fattened
liver served in the U.S. each week.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN ITALICS HERE) Ginor's stature (enhanced now by a punitive
tariff on French foie gras) was to be recognized at the Smithsonian
event Sept. 21. It was promoted in a mailing to members: (END
ITALICS HERE)
</P>
<P>
   ``In a mouth-watering evening, join Mr. Ginor and other
celebrated chefs for a discussion of the history, production and
ever-rising popularity of foie gras today. ...
</P>
<P>
   Following the talk, sample several small, specially prepared
foie gras hors d'oeuvres along with a glass of wine. ...''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN ITALICS HERE) But then came protests organized by People
for the Ethical Treatment of Animals, notably this letter to I.
Michael Heyman, the Smithsonian's head, from Sir John Gielgud, 95,
the Shakespearean actor perhaps best known in the United States for
his Oscar-winning role as valet to a soused Dudley Moore in the
comedy film ``Arthur'': (END ITALICS HERE)
</P>
<P>
   ``Dear Secretary Heymann,
</P>
<P>
   I am extremely distressed to learn from my friends at People for
the Ethical Treatment of Animals (PETA) that the Smithsonian
Associates are planning to host a seminar `celebrating' foie gras.
I would like to tell you of the horror taking place on many foie
gras farms today. The male ducks and geese on these farms are
restrained and have their bills forced open. A long metal pipe is
then roughly pushed down their throats. Finally, an air-driven pump
thrusts two to three pounds of corn mixture into their stomachs.
The ducks and geese endure this painful and distressing procedure
three times a day for four weeks.
</P>
<P>
   The result is that the birds' livers expand to six to 12 times
their normal size, they can barely walk or stand, their bills
become deformed or broken, and they suffer damage to their pharynx
and esophagus. Sometimes the force of inserting the metal pipe can
rupture their necks. And a percentage die outright from burst
internal organs. ... Female hatchlings are usually simply thrown
away, smothered or ground up.
</P>
<P>
   Even a cursory examination of these methods would make a decent
person shudder. ...
</P>
<P>
   Sincerely,
</P>
<P>
   Sir John Gielgud''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN ITALICS HERE) Gielgud's letter was followed by one from
Bea Arthur, who played the not-to-be-messed-with New York woman in
the 1970s television sitcom ``Maude'': (END ITALICS HERE)
</P>
<P>
   ``I am not a vegetarian, but the extent of suffering of the
birds in foie gras production would be shocking to any meat-eater.
</P>
<P>
   Foie gras production is illegal in England and some other
enlightened countries, and I have had the opportunity to meet with
British members of Parliament on this very issue. ...
</P>
<P>
   I now join Sir John Gielgud in urging you to cancel this
upcoming seminar in cruelty.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN ITALICS HERE) But Ginor defends the forced feeding of the
birds as the principal author of a glossy new book, ``Foie Gras: A
Passion'' (John A. Wiley &AMP; Sons, 1999). He writes: (END ITALICS
HERE)
</P>
<P>
   ``The methods used in producing foie gras have concerned people
since the 11th century, when Rashi, the French rabbi, stated that
the Jews would pay in the hereafter for making the fattened geese
suffer. Since that time, farmers have constantly refined their
techniques.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN ITALICS HERE) He says in effect that gorging is just
ducky: (END ITALICS HERE)
</P>
<P>
   ``According to Dr. Tirath Sandhu of the International Duck
Research Cooperative ... the birds must gorge, while preparing for
their migrations, to amass the energy reserves of fat needed for
the long flight. Ducks and geese and their relations possess livers
that have specially evolved to become the main repository for this
fat. ... In the feeding process, goose and duck farmers are taking
advantage of the birds' natural eating habits and physiology.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN ITALICS HERE) And as for that tube stuck down the birds'
throats, it's plastic, not metal, Ginor said last week.
Furthermore, the author writes: (END ITALICS HERE)
</P>
<P>
   ``A waterfowl throat ... is not like the throat of a human. The
lining of the duck and goose esophagus is keratinized. This means
that it is composed of fibrous protein cells that resemble bristles
or fingernails, allowing large pieces of food to pass safely.
Because of this anatomical feature, the tube creates no discomfort
for the ducks.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN ITALICS HERE) But surely foie gras is, as PETA warns,
``extremely unhealthy'' for humans? Maybe not, Ginor writes, citing
widely reported French research suggesting a link between foie
gras-rich diets and low heart-disease rates: (END ITALICS HERE)
</P>
<P>
   ``(The) findings were corroborated by the World Health
Organization's Multinational Monitoring of Trends and Determinants
in Cardiovascular Disease (MONICA), which undertook a study of
eating habits, heart disease and mortality based in Toulouse.
Monica reported that out of 100,000 middle-aged French men,
approximately 145 died of heart attacks. In Toulouse, the number
was 80. In the United States, the number was 315. The discrepancy
between these findings and the commonly held belief regarding the
role animal fat was considered to play in the incidence of heart
disease led worldwide media to report on the phenomenon as `The
French Paradox.' ... Some (scientists) pointed to the chemical
constituents of red wine ... while others focused on the
composition of the foie gras fat itself.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN ITALICS HERE) But Ginor's arguments couldn't save the
Smithsonian event. An official alluded to potential trouble in a
letter to the scores who had forked over $25 or more to attend:
(END ITALICS HERE)
</P>
<P>
   ``Because we are always concerned with the comfort and
well-being of our participants, we have regretfully concluded that
it would be in the best interests of everyone involved to cancel
the program on foie gras. ... We will immediately process a full
refund for the foie gras evening.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN ITALICS HERE) Would-be attendees might be consoled by
Alexandre Grimod de la Reyniere, a 19th-century food critic quoted
in the Ginor book: (END ITALICS HERE)
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing is better than an excellent pate of foies gras: They
have killed more gourmands than the plague.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
