<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NOTEBOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRO FOOTBALL NOTES AND NEWS 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By MIKE FREEMAN    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bill Kuharich, the New Orleans Saints' general manager, said his
heart did not drop into his stomach when he first heard that Ricky
Williams, the man the Saints spent eight draft picks to get, had
severely hurt his ankle.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've taken a real even keel in regards to Ricky,'' Kuharich
said. ``Injuries are going to happen. You can't control them.''
</P>
<P>
   It is an intelligent approach, and one that is expected from
Kuharich. But when the franchise limped off the field several weeks
ago after a crushing hit by a Miami defensive player, did not
visions of a wasted draft bounce in his head? Were there not a few
nightmares while he waited for doctors to give a final diagnosis?
</P>
<P>
   ``No, he's a tough player,'' Kuharich said. ``I knew he'd be
fine.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams, the team said, should be ready by the season opener
Sept. 12 against Carolina. So the Saints' bold experiment _
swapping their entire draft for one player _ remains alive and
well.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, Kuharich said, the Saints have more devastating injury
problems. Their solid defensive end, Joe Johnson, ruptured a
patella tendon and will miss the entire season. The Pro Bowl
offensive tackle William Roaf hurt his knee last week, though he
should be healed in a few weeks. Kuharich remains excited about
this season despite the injuries.
</P>
<P>
   At this point in the year, every team is excited, even the
Philadelphia Eagles, who might be lucky to win five games. The
preseason is still young enough for teams to keep their dreams
intact. Reality doesn't bite for a few more weeks.
</P>
<P>
   There are several interesting stories around the National
Football League, and if the preseason is any indication it might be
a truly exciting year. Here is a look around the league's training
camps.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INDIANAPOLIS &LR;  _ Quarterback Peyton Manning has picked up where
he left off in his rookie season. In training camp, Manning has
shown the poise of a 10-year veteran, and he could put up big
numbers this season. The team will need his skills because the
Colts are in the toughest division in football, the American
Football Conference East. Still, they have an excellent chance of
making the playoffs as a wild-card team, thanks to Manning.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SAN DIEGO &LR;  _ The player chosen second behind Manning last year,
quarterback Ryan Leaf, may be the biggest draft bust of the 1990s.
The good news for the Chargers is that linebacker Junior Seau has
made some of the best catches on the team in practices. Not
interceptions, catches. Seau has been working at tight end and
could make his debut in the final preseason game against Kansas
City on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SEATTLE &LR;  _ The Pro Bowl wide receiver Joey Galloway is serious
about his threat to sit out the season if the Seahawks do not meet
his contract demands. Coach Mike Holmgren, however, remains
confident that Galloway will be there once the season begins.
</P>
<P>
   Seattle offered Galloway a seven-year deal worth $35 million
that included a $7 million signing bonus. It would have made him
the second-highest-paid wide receiver behind Green Bay's Antonio
Freeman, who is arguably the best receiver in the league. Galloway
wants a five-year contract worth $24 million with a $9 million
bonus.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, quarterback Jon Kitna has had a solid camp. What
worries Holmgren is the situation at backup quarterback. Glenn
Foley, the former Jet, has been disappointing so far.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; GREEN BAY &LR;  _ The reason Ron Wolf, the general manager of the
Packers, is perhaps the best at what he does is because of his
vision. When Holmgren left for Seattle, Wolf felt that Ray Rhodes,
dismissed as coach by the Philadelphia Eagles, would be a perfect
fit for the Packers, and so far Wolf is correct. The players have
taken to Rhodes. And the offensive coordinator Sherman Lewis said
the Packers' offense is going to be more aggressive than in the
past.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; JACKSONVILLE &LR;  _ Running back Fred Taylor rushed for 1,223 yards
and 14 touchdowns in 12 starts as a rookie last season. Taylor
thinks that he can break the 2,000-yard barrier this season. He may
be right. Against a good Kansas City defense last Thursday night,
Taylor had touchdown runs of 16 and 86 yards.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SAN FRANCISCO &LR;  _ One of the most amazing stories of the
preseason is defensive lineman Bryant Young. It was thought that
Young might not be ready to play until the middle of this year
after breaking his leg at the end of last season. But he has
recovered faster than expected, and he could get 15 to 20 snaps in
the season opener against Jacksonville.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TAMPA BAY &LR;  _ The Buccaneers know that if they are ever going to
be a serious Super Bowl contender, they must improve their offense.
This preseason the team is using additional offensive formations,
including more four and five wide receiver sets, and increasing the
number of passing attempts on first down. Before their preseason
game yesterday against New England, the Buccaneers were 2-0, the
first time that had happened in the preseason in nine years.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; KANSAS CITY &LR;  _ Quarterback Elvis Grbac has played so poorly in
the preseason that it would not be surprising if Warren Moon is
starting by Game 6 against Baltimore.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUFFALO &LR;  _ Just as quarterback Doug Flutie was ready for his
chance last season when the starter Rob Johnson stumbled, Johnson,
now the backup, is ready to step in should Flutie prove a fluke. In
practices, Johnson has been just as efficient as Flutie.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; JETS &LR;  _ Defensive players say that subtle, smart changes made
by the defensive coordinator Bill Belichick have made the defense
even better than it was last season. They will not yet say what
those changes are, but they feel the Jets could have the top-ranked
defense this season.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; GIANTS &LR;  _ General Manager Ernie Accorsi made a smart move in
selecting offensive lineman Luke Petitgout in the draft in April.
The team has lost the starter Lance Scott to a knee injury for
possibly the entire season, and Petitgout has been moved to Scott's
guard position.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; College vs. Pros, Part I  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   As someone who has had three coaching stints in college football
_ two at Southern California and one at Nevada-Las Vegas _ in
addition to coaching the Los Angeles Rams, John Robinson is highly
qualified to assess the differences between coaching in college and
in the pros. His words on the subject are interesting.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the pro athlete, your relationship is pretty much
football,'' Robinson said. ``If he has financial problems or if he
has legal problems or emotional problems, he tends to go somewhere
else.''
</P>
<P>
   That's not what happens in college, Robinson said. There a coach
becomes everything to a player. Most coaches, professional or
college, do not want to be involved in a player's life outside of
football, despite whatever public stance they may take to the
contrary. But unlike professional coaches, college coaches cannot
ignore the difficulties a player may have off of the field.
</P>
<P>
   ``In college, most of a players' problems get dumped in your
lap,'' Robinson said, ``and you take those home and then you become
a surrogate parent whether you want to or not.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
