<DOCNO> NYT19990828.0117 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-28 12:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2316 &Cx1f; var-z
u a BC-INEPT-LAWS-REVIEW-NYT     08-28 0936
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INEPT-LAWS-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHEN LAWS SHOOT THEMSELVES IN THE FOOT 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
 (NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact Olivia Vasquez in Los
Angeles (Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089)  
 (bl)  
 By DAVID E. ROSENBAUM   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Toward the end of every year, millions of Americans
go on medical shopping sprees. They get their teeth cleaned and
their eyes checked. They buy designer eyeglasses, orthopedic shoes
and long-term supplies of birth-control pills. Some even make extra
appointments with their analysts.
</P>
<P>
   These people are taking advantage of a tax break called flexible
spending accounts that hardly anyone believes is good public
policy. While the government's goal is to hold down medical costs,
this part of the tax law encourages extra medical spending.
</P>
<P>
   There are probably dozens of other such laws on the books _ laws
that may have been enacted with the best of intentions but that
turned out to work at cross-purposes with government policy.
</P>
<P>
   Stuart Butler at the Heritage Foundation says, for example, that
it makes no sense for buildings across the country to remain
dilapidated because the historic preservation law makes it too
costly to restore them.
</P>
<P>
   Mary Hevener, a tax lawyer, says nothing could be more absurd
than tax-subsidized parking, which encourages commuters to drive,
thus consuming fuel and worsening pollution.
</P>
<P>
   John Frydenlund at Citizens Against Government Waste believes
the most ridiculous laws are the federal subsidies for the domestic
sugar, peanut and dairy industries, which cost Americans billions
of dollars in higher food prices.
</P>
<P>
   Each of those is a candidate for a list of laws with unintended
consequences that outweigh whatever benefits exist. But here are
one reporter's favorites:
</P>
<P>
   FLEXIBLE SPENDING ACCOUNTS. Since 1984, the tax law has allowed
employers to offer these accounts to workers. More than 50,000
employers, including almost all large companies and many states and
municipalities, offer the benefit to more than 6 million workers.
</P>
<P>
   At the beginning of the year, employees declare how much money
they want withheld from their pay to cover out-of-pocket medical
expenses _ not just insurance deductibles and copayments but also
expenses not covered by insurance. Since the workers do not pay
federal or state income or payroll taxes on this money, they can in
effect save 30 to 50 percent on their medical expenses. The richer
they are, the more they save.
</P>
<P>
   The catch is that at the end of the year they must forfeit to
their boss all the money in their account that has not been spent.
This use-it-or-lose-it aspect leads participants to go on spending
binges at the end of every year to clean out their accounts.
</P>
<P>
   The Employers Council on Flexible Spending, the lobby behind the
law, would like to eliminate the use-it-or-lose-it rule, but that
would cost more than politicians are willing to allocate. Others
would like to abolish the accounts altogether on the ground that
people who are well off and work for large employers should not get
a tax benefit unavailable to those who are less affluent.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are only two words by which you can characterize this _
venal and stupid,'' said Uwe Reinhardt, a health-care economist at
Princeton. He has such an account himself, and last December, he
discovered he had money left in it. So he and his wife went to the
doctor on Christmas Eve and got colonoscopies.
</P>
<P>
   FLOOD INSURANCE. The original idea was to give subsidized
insurance to people in areas that often flooded. In return, the
communities were required to enact strict controls on land use and
building codes that would reduce the likelihood of flood damage.
</P>
<P>
   In many cases, this has worked. But in many others, a study by
the National Wildlife Federation found, the availability of
inexpensive insurance ``encourages development and rebuilding in
areas with a predictably high risk of future catastrophic loss.''
The federation found 32,000 insured properties in 300 communities
that had been flooded and repaired at least twice. A house in
Houston worth about $100,000 was flooded 16 times, with $800,000 in
insurable repairs.
</P>
<P>
   Edward Pasterick, a spokesman for the Federal Insurance
Administration, said it was a ``misperception'' that cheap
insurance led people to build in flood-prone locales. But he
conceded that federally subsidized premiums on new structures
averaged less than 40 percent of what private insurance would cost.
</P>
<P>
   CONSUMER COMPLAINTS. When Congress created the Consumer Product
Safety Commission in 1972, the law specified that the new agency's
mission was ``to assist consumers in evaluating the comparative
safety of consumer products.'' But the law added a zinger. It
prohibited the agency from making public any consumer complaint
about a product without first getting permission from the
manufacturer. It is the only regulatory agency that has such a
restriction.
</P>
<P>
   ``This allows companies to control the information flow,'' said
Ann Brown, the head of the commission. ``Those who ought to control
the flow are consumers. Our hands are tied.''
</P>
<P>
   Commission officials said that, in fact, only a handful of
companies take advantage of their ability to block publicity. Which
companies are those?
</P>
<P>
   It is against the law, the officials said, for them to reveal
that information.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
