<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-28 12:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2735 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-TEN-VECSEY-COLUMN-NYT     08-28 0912
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-VECSEY-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: NEW PRESIDENT ALREADY HAS LEGACY AT ASHE STADIUM 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By GEORGE VECSEY    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Judy Levering sat in her hotel room in the middle of
the night and jotted down four or five pages' worth of notes.
</P>
<P>
   Her prep work was worth it. Levering's arguments the next day
finally convinced her colleagues that the new stadium at the
National Tennis Center should be named after the late Arthur Ashe.
</P>
<P>
   The name is now an ancient tradition, as American stadiums go
these days, heading for its third U.S. Open on Monday. Saturday,
the place was bustling with Arthur Ashe Kids' Day, for fun and
charity, and Levering promises that the name will stand, unblighted
by the name of some transient corporate sponsor.
</P>
<P>
   In her first Open as the first female president of the U.S.
Tennis Association, Levering now has another challenge _ filling
the ludicrously oversized 21,000-seat stadium with actual tennis
fans.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to get more people in here,'' Levering said the
other day.
</P>
<P>
   She was standing on the floor of the handsome new stadium.
Workmen were bustling at the south end, installing a contraption
that will allow a television camera to zoom from one corner to
another (but not during points).
</P>
<P>
   Jim Courier was preparing for a workout on the main court.
Levering waved at him, a favorite for his devotion to Davis Cup
competition. Then she nodded at the seats just a few feet away.
</P>
<P>
   ``The players love to have an audience,'' Levering said.
</P>
<P>
   That does not always happen. For the first eight or nine days of
the Open, thousands of fans flock to the downsized Louis Armstrong
Stadium, thousands flock to the intimate grandstand, and thousands
more flock to the outer courts to literally peer over the players'
shoulders.
</P>
<P>
   What is worse, thousands of wine-sippers and shrimp-ingesters
hide out in the air-conditioned sanctums of the luxury boxes to
watch the soaps, to check up on their flitting fortunes in the
market, anything to avoid sitting in the elements and watching
tennis.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you put the stars in the stadium court, very often they
have easy matches in the early rounds,'' Levering said. ``People
might go to the hotly contested matches, and the stadium is
one-third empty.''
</P>
<P>
   Or one-third full. Like her friend and predecessor, Harry
Marmion, Levering seems genuinely committed to not doing what the
three other Grand Slam events have been doing, which is selling out
the secondary arenas, packing the grounds, and fairly forcing
people to stay in the main stadium.
</P>
<P>
   This is going to be hard to believe, given New York's
well-deserved reputation for venality and cacophony, but the Open
is now the most pleasant of Grand Slam events _ the courts more
accessible, the aisles less jammed, the services more available.
</P>
<P>
   ``I lived in London from 1976 through 1979 and it was just
starting,'' Levering said, with all due respect. ``This year at
Wimbledon I wanted to go over to watch Alexandra Stevenson, but I
had some duties in the Royal Box, and I could not even get to the
reserved area at the second court.''
</P>
<P>
   This year the Open will make available 1,000 grounds tickets for
each of the first nine days, at prices from $25 to $35, on sale
that day, theoretically making it easier for locals to get a
glimpse.
</P>
<P>
   Levering reminds New Yorkers that the center, open year round,
``is the best public facility in the country.'' She thinks, as the
first female president, that she can make tennis more popular on
the grass-roots level.
</P>
<P>
   ``Men and women approach issues differently,'' she said the
other day. ``Women generally don't have big egos. We generally
don't always have to be right. Now that will change as women get
into situations where men have been. But in general, women
understand how things work at the community level because that's
how we've lived it. We've looked at values differently, been
involved in the rearing of children.''
</P>
<P>
   For all her interest in the care and handling of young people,
Levering has not yet persuaded recalcitrant youths named Sampras
and Agassi to come out for all Davis Cup play. She has had better
success with her peers in the USTA, who nicknamed her The Velvet
Hammer for her perseverance.
</P>
<P>
   This mannered white-haired grandmother (from Kansas City, Mo.,
and Lancaster, Pa., now living with her husband in Stowe, Vt.)
pushed board members to think beyond the lucrative but grubby
practice of courting a corporate name. She was convinced it should
be named for the Open and Wimbledon champion who was activist,
scholar, businessman, Davis Cup captain and hero for the way he
faced his early death from AIDS, acquired from a blood transfusion.
</P>
<P>
   ``We could have named it USTA Stadium or we could name it after
a person,'' Levering said. ``If it would be an outstanding player,
well, that is debatable, but Arthur was a champion who transcended
the sport. Every other sport would have loved to have Arthur Ashe
play that sport. We were lucky to have Arthur.''
</P>
<P>
   After writing down her thoughts, Levering convinced Marmion and
the others the next day. If she does nothing else, the name will be
a monument to her volunteer work with the USTA.
</P>
<P>
   During her two summers as president, Levering will search for a
method _ bribes or point of a gun or moral coercion _ to induce
denizens of the luxury boxes to emerge from the shadows to watch a
bit of tennis. They might even enjoy it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-28-99 1225EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990828.0121 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-28 12:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2738 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-TEN-SAMPRAS-NYT &LR;      08-28 1134
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-SAMPRAS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAMPRAS AIMS TO COLLECT A 13TH GEM AT U.S. OPEN 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By ROBIN FINN    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Perhaps he was an aerialist in another incarnation,
because Pete Sampras, not weighed down at all by his baggy shorts
and graphite racquet, surely has no fear of flying. Hitting new
heights has become part of his daily routine.
</P>
<P>
   On the grass at Wimbledon, his horizontal swan-dive volleys
mimic Superman taking off on a mission. On the hardcourts, his
vertical leaps pay out-of-context homage to the slam dunks of his
role model, Michael Jordan. And in the record books he is
attempting to hit the stratosphere during the next two weeks at the
U.S. Open.
</P>
<P>
   If Sampras, top-seeded as usual when the Open gets under way
Monday at the National Tennis Center, collects his fifth career
Open championship two weeks from Sunday, he will not only equal
Jimmy Connors' Open record but will become the only man to win 13
Grand Slam singles crowns.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no reason why I can't do it,'' a confident Sampras
said late last week on Long Island after a pre-Open hiatus at home
on his couch in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   The rest was designed to heal the right hip flexor injury that
curtailed his formidable midsummer winning streak at 24 victories.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm back on hardcourts,'' he said. ``I love this time of year.
I'm right where I want to be, and it certainly would be nice to
break the record here where it all started.''
</P>
<P>
   He was referring to the 1990 Grand Slam breakthrough that made
him the Open's youngest men's champion at 19.
</P>
<P>
   Now at age 28 and top-ranked for a record six years in
succession, Sampras, whose game possesses a completeness and
complexity his contemporaries have been able to challenge only in
spurts, has just entered his 275th week at No. 1 after eclipsing
Lendl's record of 270 weeks this summer.
</P>
<P>
   In July, Sampras handcuffed the 29-year-old Andre Agassi, this
year's French Open champion, in a stirring Wimbledon final that
earned Sampras his sixth title there and his 12th Slam over all.
The feat tied him with Roy Emerson for the career Grand Slam
record.
</P>
<P>
   Emerson, who earned half of his dozen titles on home turf at the
Australian Open, said it would be unrealistic to not expect Sampras
to break his 32-year-old record.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously it's going to be done,'' the 62-year-old Emerson
said last week from Newport Beach, Calif. ``I think Pete is a great
champion. His strokes are terrific on both sides. He can serve like
crazy. He can also play the net. He's great for all the young
players in America to emulate. The only way I think you can get to
Pete is if his serve goes off a bit. He's a tough customer.''
</P>
<P>
   Ever since Sampras regrouped after yet another dismal exit from
the French Open, the only Slam to thwart him, he has been the
toughest customer in tennis. Just ask his closest rivals, the
two-time U.S. Open champion, Patrick Rafter, seeded to meet Sampras
in the semifinals. Or ask the 1994 Open champion Agassi, seeded to
face Sampras in the final.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's starting to become scary for the rest of the players and
becoming a habit for Pete; you know if he's in that sort of form
going into the Open, it's going to be tough,'' Rafter said about
Sampras' summer tear.
</P>
<P>
   The 24-match tear started with his Wimbledon tuneup at Queens
and carried him to hardcourts titles at Los Angeles and Cincinnati,
and included the closure of worrisome losing streaks against Rafter
(three matches) and the 1996 Wimbledon champion Richard Krajicek
(four) before ending in a default because of injury in the
quarterfinals at Indianapolis after he tweaked his hip performing
an airborne maneuver.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got everything; we all know that,'' said Rafter, who
admitted to being ``intimidated the whole time'' by Sampras' serve
in their Cincinnati final.
</P>
<P>
   ``I beat the guys I needed to beat this summer,'' said Sampras,
whose recent conquests include three victories against his
archrival, the second-ranked Agassi.
</P>
<P>
   Now 10-16 against Sampras, with losses to him in the 1990 and
1995 Open finals, Agassi provided a letter of recommendation for
the game Sampras brings to the Open.
</P>
<P>
   ``He can hit four corners with a number of various spins as well
as pace,'' Agassi said. ``He can cover the forehand, run better
than anybody in the game. He can go from defense to offense in the
matter of a split second. He can stay back and rally with the best
of them or chip and come in like he's Pat Rafter.''
</P>
<P>
   Agassi also finds a panorama of personalities in the
Californian's style. ``He can take on a lot of faces out there and
you never know which one he's going to bring to which point,''
Agassi said. ``He's obviously made himself the guy to beat again.
He played inspired tennis at Wimbledon and he hasn't stopped
since.''
</P>
<P>
   The only Slam where Sampras has not played up to his potential
is the French Open. Emerson is convinced Sampras should have won it
by now, as is Rod Laver, the only man to twice win all four Grand
Slams in a calendar year, hence his positioning in the record books
as the greatest player of the century.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Laver has summed it up pretty well, that if Sampras is
going to go down as the greatest ever, the experts say he's got to
win a French Open,'' Rafter said. ``But on every other surface,
he's probably the greatest ever.''
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Laver said he did not think Sampras had to win the
French to prove himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``His career stands up pretty good on its own,'' Laver said.
``That doesn't mean he can't win it, but it's a tough row to hoe.
And I don't believe in that greatest ever stuff, anyhow. I think
you have to stay in your own era, and certainly he is the best of
his, even without the French. He's already done so much he's
complete without it.''
</P>
<P>
   Sampras' successful retention of the year-end No. 1 ranking in
1998, which broke a tie with Connors, and his successful defense of
his 1998 Wimbledon title, which fulfilled his personal prerequisite
of collecting at least one Slam a year, have landed him at the Open
in a sanguine frame of mind.
</P>
<P>
   Sampras said: ``Will I be able to go to sleep at night and eat
my meals if I'm not No. 1? The answer is yes, because I haven't
been No. 1 every week of my career. It's not an obsession. But I
feel like if I'm playing the tennis I should be playing, and I'm
healthy, I should be there. As far as this Open goes, it's open but
not that open. I've played the kind of tennis going into it to make
me feel like I'm in serious contention.
</P>
<P>
   ``Can I win it? Sure I can, but if I don't, I'll still feel like
this has been a good year for me. It was a big relief winning
Wimbledon, because I felt like I achieved my main goal. Now I'm
just riding the wave and I hope that wave doesn't crash anytime
soon.''  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-28-99 1229EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
