<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-28 12:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2743 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-CHASS-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      08-28 0894
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHASS-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THERE'S NO USE CRYING OVER RUINED 12-YEAR-OLD ARMS 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By MURRAY CHASS    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The people who every August give us the opportunity to watch the
spectacle of 12-year-old boys crying on national television boast
of Hall of Famers who played in their leagues across the country,
the leagues with the capital L's.
</P>
<P>
   Nolan Ryan, George Brett and Robin Yount, the newest Hall of
Famers, we are told, played Little League Baseball. So did Catfish
Hunter, Tom Seaver, Jim Palmer and a few others. Chances are,
however, these players would be in the Hall of Fame if they had
played pickup baseball in their neighborhood playgrounds or parks.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, how many more good players could have come
out of those playgrounds and parks over the years if left to their
own devices and not restricted by the straitjacket practices
engendered by Little League and other youth organizations?
</P>
<P>
   ``In the generations we grew up in,'' said Larry Rothschild,
manager of the Tampa Bay Devil Rays, ``when you wanted to play
baseball, you went to the park and played all day long and threw
and threw and threw. I remember being told just come home when the
street lights go on. The only way kids play baseball today is
organized baseball. Moms drive them to practice and pick them up.
You never see kids with their glove on the handlebars of their
bicycle going to the park. You don't see kids playing without
supervision.''
</P>
<P>
   What is seen in Little League games is pitchers dazzling
opposing hitters with curveballs. Those 12-year-old curveballs are
so impressive ESPN announcers wax poetic about them while ESPN
cameras zoom in on the hitters they struck out and now are in tears
from the humiliation of letting their teams down on national
television.
</P>
<P>
   So much has been studied and written about the dangers of
pre-teen-agers throwing curveballs that by now Little League might
have listened and imposed rules outlawing the pitch just as it
mandates the maximum number of innings a youngster can pitch, oh,
that is, unless it's tournament time and then the limit rises.
</P>
<P>
   ``Until the bone plates have closed, generally around 14 or 15,
you have to be very careful with the curveball,'' Rothschild, a
former pitcher, said.
</P>
<P>
   ``When can he or she learn to throw a curve?'' asks one recent
publication, The Physician and Sportsmedicine. The answer:
</P>
<P>
   ``Throwing a curveball increases the risk of injury because
forceful supination and ulnar deviation places more medial stress
on the forearm. Safe mechanics for throwing the curveball are
difficult to master before the age of 13 or 14.''
</P>
<P>
   David Osinski, executive director of the American Baseball
Foundation in Birmingham, Ala., agrees. ``When you release the ball
throwing any pitch, the hand turns outward from the body,'' Osinski
said in a telephone interview. ``Most people who teach the curve
require that the pitch be thrown turning the hand in toward the
body. You're asking your body to do something that's not normal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Normal movement is for the hand to go away from the body once
the ball is released. By doing it the other way purposely, you're
putting more stress on the shoulder and the elbow. So for a young
child who can barely control his body, to ask him to change the way
he moves his hand is quite demanding.''
</P>
<P>
   What is a safe age for youngsters to start tinkering with the
curveball?
</P>
<P>
   ``The trite way,'' Osinski said, ``is to say when you're old
enough to shave. The idea is to wait until you have a
well-developed young athlete and his bones have fused. We probably
inhibit the competitiveness of the pitchers who come to us because
we don't teach them the curve until they're 14.''
</P>
<P>
   The coach of the Toms River, N.J., Little League team defended
the use of curveballs by his pitchers, including his son, saying
that he has his pitchers apply ice to their throwing arms after
games. He has evidently discovered a secret that physicians and
professionals haven't, that the application of ice hastens the
fusing of bones.
</P>
<P>
   But Little League coaches love the curveball as much as their
pitchers. ``Kids can't hit breaking balls,'' Rothschild said, ``so
pitchers throw it and strike out hitters. They like it so much they
don't throw enough fastballs and don't develop their arm that
way.''
</P>
<P>
   That's another element that works against the development of
modern-day Seavers and Palmers. Dave Duncan, the noted St. Louis
pitching coach, said fewer and fewer power pitchers are coming
along, and he attributed the decrease to the decline of throwing in
general and playing long toss in particular.
</P>
<P>
   When kids pick up a ball only for Little League purposes, they
are doing their arms a disservice, he and other professionals said.
</P>
<P>
   Adding a variation on that theme, Rothschild said: ``If you
don't play by yourself and have a chance to experiment, it's
putting everyone in a little box. You get a lot of similarities.
Little League coaches don't let kids develop their own
personalities.''
</P>
<P>
   Playing all day long with friends rather than uniformed
teammates, the Devils Rays' manager said, is where the creativity
comes in, ``the uniqueness in a delivery or a batting stance.''
</P>
<P>
   Rothschild added: ``There has to be some personality playing the
game. We've lost that.''
</P>
<P>
   The losers even cry alike.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-28-99 1236EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990828.0123 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-28 12:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2745 &Cx1f; var-z
u i BC-TURKEY-QUAKE-CORRUPT-     08-28 1081
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TURKEY-QUAKE-CORRUPT-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TURKISH QUAKE'S SECRET ACCOMPLICE: CORRUPTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
 (NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact Olivia Vasquez in Los
Angeles (Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089)  
 (bl)  
 By STEPHEN KINZER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ISTANBUL, Turkey _ It is common to refer to earthquakes as
natural disasters, but the one that took thousands of lives in
Turkey this month was more than that. Many of the victims would
have survived if their homes had been built in accordance with
basic safety standards. Instead they were built with cheap
materials by contractors who had learned they could make up in
corruption what they lacked in skill and experience.
</P>
<P>
   Turkey is home to some of the world's most respected
construction companies, which have built hotels, airports and
housing projects not only here but across Asia, North Africa and
the former Soviet Union. The earthquake showed, however, that there
are also many ignorant and unscrupulous contractors. They have made
their way to success through bribery and other forms of dishonesty,
and the system that brought them wealth must now share the blame
for the tragedy that has brought Turkey to its knees.
</P>
<P>
   Corruption in Turkey is not as pervasive as it is in many nearby
countries. Government jobs are not for sale to the highest bidder,
as they are in Azerbaijan. Teachers and doctors do not demand
payoffs for their services, as they do in Georgia. Theft is still
uncommon, and there have been remarkably few cases of looting in
the aftermath of the quake. This reflects a culture in which
murderers are sometimes esteemed because they are presumed to have
acted in defense of family honor, while thieves are despised for
violating one of God's most elemental laws.
</P>
<P>
   But in recent years, the kind of corruption that has crippled
many nations' development efforts has begun to take hold in Turkey.
It is a trend this country will have to confront and reverse if it
hopes to join the European Union and become a fully trusted partner
of the West.
</P>
<P>
   Turkey was for years an inward-looking country where foreign
travel was discouraged, possession of many imported items was a
crime and private enterprise was choked by a host of regulations.
These restrictions effectively cut Turkey off from the world, but
they also insulated the country against worldwide trends like
corruption. National leaders valued propriety above economic
growth, and most ordinary people followed their example.
</P>
<P>
   All that changed in the mid 1980s with the emergence of Turgut
Ozal, a giant political figure who proved to be the most
revolutionary leader Turkey had seen since Mustafa Kemal Ataturk
half a century before. As prime minister and later as president,
Ozal flung open doors and windows that had been tightly shut for
decades, freeing what proved to be the enormous energies of Turkish
entrepreneurs.
</P>
<P>
   It was a profoundly important step, and it brought Turkey into
the international mainstream in a very short time. But as Ozal
urged Turks to free themselves from the outmoded rules that had
held them back for so long, he also seemed to send a subtle message
that rules in general were bad. Some ambitious Turks understood him
to say that getting rich was such an important and wonderful goal
that it didn't matter how one accomplished it.
</P>
<P>
   What sort of business could an unschooled and capital-poor Turk
launch to propel him on the road to wealth? Thousands chose to
start construction companies, relying on the help of friends in
local politics to win contracts. In a wide-open economy that was
growing at an astonishing rate, many of these contractors quickly
became rich.
</P>
<P>
   The price that society paid for their rise to wealth became
tragically clear when this month's earthquake struck. The
contractors had built countless apartment blocks with sandy
concrete and reinforcing rods far too weak to withstand the forces
of nature that regularly shake the country.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the blame must be apportioned to a social system in
which everything is negotiable and friends always help each other.
If a mayor or other public official has a friend or relative who
owns a construction company, tradition dictates that they make some
arrangement so both can prosper. To allow such deals to founder
simply because the contractor lacks capital or experience or
training would seem hard-hearted.
</P>
<P>
   In the days following the earthquake, furious survivors sought
to lynch several contractors who had made careers of building poor
housing that collapsed like cards when the ground began to shake.
But the contractors, realizing that they would become targets, had
disappeared.
</P>
<P>
   The contractors are not the only guilty parties. Buyers of homes
are also complicit in the system that led to the unnecessary deaths
of so many people. Turkey has suffered great social dislocation
over the last two decades, with millions of migrants streaming out
of the impoverished and war-torn southeast to prosperous western
towns. Many were eager to buy new apartments for $15,000 or less,
and didn't worry about safety. Inspectors were never around to
spoil the party, and as a result, many of those apartments became
tombs.
</P>
<P>
   In many countries, the popular anger that this quake has
produced might have led the government to fall. But in Turkey,
everyone realizes that it is not simply the current government that
is responsible. It is the state itself, and the culture of
irresponsibility it has fostered.
</P>
<P>
   Turks have traditionally maintained an exaggerated respect for
the state and its institutions. That respect began to crumble in
1996, when a spectacular scandal revealed the state's involvement
with gangsters, assassins and drug smugglers. Now it has suffered
another blow, which deeply disturbs some senior political and
military leaders because it weakens their psychological hold on
their people.
</P>
<P>
   But if the earthquake leads Turks to recognize the need to
accept and obey rules in order to promote the general good, if it
leads them to demand more accountability from their leaders instead
of assuming that ``devlet baba'' _ Daddy State _ always knows best,
it may turn out to be a turning point for this highly dynamic but
still unformed country.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-28-99 1239EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990828.0124 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
