<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990828.0126 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-28 12:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2748 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-TIMOR-VOTE-ART-660(2T     08-28 0721
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TIMOR-VOTE-ART-660(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FEARFUL OF MILITIAS, EAST TIMOR TO VOTE ON ITS FUTURE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A locator map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(js) 
 By SETH MYDANS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DILI, Indonesia _ After 24 years of bloodshed and fear, East
Timor has reached its moment of truth, a referendum on Monday that
could lead it into a new era of freedom and reconciliation or one
of even fiercer civil war.
</P>
<P>
   The referendum offers a choice between independence or an
autonomous relationship with Indonesia, which invaded this former
Portuguese colony in 1975 and has fought against separatist rebels
ever since.
</P>
<P>
   But as the vote has drawn near, what should have been an
election campaign in this tiny, remote territory has been instead a
campaign of terror by brutal, rag-tag militias that oppose
independence.
</P>
<P>
   The militias, backed and organized by the Indonesian military,
have largely ignored appeals for calm from the United Nations,
which deployed here in May to organize the referendum. On Friday,
Secretary-General Kofi Annan said he was ``appalled'' by the
continuing attacks and demanded that Indonesian forces fulfill
their obligation to maintain order.
</P>
<P>
   If they lose the vote and East Timor becomes free _ as most
analysts now predict _ leaders of these militias proclaim that they
will turn this South Pacific territory into ``a sea of blood.''
</P>
<P>
   With East Timor's history of warfare and revenge, both sides in
the conflict are more likely to return to battle rather than to
accept defeat, a number of Indonesian and foreign analysts predict.
</P>
<P>
   But beneath the fear that has gripped East Timor's 800,000
people, there is a tremor of hope, seen most vividly on Wednesday,
when thousands of people gathered in the streets to cheer
independence, waving the green, blue and white flag of East Timor,
which had been banned.
</P>
<P>
   Jose Alexandre Gusmao, the jailed separatist leader who could
become head of an independent East Timor, said last week while
under house arrest in Jakarta that he would declare an amnesty for
combatants in the long-running conflict.
</P>
<P>
   Indonesian officials say they will allow Gusmao to return to
East Timor shortly after the vote.
</P>
<P>
   If the military withdraws its support, the tough-talking militia
leaders could find that their best option is accommodation. ``There
is a feeling that we are on the verge of something that could be
marvelous for East Timor, a release from 24 years of hurt _ but
people are afraid to hope too much,'' said James Dunn, who was the
last Australian consul to a Portuguese-controlled East Timor.
</P>
<P>
   Since the 1975 invasion, at least 200,000 people are believed to
have died in the endless fighting, a proportion of the population
that Dunn compared to the mass killings by the Communist Khmer
Rouge in Cambodia in the late 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   For Indonesia, too, East Timor has been an open sore, costing as
much as $100 million a year to subdue and administer, arousing
continuing condemnation abroad and requiring, at the peak of the
fighting, the deployment of as many as 40,000 troops.
</P>
<P>
   Indonesia seems to have been able to do nothing right in East
Timor, and the endgame that has arrived now with unexpected
suddenness seems as clumsy and self-defeating as the long-running
occupation.
</P>
<P>
   The referendum is the brainchild of President B.J. Habibie, who
surprised many in his own government by announcing in January that
if East Timor rejects his offer of autonomy he will simply let it
go free.
</P>
<P>
   Under his proposal Indonesia would continue to be responsible
for the territory's external defense, foreign policy, parts of the
judicial process and currency.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do not want to be burdened with the problem of East Timor
after Jan. 1, 2000,'' Habibie said.
</P>
<P>
   This quick timetable ignored most proposals for solving the
problem of East Timor. Even the territory's separatist leaders had
argued that it would need a transition period of several years
before voting on independence.
</P>
<P>
   ``By ignoring confidence-building measures from both sides, he
is making a new hell in East Timor,'' said J. Kristiadi, a
political scientist in Jakarta.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The change in policy also ignored the deep commitment of
Indonesia's armed forces to East Timor _ the only battleground in
their history, the proving ground of most top generals and the
graveyard of thousands of their comrades.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, many in the military fear that if East Timor is
allowed to break away, separatist demands could be accelerated in
other troubled regions of Indonesia, particularly Aceh, Irian Jaya
and the Moluccas.
</P>
<P>
   The military has repeatedly disavowed any involvement in the
violence here, but its denials have taken on a slapdash quality in
the face of clear evidence that includes open gatherings of militia
fighters in military compounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most disturbing aspect of what we see here is that there
seems to be, from what I can see, not even any pretense by the
military to be operating under the civilian government,'' said a
Jakarta-based diplomat.
</P>
<P>
   Almost immediately after Habibie's announcement in January, the
military began recruiting and organizing the armed militias, a
collection of farmers and unemployed young men with greater or
lesser commitments to or understanding of their political cause.
</P>
<P>
   ``The pattern is to try and intimidate people from voting either
by direct threats of physical violence now or by threatening dire
consequences after the vote,'' said David Wimhurst, the spokesman
for the United Nations in East Timor.
</P>
<P>
   For much of this year the militias have carried out attacks on
villages deemed to be strongly in favor of independence and have
forced as many as 60,000 people to flee their homes _ nearly 15
percent of the 450,000 registered voters.
</P>
<P>
   The United Nations has taken pains to allow these displaced
people to participate in the referendum.
</P>
<P>
   As the vote nears, the violence has escalated along with a quiet
campaign of terror in which people have been kidnapped, threatened
and forced into hiding.
</P>
<P>
   If Habibie was trying to remove an irritant from Indonesia's
public image, his policy seems to have backfired. Both Secretary of
State Madeleine Albright and members of Congress have condemned the
violence.
</P>
<P>
   Former President Jimmy Carter _ whose human rights and diplomacy
organization, the Carter Center, is monitoring the referendum here
_ said this month that ``Some top representatives of the government
of Indonesia have failed to fulfill their main obligations with
regard to public order and security.''
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``Indonesian military and other government agencies
are supporting, directing and arming pro-integration militias to
create a climate of fear and violence.''
</P>
<P>
   As much as its past has been violent and harsh, the future of
East Timor is a troubled one, even under the best of scenarios.
</P>
<P>
   Remote and poverty-ridden, with few natural resources other than
coffee plantations, East Timor would have difficulty surviving on
its own, even with promised infusions for foreign aid. Indonesia
currently provides about 90 percent of East Timor's operating
budget.
</P>
<P>
   The territory's human resources are just as thin. During its
years of occupation, Indonesia has imported administrators to run
government agencies, schools, utilities and transport. Virtually
all of these people are expected to depart if East Timor becomes
independent.
</P>
<P>
   In a recent conversation, one pro-independence leader talked
hopefully about the example of Singapore, a tiny resource-poor
island nation that survived and prospered by its wits.
</P>
<P>
   It is an example that only underscores the hardships faced by
East Timor: As many as 80 percent of the people here are
illiterate.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
