<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-28 13:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2758 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r f BC-POKEMON-MOVIE-2TAKES-     08-28 0643
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POKEMON-MOVIE-2TAKES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PREPARE FOR THE POKEMON INVASION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY DAVE McNARY  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- If you haven't hung around 8-year-old boys
lately, you probably don't know the next wave of globalization has
already arrived in the form of Pikachu, Raichu and 149 other
animated Pokemon characters.
</P>
<P>
   Pokemon -- the Japanese name for ``pocket monster'' -- is
becoming more prominent each day in the United States with a
mind-boggling array of video games, trading cards, clothing and
toys along with its own TV show. And in a reversal of the usual
practice of American hit films going to foreign markets, a
made-in-Japan Pokemon movie will arrive at U.S. multiplexes Nov.
12.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, ``Pokemon'' won't be the first Japanese animated movie
to show up in theaters this fall. ``Princess Mononoke,'' Japan's
second-highest grosser of all time after ``Titanic,'' will open in
the 20 biggest U.S. markets Oct. 29. But it's ``Pokemon'' that has
emerged as a potential sleeper hit.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pokemon is the only thing kids are talking about these days,''
said Merrill Lynch analyst Andrew Slaban. ``The movie could do very
well.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Pokemon the Movie: Mewtwo Strikes Back,'' made by Shogakukan
Productions Co., was the fourth-highest grosser in Japan last year.
Warner Bros. has renamed it ``Pokemon: The First Movie'' for its
U.S. release and recently began a low-key ad campaign with trailers
and lobby posters. A sequel for next summer is already in the
works.
</P>
<P>
   More impressively, the studio assigned ``Pokemon'' a valuable
opening date -- one where the target audience of kids 5 to 13 are
still in school but on the verge of having vacation time around
Thanksgiving and the winter holidays. What's especially bold about
Warner's move is that the slot is a mere dozen days before Disney
debuts its expected holiday season blockbuster, ``Toy Story 2.''
</P>
<P>
   But trackers believe the craze over Pokemon -- which mostly
resemble plush-toy versions of cats, hamsters and dogs -- will be
even hotter at that point. ``I suspect that Pokemon has not yet
crested in this country,'' said Martin Brochstein, editor of the
Licensing Letter. ``It's been big, but the real thrust of
merchandise has only started to hit shelves.''
</P>
<P>
   Pokemon is already a certifiable marketing bonanza. As children
return to school this month, rest assured they will be wearing
Pokemon T-shirts and carrying Pokemon trading cards, toys, comic
books and Game Boy videos. Some schools already have barred Pokemon
cards from campuses as being too much of a distraction.
</P>
<P>
   ``We as adults may be a little naive about the true extent that
U.S. kids nowadays have gravitated to Japanese culture,'' asserted
entertainment analyst Kevin Skislock of Laguna Research Partners.
``Japanese-sourced entertainment product is a much bigger part of
the lives of kids under 16 than people over 16 realize.''
</P>
<P>
   For those wondering what the fuss is about, here are the facts:
</P>
<P>
   ----The Pokemon craze is 4 years old in Japan and still going
strong. Need proof? Three All Nippon Airways jumbo jets are
decorated with Pokemon characters.
</P>
<P>
   __Nintendo Co., which owns the property, already has sold more
than 4 million Pokemon-based games in this country.
</P>
<P>
   __New York-based 4 Kids Entertainment, the exclusive licensing
agent for Nintendo in countries outside Japan, has signed 90
licensing deals in this country.
</P>
<P>
   __The ``Pokemon'' TV show became the top-rated syndicated
children's program within a few months of its launch; it now is the
highest-rated series for kids on Saturday mornings.
</P>
<P>
   __The WB Network will become the exclusive broadcaster of
``Pokemon'' in U.S. markets with the fall season and plans to
telecast a dozen new episodes per week.
</P>
<P>
   (STORY CONTINUES ON NEW TAKE)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
