<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARIZ-ABORTION-FIGHT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
14-YEAR-OLD GIRL IS FOCUS OF DEBATE OVER A LATE-TERM ABORTION 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By DAVID SCHWARTZ   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ She has been in state care since she was 5 years old,
and is described by the authorities as a frequent runaway from
foster and group homes. Her mother died in January. Her father is
absent.
</P>
<P>
   Now, this 14-year-old ward of the state is at the heart of a
highly charged public debate in Arizona because a local judge has
granted her request for a late-term abortion. The case is being
watched by those on both sides of the abortion issue because of the
girl's age and the controversy over late-term abortions.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona officials confirmed this week that Judge William
Sargeant of Maricopa County Superior Court had ordered state child
welfare workers to send the girl, who is 24 weeks pregnant, out of
state to have the abortion. State law allows late-term abortions,
but doctors in Arizona generally do not perform them past 20 weeks.
</P>
<P>
   It remained uncertain Saturday whether the abortion would take
place. The case has unleashed impassioned protests by abortion
opponents and state lawmakers since word of it was leaked to an
anti-abortion group. The Arizona Republic reported on Friday that
Sargeant was reconsidering his decision.
</P>
<P>
   Conservatives including Republican presidential candidate Steve
Forbes and Dr. Laura Schlessinger, the syndicated talk show host,
have weighed in to oppose the decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a very unfortunate situation that's really sad,'' said
Francie Noyes, a spokeswoman for Gov. Jane Dee Hull. ``Nobody is
happy about this, but it's a court order. The girl requested this,
and it's been carefully evaluated by experts close to her.''
</P>
<P>
   Details of the case remain sketchy because of the
confidentiality granted juveniles. Court records are sealed, and
all hearings have been closed.
</P>
<P>
   Officials have disclosed that the girl asked for the abortion
several months ago and then ran away, and that it was not until
recently that she was back in state custody.
</P>
<P>
   The girl's request was granted after the court was told that the
pregnancy was the result of rape and that the mother had since used
``myriad illegal drugs,'' said Maurice Portley, the presiding
juvenile court judge, in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   State officials said the girl was again counseled on her options
late this week, and she told them that she still wanted to have an
abortion.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a 14-year-old kid,'' Ms. Noyes said. ``Everyone wants
to make sure that we have done everything we can. And we think we
have.''
</P>
<P>
   The abortion would be paid for with federal money, which can be
used in cases where a pregnancy is the result of rape or incest, or
poses a threat to the health of the mother.
</P>
<P>
   But abortion opponents say the state has no business in this
area.
</P>
<P>
   ``The state should have an interest in fostering life, not in
supporting, sanctioning and otherwise becoming involved in
fostering the death of a child,'' said John Jakubczyk, president of
Arizona Right to Life, the anti-abortion group that was told of the
case.
</P>
<P>
   Jakubczyk said the impact of the abortion would be lasting.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any time you destroy a child, that has to be a negative for
the person involved,'' he said. ``You can't even imagine what the
psychological impact will be on her life.''
</P>
<P>
   An official from Planned Parenthood of Central and Northern
Arizona said the case was no different from sending a patient
elsewhere because care was not available.
</P>
<P>
   ``Were this heart surgery and the facilities were not there to
treat her, we would not hesitate to take her to another state for
care,'' said Joseph Feldman, the group's education and counseling
director. ``This is the same.''
</P>
<P>
   Providers of abortion said pregnant women regularly were forced
to cross state lines for a variety of reasons to be able to obtain
the procedure.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
