Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   GORE-PRIMARIES _ MANCHESTER, N.H. - Vice President Al Gore is
well ahead of his only opponent, Bill Bradley, in building a
campaign organization in the key primary states of Iowa and New
Hampshire. Bradley may have the money to go the distance, but the
Gore forces are so entrenched in the early primary states that he
may deliver an early knockout punch. (Shepard, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   Eds: MOVED Friday in (w) Washington and (p) politics categories.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   TAX-STAKES _ WASHINGTON _ Analysts disagree whether the
Republican or Democratic approach to cutting taxes and dealing with
projected budget surpluses would help the economy more. But they
agree that the decision could have a huge long-term impact on the
nation's economy. (Deans, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   Eds: MOVED Tuesday in (w) Washington and (f) financial
categories.
</P>
<P>
   SCHOOL-BUS _ WASHINGTON _ Education Secretary Richard Riley,
celebrities and school officials, all seeking to involve more
parents and citizens in their local schools, take a three-day
``back to school bus tour'' this week through Tennessee, Alabama,
Georgia, North Carolina and South Carolina. (Mollison, Cox News
Service).
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
<P>
   Eds: MOVED Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   YUGOSLAVIA-OPPOSITION _ BELGRADE, Yugoslavia _ NATO's
devastating air-bombardment campaign rearranged entire landscapes
at ground level, but a couple of facts important to Serbia's
beleaguered and frustrated democratic opposition remain firmly in
place. First, Yugoslav president Slobodan Milosevic, still rules.
And second, the Clinton Administration's policy of using economic
isolation and bare humanitarian assistance to force Milosevic's
removal hasn't budged. (Jolidon, Cox News Service) M0VED.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   YUGOSLAVIA-BOX _ A thumbnail box of Serb Democratic opposition
leaders. (Jolidon, Cox News Service) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   PUERTORICO-VIEQUES _ VIEQUES, Puerto Rico _ Sixty years of U.S.
Navy bombing practice and mock invasions on this small island off
Puerto Rico's east coast have outraged residents, sparking numerous
protests and an investigation by a Clinton-appointed commission.
The panel is scheduled to issue recommendations in August, but may
be delayed as new issues keep cropping up, including claims that
the bombing has led to increased cancer rates among Vieques' 9,000
residents. Puerto Rico's normally fractious political parties have
united on the issue, with Gov. Pedro Rossello leading the call for
the Navy to leave Vieques, clean up its toxic waste and other bomb
damage and pay residents for the years it has crippled their
economy. We visit a small encampment of protesters who are
occupying a part of the bombing range and vow not to leave until
the Navy does. (MWilliams, Cox News Service). WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: MOVED Wed., Aug. 25.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-FALUNGONG _ BEIJING _ A story focusing on the incredible
propaganda push that continues in China against the Falun Gong
religious sect, which is being portrayed as a treasonous and
dangerous force out to destroy decent Chinese society. Apparently,
the government anti-Falun Gong campaign is having considerable
success. People are being convinced to leave the movement, as
exemplified by a little old shoemaker who told Cox Newspapers
recently that he suddenly was awakened to the treachery of the
movement by all the news. (Kunstel/Albright, Cox News Service).
WITH PHOTOS. MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: FALUNGONG-BOX. MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-INTERNET _ VOLOGRAD, Russia _ An Internet provider in the
city of Volograd, has taken the FSB (formerly the KGB) to court
claiming that the spy agency's operatives have been violating
privacy laws by snooping on Russian email Internet activity. The
allegation is that the government ``Big Brother'' attitude, thought
to have died down after the Cold War ended, is pretty widespread.
(Holmes, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: MOVED Thurs., Aug. 26, in both International/Financial
categories.
</P>
<P>
   OPED/EDITORIAL
</P>
<P>
   EDITORIAL-NEWT29 _ News of his affair has exposed Newg Gingrich
to charges of hypocrisy, not to mention a substantial bit of
snickering. Some of that's deserved. The man who decried what he
called ``a multicultural, nihilistic hedonism that is inherently
destructive of a healthy society,'' and who blamed liberals for
Woody Allen's affair with his stepdaughter and for Susan Smith's
murder of her two children, can't expect much sympathy when the
chickens come to roost on his own bedpost. However, on the most
specific and damaging charge of hypocrisy _ that Gingrich was
bashing Bill Clinton for immorality even while he himself carried
on with a House employee _ the issue is a little more complicated.
Because even as other Republicans were calling Clinton everything
up to and including rapist, Gingrich largely refrained. The record
of that period instead reveals Gingrich struggling with a deeply
personal dilemma. (Bookman, Atlanta Constitution). MOVED THURSDAY.
</P>
<P>
   TEEPEN-COLUMN _ Generation X-ers who remember the olden times
B.MTV. (Before MTV) can only stare dumbfounded at the sight of the
American Medical Association throwing in with a Democratic-led plan
for federal regulation of the practice of medicine. (Tom Teepen is
national correspondent for Cox Newspapers.) MOVED THURSDAY.
</P>
<P>
   KLEINBERG-COLUMN _ MIAMI _ This is the lousy part. There is a
storm out there, somewhere between there and here. It's sitting,
deciding which way to go, growing in strength. And you don't know
when to panic. (Howard Kleinberg is a columnist for Cox News
Service.) Eds: MOVED Thursday for immediate release.
</P>
<P>
   GLASS-COLUMN _ WASHINGTON _ Each year, a radio station
hereabouts sponsors a ``Christmas in August'' festival. It could
serve as metaphor for a time when most voters, while far from ready
to select the next occupant of the White House, don't mind
listening to some unseasonal mood music. (Andy Glass is a columnist
for Cox News Service in the Washington bureau.) MOVES THURSDAY.
</P>
