<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-28 14:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2777 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-VENEZUELA-CRISIS-NYT &LR;      08-28 0814
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VENEZUELA-CRISIS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRISIS DEEPENS IN VENEZUELA AS LEGISLATORS SPURN ACCORD
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By LARRY ROHTER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   CARACAS, Venezuela _ The political and constitutional crisis
here deepened Saturday as an agreement to avoid a confrontation
between Congress and a new constitutional assembly, both of which
claim to have supreme legislative authority, appeared to have
foundered. Legislators vowed to take steps to cripple the rival
constitutional panel.
</P>
<P>
   Stripped of their right to pass laws or even to meet as a result
of a decree the assembly handed down on Wednesday, members of
Congress retaliated by saying they would exercise one of the few
powers left to them and refuse to authorize the funds the
constitutional panel needs to operate.
</P>
<P>
   They also said they would withhold the legal permission
President Hugo Chavez needs to leave Venezuela for state visits
scheduled for next month.
</P>
<P>
   Elected last month, the constitutional assembly is dominated by
supporters of Chavez, a 45-year-old former army paratrooper who in
1992 led an unsuccessful coup attempt. After his release from jail,
Chavez promised to lead a ``peaceful social revolution'' that would
sweep away existing institutions like Congress and the Supreme
Court. He won an overwhelming victory at the polls last December
and took office in February.
</P>
<P>
   From the start, Chavez has argued that only a new constitution
will enable him to transform Venezuela. But since beginning its
deliberations early this month, the assembly charged with that duty
has sought to expand its powers, decreeing first a ``judicial
emergency'' that gives it power over the courts and then a
``legislative emergency'' that all but dissolves Congress, in which
opposition parties have a majority.
</P>
<P>
   An agreement brokered by the Roman Catholic Church and announced
Friday afternoon was supposed to diminish tensions by setting up a
commission to discuss the differences between Congress and the
assembly.
</P>
<P>
   But on Friday night, members of Congress, which had been in
recess, returned to their building, defying threats by government
security forces that they would be expelled.
</P>
<P>
   The legislators have quickly found an ally in the mayor of
Caracas, Antonio Ledezma. A member of Accion Democratica, one of
the two traditional political parties Chavez describes as corrupt
and useless, Ledezma offered the chambers of the city council, just
around the corner from the Congress building, to the lawmakers and
criticized Chavez for what he called ``usurpation of powers.''
</P>
<P>
   Furious, some Chavez supporters have responded by pressing for a
new, tougher decree that would formally dissolve Congress. Luis
Miquilena, president of the constitutional assembly and the
president's closest political adviser, said it was premature to
talk of such a step, but added, ``At this moment, given the
irrational attitudes, nothing can be ruled out.'' He accused
legislators of acting in bad faith.
</P>
<P>
   Miquilena complained that it was impossible to negotiate with
people who ``make a commitment, sign it and three hours later turn
their back on it.'' He said it might be necessary to ``amplify some
aspects'' of the original decree to avoid what he termed ``a power
vacuum.''
</P>
<P>
   Legislators, however, said that they had never authorized their
leaders to sign an agreement, especially one that, in their view,
offers them so little.
</P>
<P>
   They also threatened to replace the president of the Senate, who
is a Chavez ally, and the speaker of the House, accusing them of
failing to protect the interests of Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ``The majority of parliamentarians do not accept the terms of
the agreement because the constitutional assembly commits itself to
nothing, while we promise we will not hold any sessions,'' said
Mireya Rodriguez, a member of the lower house from the right-center
Project Venezuela party.
</P>
<P>
   This week, in an action likely to increase tensions, the
constitutional panel is expected to expand its powers further by
decreeing a state of ``executive emergency.'' Such a measure would
give an 11-member committee designated by the assembly the
authority to fire the governors of Venezuela's 23 states as well as
mayors like Ledezma.
</P>
<P>
   According to a draft of the proposal, all governors and mayors
would be ordered ``not to take any acts of governance or
administration contrary to the authority of the assembly.'' Those
dismissed by the assembly would be replaced by ``regional governing
councils composed of three or five members who enjoy high prestige
and honor in the community.''
</P>
<P>
   But efforts to solve the worsening crisis without further
confrontation are also under way. Henrique Capriles Radonsky, the
27-year-old speaker of the lower house of Congress, said he would
go to the Supreme Court this week and ask for a formal judgment on
the state of legislative emergency.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
