<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-28 14:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2782 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-WEST-WILDFIRES-ART-40     08-28 0848
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEST-WILDFIRES-ART-400&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SMOKE FROM WILDFIRES IN THE WEST PRODUCES THE WORST AIR IN 25
YEARS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Nev., Texas, Mont., Idaho, Ore., Wash.)  (ART ADV: A locator map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(js) 
 By EVELYN NIEVES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO, Calif. _ The fire season arrived early this year,
allowing no time to brace for its spectacular tantrums.
</P>
<P>
   In the last six days, major blazes raged across more than
150,000 acres in seven states, poisoning the air over Northern
California and testing more than 10,000 firefighters.
</P>
<P>
   By the weekend, more than two dozen serious wildfire clusters,
containing hundreds of individual fires, were burning in
California, Nevada, Oregon, Washington, Idaho, Montana and Texas.
</P>
<P>
   More than half the fires tore through Northern California, where
3,000 lightning strikes early last week torched the parched scrub
lands and forests.
</P>
<P>
   Six acres of grass, brush or timber were ablaze for every
available firefighter, officials said, leaving no choice but to let
some fires burn. Yellow-brown plumes of ashy air settled over
hundreds of miles of the northern third of California, causing what
air quality monitors called some of the worst pollution in the
state in 25 years.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, Gov. Gray Davis asked President Clinton to declare a
state of emergency in four northern counties. Many of the biggest
fires had simmered down, the California Department of Forestry and
Fire Protection said, but officials warned that the ordeal was far
from over and could become worse if hot, dry weather persisted.
</P>
<P>
   The fires were blamed for one death. In Butte County, in the
northeastern part of the state, a woman died on Tuesday when she
apparently became confused by the black smoke she was driving
toward and veered her truck into flames.
</P>
<P>
   No other injuries were reported, and the rash of blazes had
torched relatively few structures. But about 40,000 residents in
Butte County, where fires were consuming more than 20,000 acres,
were advised to stay on the alert for possible evacuation, said a
spokeswoman for the Department of Forestry.
</P>
<P>
   Fire departments around the country, from Alaska to Maine, have
brought teams and supplies to control the blazes. But resources
have been stretched so thin that requests for 800 additional
firefighters remained unfulfilled, the forestry department said.
</P>
<P>
   Jolene DeGroot, a department spokeswoman, said officials were
prepared to request additional assistance.
</P>
<P>
   ``And we can always turn to Canada and the military,'' Ms.
DeGroot said, ``if more help is necessary.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In northern Nevada, where fires have been breaking out for
weeks, firefighters stopped the spread of blazes that scorched
1,500 acres near Carson City, the state capital, and successfully
contained other fires near Elko and Winnemucca. They were close to
besting the fires over 30,000 acres about 45 miles west of Reno,
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   But in California, red flag warnings, the highest level of
alert, remained in effect Saturday for the entire northern part of
the state except for the coastline, said David Rowe, a fire weather
specialist at the National Weather Service here.
</P>
<P>
   Davis declared emergencies in Tehama, Butte, Tuolumne and Shasta
counties on Thursday, when it was clear that firefighters were
outgunned by the blazes, and ordered the California National Guard
to assist. The Guard brought in Blackhawk helicopters and C-130
cargo planes to carry supplies and firefighters into thick dense
forests and mountain land too difficult to reach by truck.
</P>
<P>
   Smoky air from the fires in Butte County drifted as far as
Oakland, 160 miles away.
</P>
<P>
   Teresa Lee, a spokeswoman for the Bay Area air quality
management district, said that the air filled with particulates
from the Butte fires had combined with the already smoggy air of
August to create the worst combination of pollution that reached
from the Bay Area to Sacramento that she had seen in 25 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an unusual combination,'' Ms. Lee said, because usually
the kind of smoke now hovering in the air is a winter phenomenon,
caused by wood-burning stoves and fireplaces.
</P>
<P>
   In Sacramento, about 65 miles south of the Butte County blazes,
the air combined with temperatures above 90 degrees on Thursday to
make stepping outside a test of endurance. The skyline was obscured
by a menacing fog, hospitals were inundated with calls from asthma
and allergy sufferers and the streets were empty.
</P>
<P>
   By Friday, following overnight rains, the air was visibly
cleaner and brighter. But people were still talking about what a
jewelry vendor called ``black Thursday.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm suffering today because of yesterday,'' said the vendor,
who sells Navajo jewelry and crafts in Old Sacramento. ``My
sinuses, my headaches, my allergies _ they're all going now. No one
has to tell anybody here that the fires in the Sierras are bad.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
