u p BC-POLITICAL-BRIEFS-NYT &LR;      08-28 1413
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POLITICAL-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLITICAL NOTES AND NEWS 
</HEADLINE>
  
(ATTN: Calif., Miss.) (jt) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Fraud Worries Greet a Vote-Delivery Bill
</P>
<P>
   Voter turnout lags in California, as in most states. But give
the Golden State credit for trying to improve participation.
</P>
<P>
   Registering to vote is easy. Sometimes newspapers distribute the
forms.
</P>
<P>
   Too busy, or lazy, to go to the polls on Election Day?
</P>
<P>
   Send in an absentee ballot, so readily available that many
candidates distribute the forms for requesting one and even offer
to deliver the completed application forms to election officials.
In the process, of course, the candidates usually manage to get in
a campaign pitch.
</P>
<P>
   One of every four Californians now votes by absentee ballot, a
participation rate six times what it was two decades ago when
absentee voting was restricted to voters who were hospitalized or
away on a trip. That already impressive rate would spurt even
higher if a few minor changes were made in state regulations, some
California legislators and get-out-the-vote advocates say.
</P>
<P>
   Under current law, absentee ballots must be mailed in, or if
sent in at the last minute, must be delivered by a family member.
But what would absentee participation be like if the law were
changed to allow someone other than a family member to make a
last-minute delivery?
</P>
<P>
   That seemed like a good idea to two Assembly members, Kevin
Shelley and Carole Migden, San Francisco Democrats whose districts
include many homebound elderly, many people involved in unmarried
or same-sex relationships and many young people living in group
houses. So earlier this summer, each put in a bill that would
authorize such a change, with the Migden measure being somewhat
more restrictive.
</P>
<P>
   Both measures were passed and forwarded to the Senate. That's no
great surprise because Democrats control the Assembly, and
California Democrats, like Democrats in most states, are always
looking for ways to increase voter participation.
</P>
<P>
   Over on the Senate side, Democrats are also in control. But the
legislative-going there for an election law change could be more
difficult. Since the Assembly voted for change, concern has spread
that if the law is modified to allow absentee ballots to be
delivered to election officials by someone other than a family
member, the door will be opened for widespread voting fraud.
</P>
<P>
   What would happen, wonders Secretary of State Bill Jones, if
candidates not only began organizing efforts to get people to
request absentee ballots but then began pushing to have the ballots
filled out and, at the same time, offered to deliver the marked
forms to election officials?
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to keep a fire wall up between campaigns and voters
when it comes to delivery of ballots,'' contended Jones,
California's top election official and also the top elected
Republican in the state.
</P>
<P>
   The Shelley and Migden bills, he warns, would open up loopholes
that candidates might use to slip in and begin controlling the
absentee balloting process.
</P>
<P>
   Shelley and Ms. Migden say they are as opposed as any Republican
to voting fraud. But they argue that ways must nevertheless be
found to increase voter participation, which has never been a
front-burner issue with many Republicans. They reason that the
people least inclined to vote are often the Democratic poor.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's never been a perfect bill to expand voter
participation,'' Shelley said.
</P>
<P>
   Off-Year House Race Intrigues Both Parties
</P>
<P>
   Ever since Rep. George E. Brown Jr., the veteran Democrat who
represented California's 42nd Congressional District, died last
month, Republicans have viewed the Sept. 21 special election that
will choose his successor as an opportunity to strengthen their
slim hold on the House. Democrats have seen the contest as a way to
weaken that hold.
</P>
<P>
   Both sides also think that a win in the 42nd, which lies east of
Los Angeles in the San Bernardino area and is closely divided
between Democrats and Republicans, could help give the victorious
party a jump-start heading into next year's House elections.
</P>
<P>
   But the September contest also seems likely to be important for
another reason. In the wake of last Monday's vote by the California
Legislature to outlaw production and sale of so-called Saturday
night special handguns, gun control has become an issue in the
race, maybe one of the bellwether issues for Election 2000.
</P>
<P>
   One of the leading Democratic contenders for the Brown seat,
state Sen. Joe Baca of Rialto, abstained on that vote, although he
has been an outspoken opponent of gun controls for many years. Only
a few weeks earlier he had voted against passage of a similar
control measure.
</P>
<P>
   Why the shift?
</P>
<P>
   Baca, closely allied with the National Rifle Association, is not
saying. But the other leading Democrat in the race, Marta Macias
Brown, Brown's widow and an advocate of gun controls, says she has
the answer: A poll released last weekend by Emily's List, a liberal
women's group that advocates gun controls, found that voters in the
42nd District favored her over Baca by 2-to-1 when told where both
she and he stood on guns.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an especially important issue to women in both parties,''
said Bobi Johnson, Mrs. Brown's campaign manager.
</P>
<P>
   In the aftermath of recent shooting rampages in California,
Colorado and Georgia, it is an issue that now transcends many
others, contends Luis Tolley of Handgun Control Inc., which has
endorsed Mrs. Brown.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's now touching ordinary people,'' he said. ``It's moved
beyond violence in the inner cities.''
</P>
<P>
   The leading Republican in the September race, Elia Pirozzi,
Brown's opponent in 1998, is more conservative than Mrs. Brown but
has not yet become embroiled in the gun debate. He ran slightly
better than Baca in the Emily's List poll.
</P>
<P>
   Should none of the 10 candidates in the contest win a clean
majority in the September voting, a runoff between the top finisher
from each party will be held on Nov. 16.
</P>
<P>
   Now, a New Episode of the Fordice Saga
</P>
<P>
   Now for our latest installment of the Fordice saga, in which we
learn that while rekindled love for an old high school flame
brought Kirk, the governor of Mississippi, all of his troubles, it
was not the heat in that love that saw him through the hard times.
It was politics.
</P>
<P>
   In earlier installments, the governor menaced nosy reporters who
pestered him about his spring trip to Paris with the old flame, Ann
Creson of Memphis ... he sloughed off criticism of his subsequent
demand that Pat, his wife of 44 years, decamp the Executive Mansion
in Jackson and grant him a divorce so he could wed Ms. Creson ...
he saw nothing amiss in using the state jet to rendezvous at the
beach with Ms. Creson, and accused those who saw something amiss of
hounding him.
</P>
<P>
   But today we discover that all that was largely bluster.
</P>
<P>
   The governor confesses that though he may have appeared to be
hanging tough back then, on the inside he was so weary and fed up
with all the questioning and carping about matters he considered
private that he came close to resigning rather than be ``tortured''
out of office. The way he began to see things, he now says, he had
less than six months left to serve in his second and final term, so
it would make little difference if he cut out a bit early.
</P>
<P>
   Except for one catch: He is a Republican, while the man who
would fill out his term, Lt. Gov. Ronnie Musgrove, is a Democrat _
and the Democratic Party's big hope to defeat the Republican
candidate, Mike Parker, in next year's governor's race.
</P>
<P>
   If Musgrove were permitted to run the state for a few months as
acting governor, Fordice began to worry, Musgrove just might get
the political lift needed to win. So the governor decided to ride
out the storm, explaining to The Associated Press on Wednesday:
</P>
<P>
   ``If I hadn't been preventing Ronnie Musgrove, who is
archliberal, anti-business and very bad for the state, from being
the incumbent in this race, I'd have been out of here six months
ago. No human being needs the stuff I'm taking. And if he wins,
I've just wasted a bunch of time and taken a lot of misery I didn't
need.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile ... Pat Fordice has still not decamped the Executive
Mansion, the divorce is still pending, and the governor has
concluded that the better part of stonewalling on the plane ride to
the beach is to send the state auditor a personal check for $865.
</P>
<P>
   Stay tuned.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
