<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Sunday, Aug. 29, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
(js) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Hurricane Dennis will affect the Southeast Coast in a more
serious way Sunday. The strengthening storm will be near the north
Florida shoreline, allowing its gales and squalls to move onshore.
The persistent flow from the east combined with large swells
generated by the hurricane will produce dangerous surf at the
beaches from Georgia to North Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   The wind circulation associated with a disturbance at 15,000
feet over Mississippi should continue to draw the hurricane toward
the mainland. Should Dennis accelerate during the next 24 hours, it
could be drawn into the Carolinas by a departing trough of low
pressure over the Northeast. Odds favor the hurricane being left
behind and pursuing an erratic course near the Florida and Georgia
coasts.
</P>
<P>
   Burgeoning high pressure in Manitoba will influence the weather
in the northern third of the nation early this week. A surge of
much cooler, drier air on the east side of the fair weather system
cause pleasant late summer conditions from the Great Lakes to New
England, though a few sprinkles are expected in the northern
Appalachians. The Gulf states and southern Plains will stay mostly
sunny, hot and humid.
</P>
<P>
   Low pressure in the Black Hills will be supplied with moisture
from the south and west. Clusters of thunderstorms will soak parts
of the northwest Plains and eastern Rockies, while afternoon
thundershowers form over the southern Rockies and southeast
California. The hot weather in the Northwest will be pushed inland
by a surge of marine air west of the Cascades.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Easing the Deficit
</P>
<P>
   Last Thursday, a deluge produced 2.03 inches of rain in
Washington, marking the most rain to fall in one day since August
of 1997. The Wednesday into Thursday rainfall of 3.40 inches was
the greatest two-day total in over 5 years. After a parched spring
and first half of the summer, numerous rainfalls have helped to
ease the drought across the Middle Atlantic States, though long
term water deficits remain quite high. With some computer models
suggesting that moisture from Hurricane Dennis will reach the
region this week, the deficit may be further erased. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
