<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-KICKOFF-CLASSIC-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
QUARTERBACKS FACE FIRST TEST IN THE KICKOFF CLASSIC 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By TIMOTHY W. SMITH    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ohio State Coach John Cooper said he sees a lot of similarities
between his team and the University of Miami team that the Buckeyes
will play at Giants Stadium Sunday afternoon in the Kickoff
Classic.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both teams have good wide receivers, good tight ends, both
teams have young quarterbacks and both teams can burn you deep,''
Cooper said.
</P>
<P>
   The question is whether those young quarterbacks will be able to
get the ball deep to the receivers.
</P>
<P>
   The Hurricanes' quarterback is Kenny Kelly, a sophomore who
plays baseball in the Tampa Bay Devil Rays' minor-league system.
The Buckeyes' quarterback is Austin Moherman, a sophomore who was
in close competition during training camp with Steve Bellisari.
</P>
<P>
   Cooper said he has every confidence in Moherman, who is
replacing the departed Joe Germaine.
</P>
<P>
   ``He calls a pass and gets the ball to the best receiver,''
Cooper said of Moherman. ``That's the thing he does best.''
</P>
<P>
   Moherman's two main targets are Reggie Germany, the team's
leading returning receiver, and Ken-yon Rambo, one of the fastest
players on the team. The Buckeyes will welcome single coverage on
either one.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they play us in man coverage, we'll see how good they
are,'' Cooper said.
</P>
<P>
   With the speedy receiver Santana Moss, the Hurricanes are
looking for the same opportunity to exploit.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got four or five great wide receivers, and to see those
guys out there one-on-one with any defensive back is something that
we're real comfortable seeing,'' Kelly said.
</P>
<P>
   Ohio State's defense is hoping to make things uncomfortable for
Kelly.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're definitely going to get after him early,'' said Ohio
State linebacker Na'il Diggs. ``We're going to get in his face and
make him think. We need to keep him contained in the pocket.''
</P>
<P>
   The Buckeyes' defense will be missing two starting linebackers,
Chris Kirk and Courtland Bullard. Kirk is academically ineligible,
and Bullard was suspended for one game this past Tuesday for
violating a team rule.
</P>
<P>
   ``It really affects us depth-wise,'' Cooper said. ``It leaves us
with a big void. It was not only losing those guys, but the timing
of it with Bullard. We didn't have a chance to bring anybody else
with us on this trip.''
</P>
<P>
   The Hurricanes are looking at this game as the launching pad for
an outstanding season. They are looking to regain the swagger that
they once had when they were routinely in the national championship
picture.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some teams would shy away from the Kickoff Classic, because it
could hurt your season if you don't play well,'' said the
Hurricanes senior guard Richard Mercier, who wore a black T-shirt
with the team's new motto ``Bigger, Stronger, Faster'' on the back.
``But we look at this season as something that will be good for the
program. We have the opportunity to leave on top and have our own
swagger.''
</P>
<P>
   Ohio State has high aspirations as well. They have an unrequited
national championship desire that has been stewing since 1968 _ the
last time they won a national title. The Buckeyes fell one game
short of going undefeated and vying for a national championship
last year.
</P>
<P>
   After a 24-14 victory over Texas A&AMP;M in the Sugar Bowl, the
Buckeyes finished the season ranked No. 2 in the nation with an
11-1 record. A late-season loss to Michigan State knocked them out
of the No. 1 spot.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were disappointed,'' Cooper said. ``We were ranked No. 1
for 10 straight weeks. But disappointment lasts only as long as you
let it.''
</P>
<P>
   Cooper said there has been no carryover to this year, because it
is a fresh season. It may have been one of the reasons why Cooper
decided to play in the Kickoff Classic game. It gives teams an
extra 10 days of practice. The Ohio State players seem to have
embraced that idea. But last season is still fresh in their minds.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were one play away,'' the senior fullback Matt Kelly said.
``It makes you sick. But you have to look at the season we had. We
played in the Sugar Bowl, and we finished No. 2. It's very hard to
go undefeated. It takes some luck. A few teams are able to stick it
out. But we just have to go out there and play the best we can and
see what happens.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
