<HEADER>
A2793 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-REFUGEES-COLLEGES-     08-28 0888
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-REFUGEES-COLLEGES-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK WOMAN HELPS KOSOVAR REFUGEES TRADE CAMPS FOR CAMPUSES
</HEADLINE>
  
 ATTN: Ind., Ill., Mo., N.C., Ore., Pa.)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers may make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(rk) 
 By   NINA SIEGAL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Receiving a phone call from Carol Detweiler has been like
winning the lottery for a group of Albanian refugees from Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   What she has to offer is something few Americans can fathom: a
free college education in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``I joke with my cousin and I say: `Wake up, Wake up. Maybe
we're dreaming,''' said Milot Hajzeraj, 21, who recently learned
that he and his cousin, Mentor Ferataj, 23, had both received full
scholarships to Hartwick College in Oneonta, N.Y., with the help of
Mrs. Detweiler, 53.
</P>
<P>
   The two cousins arrived in New York in late June after an
odyssey that began six months earlier in Pristina, where they were
attending the state university.
</P>
<P>
   This spring, as 4,000 refugees were given shelter at Fort Dix,
N.J., Mrs. Detweiler and her husband, Richard Detweiler, the
president of Hartwick College, were trying to figure out how they
could help. Mrs. Detweiler said she was moved by news reports.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought of them being thrown out of their homes, their
lives,'' she said. ``And many of them were college students and
they couldn't continue their college.''
</P>
<P>
   She said she knew they could not possibly afford to go to
college in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   She asked her husband if Hartwick, a 1,500-student college
founded in 1797, could accommodate at least two refugees. After he
said it could, she began looking for other schools that could do
the same. Twenty-two small liberal arts colleges across the nation
responded to her call, offering to waive tuition and provide
housing for refugees who qualified. In the meantime, 145 refugees
applied for the program. As of Friday, the Detweilers had found
places for 45.
</P>
<P>
   For its two students, Hartwick will absorb the cost of four
years of tuition. College officials hope to cover additional
expenses by soliciting donations from community organizations and
religious groups. Mrs. Detweiler said the gift amounts to about
$100,000 over four years for each student.
</P>
<P>
   Other colleges will cover the costs with donations and asking
some students to pay for living expenses through work-study
programs. Mrs. Detweiler said some schools intend to help students
apply for federal aid available for refugees.
</P>
<P>
   Other schools that are providing scholarships to refugees
include Chatham College in Pittsburgh; Rockhurst University in
Kansas City, Mo.; George Fox University in Newberg, Ore.; Quincy
University in Quincy, Ill; and Manchester College in Manchester,
Ind.
</P>
<P>
   Greensboro College, a 1,000-student college in Greensboro, N.C.,
which is affiliated with the United Methodist Church, has accepted
six Kosovar refugees. When the college's president, Craven E.
Williams, heard about the Detweilers' project, he responded
immediately, said his spokesman, Mike Clark.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our president said, `These students are living history and
we're a college of the church; we can't give money or food or
shelter, but we can give education,''' Clark said.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Ferataj and Hajzeraj were packing their bags and
preparing to attend the international student orientation at
Hartwick. It will be a far cry from what they left behind. In
Kosovo, they said, Albanian students were not allowed to attend
classes on campus or study in the Albanian language. They took
classes in private homes instead.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will be like night and day,'' said Hajzeraj, who was
studying veterinary science in Kosovo but may concentrate on
computer science at Hartwick. ``When I used to go to school, I
never took a bag with me because if the police would find our
books, they would beat us and say: `Why are you studying in
Albanian? This is a Serbian land.'''
</P>
<P>
   In April, shortly after the NATO airstrikes began, the two men
were rounded up by Serbian paramilitary forces wearing masks and
carrying machine guns and told to leave on the next train to
Macedonia, they said.
</P>
<P>
   They were not allowed to return to their homes in Istog, in
northwest Kosovo, they said, but went directly to Macedonia, where
they joined thousands of other refugees living in tents and under
the open sky.
</P>
<P>
   In June, they were allowed to come to the United States under
the sponsorship of a cousin who lives in the South Bronx. Since
then, they have been learning English, have found jobs and moved
into an apartment in the Pelham Park section of the Bronx. And now
Hartwick is the next stop in their journey.
</P>
<P>
   Even though classes are already under way at some schools, Mrs.
Detweiler said, she was still receiving calls on Friday from
students and colleges interested in participating in her program.
And she is still receiving calls of thanks. ``I've gotten phone
messages where students say, `Thank you, thank you, thank you a
million times,''' Mrs. Detweiler said. ``I save those messages.''
</P>
<P>
   Ferataj, who will continue his studies in economics at Hartwick,
was one of those callers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know you have a lot of opportunities in the United States,
but we never thought it would be like this,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-28-99 1429EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
