<SLUG> BC-N.Y.-SUNY-PRESIDENT-400&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TULANE MEDICAL CENTER'S CHIEF WILL LEAD SUNY DOWNSTATE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: La.)  (js) 
 By KAREN W. ARENSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ John C. LaRosa, the chancellor of the Tulane
University Medical Center, a researcher in cholesterol and heart
disease and a passionate jazz pianist, will become president of the
State University of New York's Health Science Center in Brooklyn on
Sept. 1.
</P>
<P>
   Although hospitals and medical schools have undergone enormous
change in recent years, LaRosa, 58, says he sees a period of
opportunity for the center, also known as SUNY Downstate, which is
``primed to take off.''
</P>
<P>
   As chancellor of Tulane's medical center for five years, he has
tried to improve patient services, broaden the school's research
and raise money. He also presided over the 1996 transfer of
Tulane's hospital and clinic into a joint venture with Columbia/HCA
Healthcare.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a tremendous loss for Tulane,'' said Kenneth E. Thorpe,
who taught at Tulane's Medical Center until he moved this summer to
Emory University as chairman of the department of health policy and
management. ``He's a real visionary in terms of research.''
</P>
<P>
   LaRosa said that some of the same priorities he had for Tulane
should hold for Downstate. He wants to improve patient services and
to raise money but says he has no preconceived notion of whether
the medical center would be better served by some structure other
than the current one.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know enough to know how Brooklyn should go,'' he said.
``I have an open mind about that.''
</P>
<P>
   One of four health science centers at SUNY, Downstate is
somewhat larger than the Tulane center. Established in 1860, the
Brooklyn center includes the 15th-largest medical school in the
United States and University Hospital of Brooklyn, with 376 beds.
It also includes a college of nursing, a college of health-related
professions and a school of graduate studies, and is noted for its
research in areas like AIDS, alcoholism and organ transplants. Last
year, an emeritus professor, Dr. Robert F. Furchgott, received a
Nobel Prize.
</P>
<P>
   One of LaRosa's preoccupations is how to improve what he calls
customer service in health care. He says that most academic medical
centers _ and health centers generally _ ``don't do a very good
job.''
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of improvement doesn't cost much in terms of money, but
requires changes in attitude,'' he said. ``Your dentist calls you
the day before an appointment to remind you of your appointment.
Your service station calls a day or two after your car comes out of
service. Imagine if you got that kind of service at a hospital.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   He said he had had ``mixed success'' at making improved patient
service a priority at Tulane. ``It's a cultural change,'' he said.
``It doesn't happen by edict.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he also hoped he could generate more support from
Downstate's alumni, former patients and community members by paying
more attention to them.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a core of alums who have been very supportive,'' he
said. ``But there is a lot of that building that we can do.''
</P>
<P>
   LaRosa, who will be paid $225,000 a year, said that part of the
attraction of the new job, where he succeeds Eugene B. Feigelson,
Downstate's interim president since 1997, was New York and its
cultural life.
</P>
<P>
   Raised in Pittsburgh (he graduated from the University of
Pittsburgh summa cum laude and from its medical school), he did
postgraduate work at the National Institutes of Health and spent 20
years at the George Washington University Medical Center, where he
rose to dean for clinical affairs and then dean for research. His
wife, Judith, is still chairwoman of Tulane's department of
community health sciences in its public health school and director
of the Tulane-Xavier Center of Excellence for Women's Health.
</P>
<P>
   LaRosa said he had been dreaming about taking in some of New
York's cultural offerings when he arrives in Brooklyn. High on his
list are events at the Brooklyn Academy of Music and some opera and
jazz _ and playing jazz piano with local musicians.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like New Orleans,'' he said last week. ``But I really miss
the cultural vitality of the Northeast.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-28-99 1433EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
