<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-28 14:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2795 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e BC-PBP-TV29-COX     08-28 1291
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PBP-TV29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    New TV season may be best debut in years
 &HT;    By Kevin D. Thompson
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   I'm looking forward to the new fall TV season.
</P>
<P>
   There, I said it. I feel much better now.
</P>
<P>
   There are 36 new network programs coming your way in the next
few months. Of those, I'd say a good dozen actually forced me to
sit up and pay attention. Even such syndicated shows as ``Richard
Simmons' Dream Maker;'' the Indiana Jones-like ``Relic Hunter'' and
a new ``Family Feud .''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike last year's dismal crop (''Encore! Encore!,''
``Costello,'' ``The Brian Benben Show''), this season, which
officially begins the week of Sept. 20, is brimming with potential
and good buzz. ``Once and Again,'' ABC's tender new adult drama
from the thirty(ITAL)something(END ITAL) producers, is the year's
best new show. The key word is (ITAL)adult.(END ITAL) We don't see
many new adult shows on TV. It's obvious the TV suits have bought
into the ``Logan's Run'' theory: Once you hit 30, you die. All
Madison Avenue really cares about are young, money-dropping kids
wearing J.Crew threads. That's why you'll see more teen-skewing
shows than ever before this fall.
</P>
<P>
   TV needs a banner season more than it ever has. Just look at
what's been happening the last few years. More and more, viewers
are defecting to cable, where the shows are often edgier and
better. It's no accident that The Sopranos, HBO's mob drama, nabbed
16 Emmy nominations. Such shows as ``Behind the Music,'' ``Sex and
the City,'' ``Oz,'' ``La Femme Nikita'' and ``Any Day Now'' have
made cable hip and happening. Network TV often looks like the geeky
loner by comparison.
</P>
<P>
   Cable continues to influence how the broadcast networks do
business. Take Fox, for example, ``Action,'' an envelope-shoving
spoof about an arrogant movie producer (Jay Mohr), was developed
for HBO. And it still (ITAL)feels(END ITAL) like an HBO show.
Mohr's character uses salty language only a hardcore sailor would
love (all obscenities are bleeped) and he has a hooker as an
assistant. And the network's upcoming oddball comedy, ``Malcolm in
the Middle,'' could easily air on Showtime. After all, how many
times on network TV do you see a naked dad getting his thighs
shaved by his wife in front of his breakfast-eating kids?
</P>
<P>
   Networks are also less skittish about putting more gay
characters on TV. Remember when Ellen DeGeneres' character came out
a few years ago? It generated more controversy than Bill and
Monica. Now gay characters are becoming as common as the wacky next
door neighbor. Such new ABC shows as ``Then Came You,'' ``Oh Grow
Up'' and ``Wasteland'' feature prominent gay characters.
</P>
<P>
   While network executives acknowledge shows need to get edgier to
keep pace with cable, they admit they can only go so far. ``HBO's
job is different than my job,'' says Les Moonves, CBS' president
and CEO. ``HBO's purpose is to get subscribers. When we put on a
program on CBS, we have to get viewers. We don't have to get people
to put down $29.95 a month. We have to be a little bit more broad
than that.''
</P>
<P>
   Not UPN. The identity-challenged network may have finally found
a niche: young males. Its wrestling show, ``WWF Smackdown!,'' is
the network's cornerstone to helping pump up sagging ratings.
Wisely, UPN choose to launch its new fall shows in August before
the competition heats up in September. Last year, UPN's shows
debuted in October and no one cared.
</P>
<P>
   TV does care about one thing: copying success. ``Providence,''
the NBC drama about a female doctor moving back home, was a
surprise midseason hit. That means we'll see more shows boasting
strong female characters. Enter CBS' ``Judging Amy'' about a judge
(''NYPD Blue'''s Amy Brenneman) who moves back in with her mom, and
``Family Law,'' which stars Kathleen Quinlan as a marital attorney
with marital woes.
</P>
<P>
   TV will be no laughing matter this season. Twenty-two new dramas
will be launched. That probably can be directly traced to the
success of such shows as ``The Practice,'' ``Felicity'' and
``Providence.''
</P>
<P>
   Like cable, broadcast TV is becoming more niche oriented. And
that's not a good thing. The networks used to be broadcasters. Now
they're narrowcasters, concerned only with a thin demographic.
Quick, think of a network. You can automatically attach an audience
demo to it. CBS: old; NBC: white, upscale; WB: young, hip; Fox:
young, hip; UPN: young males.
</P>
<P>
   You don't see any people of color, do you? Out of the 36 new
shows on the six networks, only two _ ``Grown Ups'' and ``The
Parkers'' _ feature a minority lead. And both of those are on UPN,
which means their chances of becoming hit shows lies somewhere
between slim and never. Forget about Latinos, Asians and American
Indians. You see more aliens on TV than you see of those ethnic
groups. Of course, the problem isn't a new one. But the NAACP
brought more attention to TV's abysmal track record after publicly
blasting ABC, NBC, CBS and Fox. The organization also threatened to
boycott and sue the networks.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's never been a particularly great year for minorities on
TV,'' laments ``Moesha'' creator Ralph Farquhar. ``But when you
have four, five of the seven networks making a complete about-face,
it becomes ludicrous.''
</P>
<P>
   So what's happening now is simply insulting. Just about every
producer is scrambling to add minority characters to their shows.
``Sabrina, The Teenage Witch,'' for instance, added a hunky Latino
guy who'll play Harvey's best friend. The writers also added a
black female witch whom Sabrina will mentor. ``Wasteland'' tapped
Jeffrey D. Sams (''Cupid'') to play an assistant D.A. who might
have an interracial relationship with his assistant, played by the
yummy Rebecca Gayheart.
</P>
<P>
   At the recent Television Critics Association press tour in
Pasadena, it was almost comical watching the networks rushing out
token minority producers as if to say, ``See, we're doing the right
thing!'' Yvette Lee Bowser was one. The ``Living Single'' creator
is developing a drama pilot for the WB. You could tell she was
delighted with her deal when she made this ill-informed comment:
</P>
<P>
   ``The WB is the network I believe is the most enthusiastic about
showcasing actors of multicultural backgrounds in a dramatic
form.''
</P>
<P>
   Really? Bowser was asked which WB dramas she was talking about.
The last time I checked, there are (ITAL)no(END ITAL) WB dramas
boasting black leads.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, I'm not saying they've done well in the past, I'm saying
that I have a strong belief that they (ITAL)will(END ITAL) do
well,'' she clarified.
</P>
<P>
   Why do networks continue to whitewash TV? The answer isn't as
obvious as you think.
</P>
<P>
   Hollywood is not racist. Well, it can be. But that's not the
primary reason why there are so few minority shows. Warped
Hollywood works like this: If the awful Homeboys In Outer Space
became a top 10 hit, we would have seen a slew of clone shows
featuring blacks in space. The industry wants to make money. It's
that simple. Upscale white shows sell on Madison Avenue.
Minority-themed shows don't sell as well.
</P>
<P>
   Green is the main color in Tinseltown, not white.
</P>
<P>
   ``Racism isn't an issue,'' notes Steven Bochco, who created
``City of Angels,'' a black medical drama scheduled to air on CBS
in January. ``Economics is the issue. When things that you try
don't succeed, there's a reluctance to try them again. When they do
succeed, you try them over and over again. That said, if I'm a
black artist in this community, I don't give a s--- what the reason
is. The reality is, I don't have a job.''
</P>
<P>
   Kevin D. Thompson writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm
Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
