<HEADER>
A2802 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-EDIT-SOFT-MONEY-NYT &LR;      08-28 0628
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-SOFT-MONEY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: 'THUGGISH TACTICS IN CONGRESS
</HEADLINE>
   (jt) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Sunday, Aug. 29:
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Mitch McConnell loves to invoke the First Amendment to
justify the way politicians squeeze money from special interests.
He and other Republican fund-raisers defend campaign contributions
from businesses, unions and rich people as free speech. As it turns
out, where they see free speech, others _ including some donors _
see extortion. A group of business leaders is now lobbying Congress
to stop the shakedowns and approve campaign finance reform
legislation banning ``soft money'' donations to the parties. Some
even suggest that business donors just say no. McConnell is trying
to get these executives to shut up. Evidently, for him, free speech
has its limits.
</P>
<P>
   A bill to ban soft money comes before Congress this fall. Most
House members and senators favor the bill, but Speaker Dennis
Hastert and Trent Lott, the Senate majority leader, plan various
means to intimidate the rank and file or gut the legislation if it
cannot be blocked. That is why it is encouraging to see business
and academic leaders step forward. The Committee for Economic
Development, led by Edward Kangas, chairman of Deloitte Touche
Tohmatsu, and George Rupp, president of Columbia University, has
enlisted scores of business executives to support various reforms,
including the soft-money ban. Among those demanding change are
current or retired executives at General Electric, the Sara Lee
Corp., the Pennsylvania Power and Light Co. and many other
concerns.
</P>
<P>
   These businessmen have already drawn blood, as demonstrated by
the wounded and threatening tone of a letter from McConnell
demanding that various businesses resign from the committee.
McConnell accused some of the committee leaders of trying to
``eviscerate private sector participation in politics'' by imposing
``anti-business speech controls.'' He also warned that banning
corporate contributions would ``render the Republican Party
powerless to defend pro-business candidates from negative TV
attacks by labor unions, trial lawyers and radical
environmentalists.'' The inference drawn by some donors is that if
they do not behave, Republicans will not fight for their interests.
</P>
<P>
   The idea that campaign reform is some sort of plot against
Republicans is absurd. The soft-money ban has won support from
former Presidents Gerald Ford and George Bush, as well as from Bob
Dole and Howard Baker. But McConnell's letter, which one recipient
characterized as ``thuggish,'' at least clarifies what this fight
is about. The Committee for Economic Development put it well when
it replied to McConnell that ``we find it ironic that you are such
a fervent defender of First Amendment freedoms but seem intent to
stifle our efforts to express publicly our concerns about a
campaign finance system that many feel is out of control.''
Businesses are not demanding radical reform. They want a system in
which the quality of the candidates and their positions, not their
fund-raising skills, determines outcomes.
</P>
<P>
   The House plans to act in September on campaign reform
legislation sponsored by Reps. Christopher Shays of Connecticut and
Martin Meehan of Massachusetts. The Senate plans to act on its
version a month later. With public disgust rising, members of
Congress must remember why they were elected in the first place,
which was to pay heed to the voters, not to the clanging of
campaign cash machines and the intimidating tactics of McConnell.
As the Committee for Economic Development points out, campaign
reform will not eliminate donations. The goal is to place
reasonable curbs on a system that is now ``out of control.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
