<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUMMER-FOOTBALL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOWNS COLUMN: HIGH SCHOOL FOOTBALL FAME REQUIRES SUMMER
SACRIFICES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Conn.)  (js) 
 By IVER PETERSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   FAIRFIELD, Conn. _ It is still summer, after all. The stores may
be advertising back-to-school specials, but they've been doing that
since June, practically, so that doesn't prove anything. Deep in
bed and denial, most teen-agers are still sleeping late and
pretending that September is weeks away.
</P>
<P>
   But not Bernard Thompson and Roy Gless and Andy Dwyer and the
rest of the Notre Dame Catholic High School football team. While
their friends are still hitting the beach, they and thousands of
other high school students are back on practice fields, hitting
each other and running through plays in the ancient tradition that
says the first ones back to school each year are the football
players.
</P>
<P>
   ``Somebody said something about the rites of spring, but to me,
this is the rites of summer,'' said Jeffrey Bevino, Notre Dame's
new football coach and athletic director. ``It's easy to remember
why these guys show up to play during the season: It's for Friday
night lights, to get all that glory and attention. But to get
there, they still have to show up early for camp, and they're still
doing it.''
</P>
<P>
   This has been a season of worry about teen-agers, especially
about boys. School shootings, postures of alienation and violent
music and video games seem to belong to a youth culture that stands
deliberately at odds with parental dreams and ambitions, and
certainly the violence and swagger of football players have
attracted some of that glare. But not to the people who see it up
close, people like the Rev. Bill Sangiovanni, the principal of
Notre Dame.
</P>
<P>
   ``The things we have been seeing on the news, capped off by
Littleton, have brought a kind of fear about kids into people's
minds,'' he said. ``I wish they could see some of our football
players.''
</P>
<P>
   Bernard Thompson, a senior and one of the team captains, worked
at a camp for city youths this summer and quit only to put in one
more season as a linebacker for the Lancers. Ask him what he's
doing suited up on a hot afternoon for the second practice session
of the day, and he will talk of the simplest and most complicated
emotion.
</P>
<P>
   ``I play it because I love it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Roy Gless, another senior, hinted at the work-today,
reward-tomorrow connection that generations of parents have tried
to drum into their children's heads. ``I think it teaches you
things,'' he said. ``Like, it's a lot of work, but it's worth it on
Friday or Saturday when you're in the game.''
</P>
<P>
   The sacrifices that boys make to play football are not all about
selflessness and motivation, of course, nor are they as universal
as they once might have been.
</P>
<P>
   Notre Dame used to get as many as 70 boys to show up for summer
camp, Bevino said, and this year there are between 30 and 40 _ the
number is still shaky because who knows how many will stick?
Players will show up one day and disappear the next, without saying
a word, without even properly returning equipment. Not like when he
was coming up, sigh.
</P>
<P>
   ``These kids have a lot of options that we didn't use to have,''
the coach said. ``Their parents are hiring special trainers who
tell them to focus on one sport _ nothing but basketball, or
nothing but baseball. Whatever happened to the three-letter man?
The football-basketball-baseball guy, bing bing bing. He used to
define the high school athlete, but you don't see him that much
anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   And, to be truthful, not every recruit who pulls on a helmet and
shoulder pads is there 100 percent voluntarily. Sometimes fathers,
thinking of college applications and manhood memories, are more
interested in their sons' football careers than the sons are
themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was forced to play,'' Bruce Gay, a sophomore from Stratford,
said in a kind of grumpy teen-age shorthand. ``My Dad. I wanted my
summer to last, then I had to come here.'' He doesn't care that a
handful of other sophomores are chuckling at his griping, or notice
that while they tend to exaggerate their height and weight, when
asked, he minimizes his. A good 130-pounder if he's an ounce, he
insists that he can't top 115.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like my summer ended a week ago,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, sometimes the dads have to push them a little, Bevino
agreed. ``Sometimes they need a little help getting going.'' And
with a 6-4 season last year, 5-6 the year before, Notre Dame is not
the powerhouse its university namesake is. But nobody brings that
up.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not thinking about winning or losing right now,'' said
Mike Romano, a sophomore. ``I just love football.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-28-99 1442EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990828.0160 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-28 14:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2810 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-COX-DENNIS-MAIN0828     08-28 0714
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COX-DENNIS-MAIN0828 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    DENNIS SPINS TOWARD SOUTHEAST COAST
 &HT;    Editors Note: This story requires updates in the second graf as
indicated below. The National Hurricane center will be issuing
advisories that should move on all available wires shortly after 5
PM. 8 PM. and 11 PM. Saturday.
 &HT;    By Mike Williams
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   COCOA BEACH, Fla. - A strengthening Hurricane Dennis spun toward
the Southeastern coast Saturday with growing winds and falling
pressures, sending coastal residents from Florida to the Carolinas
scrambling to prepare for a landfall that experts still sought to
predict.
</P>
<P>
   (insert material required here)
</P>
<P>
   At xx p.m., the storm was located about xxx miles southeast of
Cape Canaveral with sustained winds of xxx miles an hour. Dennis
was moving northwest at xx miles an hour. Forecasters expected the
storm to continue on its northwesterly track, which make it a
threat to the coasts of North or South Carolina, perhaps by
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   (end inserts)
</P>
<P>
   Dennis was expected to grow into a Category 3 storm by the time
it makes landfall, with winds of 111 miles an hour or greater,
meaning it would be capable of major damage.
</P>
<P>
   But the predictions were complicated by the storm's slow
movement, coupled with uncertainty over the impact of weak upper
level weather systems that could still help kick the hurricane out
to sea.
</P>
<P>
   Officials at the National Hurricane Center worried that Dennis
might stall again as it had done on Friday, giving it the chance to
grow even stronger while making its track even less predictable.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fear of a stall is that it makes the storm surge much
larger because it sits there and pushes water up onto the coast for
a long period of time,'' Jerry Jarrell, the center's director, told
the Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
   Hurricane watches were posted along 200 miles of Florida's coast
from Sebastian Inlet north to the Georgia state line. But it
appeared Dennis would brush past Florida, narrowly missing its long
coastline on its way to landfall somewhere further north.
</P>
<P>
   Winds along Central Florida beaches gusted to 40 miles an hour
Saturday afternoon as Dennis' outer bands swept near.
Six-to-ten-foot waves pounded the beaches, eroding sand dunes and
keeping all but adventurous surfers out of the water.
</P>
<P>
   By Saturday, Dennis had already done some damage in the Bahamas,
toppling trees and pounding beaches on the islands of Great Abaco
and Grand Bahama, as well as several smaller keys.
</P>
<P>
   ``The seas were very bad,'' said Martin Havill(cq), manager of
the Bluff House Beach Hotel on Green Turtle Cay just off Great
Abaco. ``But it really was not a problem. We had a couple of roofs
with some shingles off, a lot of trees down and our pool is full of
leaves. But we had everybody up for breakfast.''
</P>
<P>
   Early reports indicated some damage to buildings in Marsh
Harbour, Great Abaco's largest town, where two buildings under
construction had collapsed walls. But there were no early reports
of injuries.
</P>
<P>
   Dennis packed sustained winds of about 80 miles an hour when it
roared over Great Abaco, with some reports of gusts as high as 115
miles an hour.
</P>
<P>
   After clearing the islands early Saturday, the storm began to
strengthen, with pressures falling and winds jumping to 100 miles
an hour. Forecasters worried that the storm would continue building
as it moved across the warm Gulf Stream waters off the Florida
coast.
</P>
<P>
   Florida coastal residents were not ordered to evacuate, although
emergency officials kept a close eye on the storm. Along Central
Florida's beaches, dozens of sightseers drove to overlooks to watch
the powerful waves kicked up by Dennis.
</P>
<P>
   Surfers were out by the hundreds, some paddling out before the
sun came up Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was at the pier this morning at 6 a.m. and there were
hundreds of kids scrambling around,'' said Doug Monda, 30, a Cocoa
Beach surfer. ``This is big surf for Florida, so everybody's
excited.''
</P>
<P>
   Up the coast in coastal towns of Georgia and Charleston, S.C.,
residents and officials nervously watched the storm's progress,
mindful of powerful Hurricane Hugo, which lashed South Carolina in
1989, doing extensive damage.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
