<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-N.Y.-SENATE-ANALYSIS-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEWS ANALYSIS: IN THIS SENATE RACE, SCRUTINY IS PERSONAL 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By ADAM NAGOURNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Quick: Was Sen. Alfonse D'Amato divorced from his wife? Where
does D'Amato's successor, Charles Schumer, live _ and does his
house have a swimming pool? What is the name of Schumer's wife?
Where does Schumer like to go on vacation?
</P>
<P>
   Even the most devoted followers of New York politics would be
hard pressed to answer such personal questions about these two
familiar politicians, even though they were the headliners of what
was arguably the most widely watched Senate contest of 1998. For
all the intensity of the Schumer-D'Amato race, this was one area of
inquiry that was barely touched _ ignored by candidates, voters and
the media alike.
</P>
<P>
   But these days, many people would have little difficultly
answering similar questions about Mayor Rudolph Giuliani or Hillary
Rodham Clinton, the two likely contestants in New York's next race
for the U.S. Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Their marital difficulties have already been examined in
newspapers and magazines. Giuliani has expounded from a City Hall
lectern about why he has not tried marijuana or cocaine. A squadron
of reporters is tracking the first lady this weekend as she
vacations in the Hamptons and looks at houses in Westchester
County.
</P>
<P>
   Inquiries into the lives of White House candidates, from the
most mundane to the most searingly personal, have been a staple of
the presidential selection process at least since 1987, when a
Washington Post reporter asked Gary Hart at a news conference if he
had ever committed adultery. By contrast, in congressional
campaigns the personal has usually taken a back seat to the
political.
</P>
<P>
   But the prospect of a Clinton-Giuliani race is challenging this
familiar political calculus. Everything about these two, from
youthful indiscretions to intimate accountings about their
upbringing and family lives, now seems sure to be fully explored in
the year ahead, filling what appears to be a huge public (or at
least media) hunger for information.
</P>
<P>
   At this early date, it is far from clear how much this will
matter come November 2000. Several analysts contended that it
seemed unlikely, given the political differences between Giuliani
and Mrs. Clinton, that personality would trump ideology in the end.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, workers in both campaigns are nervously gearing up
for exhaustive reviews of their candidates' lives, and even taking
steps to try to head them off. That may account for Mrs. Clinton's
pre-emptive interview about her marriage with Talk magazine this
month or Giuliani's scolding of reporters for their inquiries into
rumors about past drug use by George W. Bush, the Texas governor
and a Republican candidate for president.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, these early developments are raising questions
about the direction U.S. politics may be heading. Are the rules of
play for presidential races now seeping down to the congressional
level or is this a onetime phenomenon? Will a Clinton-Giuliani race
be to congressional politics what Hart's candidacy was to
presidential races? And should someone running to be one of 100
members of the Senate be subjected to the same personal scrutiny as
a candidate running for the White House?
</P>
<P>
   This new environment results, at least in part, from the fact
that the New York contest is likely to include on the Democratic
side the highest-profile first lady this nation has seen in 50
years, a woman whose political and personal evolution has been
minutely chronicled since the Clintons came to the nation's
attention at the start of 1992.
</P>
<P>
   What is more, both Mrs. Clinton and Giuliani are at once
electrifying and polarizing figures. And they are running in a
state that many political strategists view as the toughest
political environment in the nation and are already enduring the
kind of saturation coverage that typically does not begin until the
week before an election.
</P>
<P>
   It is a matter of debate how much this is driven by the news
media's fascination, as opposed to the genuine curiosity of voters.
But whatever the reason, the laserlike focus on both candidates is
unlike anything political consultants can recall.
</P>
<P>
   ``I mean, can you tell me whether Chuck Schumer's been divorced
or not?'' said Kieran Mahoney, the Republican consultant who ran
D'Amato's unsuccessful campaign last year. ``Most people can't. The
point is, this isn't a Senate race, this is a presidential race. In
a Senate race, nobody would care. They wouldn't even question it.
It would never get to that level. You're lucky if they know the
names of the candidates.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   As a rule, pollsters say, voters use different criteria in
considering congressional candidates versus candidates for the
White House. A president is seen as a symbol of the nation; thus
his values, morals and public presence are critical factors in
electoral decisions. ``The president has the button to blow up the
world,'' said Dick Morris, the political consultant who once worked
for the Clintons.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, voters in a Senate race are choosing members of a
deliberative body. They are likely to give more weight to a
candidate's beliefs, party affiliation and agility at fighting for
their state. ``Issues and ideology are more important for senators
because they are seen as acting primarily as members of a team,
more so than governors and presidents,'' said Whit Ayres, a
Republican pollster based in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   For example, in last year's New York contest, Schumer
relentlessly highlighted D'Amato's opposition to abortion rights
and some forms of gun control, while D'Amato presented himself as
New York's advocate in Washington. Neither candidate made mention
of his opponent's personal life. (Yes, by the way, D'Amato is
divorced; Schumer is not. Schumer lives in Brooklyn with his wife,
Iris, without a pool. His preferred vacation destination, an aide
says, is any of the national parks.)
</P>
<P>
   In this case, Mrs. Clinton and Giuliani, while holding similar
opinions on gun control and abortion rights, clearly have different
views about the role of government. That means both candidates have
the potential to drive the campaign away from themselves and toward
their ideologies, and their advisers say that is what they intend
to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``At different times, people are intrigued and curious about
personal aspects of candidates,'' said Mandy Grunwald, a longtime
consultant to Mrs. Clinton. ``But I think, ultimately, this is an
issue-based decision.''
</P>
<P>
   Robert Shrum, a Democratic consultant who worked for Geraldine
A. Ferraro in the 1998 Senate race and for David N. Dinkins in both
his mayoral bids, said there was a matter of political
self-preservation at play here. ``I think the voters will severely
punish anyone who tries to drag personal stuff into the New York
Senate race,'' Shrum said.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, if there is one thing Giuliani and Mrs. Clinton seem to
agree on, it is that they do not want the campaign to be too much
about them. In an interview on MSNBC last week, for example,
Giuliani served notice that he considered inquiries about his own
life off limits. ``When people ask me about my private life, I
don't tell them about it,'' Giuliani said. ``It's none of their
business.''
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, after Mrs. Clinton discussed her troubled marriage
with Talk magazine, she declared she would not answer any more
questions on the subject. Her aides said they hoped that would put
an end to the subject.
</P>
<P>
   Will that work?
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a race like no other,'' said James Carville, the
Democratic consultant whose clients have included Mrs. Clinton's
husband. ``I can't tell you how many stories I've seen on her
buying the house _ just the normal things that people do. Do I
think it's going to affect a voter? No. But we don't know. Because
nothing like this has ever happened before.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-28-99 1459EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
