<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990828.0165 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-28 15:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2815 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-TOURIST-CEMETERIES-AR     08-28 0711
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOURIST-CEMETERIES-ART-630(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HISTORIC GRAVEYARDS TRY TO GET TOURISTS TO STROLL THEIR LAWNS
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mass., Ohio)  (ART ADV: Photos  were sent on Tuesday, August 24, as
NY-CEMETERY-TOURISM to NYT photo clients. Graphic is being sent to
NYT graphics clients. Non-subscribers may make individual purchase
by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(rk) 
 By LESLIE EATON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The graveyard business is just not what it used to
be. So Green-Wood Cemetery, the huge and historic burial ground in
Brooklyn, is taking its first slow steps toward a new identity:
tourist attraction.
</P>
<P>
   This is not as goofy _ or as ghoulish _ as it might sound. A
century ago, Green-Wood was a tourist attraction, ranking right up
there with Niagara Falls on the 19th-century must-see list.
</P>
<P>
   Modern visitors who do not share the Victorians' obsession with
death _ or their admiration for mawkish statues of angels and urns
_ could be swept away by the magnificent landscape at Green-Wood.
Another lure is the colorful stories of the politicians and
gangsters, Civil War generals and industrial magnates, victims of
disasters and stars of scandals whose tombs cover most of the 478
acres.
</P>
<P>
   So the cemetery's management recently began trying to entice the
public to enter its faux-Gothic gates. ``I'd like to see us become
one of the highlights of the Brooklyn tour circuit,'' said Richard
J. Moylan, president of Green-Wood, which opened in 1840.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Green-Wood published a lively history chronicling the
deeds (and misdeeds) of its denizens. This summer, it held its
first concert, featuring the music of composers buried on site.
Next month, it will start selling a guide that visitors can use to
find the graves of everyone from Boss Tweed to the original Brooks
Brothers, and will sponsor a booth at the annual New York Is Book
Country fair in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   Green-Wood is hardly the only historic American cemetery trying
to lure visitors and raise its public profile. In Cleveland, there
are trolley tours of cemeteries. In Rochester, N.Y., Mount Hope
Cemetery has an ``adopt-a-grave'' program. Woodlawn, in the Bronx,
has a concert series _ next month it will hold its first
performance of Latino music _ and is considering an Easter egg hunt
for the spring. Mount Auburn, in Cambridge, Mass., bills itself as
an arboretum as well as a burial ground, and has developed a number
of programs for the public.
</P>
<P>
   There are many reasons _ historical, sociological and financial
_ for these efforts.
</P>
<P>
   With fewer people choosing burial, cemeteries find themselves
needing to advertise the benefits of having a memorial. Cremation,
which is less lucrative for cemeteries than burial, has increased
in popularity, as has the scattering of ashes and burial at sea.
</P>
<P>
   Then there is the belief that graveyards full of visitors may
discourage thieves intent on stealing their Tiffany glass windows
or bronze statues. And cemeteries are searching for money to
restore some of their moldering monuments.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't expect current sales dollars to cover 100 years of
history,'' said Thomas G. Roberts, president of the Allegheny
Cemetery in Pittsburgh and chairman of the historic cemeteries
committee of the International Cemetery and Funeral Association.
Almost 20 years ago, Allegheny set up a foundation and began
raising money for historic preservation, he said. ``Foundations
have been very understanding, once we get past what I call the
laugh factor.''
</P>
<P>
   But in New York, in death as in life, the clincher is real
estate. Green-Wood, like other burial grounds around the city, is
running out of space.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are in our twilight years as an active cemetery,'' Moylan
said. The space problem is not yet acute, he added; the cemetery,
which buries the remains of about 2,000 people a year, probably has
enough room for another decade's worth.
</P>
<P>
   But that is only because the cemetery has taken to removing some
of its miles of roads and pathways, and using that space to bury
the dead. Only a few more scenic paths can be replaced with graves
before the overall appearance of the cemetery is affected, he said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Even after the last $5,000 plot is sold, Green-Wood will
continue to make money from the services that provide much of its
income. Each grave can hold as many as three coffins, stacked, so
family members can be buried together. Some tombs have a lot of
empty slots; the piano-building Steinway family built a huge tomb
in the 1870s, with space for more than 150 bodies, according to
Jeffrey I. Richman, the author of the book the cemetery published,
``Brooklyn's Green-Wood Cemetery: New York's Buried Treasure.''
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, however, the cemetery will have to live off the
income from its investments, already its largest source of revenue.
Green-Wood had almost $200 million in its various funds at the end
of 1998, according to its filings with the state Division of
Cemeteries. It is one of the best endowed of the state's 1,900
nonprofit cemeteries, said Richard D. Fishman, director of the
division.
</P>
<P>
   But Green-Wood is also one of the most expensive cemeteries to
maintain. It takes 135 people to manicure its steep slopes, trim
its trees and shrubs and rake its leaves. The cemetery spent more
than $4 million on maintenance last year, according to its filings.
</P>
<P>
   Although the cemetery, which is just south of Park Slope, looks
pristine _ the grass neatly cut, the monuments well kept _ some of
the historic markers and statues are in sore need of conservation
and restoration. At the Soldiers' Monument, the four life-size
statues of Civil War soldiers are missing pieces _ a hand here, an
ax there, a rifle over there _ and the bronze is split in places.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the severe damage has occurred to monuments made of
marble, which has not held up well in the face of acid rain and
salt breezes. (Green-Wood has a view of New York Harbor and the
Statue of Liberty.)
</P>
<P>
   At the monument to composer and pianist Louis Moreau Gottschalk,
for example, ``you can't make his name out and, if you touch the
marble, it comes off on your hand like salt,'' said John J.
Cashman, a retired police sergeant who, with Frank Mescall, leads
tours at the cemetery.
</P>
<P>
   At one time, Cashman's tours were pretty much the only way to
see the cemetery, which for much of the 20th century has maintained
a low-key stance, welcoming only lot owners and their families. In
this century, visitors who were not discouraged by the cemetery's
miles of spiky iron fencing, topped here and there with razor wire,
had to get a special pass to walk the grounds, and were strictly
forbidden to take photographs. ``I've been turned away at the
gate,'' said Kenneth T. Jackson, a professor of history at Columbia
University.
</P>
<P>
   Until early in this century, Jackson noted, the sort of people
who built the elaborate, expensive monuments at Green-Wood and
Woodlawn expected sightseers. ``You would only be spending that
kind of money if you thought someone would come to see it,'' he
said. He added that in the 19th century, having a fancy cemetery
was a point of civic pride, much as having a major-league baseball
team is today.
</P>
<P>
   Technically, the lots are private property and the monuments are
not the responsibility of the cemetery, but of the families of the
dead. But for historic cemeteries, even those family members who
are still nearby may not have the means to repair the marble bust
of Great-Great-Uncle Horace or to fill the cast-iron urns with
begonias.
</P>
<P>
   That is why Mount Hope in Rochester created the adopt-a-grave
program, in which volunteers care for the plantings and flower
beds, said Nancy M. Hilliard, director of cemeteries for the city.
Churches, garden groups and individuals maintain about 75 graves at
the 196-acre cemetery, which is 160 years old and has the graves of
Susan B. Anthony and Frederick Douglass.
</P>
<P>
   At Green-Wood, the management has established a fund to be used
for restoration; Cashman donates $1 of the $6 he charges for his
tours, which he leads on Sunday afternoons in the spring and fall.
</P>
<P>
   Moylan is learning about fund-raising and grants, and is
investigating that '90s concept, corporate sponsorship, to restore
monuments with strong ties to New York companies. Among the
well-known corporate names represented at Green-Wood are Tiffany,
Brooks (as in Brothers), F.A.O. Schwarz, Eberhard Faber of pencil
fame, and the Browns of the investment firm Brown Brothers
Harriman.
</P>
<P>
   Visitors lucky enough to tour with Richman, a lawyer who became
an author and passionate Green-Wood fan, can hear about all these
and more. Leonard Bernstein is buried at Green-Wood, and so is
actor Frank Morgan, who played the Wizard of Oz.
</P>
<P>
   There are artists _ both Currier and Ives _ and newspapermen,
including Horace Greeley. Inventors abound, and are credited by
Richman with creating everything from the telegraph and typewriter
to safety pins and hotel room service.
</P>
<P>
   Most entertaining, perhaps, are Richman's stories of the
outrageous, extravagant and eccentric celebrities of 19th-century
New York. Richman describes the miser who left his fortune to the
American Society for the Prevention of Cruelty to Animals., the
mining magnate with a heated tomb, and the woman who vowed to give
the most lavish party ever, which she did _ and then fled the
country a step ahead of the tax man.
</P>
<P>
   What kind of people go on his tours? History hounds, Brooklyn
buffs, Civil War enthusiasts, bird-watchers and genealogy mavens,
Richman said. And then there are the increasing number of Americans
who just love cemeteries.
</P>
<P>
   Katie Karrick said that when she started a newsletter called
``Tomb With a View'' in 1995, ``I got 60 subscribers, and I was
flabbergasted.'' Today, she has 500 paying customers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Victorians really glorified death; we try to ignore it,''
Ms. Karrick said. But that may be changing as the baby boomers
think about dying and want to make sure they are noticed even after
death, she said. The new fashion in headstones is to include a lot
of information about the deceased, like their occupations and
hobbies, as well as photographs. ``I call them resume stones,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Karrick leads a tour in Cleveland called ``Stones and
Bones,'' which is one of the graveyard trips run by Trolley Tours
of Cleveland. ``If you do it in a reverential, pleasant way, and
with a sense of humor, people are very receptive,'' said Sherrill
Paul, president of the tour company, which takes more than 500
people a year on cemetery trips.
</P>
<P>
   Mount Auburn in Cambridge has produced a cassette tape, titled
``Reflections,'' that guides drivers around its 12 miles of roads.
It also has maps showing the locations of unusual trees. As many as
125,000 people a year visit the cemetery, said Janet Heywood,
director of interpretive programs for Mount Auburn, though some of
those are mourners, not tourists.
</P>
<P>
   So Moylan may be right when he predicts that people will start
visiting Green-Wood again, the way they did a century ago. ``I
don't know if we can get back to the picnic baskets around the
lake,'' he said, ``but we can hope.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
