<HEADLINE>
UNION LEADERS SAY THEY SUPPORT BOEING'S FINAL CONTRACT OFFER 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Wash.)  (js) 
 By LAURENCE ZUCKERMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Leaders of the International Association of Machinists and
Aerospace Workers endorsed a contract proposal from Boeing Co. on
Saturday, greatly reducing the chances that its 44,000 members will
strike on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   After 12 days of intense negotiations at a hotel outside
Seattle, Boeing submitted its final contract proposal to the
machinists early Saturday, offering several concessions and a wage
increase of nearly 16 percent over three years.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe this contract is the best contract in aerospace,
period,'' said Bill Johnson, a union negotiator who is also
president of the Seattle local that represents 31,000 Boeing
workers. ``They gave us everything we wanted.''
</P>
<P>
   But the endorsement of the leaders of the union, which
represents nearly one-quarter of Boeing's 207,000 workers, does not
guarantee that a strike will be averted. The union leadership also
backed a company proposal in 1995, only to see it rejected by the
workers, leading to a 69-day strike. In 1992, the leadership was
neutral about the company's offer that was subsequently approved by
the membership.
</P>
<P>
   Union members will vote on the proposal on Wednesday, the last
day of their 44-month contract. A majority is needed to approve the
offer. If that vote fails, a two-thirds majority is needed to
initiate a walkout that could begin as early as 12:01 a.m. on
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   A strike would cripple the Seattle-area factories that produce
Boeing's flagship commercial jets at a time when the company is
beginning to recover from a costly production foul-up that forced
it to halt production for a month in 1997 and caused the company to
post its first annual loss in 50 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that we have a contract we can be proud of,'' Philip
M. Condit, Boeing's chairman and chief executive, said in an
interview Saturday. ``I think it is saleable to the membership.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   One hour after the union's midnight Friday negotiating deadline
had passed, Boeing caved in on several important issues. The
company withdrew its effort to introduce alternative work schedules
that would have forced union members to work weekend shifts without
earning overtime pay. It also dropped a proposal that union members
contribute to health insurance premiums, which are now fully paid
by Boeing.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Boeing agreed to increase retirement benefits by 25
percent, raising the monthly benefit to $1,500 for a worker who
retired after 30 years of service. The final proposal also promised
that no jobs would be cut as a result of subcontracting, a major
concern of the machinists, who fear that Boeing will try to
increase its profits by shifting work to outside suppliers.
</P>
<P>
   Workers are especially jittery because after expecting to
produce a record 680 airplanes this year, Boeing is planning to
make only 480 next year. Last December, the company said it planned
to lay off 48,000 union and nonunion employees by the end of next
year. More than 30,000 jobs have been cut in the past year.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing executives said the new contract would make union members
among the best-paid workers in the nation. Today the average
machinist at Boeing earns $21.07 an hour, or about $44,000 a year,
the company said, although that figure can more than double with
overtime earned during peak production. Over the course of the
proposed contract, the average wage would rise to $24.35 an hour.
Boeing is also offering a 10 percent signing bonus, or about $4,400
per worker, if the contract is ratified by Wednesday.
</P>
</TEXT>
