<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-STADIUMS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    VANISHING BALLPARKS
 &HT;    A handful of stadiums live on as endangered monuments to
baseball's past
 &HT;    (EDS: Package includes: BBO-STADIUMS-CANDLESTICK,
BBO-STADIUMS-COUNTY, BBO-STADIUMS-FENWAY, BBO-STADIUMS-TIGER,
BBO-STADIUMS-WRIGLEY, BBO-STADIUMS-YANKEE)
 &HT;    By Terence Moore
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   (BEGIN ITAL) And there used to be a ballpark
</P>
<P>
   where the field was warm and green
</P>
<P>
   And the people played their crazy game
</P>
<P>
   with a joy I'd never seen
</P>
<P>
   And the air was such a wonder
</P>
<P>
   from the hot dog and the beer
</P>
<P>
   Yes, there used to be a ballpark right here. (END ITAL)
</P>
<P>
   _ Frank Sinatra
</P>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ One by one in the 1960s or 1970s, their sacred walls
were rocked by wrecking balls instead of baseballs. Crosley, Ebbets
and Forbes fields. The Polo Grounds, Sportsman's Park and the rest.
</P>
<P>
   They were replaced by multipurpose flying-saucer stadiums or
domed facilities. Now, the trend is for new-old ballparks that
resemble their distant forefathers _ minus the bad sight lines,
sparse restrooms and lack of luxury boxes.
</P>
<P>
   However, even with the Braves' Turner Field and the Orioles'
Camden Yards leading the explosion of new-old ballparks into the
next century, the old-old places still exist.
</P>
<P>
   For the moment.
</P>
<P>
   Of baseball's six oldest major-league ballparks, three will be
gone after this year: Tiger Stadium in Detroit, Milwaukee County
Stadium and San Francisco's 3Com Park, formerly known as
Candlestick. In Boston, Fenway Park is fading fast, and although
New York's Yankee Stadium and Chicago's Wrigley Field are safe now,
both could vanish in a flash.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all like new things, but baseball history is starting to
pass us by,'' said Billy Williams, who spent most of his Hall of
Fame career at Wrigley with the Cubs. ``When you think of these
ballparks, you go back to the turn of the century. You think of all
of the players who sat on those benches and dressed in those
clubhouses.''
</P>
<P>
   Others aren't as sentimental. Past and current players at
Milwaukee County Stadium say the home clubhouse reeks after heavy
rains from an eternal sewage problem. Former Red Sox catcher
Carlton Fisk suggests that ``the varmints and rodents'' at Fenway
are bigger than the Green Monster. Jack Clark often spoke during
his Giants days of praying for an earthquake to destroy windy and
chilly Candlestick Park.
</P>
<P>
   ``At Tiger Stadium, the dugouts are so low that you walk in and
hit your head on the ceiling,'' said Harmon Killebrew, the former
Twins slugger. ``People would say, `Don't feel bad. Ty Cobb did the
same thing.' That's when I first came into the league (in 1954),
and they were even talking about a new ballpark in Detroit back
then.''
</P>
<P>
   Former Orioles great Brooks Robinson shrugged, saying, ``Hey,
it's sad to see all of these places go, but after a while, you
really don't think a whole lot about it. I'll miss them, though.''
</P>
<P>
   Terence Moore writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
