<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-28 15:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2824 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-BBO-STADIUMS-CANDLEST     08-28 0759
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-STADIUMS-CANDLESTICK-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Candlestick's cold creates home-field advantage
 &HT;    By Terence Moore
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Mark Twain died nearly five decades before the Giants moved from
New York to San Francisco. To paraphrase the noted humorist,
however, the coldest winter that anybody could spend would be to
attend a baseball game at Candlestick Point.
</P>
<P>
   No ballpark is more affected by Mother Nature than Candlestick _
or 3Com, as it's been known since 1995 _ where games often are
played in swirling winds, brutal temperatures, blinding fog or all
three.
</P>
<P>
   ``Over the years, the weather actually has gotten better for
us,'' says Dusty Baker, an expert on the horrors of Candlestick
Point. This season is his seventh as the Giants' manager. He
visited San Francisco for 14 years as a Brave or Dodger, and he was
a Giants outfielder for a season and a Giants coach for five more.
</P>
<P>
   ``The wind isn't as bad as it has been, because we play more day
games,'' Baker says, smiling. Then he quickly frowns, because he
knows pleasant days at Candlestick Point don't help his team retain
baseball's most striking home-field advantage.
</P>
<P>
   It is an advantage only when Giants players realize it. Except
for brief periods, most of those on the home team have loathed the
place more than their opponents.
</P>
<P>
   Right-handed slugger Willie Mays quietly adjusted his swing to
take advantage of the wind gusts to right field before the park was
enclosed at that end. But many former Giants, particularly Jack
Clark and Johnnie LeMaster, spent most of their careers ripping
Candlestick between chattering teeth.
</P>
<P>
   Given the location near the coldest part of San Francisco Bay,
even the builders knew that the ballpark would become a freezer
with a diamond in the middle.
</P>
<P>
   A radiant heating system was installed in the reserved-seating
area, but it rarely worked. A fan once sued the Giants, saying he
was forced to leave his seat during rallies because his feet were
freezing. A jury awarded him $1,597.
</P>
<P>
   ``On those cold nights, we put on hot Vaseline and baby oil,
stuff like that, to make us warmer,'' says Hall of Famer Juan
Marichal, a Giants pitcher during the 1960s. ``Some guys, they
really hate that place. But I loved it. I had so many great games
there, I cannot complain. If the opposing player didn't like it,
I'd take advantage of it.''
</P>
<P>
   More than a decade after Marichal's retirement, former Giants
manager Roger Craig's no-griping philosophy helped turn a
struggling franchise into a playoff contender.
</P>
<P>
   Baker worked for Craig, and has kept the old philosophy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our players really don't complain about the weather,'' Baker
says. ``It is a great advantage for us. If a team is on a West
Coast swing, and if their star needs a day off, you know what will
happen? He won't take that day in Los Angeles or San Diego, where
the weather is sunny, warm and bright. He'll take it in San
Francisco.''
</P>
<P>
   So, when the Giants move next season, will Baker be
disappointed? ``Not really,'' Baker says, laughing. ``Unh-uh.''
</P>
<P>
   MEMORABLE MOMENTS
</P>
<P>
   July 11, 1961: The Giants' Stu Miller is blown off the mound by
raging winds during the first of two All-Star Games.
</P>
<P>
   Aug. 22, 1965: Pitcher Juan Marichal uses a bat to bash Dodgers
catcher John Roseboro in the back of the head during a brawl.
</P>
<P>
   July 3, 1966: Braves pitcher Tony Cloninger becomes the first
National League player to hit two grand slams in the same game.
</P>
<P>
   Sept. 17-18, 1968: The Giants' Gaylord Perry and the Cardinals'
Ray Washburn throw consecutive no-hitters.
</P>
<P>
   Oct. 17, 1989: Before Game 3 of the World Series, an earthquake
strikes. The Series returns to Oakland and the A's complete a 4-0
sweep.
</P>
<P>
   CANDLESTICK (3COM) PARK
</P>
<P>
   Opening day: April 12, 1960. The Giants beat the St. Louis
Cardinals 3-1.
</P>
<P>
   Location: On Candlestick Point, just southeast of downtown San
Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Capacity: 63,000.
</P>
<P>
   Status: This is 3Com's final season. Next year the Giants will
move into Pacific Bell Park, an open-air stadium located downtown
near the China Basin area around San Francisco Bay.
</P>
<P>
   History lesson: When city officials held a contest to name the
stadium, they received more than 20,000 entries. The sports editors
of San Francisco's four daily papers served as judges, and they
chose the name because of its location on Candlestick Point.
</P>
<P>
   Terence Moore writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
