</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-STADIUMS-COUNTY-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    At County Stadium, Braves memories prevail
 &HT;    By Terence Moore
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   It doesn't have Wrigley's ivy or the legendary right-field porch
of Tiger Stadium. A Green Monster? The most striking thing
involving that color inside County Stadium was the Packers, but
they eventually left to play all of their games in Green Bay, Wisc.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine an often chilly and an eternally gray building in the
middle of a parking lot. It's either one of the city's abandoned
breweries or County Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   The ballpark was built during the early 1950s, and it
accommodated the Braves after their swift move from Boston in 1953.
When the Braves scooted away before the 1966 season to play in
Atlanta, County Stadium was mostly vacant until the Brewers arrived
four years later.
</P>
<P>
   Braves. Packers. Brewers. It hasn't mattered. Courtesy of
Wisconsin's brutal winters, County Stadium isn't aging gracefully.
``You definitely have to say that, aesthetically, it isn't the
greatest thing to see from the outside,'' says Hall of Famer Robin
Yount, who spent his career with the Brewers. ``It's also pretty
straightforward on the inside. It doesn't have any of those goofy
little things that would give you an advantage over the opponent.''
</P>
<P>
   Even so, County Stadium manages to glow despite its physical
gloom, and it has nothing to do with the large barrel beyond the
center-field bleachers featuring Bernie Brewer. He's the team
mascot who slides into a stein of balloons after a Brewer hits a
homer.
</P>
<P>
   Two things rank County Stadium among the game's special places:
food and memories.
</P>
<P>
   County Stadium is peerless when it comes to making the perfect
hot dog, bratwurst and Polish and Italian sausages. The concessions
serve a distinctive German mustard, and they have a ``secret
sauce'' for meats that is so popular that local stores sell it by
the gallon.
</P>
<P>
   A bakery turns out cookies, cinnamon rolls and pecan rolls fresh
by the inning.
</P>
<P>
   Also common at County Stadium are memories _ especially the ones
that broke an entire state's heart 34 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The Brewers have been here 30 years and reached the World Series
in 1982, but fans feel the 1950s Braves when they walk through the
gates.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always thought (County Stadium) was good to pitch in,
because the people of Milwaukee and of Wisconsin were such great
fans,'' says Warren Spahn, who helped the Braves of Hank Aaron and
Eddie Mathews capture two National League pennants and a world
championship. ``The atmosphere was one of camaraderie. They made us
feel at home.''
</P>
<P>
   Brewers great Paul Molitor says, ``What makes that ballpark
magical . . . is that you always realized what took place back when
the Braves were there.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being a small town, Milwaukee is almost the Green Bay of
baseball. You have a greater sense of community in that stadium.
People take pride in that they are the underdog. The tailgate
parties are so much bigger than any other ballpark.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't have the uniqueness of a Fenway or the intimacy of
a Wrigley, but Milwaukee County Stadium has emotion.''
</P>
<P>
   MEMORABLE MOMENTS
</P>
<P>
   Sept. 23, 1957: Hank Aaron's homer in the bottom of the 11th
wins the pennant for the Braves.
</P>
<P>
   May 26, 1959: The Pirates' Harvey Haddix pitches 12 perfect
innings but loses 1-0 to the Braves in the 13th.
</P>
<P>
   April 30, 1961: The Giants' Willie Mays hits four home runs in a
game against the Milwaukee Braves.
</P>
<P>
   July 20, 1976: Hank Aaron slams the 755th and final home run of
his career.
</P>
<P>
   Oct. 10, 1982: The Brewers become the first team in the history
of the League Championship Series to win the pennant after losing
the first two games of a best-of-five series. They beat the Angels
3-2 in the decisive game.
</P>
<P>
   COUNTY STADIUM
</P>
<P>
   Opening day: April 14, 1953. The Braves beat the St. Louis
Cardinals 4-3 in 10 innings.
</P>
<P>
   Location: On Milwaukee's west side, about five miles from
downtown, near I-94.
</P>
<P>
   Capacity: 53,192.
</P>
<P>
   Status: The Brewers were scheduled to move next season into
Miller Park (under construction, above), but a major construction
accident with the retractable roof has left the move in limbo.
</P>
<P>
   History lesson: This ballpark was the first built with public
money. Even though Milwaukee didn't have a team, the city broke
ground for a $5 million facility in 1950. The ballpark was nearly
finished when the Braves announced on March 18, 1953, that they
were moving from Boston to Milwaukee.
</P>
<P>
   Terence Moore writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
