<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-28 15:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2827 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-BBO-STADIUMS-FENWAY-C     08-28 0869
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-STADIUMS-FENWAY-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Fenway: Historic but humble
 &HT;    By Terence Moore
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   One of baseball's myths is that everybody loves Fenway Park.
Many do, of course. In fact, most who know the difference between
Carl Yastrzemski and a bowl of clam chowder tend to view this
quaint home of the Red Sox as perfection on earth.
</P>
<P>
   But more than a few New Englanders say it's time to rid their
historic landscape of a relic that is cramped and rickety.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Skusevich and Paul Mahoney are Boston natives, best buddies
and lifelong Red Sox fans. They are chatting in the narrow
concourse in Fenway's lower grandstands, where they prefer to stand
rather than to squeeze down the narrowest rows in the major leagues
to reach their season-ticket seats.
</P>
<P>
   As is the case throughout Fenway, their seats are comfortable
only for munchkins.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love the Sox, but this place stinks. It really does,'' says
Mahoney, 43, laughing and shaking his head. ``I've been coming here
since the Sox's Impossible Dream season of 1967, but I'll tell you
something. Since I'm getting older, wiser and wider, I need bigger
seats.''
</P>
<P>
   Skusevich, 47, chuckles. ``All I can tell you is that I'll be
very proud of the next ballpark in Boston,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   So you think these are just disgruntled fans, still distraught
about the sale of Babe Ruth to the Yankees, Bucky Dent's homer and
Bill Buckner's gaffe?
</P>
<P>
   Well, listen to Carlton Fisk, the former Red Sox catcher, who
kept jumping and waving until his home run in Game 6 of the 1975
World Series sailed fair, high over Fenway's left-field foul pole.
``Leaving Fenway will be a good thing,'' Fisk says, ``and I
certainly won't miss all of the varmints and rodents that crawl
around that place.''
</P>
<P>
   If Fisk isn't persuasive, how about Ted Williams, the greatest
Red Sox player of all? Asked if he holds the same sentiments of the
group known as Save Fenway, Williams says, ``Forget trying to
remodel. Get a new ballpark.''
</P>
<P>
   Don't get the wrong idea. Fenway definitely has its pluses.
There are many of them inside and outside the ballpark, whose debut
was pushed off the front pages of Boston newspapers by another big
story in April 1912. Something about the Titanic.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fenway has marvelous memories, and in the process of creating
the brand-new `old' Fenway, those memories won't disappear,'' says
Fisk, a New England native. ``The home runs will still have been
hit. The wins and the losses, along with the exciting times that
happened in that park, they all will remain. They will be in your
head forever.''
</P>
<P>
   Fenway is more than the Green Monster, the left-field wall that
is 37 feet high and 240 feet long. It's more than the quirky angles
and curves along the outfield wall.
</P>
<P>
   Fenway is the Citgo sign in the distance beyond left. Fenway is
Lansdowne Street, where drinking holes are packed, and fans gather
to wait for homers that sail over the 23-foot-high net above the
Monster. Fenway is Helen Robinson, telephone receptionist for the
Red Sox for 57 years. Fenway is the epidemic of pigeons that once
caused Williams to draw the ire of the humane society becaue he
shot some of them with his rifle.
</P>
<P>
   Mostly, according to a surprising number of observers, Fenway is
a creaky ballpark whose time has come.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think anybody really wants to leave Fenway Park,''
American League president Gene Budig says. ``Even so, it must be
done, and I think people have come to accept that.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Yankees manager Joe Torre, ``Fenway Park certainly
is one of the great places to watch baseball, but its time for a
change, and it's time for an upgrade.''
</P>
<P>
   Skusevich and Mahoney agree. Emphatically.
</P>
<P>
   MEMORABLE MOMENTS
</P>
<P>
   June 18, 1953: The Red Sox set a major-league record by scoring
17 runs in an inning against the Tigers.
</P>
<P>
   Sept. 28, 1960: Williams homers in his last at-bat in the
majors, circles the bases and heads to the clubhouse.
</P>
<P>
   Oct. 22, 1975: Carlton Fisk hits the left-field foul pole in the
bottom of the 12th inning against the Reds to win Game 6 of the
1975 World Series.
</P>
<P>
   Oct. 2, 1978: The Yankees' Bucky Dent hits a home run to left to
knock the Red Sox out of the postseason.
</P>
<P>
   FENWAY PARK
</P>
<P>
   Opening day: April 20, 1912. The Red Sox defeated the New York
Highlanders, later known as the Yankees, 7-6 in 11 innings.
</P>
<P>
   Location: Corner of Yawkey Way and Van Ness Street in the Fenway
section of Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Capacity: 33,871.
</P>
<P>
   Status: The Red Sox have announced plans for a $545 million
ballpark to be built next door to Fenway, although no timetable has
been set. Parts of the old park would become a museum.
</P>
<P>
   History lesson: Fenway's left-field wall was not known as the
Green Monster until 1947, when large advertisements were painted
over. Before, left field was notorious for a 10-foot embankment in
front of the wall, and fans sometimes were allowed to sit there.
Boston's Duffy Lewis was so skilled at playing balls hit to the
hill that it became known at ``Duffy's Cliff.''
</P>
<P>
   Terence Moore writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
