<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-28 15:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2828 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-BBO-STADIUMS-TIGER-CO     08-28 0862
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-STADIUMS-TIGER-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Tiger Stadium: Cozy, magical
 &HT;    By Terence Moore
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Moisture glistens in Al Kaline's eyes as he stands near the
batting cage at Tiger Stadium discussing his deepest love in
baseball.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first time I saw this ballpark was when I was 18,'' says
Kaline, a Hall of Fame outfielder who joined the Tigers in 1953.
</P>
<P>
   ``I came in right over there,'' he says, pointing toward an
entrance behind the seats along the third-base line. ``It was a
bright, sunny day, and all of the seats were a dark green. And it
was the most beautiful thing that I ever saw.
</P>
<P>
   ``The grass was so green. The dirt was so brown. I remember the
reflection of the sun against the green seats, and I still get
chills.''
</P>
<P>
   As Kaline chats with a visitor, never has the late-afternoon
Michigan sky been so lovely. Seagulls glide through the upper deck.
Ernie Harwell delivers pretty words about his ``Tig-ehs'' over the
airwaves. This is Tiger Stadium, and all is well with the world.
</P>
<P>
   With apologies to Fenway Park, Tiger Stadium is the most magical
ballpark this side of Wrigley Field. They have played baseball at
the corner of Michigan and Trumbull avenues for 103 years,
including the last 88 seasons in Tiger Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   The place is so cozy, you nearly step onto the field when you
walk through the turnstiles. The distant seats, amongst the
seagulls, seem just a couple of arm-lengths from second base.
</P>
<P>
   The flagpole in center field sits in fair territory. When you're
on the infield, it is evident that the legend about home plate
leaning toward right field is true.
</P>
<P>
   A porch of seats hangs over the field in right. The light
standards along the roof could tell stories, none greater than the
one about the home run that Reggie Jackson blasted there during the
1971 All-Star Game.
</P>
<P>
   And Kaline, always Kaline. ``I've spent every summer here for 46
years now,'' says Kaline, 64, who played for 22 seasons and now is
color commentator for the Tigers' TV network. ``This place really
has been a major part of my life.''
</P>
<P>
   Kaline was a perennial Gold Glove winner, noted for falling over
the low wall down the right-field line in pursuit of foul fly
balls. The fans called it ``Kaline's Corner,'' and the Tigers
removed several box seats from that area to keep their star player
from a premature death.
</P>
<P>
   Good thing, or Kaline wouldn't have been around to help the
Tigers soothe a riot-torn city in the fall of 1968, after they beat
the St. Louis Cardinals in a thrilling World Series.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I'll actually remember more is the day we clinched the
'68 pennant here,'' Kaline says. ``I'm looking around now, and I'm
sensing the presence of guys like Ty Cobb, Charlie Gehringer, Babe
Ruth, Hank Greenberg. It's great to know that you played on the
same field as those guys.''
</P>
<P>
   But this field of dreams is just weeks from its final memory.
Tiger Stadium will be replaced next year by one of those new-old
ballparks in the middle of downtown.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to televise the last game, and I just hope I can
get through it,'' Kaline says. ``I'm sure they'll have special
festivities. They'll bring back former players. So many teams. So
many guys who are no longer with us.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of things will be going through my mind. I hope I'm not
too emotional, but I know I will be.''
</P>
<P>
   MEMORABLE MOMENTS
</P>
<P>
   Oct. 9, 1934: Enraged fans throw fruit, garbage and shoes at St.
Louis outfielder Joe Medwick after he spiked Tigers third baseman
Marv Owen in a World Series game. Commissioner Kenesaw Mountain
Landis has Medwick removed from the game for his safety.
</P>
<P>
   May 2, 1939: Lou Gehrig's streak of games played ends at 2,130.
</P>
<P>
   July 13, 1971: Six future Hall of Famers _ Johnny Bench, Hank
Aaron, Reggie Jackson, Frank Robinson, Harmon Killebrew and Roberto
Clemente _ homer during the AL's 6-4 All-Star Game victory.
</P>
<P>
   June 28, 1976: Pitcher Mark ``The Bird'' Fidrych thrills a
packed house by talking to the baseball on the mound during a
nationally televised victory over the Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   July 8, 1941: Ted Williams ends the most dramatic All-Star Game
with a three-run homer in the bottom of the ninth inning, giving
the American League a 7-5 victory.
</P>
<P>
   TIGER STADIUM
</P>
<P>
   Opening day: April 20, 1912. The Tigers defeated the Cleveland
Indians 6-5.
</P>
<P>
   Location: The corner of Michigan and Trumbull avenues in
Detroit's Corktown neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   Capacity: 46,945.
</P>
<P>
   Status: This season is Tiger Stadium's last. Next year, the team
will move into Comerica Park, an open-air stadium being built one
mile southeast of Tiger Stadium in Detroit's theater district.
</P>
<P>
   History lesson: They've played baseball on what is known as
``The Corner'' since 1896. The original structure was called
Bennett Park. The facility was reconstructed into its basic current
shape in 1912 and was named Navin Field the following year. It was
changed to Briggs Stadium after another expansion project in 1938
and to Tiger Stadium in 1961.
</P>
<P>
   Terence Moore writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-28-99 1529EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990828.0175 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-28 15:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2829 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-BBO-STADIUMS-WRIGLEY     08-28 0830
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-STADIUMS-WRIGLEY </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Wrigley: The only ancient ballpark that still works
 &HT;    By Terence Moore
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's the All-Star Game in Boston, and Ernie Banks loses his
smile for the first time ever. A guy just asked the Hall of Famer
if he thinks somebody will do the unthinkable some day by yanking
the ivy _ and everything else _ out of Wrigley Field.
</P>
<P>
   Inquiring minds want to know. After all, most of baseball's
magic places of yore are gone or on the endangered list.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think they'll ever tear down Wrigley Field,'' Banks
says. ``It will withstand the test of time and the history of
baseball.''
</P>
<P>
   Even so, these are the final days of Tiger Stadium, and Fenway
Park is going the way of the British in New England. When they're
gone . . .
</P>
<P>
   ``Wrigley would be the last of the great ballparks, wouldn't
it?'' Banks says, slowly regaining the happy face he owned during
19 seasons as Mr. Cub.
</P>
<P>
   Wrigley is the only ancient ballpark that still works, thanks to
renovation over the years. Former Cubs owner Philip K. Wrigley
replaced many of Wrigley's seats in the 1950s to angle them toward
home plate. The Tribune Company bought the Cubs in 1981 and have
added new clubhouses and luxury boxes. They also added lights in
1988 for a limited number of night games.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Wrigley remains Wrigley. The concourses and the rows
between seats are strikingly wide for a place of Wrigley's age. The
hand-operated scoreboard in center field rises 27 feet and
stretches 75 feet wide. Fans watch games from rooftops of homes
just yards from the outfield. Sailboats glide along Lake Michigan.
The distinctive Chicago skyline can be seen everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   And the ivy is thick and green across the red bricks of
Wrigley's outfield walls.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been walking into that ballpark for 38 years,'' Banks
says, ``and it's better-looking now than it was when I played
there.''
</P>
<P>
   Billy Williams agrees. Like Banks, Williams is a Hall of Famer,
and he spent 16 years at Wrigley after joining the Cubs in 1959.
</P>
<P>
   ``At that time, people didn't cherish Wrigley like they do
now,'' Williams says. ``When I first walked inside, it wasn't
nearly as beautiful as it would become. You had the old coal
furnaces. The dirt was black. It didn't seem as if the sun shined
that much.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, you see all of the changes. It's not just the things on
the inside that attract people but things on the outside.''
</P>
<P>
   Street musicians play, the acts ranging from fancy saxophones to
a guy using tree limbs to beat a plastic garbage can. Old men on
bikes sell ice cream. Kids are everywhere. People talk Cubs
baseball until closing time at the many bars and restaurants nearly
as ancient as Wrigley's foundation. ``One of the great things about
Wrigley is that it is full of novelties, and that gives you so many
opportunities for different things to happen,'' says former
Phillies third baseman Mike Schmidt, who once hit four homers in a
game at Wrigley.
</P>
<P>
   Cubs announcer Chip Caray says, ``Wrigley is like walking back
into time. People like that. It's a sense of consistency in an era
of turmoil and uncertainty. Imagining Cub baseball without Wrigley
Field is like trying to imagine baseball without a bat.''
</P>
<P>
   MEMORABLE MOMENTS
</P>
<P>
   Oct. 1, 1932: Babe Ruth allegedly points toward the center-field
bleachers in Game 3 of the World Series, then slams the next pitch
from the Cubs' Charlie Root there for a homer.
</P>
<P>
   Sept. 28, 1938: Gabby Hartnett's ``Homer in the Gloamin' ''
beats the Pirates and wins the pennant for the Cubs, just before
umpires would have called the game because of darkness.
</P>
<P>
   May 12, 1970: Ernie Banks slams his 500th career homer off
Atlanta's Pat Jarvis.
</P>
<P>
   Sept. 8, 1985: Pete Rose raps his 4,191st career hit, which ties
him with Ty Cobb for the most in baseball history.
</P>
<P>
   Aug. 9, 1988: Wrigley Field becomes the last team in the major
leagues to host a night game. Cubs win, beating the Mets 6-4.
</P>
<P>
   WRIGLEY FIELD
</P>
<P>
   Opening day: April 20, 1916. The Cubs beat the Cincinnati Reds
7-6 in 11 innings before a crowd that included a bear cub.
</P>
<P>
   Location: Corner of Clark and Addison streets on the north side
of Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   Capacity: 39,957.
</P>
<P>
   Status: Great. Given the improvements at Wrigley over the last
17 years, the ballpark is nearly as profitable as some of its
new-old counterparts.
</P>
<P>
   History lesson: Originally known as Weeghman Park, Wrigley Field
was built in 1914 as a home for Chicago's entry in the Federal
League. When the league folded after the 1915 season, owner Charles
H. Weeghman bought the Cubs and moved them into his two-year-old
ballpark. The stadium was renamed Cubs Park in 1920 after the
Wrigley family purchased the team, and the name was changed to
Wrigley Field in 1926 in honor of William Wrigley Jr.
</P>
<P>
   Terence Moore writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
