<HEADER>
A2830 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-BBO-STADIUMS-YANKEE-C     08-28 0732
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-STADIUMS-YANKEE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Yankee Stadium has changed, but the ghosts remain
 &HT;    By Terence Moore
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The new Yankee Stadium isn't the old Yankee Stadium. For
decades, the House that Ruth Built featured a copper facade along
its majestic roof. This was long before they altered the ballpark
in the mid-1970s, lowering the playing field, shortening the
home-run distances in all but right field and adding escalator
towers.
</P>
<P>
   What didn't change was the ghosts.
</P>
<P>
   Next to Notre Dame Stadium, no American sports facility has more
ghosts than Yankee Stadium. They're everywhere, as prevalent on
that side of the Bronx as the monuments behind the left-field fence
to honor Henry Louis Gehrig, Miller James Huggins, Mickey Charles
Mantle, Joseph Paul DiMaggio and George Herman Ruth.
</P>
<P>
   Thirty-one years later, Bobby Cox still tingles when he talks
about the first time he walked into Yankee Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was my first year in the big leagues, and I was in the
starting lineup for the Yankees,'' the Braves' manager says. ``I'll
never forget how I got chills when they began to play the national
anthem.
</P>
<P>
   ``They had that old safe in the clubhouse, where Gehrig and Ruth
used to put their valuables. It was exactly the same safe. You knew
those great Yankee players went through that same door to the
clubhouse. The dugout was exactly the same, too. You just had the
feeling of what had taken place before. You felt the Yankee
mystique.''
</P>
<P>
   You still do. Underneath Yankee Stadium is a wonderful maze. A
series of tunnels take you to both clubhouses, various equipment
rooms and other places of mystery.
</P>
<P>
   Your heart pumps faster. You imagine those ghosts. Maybe this
dent in the floor came from Lou Gehrig's spikes. Did Babe Ruth
smoke cigars in that room over there? Which one of these door knobs
has Mickey Mantle's fingerprints?
</P>
<P>
   ``You really can't do that, because that area was redone during
the renovation,'' says Marty Appel, 51, a Yankee historian and
former public-relations director. Like Cox, Appel cherished the
Yankees' old safe. It dated to 1903, when the franchise was known
as the Highlanders. Its drawers featured the names of star players,
from Wee Willie Keeler to Jack Chesbro.
</P>
<P>
   Appel made it a personal mission to make sure the safe would be
preserved during renovation. But soon after the final game of the
1973 season, wrecking balls ripped into the stadium's sacred walls,
and Appel's worst fears were realized.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people I talked to about removing the safe forgot about
it,'' Appel said. ``The safe probably was destroyed. It's been 25
years. So, if somebody stole it, it would have shown up by now.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sorry to say this, but you can't say that anything at
Yankee Stadium now is the way it was when Ruth and Gehrig played.''
</P>
<P>
   That sound you hear isn't Ruth or Gehrig flipping in their
graves. It is their ghosts, moaning as they walk unfamiliar
hallways in the new Yankee Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   MEMORABLE MOMENTS
</P>
<P>
   July 4, 1939: A dying Lou Gehrig tells the crowd, ``Today, I
consider myself the luckiest man on the face of the earth.''
</P>
<P>
   Oct. 8, 1956: Don Larsen throws the only perfect game in World
Series history against the Brooklyn Dodgers.
</P>
<P>
   Oct. 1, 1961: Roger Maris' 61st homer breaks Babe Ruth's single
season record.
</P>
<P>
   Oct. 18, 1977: Reggie Jackson slams three home runs in Game 6 of
the World Series against the Dodgers.
</P>
<P>
   May 22, 1963: Mickey Mantle sends a pitch against the facade
above the third deck in right field. According to an engineer, the
shot could have reached 620 feet.
</P>
<P>
   YANKEE STADIUM
</P>
<P>
   Opening day: April 18, 1923. The Yankees beat the Boston Red Sox
4-1.
</P>
<P>
   Location: On 161st street at River Avenue in the Bronx.
</P>
<P>
   Capacity: 57,768.
</P>
<P>
   Status: The Yankees have a lease through 2002, but owner George
Steinbrenner often threatens to move the team to New Jersey or
Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   History lesson: Before Yankee Stadium opened, the Yankees shared
the Polo Grounds with the Giants for 10 years. When the Yankees
became more popular than the Giants, as Babe Ruth started to grab
the nation's attention, Giants manager John McGraw told the Polo
Grounds' other tenant to get lost.
</P>
<P>
   Terence Moore writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
