<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-28 15:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2831 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-CAR-SERIES-WHITE-COX     08-28 1671
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-SERIES-WHITE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Rex White: A modest racing legend
 &HT;    By Al Levine
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Rex White lives a quiet, humble life in Forest Park,
Ga. He has a house trailer a few blocks from his job at a trucking
company, where at age 70 he works seven days a week from 5:45 a.m.
until nearly 10 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   ``Work is good for you, no matter how old you are,'' White said.
``If you sit around and feel sorry for yourself, you're gonna hurt;
you're gonna ache.''
</P>
<P>
   It is incongruous: A former NASCAR champion now drives a fork
lift that can't go faster than 15 mph. But White, who speaks with a
Southern-fried drawl, prefers life in the slow lane now.
</P>
<P>
   When White filled out an application at Jones Transportation, he
didn't list his racing career under ``previous employment.'' Just
mentioned that he had owned his own truck. Many of his 30
co-workers didn't learn of his accomplishments until last year,
when NASCAR named White one of the 50 greatest drivers. He is not
one to brag about his 1960 Grand National (later Winston Cup)
championship, the most popular driver award he got that year or
some of his impressive racing statistics, including 110 top-five
finishes in 233 career starts.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is such a quiet man,'' his boss, Ed Whitworth, said. ``His
background came out in little pieces. Whenever the guys would be
talking about racing, Rex would say something that gave us the idea
he had been involved.''
</P>
<P>
   When the picture of the top 50 drivers arrived from NASCAR,
Whitworth asked if he could frame it and hang it in his office.
``Rex said, `Sure,' without hesitation,'' Whitworth said. ``His
wife is dead; his daughter is dead; we're his family.
</P>
<P>
   ``And I would bet that if someone came in and offered him a
million dollars for the picture, and I said, `Remember, Rex, you
said I could have it,' he'd tell them it wasn't for sale. He's that
kind of guy. If you called him at midnight and said you had a flat
tire, he'd be right there to fix it. But if you called him at
midnight and said you wanted him to come out for a beer with a
bunch of other stock-car drivers, he'd hang up on you; he just
doesn't want that kind of exposure.''
</P>
<P>
   So when NASCAR invited White to Daytona Beach, Fla., as part of
its 50th anniversary celebration last year, he respectfully
declined. It meant he probably would be under the spotlight,
probably would have to wear a suit.
</P>
<P>
   ``That ain't me,'' he said. ``I didn't go at all. Everybody
started to hop on it, wanting to get me dressed, wanting to take me
to Daytona and do different things. Finally, I told 'em, `I ain't
even gonna go.' . . . I wasn't up for buying clothes, getting
dressed up, going down there and getting in all that mess.''
</P>
<P>
   Unrecognized at AMS
</P>
<P>
   A dozen years ago, White decided he would like to attend a race
at Atlanta Motor Speedway and called someone at the track for a
pass. He was told that he would have to pick up the credential at
the track.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went down there, went to where the people pick up their
press passes and told this woman my name,'' he said. ``She said,
`I'm sorry. You have to apply two weeks in advance to get 'em.'
When she said that, well, I just left.''
</P>
<P>
   He didn't make a fuss about it, but Neil Bonnett, now deceased,
heard about the incident, told the track employee about White and
sent the highway patrol to find him and give him his pass.
</P>
<P>
   White didn't go unnoticed when he won the 1960 championship, and
he was unprepared for all the attention.
</P>
<P>
   ``Winning that championship was like becoming a movie star,''
White said. ``Everybody's wanting your autograph; everybody's
wanting to talk to you on the phone. You can't have a telephone.
You can't go nowhere; you can't do nuthin'. Being Jeff Gordon,
that's a tough job.''
</P>
<P>
   He even dressed up to receive his award.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I went to Daytona to be at the dinner, a lot of people
had even come down there in T-shirts to collect their awards,''
White said. ``Everybody that participated in my crew, even if they
didn't get paid nuthin', I bought 'em all suits.''
</P>
<P>
   White prefers his low-key life, with few reminders of his racing
career. He can't remember when he sold his race cars. ``I did my
racing stuff just like I do everything else; when I'm done with it,
I get rid of it.''
</P>
<P>
   He never made huge paydays in racing. ``When I won the
championship in 1960, what I collected at Daytona was $13,500,'' he
said. ``In my whole racing career, I think they got me down winning
only $85,000. I don't think that includes the old style modifieds _
just in Winston Cup or Grand National. All together, it might have
been over $100,000, I forget. But it wasn't much.
</P>
<P>
   ``Didn't get rich racing. I probably got more money right now
than in any time in my racing career. I know I have, in the bank.''
</P>
<P>
   He was in the parts business once and regrets not staying in it.
``For some reason or other, my hindsight has always been better
than my foresight,'' he said. ``And I ain't never had a lot of
foresight, really. I don't think about things; I just do 'em.''
</P>
<P>
   Overcame childhood polio
</P>
<P>
   Not that he regrets having to work at his age.
</P>
<P>
   His consolation is that he did pretty well for a kid with polio.
White was stricken when he was 11. ``One leg is shorter than the
other,'' he said. ``I don't have any leg hardly at all on my right
leg; there ain't nothin' but bone. There's certain things with the
throttle I had to do to make it so my crippled foot could work it.
You'd jump in somebody else's race car, and if it wasn't fixed up
it makes it tough. Can't do it like everybody else.''
</P>
<P>
   White grew up in Taylorsville, N.C.,destined to be a race
driver. ``It's 15 miles from North Wilkesboro. Alexander Wilkes
County was the bootleg capital of the United States, of making
white liquor. Everybody hauled it; everybody sold it.
</P>
<P>
   ``This revenuer comes into town, and he asks this guy on the
sidewalk, `Where can you buy some white liquor?' He said, `You see
that building over there. That's the post office. That's the only
place in town you can't buy it.'
</P>
<P>
   ``I grew up around a lot of fast cars,'' White said. ``I never
hauled an ounce of liquor in my life. I've rode with guys hauling
it.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1941, at age 12, he was helping deliver chickens to Maryland,
without a driver's license. Seven years later, while working at a
gas station, he decided to become a racer.
</P>
<P>
   ``We used to race sometimes six times in one week, twice on
Sunday,'' White said. ``In New Jersey and Pennsylvania, there's
race tracks everywhere. We lived in the car, just went race track
to race track, slept in the car. Took baths in the creek. There
were no such things as motels.''
</P>
<P>
   Racing under two names
</P>
<P>
   By 1954, at age 25, he was running in NASCAR events. ``If you
joined NASCAR, you can't run no other car,'' White said. But
Manassas, Va., had two tracks. He won on Friday night, then ran at
the other track on Saturday under an assumed name.
</P>
<P>
   ``I ran as Johnny Nalon,'' White said, ``and won the race. They
had a race driver at Indianapolis called Duke Nalon, and that's
where I got the name. They published it in the paper. So I went to
Marlboro Raceway and I won on Sunday. I run down there under Johnny
Nalon also. The sportswriters would come up to me and say, `Who are
you tonight?' ''
</P>
<P>
   Three years later, he was hired by General Motors as a
short-track specialist.
</P>
<P>
   He won his only points title in 1960 and was well on his way to
repeating when he was penalized for altering the position of his
engine. He said Ned Jarrett, whom he had helped get a Chevrolet
ride, and another driver for whom he'd built a car, Emanuel
Zervakis, turned him in to officials.
</P>
<P>
   ``To start with, it was somethin' picky. It didn't mean nuthin'.
It didn't change nuthin'. It didn't make me win or lose,'' White
said. ``In the rear cross-member in the Chevrolet, there's two bolt
holes that hold the rear motor mount. . . . I didn't change
nuthin'. All I did was slide the engine to the back of the bolt
hole, about three-quarters of an inch.
</P>
<P>
   ``At Darlington, they complained about it, which would have been
fine. We had to go there a week for inspections. . . .Norris Field
was the head inspector for NASCAR and he waited 'til Sunday morning
to tell me I was disqualified. I couldn't fix the car. I started a
car for Jack Smith, but I couldn't do no good with it and finished
dead last. That race would have won the championship for me the
second time.''
</P>
<P>
   Jarrett won the 1961 title, by 830 points. ``It don't bother me
that much,'' White said. ``If he wants to be that way, that's fine.
I still outrun him more times than he ever outrun me.''
</P>
<P>
   A few years ago, Jarrett, a TV commentator, saw White at
Talladega and approached him for an interview. White declined. ``It
is still a sore spot,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Short and with a grin that resembled that of George Gobel, a
corny comedian of the day, White was admired for his natural feel
for a car and the way he set up a chassis. Old-timers still kid
about his difficulty getting a driver's license in South Carolina.
Unlike most states, you had to have a regular street license to
race there, and White had trouble parallel parking. But it has been
years since he's seen any of the old gang. Maybe, he has started to
think, it's time. ``I might go to that old-timer's banquet in
Daytona next year,'' White said. ``I just may buy me a . . . suit
and go on down there.''
</P>
<P>
   THE 60s: THE REX WHITE FILE
</P>
<P>
   Age: 70.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia connection: Lives, and raced for most of his career, in
Forest Park, Ga. Born in Taylorsville, N.C.
</P>
<P>
   NASCAR career: 1956-64.
</P>
<P>
   Career highlights: 1960 Grand National (later Winston Cup)
champion and most popular driver, with six victories and 35 top-10
finishes in 40 races. Had 233 career starts, 28 victories, 36
poles; won $223,514.
</P>
<P>
   Al Levine writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution, Atlanta,
Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
