<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-28 15:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2832 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-OLY-MARTINO-COX     08-28 1049
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-MARTINO-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Martino aims at Games comeback
 &HT;    By Karen Rosen
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MILLEDGEVILLE, Ga. _ The Martino family has your typical
backyard pool: just big enough to splash around in, with a diving
board and some lounge chairs.
</P>
<P>
   The Martinos also have what might be the world's most atypical
backyard pool: 50 meters long, two lanes wide and erected above the
ground so that from the side it looks like a marooned barge.
</P>
<P>
   That, pool, which holds 84,000 gallons, could accommodate the
whole neighborhood, but only one person swims in it. That's
stay-at-home mom Angel, who happens to be the Olympian next door.
</P>
<P>
   After winning six Olympic medals _ a gold and a bronze in
Barcelona; two golds and two bronzes in Atlanta _ having a baby and
taking nearly three years off, Martino, 32, is back in the swim for
next year's Sydney Games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess it's just in my blood,'' said Martino, who at age 29
in Atlanta became the oldest female to win a gold medal in
swimming. ``(Husband) Mike and I miss it; we check all the results.
This is it. At my age, I'm already pushing the envelope as far as
physiology.''
</P>
<P>
   Martino began her comeback _ although she never officially
retired _ about six months ago. She had no plans to swim when they
moved to Milledgeville two years ago so Mike could become an
assistant professor in health sciences at Georgia College and State
University. But after seeing the results from last year's spring
nationals, Martino said, ``It was worth giving it a try.''
</P>
<P>
   The lack of a 50-meter pool in Milledgeville was ``a major
obstacle,'' however. Martino had to commute four hours round-trip
to her hometown of Americus, two hours round-trip to Athens or swim
in a smaller local pool.
</P>
<P>
   To prepare properly for Australia, she needed the right place to
train, the closer to home the better to care for 2-year-old
Michael.
</P>
<P>
   New sponsors pitched in for a pool that Mike Martino estimates
would have cost $50,000-$60,000. Splash Super Pools donated the
structure, Sta-Rite the filters and pumps and Magnetizer the
chemicals.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're lucky we live in a small town, or we wouldn't be able to
have a big enough yard to do it,'' said Mike Martino, who maintains
the pool and coaches his wife.
</P>
<P>
   Fountains cool the pool in the summer, and heaters will be
installed this winter.
</P>
<P>
   Each morning, Angel opens the back door and crosses the yard
while dew is still on the grass. When she goes inside at 8:30 a.m.
after her two-hour workout, Michael has just awakened.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll come in wet, and he'll be like, `Swimming?' '' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The new pool was ready only a week before the U.S. National
Championships in Minneapolis. Representing Georgia Coastal, Martino
placed 12th in the 100-meter freestyle, but her time of 57.43
seconds qualified for next year's Olympic Trials.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just getting started,'' said Martino, whose immediate goal
is to transform five pounds of fat into five pounds of muscle.
``I'm in it for the long haul. I've been there before, and I know
what it takes. I'm willing to do that for the next year. I think I
have just as good a shot as anybody else.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, she's less ambitious this go-round.
</P>
<P>
   ``My goal is to make the relay,'' said Martino, who would have
to place in the top six in the 100 freestyle, ``and if I make the
individual (event), of course, I'd be more than thrilled.''
</P>
<P>
   However, if Martino isn't in the 100 freestyle, she finally
would be able to go to Opening Ceremonies, which were off-limits
when she had to swim the next day.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't enjoyed an Olympic experience, really, like it was
meant to be,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Martino, then Angel Myers, qualified for her first Olympics in
1988 by winning three events in the Trials, but she was removed
from the team after a positive drug test. Her family argued
unsuccessfully that the test showed metabolized birth-control
pills. Years later, Mike Martino still finds evidence supporting
the claim.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't matter now _ I'm so far removed from all that,''
Angel said. ``I think I've proven myself over the last two
Olympics. I've put in the time, gone faster and faster. I guess
that's all I needed to say.''
</P>
<P>
   In Atlanta, Martino made the the humanitarian gesture of the '96
Games when she presented her first bronze medal to friend Trisha
Henry, a volunteer who was battling cancer.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's doing great,'' said Martino, who visited Henry at the
University of Illinois a few months ago to present her with a
spirit award.
</P>
<P>
   Martino also found out months after the Olympics that she should
have had another bronze: an official told her that bronze-medalist
Sandra Volker of Germany had false-started in the 50 free but the
race was allowed to continue.
</P>
<P>
   ``But you know, I think I have enough medals,'' Martino said.
``I'm not swimming to get another medal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Really, I just want to see if it's possible. It's a challenge
to see if it's possible to come back after all that time off and
having a baby and at this age.''
</P>
<P>
   Martino admits to being a little more tired than she remembers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think a lot of that has to do with having to keep up with
Michael in between,'' she said. ``People who are seriously doing
this, all they do is train and rest.''
</P>
<P>
   However, Operation Olympics is as temporary as the backyard
pool. Some members of the local Milledgeville swim team will join
Martino next summer, getting used to a pool that could be theirs
eventually.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to take it down after next summer,'' Martino said,
``and probably just donate it to the team here.''
</P>
<P>
   Then the little pool will suffice.
</P>
<P>
   ``I used to jump in that pool for fun,'' Martino said. ``Now,
that's the last thing I want to do.''
</P>
<P>
   THE ANGEL MARTINO FILE
</P>
<P>
   Age: 32.
</P>
<P>
   Residence: Milledgeville.
</P>
<P>
   Hometown: Americus.
</P>
<P>
   Family: Husband, Mike; son, Michael, 2.
</P>
<P>
   Accomplishments: In the 1992 Barcelona Olympics won gold in 400
freestyle relay, bronze in 50 free; in the 1996 Atlanta Olympics,
won gold in 400 freestyle relay, gold in 400 medley relay, bronze
in 100 freestyle, bronze in 100 butterfly.
</P>
<P>
   Karen Rosen writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
