<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUN-WORLD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ATHLETES MAKE THE LEAP OVER NATIONAL BORDERS
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By CHRISTOPHER CLAREY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEVILLE, Spain _ Eunice Barber stood happily on the medal podium
last week with gold around her neck after winning the heptathlon
and sneaked self-conscious peeks at her image on the giant-screen
television as La Marseillaise, France's national anthem, played
over the loudspeakers. One day later, Niurka Montalvo stood on the
same podium with the same color medal after her victory in the long
jump and listened to the Spanish anthem.
</P>
<P>
   Both Barber and Montalvo had grown up imagining such a moment,
but neither had grown up imagining it would be accompanied by the
music they heard last week in Seville.
</P>
<P>
   Barber is from the tiny west African nation of Sierra Leone;
Montalvo from Cuba, and until this year, neither was competing for
France or Spain.
</P>
<P>
   Barber became a French citizen in February; Montalvo became a
Spanish citizen in May, and they are just the two most recent and
salient examples of the burgeoning hyphenation in track and field
and sport. Montalvo is a Cuban-born Spaniard. Fiona May, who
unhappily finished second to her in the long jump at this world
championship meet, is a British-born Italian.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson Kipketer, the reigning men's 800-meter champion, is a
Kenyan-born Dane. Ludmila Engquist, the hurdler who has shrugged
off chemotherapy to compete here, is a Russian-born Swede.
</P>
<P>
   And so it goes in an increasingly fluid, post-Cold War world
where borders are often not barriers to those with the potential to
answer the demand for higher, faster, stronger.
</P>
<P>
   There are dozens of Chinese competing in table tennis for other
nations; hundreds of athletes who grew up in the former Soviet
Union competing in myriad sports for other more economically
affluent and politically stable nations such as Australia, France,
Germany and the United States.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, all three of the medalists in the men's pole vault
were born and raised in one of the republics of the former Soviet
Union, and only the champion Maksim Tarasov still represents one of
them.
</P>
<P>
   Silver medalist Dmitri Markov, formerly of Belarus, is now an
Australian. Bronze medalist Aleksander Averbukh, formerly of
Russia, is now an Israeli, and it is telling that Tarasov does not
live in Moscow or St. Petersburg or any other Russian city. He
lives and trains in Budapest and does not rule out switching
nationalities himself if financial and moral support for sport in
Russia continues to deteriorate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things in sport are getting worse and worse in Russia: that's
my feeling,'' he said last week. ``They only care about politics,
the president and how bad the economy is, nothing else.''
</P>
<P>
   But if and when Tarasov decides to change national teams along
with his address, it will not be as straightforward for him as it
was for his peripatetic predecessors.
</P>
<P>
   After years of relative laxity, in which the International
Amateur Athletic Federation required athletes only to reside in a
country to be eligible to represent it, the organization voted last
Thursday that athletes must be full-fledged citizens of their new
nations to switch.
</P>
<P>
   Those who have competed previously in Olympics or world
championships for their former nation must wait three years from
their last participation before they can represent their new
country. If both countries agree, that waiting period can be cut to
one year.
</P>
<P>
   The vote brings the IAAF into line with International Olympic
Committee rules, which has long had stricter regulations about
national allegiances, but not quite in line with soccer's governing
body, FIFA, which does not allow a player to change nations at all
after he or she has represented one.
</P>
<P>
   Some migrants move for love, like May, who switched allegiances
after marrying Italian pole vaulter Gianni Iapichino; or Li
Donghua, a Chinese men's gymnast who married a Swiss tourist he met
near Tiananmen Square and won a gold medal in the pommel horse for
Switzerland in the 1996 Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   Some move for marketing, like former Canadian hurdler Mark
McCoy, the 110-meter Olympic champion in 1992 who later became an
Austrian because his agent, Robert Wagner, felt there were better
business opportunities there.
</P>
<P>
   Some even move because they want to compete: Kareem
Streete-Thompson, who competed in the long jump for the United
States at the 1992 Olympics, is now sprinting and jumping for the
Cayman Islands, the nation where he spent the first 18 years of his
life and where there is no Maurice Greene to worry about in the
national championships.
</P>
<P>
   But the majority of the migrants make the switch in search of a
better life and better training conditions, and most of them follow
the now-traditional flow from the third world to the developed
world.
</P>
<P>
   It might come as a surprise to know that Montalvo and May were
not the only long jumpers who merit a hyphen. Marion Jones, the
American superstar, has double nationality: her mother comes from
Belize. And though she once debated representing that small Central
American nation in her mid-teens, the odds are now much longer than
her jumps that she will be wearing anything other than ``USA'' on
her jersey in world championships and Olympics.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
