<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-28 16:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2854 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-SCHOOLS-CHANCELLOR     08-28 0900
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-SCHOOLS-CHANCELLOR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NYC OFFICIALS VOICE CONCERN AS SCHOOLS CHIEF MULLS NEW JOB 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.Y., Seattle)   (bl)  
 By ANEMONA HARTOCOLLIS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Chancellor Rudy Crew's ability to lead the New York
City school system could be damaged by the news _ revealed less
than two weeks before the start of a new school year _ that he is
considering taking a job at the University of Washington in
Seattle, school officials and union leaders said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   As Crew ponders his decision, some members of the city's Board
of Education raised doubts Saturday about whether his contract
would be renewed in June, if the chancellor stays until then.
</P>
<P>
   Among school officials Saturday, reaction to the chancellor's
disclosure ranged from sympathy to a sense of betrayal. But
regardless of their reaction, school officials said they wanted to
know for certain whether Crew was staying or leaving, and what kind
of timetable he had in mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``My concern is this: it's never good for a chancellor to leave
in the middle of a school year,'' said Randi Weingarten, president
of the United Federation of Teachers.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Jerry Cammarata, the Staten Island board member, and Ninfa
Segarra, who is Mayor Rudolph Giuliani's appointee to the board,
said that until the board completed an evaluation of Crew's
performance in the last year, they could not predict whether they
would support extending his contract beyond June.
</P>
<P>
   Cammarata, chairman of the committee preparing the evaluation,
said it would be ``one of the most extensive and scrutinizing
ever.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Crew disclosed in an interview Friday that he was having serious
discussions with the University of Washington about leading a newly
established institute there. Contradicting previous statements from
a top aide, Crew said he could not promise to remain until the end
of his term.
</P>
<P>
   Board of Education President William Thompson said the board
would ask to talk with Crew about his intentions, to help avoid
disrupting the new school year. ``When you hint or even mention
that you're looking at another possibility, yes, I think it's
damaging,'' Thompson said. ``It does create a situation where
people may try and wait you out.''
</P>
<P>
   Crew, through a spokeswoman, declined comment Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   But Friday, he said that although he hoped to stay until his
contract expires in June, or even until his five-year anniversary
in October 2000, when his pension will be vested, he was concerned
that the political climate in New York might prevent that.
</P>
<P>
   Last spring, Crew sparred repeatedly with Giuliani, until then a
close ally, over a series of policy decisions, from whether to
support an experimental school voucher program to how much money to
spend on school maintenance and repairs and where it should be
spent.
</P>
<P>
   Crew threatened to resign last March if Giuliani pressed a plan
to offer publicly financed vouchers for private school to children
in failing public schools.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani later backed down. But the mayor engineered a 4-3
majority on the Board of Education, including Ms. Segarra and
Cammarata, to defeat the chancellor's capital spending plan.
</P>
<P>
   In the most recent conflict, Giuliani sent a letter to Crew on
Aug. 3, chastising him for canceling their last six weekly meetings
on education. But both Crew and an aide to the mayor said that, at
their last two meetings, the relationship had been refreshingly
harmonious, as the two men agreed on programs like reducing the
number of children in special education programs and moving ahead
with efforts to end social promotion.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Friday, Crew sounded relaxed and optimistic, if torn, as he
discussed the job possibilities in Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   University of Washington president Richard McCormick confirmed
Friday that the university was recruiting Crew and said that the
university administration had not set any deadline for Crew to
decide what to do.
</P>
<P>
   Some officials close to the negotiations said Crew was exploring
the possibility of taking two jobs _ director of a new institute on
school leadership and replacement for the dean of the school of
education, who is retiring _ as a way of meeting his salary
requirements. He now makes $245,000 a year.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Cammarata said that Crew's admission that he was seriously
considering a job in the Northwest was ``truly a great shock,'' in
part because until now he had had the support of the board most of
the time. He said he was distressed that Crew had not had a
``frank'' discussion about his job hunt with the board.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Weingarten said the uncertainty about Crew's future could
undermine his authority in the midst of huge hurdles _ among them
recruiting competent principals and teachers, turning around
failing schools and carrying out a mandatory summer school program
for as many as a third of the city's 1.1 million schoolchildren.
</P>
<P>
   ``To have this layered on, I think, is a setback,'' she said.
She added, however, that over the summer, she had repeatedly urged
him to stay and would continue to do so.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Segarra said it was important for Crew to clarify his
intentions ``as soon as possible,'' so the board could make plans
for a transition, if necessary.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
