<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-28 16:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2855 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-FBN-JETS-VERSATILITY-     08-28 0707
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-JETS-VERSATILITY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON THE JETS, VERSATILITY IS REQUIRED TO SURVIVE
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By GERALD ESKENAZI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ At some point this weekend, dozens of
Jets players probably thought back to that very first day they
joined the team.
</P>
<P>
   The young and the old, and the high-priced draft picks and the
free agents heard this question from coach Bill Parcells at that
first team meeting: ``What can you do so that I can take you to the
game?''
</P>
<P>
   What it meant for those who weren't starters _ and even some who
were _ was: Are you versatile enough to play at another position,
giving me one more reason to keep you? For most players that means
the ability to play special teams.
</P>
<P>
   Even Ray Lucas, who is trying to make it as a quarterback, was
scheduled to play special teams when the Jets played the Giants
Saturday night in the hope that it would keep him around if his
throwing arm failed him.
</P>
<P>
   Each year at this time, the pressure grows on those who aren't
quite sure where they stand. It is the weekend of the next-to-last
game of the exhibition season, and the first cuts will follow soon
after Saturday night's game against the Giants. Of the 79 players
on the roster, at least 14 will be gone by Tuesday when rosters
must be trimmed to 65.
</P>
<P>
   But players who can do something else well _ snap a ball, cover
punts, even hold the ball for the place-kicker _ have an advantage
over a one-dimensional player.
</P>
<P>
   There are two other factors: age and money. Thus, all things
being equal, Parcells goes with the younger and less expensive
player. That is why he did not bring Keith Byars to camp
originally. The 35-year-old F-back suddenly became needed when
Johnny Mitchell quit and Blake Spence was injured.
</P>
<P>
   Parcells also wanted a younger player to step forward as the
club's fourth receiver. He has first-year players Chris Brazzell
and Brian Musso. But neither is ready and now 34-year-old Quinn
Early has that role, while 35-year-old Dwight Stone is in a
backup-receiver/special-teams role.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, 32-year-old Ian Beckles was brought in at right guard
when the rookies did not take command.
</P>
<P>
   Other players have shown they can play on special teams while
trying to learn how to perform at their regular position in the
National Football League. Such is the case for Kevin Williams, a
backup cornerback, Scott Frost, a backup safety, Robert Farmer, a
running back, and Spence.
</P>
<P>
   There also are players who understand their roles will be
nothing more than backup players, and they had better star on
special teams. Defensive backs Corwin Brown and Chris Hayes have
made a living doing just that for Parcells.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, of all the players who are expected to perform on the
special teams, only one _ outside of the kickers _ does nothing
else. He is John Hudson, the snapper.
</P>
<P>
   Parcells makes an exception of him because Hudson's skill at his
arcane role is so high, and his mistakes so few. In fact, in his
two years under Parcells, Hudson has never sent a long snap over a
punter's head or past a holder during a field-goal attempt.
</P>
<P>
   The 31-year-old Hudson isn't even listed in the depth chart any
more. They used to call him the backup center, but he does little
actual work with the line. Instead, while the offensive linemen
practice stopping marauding defensive linemen, he is off to the
side throwing the ball between his legs.
</P>
<P>
   Parcells has looked at other players to snap the ball:
linebacker Casey Dailey and defensive end David Viger. But Dailey
got hurt and Viger is in the Navy. Parcells even admits he has told
Hudson that the Jets are looking for someone who can play a
position as well as snap.
</P>
<P>
   Hudson is a mere 270-pounder, standing 6 foot 2. But Hudson
prevails. He is going into his fourth Jets' season. In a career
that began in 1991 with the Eagles, he has played in 115 games _
and never started.
</P>
<P>
   In theory, center Kevin Mawae is the snapper behind Hudson.
Mawae hates that job, though. He claims it takes his attention away
from his primary role, which he does very well.
</P>
<P>
   So the only nonregular who knows he has a job next week will be
Hudson, a player most fans never see standing up to his full
height.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
