<SLUG> BC-BOAT-BISHOP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: R.I.)  
 SAILOR PREFERS OLD YACHT OVER THE NEW FOR RACES 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By BARBARA LLOYD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JAMESTOWN, R.I. _ One might think that Jim Bishop had struck it
rich from the names of his boats: Golddigger, Gold Dust, Nugget,
Prospector, Fool's Gold and Motherlode. But you would not know it
by the kind of sailboat he races.
</P>
<P>
   While other big-boat owners are coming up with newer and faster
custom-made grand prix yachts each season, the 66-year-old Bishop
continues to compete with his 44-foot, nine-year-old Golddigger. It
cost about $400,000 fully rigged, roughly half of what it would
cost to build and campaign a grand prix boat.
</P>
<P>
   As chairman of Caithness Resources, an exploration and mining
company based in New York, Bishop could probably afford a newer
boat. He has homes in Saddle River, N.J., and West Palm Beach,
Fla., as well as in Jamestown. But he refuses to sink money into a
boat that will quickly become outdated.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Bishop spends some of his money keeping a 70-foot
antique houseboat, the Coastal Queen, to use as a mothership for
the J/44 sailboat race series, of which he was one of the founders.
As many as 16 J/44s compete in a Northeast circuit that has
organized 36 races this season, from Long Island Sound to
Narragansett Bay.
</P>
<P>
   The J/44, sailing's boat of the year after being introduced in
1989, is the only one-design class that has had its own start in
the Newport to Bermuda Race. This year, the group's North American
championship is scheduled for Sept. 10-12 at the Larchmont Yacht
Club in Larchmont, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   Golddigger, like other J/44s, is made to race across oceans as
well as around buoys. Its cruiser-racer pedigree gives it a longer
life than many of the new sailboats competing under grand prix or
club-level handicap rules. ``I won't race a boat I can't take to
Bermuda,'' Bishop said.
</P>
<P>
   Bishop has vivid memories of the time in 1984 when he sailed a
grand prix boat in the Newport to Bermuda Race. Rough seas started
to delaminate the boat's hull, which was built to be lightweight
and fast but not particularly safe. The composite construction did
not hold up as well as wood or solid fiberglass might have.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had to shove boat fenders between the boat's longitudinal
stringers and its outer skin to keep it from breaking apart,''
Bishop said recently of the 42-footer.
</P>
<P>
   Composite boats can be built to stand up to those conditions
with today's technology, but they would be unlikely to beat grand
prix competition. At 33,000 pounds, Golddigger is nearly 18,000
pounds heavier for its size than many of the stripped-out,
high-tech yachts built solely for inshore races. It has a teak
interior, two fresh-water showers, a generous galley and enough
bunks to sleep eight comfortably.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I go out and spend $1 million to buy a new boat,'' Bishop
said, ``my chances of winning might be one in 20. Then the next
year, the boat is obsolete. The economics just don't make sense.
The sailing industry is chasing the wrong god, and forcing people
who can't keep up out of the sport.''
</P>
<P>
   Those who do keep up, of course, spend the money at the grand
prix level. Eric Goetz, a boat builder from Bristol, R.I., has
constructed the New York Yacht Club's two new boats for the
1999-2000 America's Cup trials. He caters to boat owners who might
want a new yacht for a specific regatta or to keep up with changes
in sailing's handicap rules.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like the Indianapolis 500,'' Goetz said. ``You don't race
in a 1998 car in the 1999 race. Whether it's a displacement hull or
a new Indy engine, it's basically the same thing. You try to win in
the forum you want to be in.''
</P>
<P>
   For Bishop and his cronies, racing among themselves offers the
best competition. Owners cannot make changes to their boats unless
the others agree to make the same improvement. And the unity does
not stop there. The group spent about $150,000 for 15 sets of new
sails and hired a manager to oversee the inventory. That includes
rotating the sails. If eight sets are used on a particularly
blustery day, the manager makes sure that the remaining seven are
used on a similar kind of day next time. With the sails wearing at
the same rate, no boat stands to have an advantage over another.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
