u a BC-SENIOR-KAYAKER-ART-NY     08-28 0743
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SENIOR-KAYAKER-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AT 80, A KAYAKER SPENDS WEEKENDS GLIDING THROUGH THE REGION'S
WATERS
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers may make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(rk) 
 By WINNIE HU   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   JERSEY CITY, N.J. _ In one easy motion, Leonard LeShay swung the
17-foot kayak off his car and onto his shoulder. ``I got her up,''
he called out, waving aside any help. He balanced the kayak at a
perilous angle and headed for the water.
</P>
<P>
   At 80, LeShay had several decades on the other kayakers who were
readying themselves at Liberty State Park early Saturday morning to
paddle around Manhattan _ a 33-mile trip _ in 10 hours. But don't
tell him that. ``If anyone says, `Pop,' I kill them,'' he said.
``I'm in there as an equal. I help them. They don't help me.''
</P>
<P>
   Nearly every weekend for the past 12 years, through sweltering
summers and shivering winters, LeShay has hauled a kayak from his
home in Fresh Meadows, Queens, to rivers and bays around the
Northeast. His adventures have filled 15 photo albums _ each
holding 300 snapshots.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, he'll even bring a date along. He keeps a spare kayak
_ which, he said, makes for a great opening line with the women _
just for those occasions. He bought it for a girlfriend, but took
it back after they broke up.
</P>
<P>
   Now anyone hoping to land LeShay has to do a mean paddle.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's it, or I dump them right away,'' he said only half
jokingly. ``No kayaking? Then goodbye.''
</P>
<P>
   LeShay is an old hand in a thriving pastime around the New York
region. Last year, more than 6,000 people took out free kayaks at
the Downtown Boathouse in lower Manhattan compared with just over
100 in 1995, said Jim Wetteroth, the boathouse's president. At the
Peconic Paddler in Riverhead, Long Island, the owner, Jim Dreeben,
expects to sell about 900 kayaks this year, ranging from the $379
basic plastic model to the $4,000 Kevlar two-seater.
</P>
<P>
   Albert Ysaguirre, president of the 350-member Metropolitan
Association of Sea Kayakers, which organized Saturday's trip around
Manhattan, said LeShay has more than kept up in a club where the
average age is closer to 45. ``He never has a problem,'' said
Ysaguirre, who is 49. ``Most people have back problems and get
tired, but he can never get enough.''
</P>
<P>
   For LeShay, kayaking was a natural evolution in his life. He was
born in the Bronx to a family of ``water people.'' He said his
mother swam regularly in the Atlantic Ocean until she was 86. His
father was an avid fisherman.
</P>
<P>
   He bought his first boat _ a wood canoe for $15 _ when he was
18. He rigged a sheet to it and sailed off the shore of City Island
in the Bronx. His friends christened it the ``Plastic Wood''
because he patched it up so many times.
</P>
<P>
   But those days ended after he married a woman who could not swim
and did not care for boats. After she died in 1981, LeShay started
climbing into canoes again, but found them hard to manage alone.
When he spied a kayak at a boating show in 1988, he heard the
siren's call. He was 68 years old.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, LeShay has spent countless hours exploring crevices
along Long Island Sound, and the Delaware and Connecticut rivers.
His favorite spot is Flax Pond, a tidal area between Stony Brook
and Port Jefferson, Long Island, which has crystal-clear water and
deserted beaches.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the thing that makes him happiest _ his boat and his love
of the ocean,'' said David LeShay, his son.
</P>
<P>
   The elder LeShay, who lives alone, still works 40 hours a week
selling shoulder pads and trimming in the Garment District. He
boasts that he has not taken a sick day in 20 years. He is not on
medication. He does not even feel the occasional pang of arthritis.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday morning, LeShay packed four water bottles, an
underwater camera and a radio into his one-man
white-and-red-trimmed Nordkapp Jubilee _ an 80th birthday present
from another kayaker. He has circled Manhattan three times before.
Saturday the group was headed up the East River, across to the
Harlem River and back down the Hudson.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's something I love, so why not do it while I can?'' he
said. ``It's part of me. I'll kayak until I can't kayak anymore.
That may be until I'm 100. Maybe.''
</P>
<P>
   As he pushed off in his kayak, he raised his paddle high over
his head in joy. ``I'll be in touch,'' he called out before
paddling away on another adventure.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-28-99 1633EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
