<DOCNO> NYT19990828.0194 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-28 16:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2872 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-CANE-BAHAMAS-COX     08-28 0565
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CANE-BAHAMAS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Hurricane Dennis leaves Bahamas in his wake
 &HT;    w/ DENNIS-MAIN or CANE
 &HT;    BAHAMA REPAIRS STORM DAMAGE.
 &HT;    By Mike Williams
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   (UNDATED) _ As Hurricane Dennis churned toward the southeastern
U.S. coast Saturday, residents of the northern Bahamas were
repairing the damage caused by a near direct hit from Dennis'
eyewall in the early hours of Saturday morning.
</P>
<P>
   ``The winds were terrible, gusting to 115 miles an hour,'' said
Martin Havill(cq), general manager of the Bluff House Beach Hotel
on Green Turtle Cay, just off Great Abaco. ``It started about 10
p.m. last night (Friday) and about 5 a.m. this morning it reached
its apex. We have a lot of trees down and a couple of boats sunk,
but other than that we're okay. Thank God nobody was hurt,'' Havill
reported in a telephone interview.
</P>
<P>
   Weather officials said the center of Dennis passed within a few
miles of Great Abaco's eastern tip, pummeling the sparsely
populated island with sustained winds of 80 miles an hour and gusts
to 115 miles an hour. Huge seas thrashed the rocky Atlantic coast,
with waves to 20 feet pounding the outer reefs of several smaller
islands that lie just off Abaco's shores.
</P>
<P>
   ``The seas on the outer reef were unbelievable,'' Havill said.
``The waves were probably 20 feet plus.''
</P>
<P>
   Inside the reefs along resort beaches, however, early reports
listed the damage as minor, with smaller waves pushed in by the
storm causing some erosion.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had one large boat who stayed in the sound all night,''
Havill said. ``He had to run his engines just to stay in place over
his anchor. He reported winds in excess of 100 miles an hour.''
</P>
<P>
   Havill and other hotel workers reported little damage to
buildings other than some missing roof shingles. The worst damage
appeared to be to foliage, with trees toppled and downed limbs
littering the landscape.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are coconut trees down everywhere,'' said Avis Miller,
who works at Treasure Cay Beach Hotel about 20 miles northeast of
Marsh Harbour. ``But nobody was hurt and we had nothing
disastrous.''
</P>
<P>
   About 20 guests stayed in the hotel overnight, Miller said,
spending the night without electricity, listening to the winds
howl.
</P>
<P>
   ``The electricity is out and that's the worst of it, but
everybody is okay,'' she said. ``They're all taking coffee and
eating rice krispies. Everybody is quite safe and happy.''
</P>
<P>
   There were reports of damage to buildings in Marsh Harbour,
Great Abaco's largest town, with the walls of two buildings under
construction toppled by the gusting winds. There were no immediate
reports of injuries.
</P>
<P>
   Allan Bachewicz(cq), flew over to Great Abaco from his home in
Fort Lauderdale before the storm to secure his 50-foot sailboat,
which he keeps at the Treasure Cay Marina.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been through several hurricanes here and this was the
worst because the eyewall passed right over us,'' he said. ``My
wife was scared. Last night you had to hang onto stuff when you
were walking.''
</P>
<P>
   Others said that while the winds were powerful, the damage
remained surprisingly light.
</P>
<P>
   ``It could've been much worse,'' said Havill. ``We'll have
everything cleaned up in a day or two. Tell people who had plans to
visit that everything is fine.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
