<P>
   CAR-SERIES-WHITE _ The third installment in the NASCAR series.
The 1960s: Rex White: Rex White lives a quiet, humble life in
Forest Park, Ga. He has a house trailer a few blocks from his job
at a trucking company, where at age 70 he works seven days a week
from 5:45 a.m. until nearly 10 p.m. A former NASCAR champion now
drives a forklift that can't go faster than 15 mph. When White
filled out an application at Jones Transportation, he didn't list
his racing career under ``previous employment.'' Many of his 30
co-workers didn't learn of his accomplishments until last year,
when NASCAR named White one of the 50 greatest drivers of all-time.
He is not one to brag about his 1960 Winston Cup championship, the
Most Popular Driver award he got that year or some of his
impressive racing statistics, including 110 top-five finishes in
233 career starts. (Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 50. WITH PHOTOS.
MOVED.
