<HEADER>
A2877 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-KING-STAMP-COX     08-28 0470
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KING-STAMP-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Mayor parallels civil rights struggle to current lawsuit
controversy at MLK stamp ceremony
 &HT;    By Rhonda Cook
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ As the U.S. Postal Service unveiled a stamp featuring
Martin Luther King Jr. Saturday, Atlanta Mayor Bill Campbell used
the event to link the slain civil rights leader's crusade to the
city's mission to protect its affirmative action program.
</P>
<P>
   The Southeastern Legal Foundation sued the city in federal court
Thursday, claiming the program is unconstitutional.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let us not let anyone, any organization or any movement stop
our struggle for justice,'' said Campbell, the second of six
speakers at the unveiling of the stamp of King, one of 15 images
the public selected as representing significant people and events
of the 1960s.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will continue to fight like Dr. King. Affirmative action is
our Selma. It's our Edmund Pettus bridge,'' Campbell said of the
Alabama march from Montgomery to Selma, during which civil rights
demonstrators were trampled by police on horseback and beaten with
nightsticks.
</P>
<P>
   Campbell said his campaign to keep the program intact would
resemble the ``shoot-out at the O.K. Corral.'' He vowed to ``fight
to the death'' to defend Atlanta's 25-year-old program that
requires businesses with city contracts to share as much as 34
percent of the work with firms that are minority- or female-owned.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe as passionately in affirmative action. It's a
struggle for economic freedom,'' Campbell said.
</P>
<P>
   The imagery Campbell used in his brief comments contrasted
sharply with the scene in the hall at Atlanta's Martin Luther King
Jr. Historic Site. King's widow, Coretta Scott King, and a member
of the Postal Service board of governors released a royal blue
banner to uncover the first-class stamp as a recording echoed the
final words of King's ``I Have a Dream'' speech: ``Free at last.
Free at last. Thank God Almighty, I'm free at last.''
</P>
<P>
   Part of the Celebrate the Century series, the stamp shows the
Rev. King looking heavenward. Behind him is the crowd of 250,000
that heard his speech during the Aug. 28, 1963, March on
Washington, in what has long been regarded as a defining moment in
the movement to win political, social and economic rights for
African-Americans.
</P>
<P>
   ``That speech is as relevant today as it was 36 years ago,''
said former Atlanta Mayor Andy Young, who was an aide to King along
with Congressman John Lewis, who was also in the audience Saturday.
``There are still people isolated on islands of poverty in an ocean
of wealth.''
</P>
<P>
   The stamp will go on sale at post offices in September.
</P>
<P>
   Rhonda Cook writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
