<HEADER>
A2882 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-REAL-ELEVATOR-NYT &LR;      08-28 1184
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REAL-ELEVATOR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REAL ESTATE: CONTRACTING FOR UPKEEP OF ELEVATORS
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By JAY ROMANO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Negotiating a service contract for elevator maintenance, as many
co-op and condominium boards have discovered, can be nearly as
complicated as fixing the elevator itself.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem with elevator maintenance contracts is that there
is no standard contract in the industry,'' said Mary Ann Rothman,
executive director of the Council of New York Cooperatives and
Condominiums. ``That means that it's difficult to impossible to
find a contract that covers everything. The standing joke in the
industry is that what isn't covered by the contract is whatever it
is that just went wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Rothman explained that because of the strict laws governing
elevators in buildings, the complex nature of elevator equipment
itself and the need for the equipment to be maintained on a regular
basis, most co-ops and condominiums hired elevator service
companies to perform routine maintenance, make necessary repairs
and, in cases where the company is licensed, perform required
inspections.
</P>
<P>
   And in most cases, she said, the companies and boards enter into
fairly complicated monthly service contracts that presumably
enumerate in detail the services the company agrees to perform and
the monthly amount that the building agrees to pay for those
services.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, however, elevator experts and consultants say, what
often makes elevator maintenance contracts confusing and difficult
to negotiate is the fact that while what is covered is often
spelled out in excruciating technical detail, what is not covered
usually is not mentioned at all.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are so many moving parts to an elevator that most people
have no idea what they're looking for when they're looking at a
service contract,'' said George Johnson, president of Triboro
Technologies, an elevator consulting company based in Smithtown,
N.Y. ``Meanwhile, the elevator contractors are listing all the
things they're covering while leaving out all that aren't covered.
And some of those things are major components.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson said that under the terms of most service contracts,
covered items must be repaired or replaced by the contractor for no
additional charge to the building above the set monthly fee. At the
same time, however, parts and repairs that are not specifically
detailed in the contract remain the responsibility of the building
owner.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Johnson said, while an elevator service contract
might say it covers a detailed list of parts that make up the
motor, it will at times leave out the parts that are most likely to
require repair or replacement. ``The problem is, most people on
co-op boards don't know much at all about elevator motors and even
less about what part is most likely to break,'' he said. Paul
Capotorto, a technician for the Mercury Elevator Corp. in the
Bronx, agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most important thing to do when reading over a proposed
maintenance contract is to really read the thing,'' Capotorto said.
``You can't just glance at these contracts and know what you're
getting. One missing word could end up costing you thousands of
dollars.''
</P>
<P>
   For example, he said, while nearly all service contracts for
hydraulic elevators will include coverage for the pump used to move
the hydraulic fluid that moves the elevators, some will quietly
fail to include coverage for the motor that moves the pump.
</P>
<P>
   Another common problem with elevator service contracts is that
while most include ``24-hour coverage for emergencies,'' what
constitutes and emergency is not always clearly defined. For
example, Capotorto said, almost all contractors would consider it
an emergency if an elevator gets stuck with someone inside. At the
same time, having an empty elevator get stuck might be an
emergency, depending on the circumstances and the terms of the
contract.
</P>
<P>
   An empty elevator that goes up and fails to come down at 3 a.m.
would probably not constitute an emergency in a building with
several elevators. In a building with one elevator and lots of
people who have to get out to work in the morning, however, the
same situation might be considered serious enough to demand
immediate attention.
</P>
<P>
   If the service contract defines an emergency only as a stuck
elevator with a person inside, however, that early morning service
call could cost a co-op or condominium several hundred dollars.
``You want to know precisely what's considered an emergency,''
Capotorto said. ``Otherwise you're going to be getting billed every
time the thing shuts down and there's nobody in it.''
</P>
<P>
   Another thing boards should understand when negotiating elevator
service contracts is the concept of ``proration.''
</P>
<P>
   Joe Coyne, the president of Mercury Elevator, said that most
service companies, before taking on a new customer, would inspect
the equipment for condition.
</P>
<P>
   Once that has been done, Coyne said, the contractor will
typically include a provision in the contract that makes the
building owner responsible for part of the cost of repairing or
replacing certain components that have been specified by the
contractor.
</P>
<P>
   For example, he said, if the contractor determines that the
cables used to hoist and lower the elevator show signs of wear and
may need to be replaced in a few years, he will usually put a
clause in the contract requiring the owner to pay part of the cost
of replacing the cables when necessary. The respective parts of the
cost that the owner and the contractor are to be responsible for,
Coyne said, are then prorated over a period of years.
</P>
<P>
   So, for example, a 10-year proration clause _ which is fairly
common for an item like elevator cables _ would make the owner
responsible for 90 percent of the cost of replacement during the
first year of the contract, 80 percent responsible during the
second year, 70 percent responsible during the third year, and so
on.
</P>
<P>
   Coyne pointed out that while boards could generally negotiate
proration clauses _ and even demand that they be eliminated
entirely _ they should be wary of elevator service contractors who
do not raise the issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are companies out there that don't care what shape the
equipment is in,'' Coyne said. `They'll come in and take a job just
to get it. They figure that what happens after that is just a roll
of the dice.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, the elevator consultant, said that there was a way that
a board could ensure that it got the best possible contract from an
elevator service contractor: hire its own consultant to prepare it.
</P>
<P>
   For example, he said, to ensure that his clients have the
ability to get out of a contract if they are not satisfied with the
performance of the contractor, he inserts a clause in the contracts
he prepares giving them the right to cancel the contract simply by
giving 30 days' written notice to the contractor.
</P>
<P>
   But why would a contractor agree to such a clause?
</P>
<P>
   ``Because there's lots of competition out there,'' Johnson said.
``These guys are cutting each other's throats to get contracts.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-28-99 1730EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
