u a BC-HURRICANE-DENNIS-ART-     08-28 0846
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HURRICANE-DENNIS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HURRICANE GATHERS FORCE ON PATH TOWARD CAROLINAS
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Fla., Ga., N.C., S.C., Bahamas)  (ART ADV: Locator map is being sent to NYT graphics clients.
Non-subscribers may make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(rk) 
 By EMILY YELLIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHARLESTON, S.C. _ Hurricane Dennis strengthened and slowed
Saturday on its path toward the southeastern United States, and
while vacationers enjoyed a day at the beach, officials were
preparing for the worst.
</P>
<P>
   Jerry Jarrell, director of the National Hurricane Center in
Miami, predicted that the hurricane would intensify from a Category
1 storm into a Category 3 one, moving across the warm Gulf Stream
waters toward the Carolinas and making landfall late Monday or
early Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think it could hit anywhere in the Carolinas,'' Jarrell
said. ``The odds favor the North Carolina end.''
</P>
<P>
   Jarrell said he thought there was a 75 percent chance that the
storm would make landfall in the United States, and a 25 percent
chance that it would turn out to sea.
</P>
<P>
   Tropical storm warnings and hurricane watches were in effect
Saturday along the Florida coast, but the storm was expected to
parallel the Florida shore through Sunday, with the center
remaining about 100 miles out to sea.
</P>
<P>
   At 2 p.m., the storm was centered 200 miles east-southeast of
Cape Canaveral in Florida. It had sustained winds of 100 mph, up
from 80 mph the night before. Earlier Saturday, the storm battered
Abaco, an island in the Bahamas, The Associated Press reported.
Just back from a morning drive around Abaco's Marsh Harbour, the
Rev. Carlton Dorsette said that about 70 percent of the walls had
collapsed on a commercial building under construction and that a
number of boats had sunk in the harbor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we probably got a direct hit last night,'' Dorsette
said. ``There's real extensive damage, a lot of downed trees. It'll
take a lot of cleanup.''
</P>
<P>
   With the damage in the Bahamas in mind, state emergency
management agencies in Georgia, Florida, South Carolina and North
Carolina continued to prepare Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very much like planning for a party,'' said Tom Ditt,
spokesman for the North Carolina Emergency Management Division.
``We know we've got to do these things for the arrival of the
guest, and Dennis is not the best guest in the world. But certain
things have to be in place _ personnel, generators and equipment.''
</P>
<P>
   All along the southeastern coast Saturday, officials met to get
updates on the storm's progress and to prepare evacuation plans.
</P>
<P>
   In South Carolina, emergency management officials had a morning
conference call with representatives from all the communities along
the coast to discuss the forecast. They decided to delay any
evacuation orders because of the uncertainty about the storm's
course and because any threat could be days away.
</P>
<P>
   Here in Charleston, the preparations were influenced by memories
of Hurricane Hugo, a Category 4 hurricane that killed 504 people in
the Caribbean and the Carolinas in 1989. The South Carolina coast
has been evacuated three times since Hugo, for Hurricanes Fran and
Bertha in 1996 and for Hurricane Bonnie last year.
</P>
<P>
   Anthony Stith, chief of the Fire and Rescue Department on
Sullivans Island, a barrier island near Charleston that was hit
hard by Hugo, said workers there would spend the day handing out
re-entry stickers to island residents that will allow them back on
the island if it is evacuated.
</P>
<P>
   ``We learned from Hugo that we want residents to be able to get
back easily,'' while keeping out sightseers or looters, he said.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, Gov. Jim Hodges of South Carolina ordered 1,000
National Guard troops and 500 state troopers to prepare for duty
Saturday. In Georgia and North Carolina emergency planners were
also placed on alert.
</P>
<P>
   Even as the emergency preparations continued, surfers and
vacationers all along the coast enjoyed another day of good beach
weather and high surf.
</P>
<P>
   But many residents here were preparing to evacuate if necessary.
At the Lowe's Home Improvement Store in the Mount Pleasant area of
Charleston, Aaron Dumford, the store manager, said business had
more than tripled since midweek.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are buying generators, flashlights, plywood, batteries,
power tools, hammers and nails, tape and gas cans to hold the gas
for the generators,'' Dumford said. ``Today is busier than
yesterday, and tomorrow will probably even be busier still.''
</P>
<P>
   The store is ordering more supplies to keep up, said Dumford. It
normally keeps about 500 sheets of plywood on hand, but has ordered
an additional 3,500 sheets for residents who want to board up their
homes. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   And at marinas, boats were being taken ashore. At Folly Marina
in Folly Beach, near Charleston, the owner, Cindy O'Rourke, said,
``We have 50 boats here normally, and so far only 18 are left. All
the others have been taken onto shore.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm hoping it doesn't come here,'' she added. ``But if it
does, I'm getting out.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-28-99 1731EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990828.0199 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-28 17:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2885 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-SANFRANCISCO-VIEW-REA     08-28 1231
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SANFRANCISCO-VIEW-REAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REAL ESTATE: IN SAN FRANCISCO, DEVELOPERS BET ON HIGH-RISES 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By JOHN McCLOUD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Traditionally, a home with a view here has meant
living on one of the many hills for which the city is celebrated.
But a group of developers hopes to convince at least a few thousand
residents that living on the upper floors of a contemporary glass
and steel high-rise is as romantic and sophisticated as living in
an Edwardian building atop Russian Hill or in Pacific Heights.
</P>
<P>
   Judging by the response to Avalon Towers, a 16-story, 226-unit
apartment complex that is the first high-rise apartment project to
open in San Francisco in a decade, the developers' prospects look
strong. According to Shelby Campbell, a development manager for the
project's developers, AvalonBay Communities Inc. of Alexandria,
Va., 146 units have rented since the two-building complex opened in
July, with new leases being signed daily.
</P>
<P>
   Five other residential high-rise complexes are in construction,
with more in discussion. Developers of four of the other projects
are from New York, which has led some observers to refer to the
trend as Manhattanization. So far, the residential complexes have
attracted minimal criticism, a rarity in this often-contentious
city.
</P>
<P>
   The projects with New York origins are a condominium complex,
with two 17-story towers and one 16-story tower by Reliance
Development Group; a 40-story mixed hotel and condominium project
by Millennium Partners; a 51-story mixed condominium and apartment
tower by Swig-Burris Equities, and a 39-story apartment tower by
Related Cos. All but the Related project are under construction.
</P>
<P>
   According to Kent Swig, a Swig-Burris partner and a former San
Franciscan whose family owned the landmark Fairmont Hotel atop Nob
Hill from the 1930s until last year, his company's $125 million
project will be the tallest residential building west of the
Mississippi.
</P>
<P>
   The remaining two projects have no New York connection. Monahan
Pacific Construction Corp. of San Rafael, Calif., has a 13-story
condominium building in construction, and Carpenter &AMP; Co. of
Cambridge, Mass., will build another 40-story combined hotel and
condominium tower a block from the Millennium Group's.
</P>
<P>
   All the new projects are clustered in the northeast section of
an area known as ``south of Market,'' which lies south of Market
Street, the city's main downtown commercial corridor.
</P>
<P>
   The burgeoning district is home to most of the software,
multimedia and Internet companies that have quickly become a major
force in the city's economy. One part of the district has earned
the nickname Multimedia Gulch.
</P>
<P>
   The area is also home to numerous shops, restaurants, clubs,
museums, performance spaces and, most recently, a
360,000-square-foot entertainment complex with a 15-screen cinema.
</P>
<P>
   A new stadium for the San Francisco Giants baseball team is in
construction at the district's southern edge, as is a second campus
for the University of California at San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Until recently, the area held mostly warehouses, light
industrial facilities and lower-rent office buildings left from the
days when San Francisco was a major port. These older buildings
became popular with startup high-technology ventures, which
appreciated their ostensibly anticorporate esthetic. The influx of
these companies has spurred conversion of substantially more than 1
million square feet of vacant or underutilized properties to
offices with annual rents of $40 a square foot.
</P>
<P>
   Alan Mark, president of Mark Co. and sales director for the
Reliance Group project, Brannan Place, calls the intense
concentration a major selling point for residential development.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people are working 60 hours a week.'' he said. ``When
they get home, they want to walk to everything. This is the only
place in the city you can do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Mark is confident that Brannan Place will sell quickly, despite
prices of $500 a square foot for units averaging 1,150 square feet.
San Francisco's homebuying market is extremely tight and buyers
appear willing to pay what it costs to get in.
</P>
<P>
   The rental market is equally tight. According to most real
estate companies, the city's apartment vacancy rate has hovered
around 1 percent for 18 months and rents have risen dramatically.
Rents at Avalon Towers range from $2,400 to $5,400 for one- and
two-bedroom units of 800 to 1,650 square feet.
</P>
<P>
   The residents of the new projects will not represent a typical
cross section of San Francisco. At Avalon Towers, Ms. Campbell
says, 85 percent of the tenants earn more than $100,000 a year.
Nearly three-quarters are single or divorced and 60 percent are
under 40. Two-thirds are new to the city.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Levy, a real estate developer who moved here following a
divorce, says he chose his two-bedroom unit because of its location
in the heart of the city and for the amenities and views. Avalon
Towers has a largely unobstructed view of San Francisco Bay from
three sides and of the city's western hills from the fourth.
</P>
<P>
   Levy, who relocated to California from Stamford, Conn., a year
ago, says he likes the project's cosmopolitan image. ``I quickly
determined I didn't want old, didn't want ground floor, didn't want
walkup,'' he said, adding, ``It's simple, easy, free living.''
</P>
<P>
   Swig is counting on people like Levy for his project, which will
have 335 rental apartments and 174 condominiums. Though rents and
prices have not yet been set, he says the building, called the
Century and scheduled for completion in 2001, is aimed at the upper
end of the market.
</P>
<P>
   According to Dan Murphy, an AvalonBay vice president, most of
the projects represent a response to market demand rather than
explicit city policy, though the Millennium, Related and Carpenter
developments are in an official redevelopment zone and are partly
funded with tax-exempt bonds issued by the city's Redevelopment
Agency.
</P>
<P>
   City officials, however, have expressed support for all the
projects and are taking steps to encourage more of them. Susanna
Montana, a senior planner for the city, said that the Planning
Department wanted to raise height limits on Rincon Hill, a 12-block
area that includes Avalon Towers, to 350 feet from the current 250
to encourage development.
</P>
<P>
   ``We asked architects representing prospective buyers what they
want to build and we asked property owners, workers and current
residents what kind of area they would like to see,'' she said.
``By and large, the people who are there every day want a 24-hour
neighborhood. To get that, we need to get more people in there, and
that means going up.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether San Franciscans will take to high-rise living in numbers
sufficient to spur additional development remains to be seen, but
Murphy is confident that they will.
</P>
<P>
   ``San Francisco is a world-class city, and there's a lot of
people who would like to live here but haven't found the right type
of place,'' he said. ``I believe the market is pretty deep,''
</P>
<P>
   Swig agrees. ``I think the need is absolutely there,'' he said.
``With the right context and right design, high-rise living is a
wonderful way of life. It's not for everybody, but I think San
Francisco needs it to attract the kind of people who will keep the
economy moving forward in the 21st century.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
