<SLUG> BC-STRAWVOTE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Keyes, Hatch show up, win Alabama's straw poll
 &HT;    By Tom Baxter
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BIRMINGHAM _ It may not mean much so far as the campaign for the
GOP nomination goes, but Alabama Republicans showed Saturday that
it matters to show up when appealing for their support.
</P>
<P>
   Conservative radio commentator Alan Keyes, with 29 percent of
the vote, and Utah Sen. Orrin Hatch, with 27 percent, finished
first and second in the Alabama GOP's first-ever straw poll after
appearing to speak.
</P>
<P>
   Texas Gov. George W. Bush, who campaigned during the week in
South Carolina and Georgia but skipped this event, came in third
with 25 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``They (Keyes and Hatch) were both very, very good speakers, and
I think this was a way of saying thank you very much for coming,''
said former Birmingham Mayor George Seibels.
</P>
<P>
   Keyes' victory came after a stirring speech in which he
encouraged the delegates to vote their true feelings and not go
with Bush just because he's popular. ``If you keep voting for
people who are vague on the issues important to this country, you
will be defeated and you deserve to be defeated,'' he told party
members.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast to the frenzy around the Iowa straw poll two
weekends ago, this poll as a Republican event with more elephants
than candidates.
</P>
<P>
   While the kids lined up for $3 rides on four elephants outside,
the Alabama Republicans got to hear three of their presidential
candidates: Keyes, Hatch and educator and motivational speaker
Angel Rocker, who had her microphone yanked earlier this year when
she crashed the stage at the Georgia GOP convention in Augusta.
</P>
<P>
   Rocker didn't fare as well as Keyes and Hatch. She finished last
among the 10 candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Lt. Gov. Steve Windom, who co-chairs Bush's Alabama campaign,
saw some silver lining in Bush's finishing far ahead of the other
contenders who didn't show up.
</P>
<P>
   Conservative activist Gary Bauer came in fourth with 7 percent,
followed by Elizabeth Dole, Steve Forbes, Pat Buchanan, Dan Quayle,
John McCain and Rocker.
</P>
<P>
   This state doesn't hold its presidential primary until June 6,
when the nomination will almost certainly be decided. That made it
an easy decision for the major candidates in the race, including
Bush, to skip the state party's first straw poll.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some folks were disappointed he didn't come in for this but he
will be in Alabama before the campaign is over,'' said Lt. Gov.
Steve Windom, the co-chair of Bush's Alabama campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Keyes, a fiery speaker who has been critical of Bush in earlier
speeches, defended him regarding the recent spate of stories
questioning whether he ever used drugs.
</P>
<P>
   The media has been ``more willing to talk about something that
as far as I can tell, has no basis in a specific allegation . . .
than they care to examine the witnesses and facts and the evidence
against Bill Clinton,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Holding a ``skinny cat'' doll given him by a supporter, Hatch
warned against giving the nomination to Bush simply because he has
raised the most money.
</P>
<P>
   ``Remember President John Connally, President George Romney,
President Edwin Muskie and President Phil Gramm,'' Hatch said.
``They were all people deemed likely to win because they had
money.''
</P>
<P>
   Tom Baxter writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution, Atlanta,
Ga. The Associated Press contributed to this article.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
