<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-PENNSTATE-ARIZONA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NITTANY LIONS SHOW FLASH OF THEIR OWN 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By JOE DRAPE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   STATE COLLEGE, Pa. _ It was the earliest home opener in Penn
State history _ an August debut under the clear, sunny skies of
central Pennsylvania. And the third-largest crowd in Beaver Stadium
history needed barely six minutes to understand all this sweaty
talk about a national title returning to Happy Valley was more than
a hopeful forecast.
</P>
<P>
   The Nittany Lions rolled to a 41-6 victory over Arizona, a team
coming off a 12-1 season with 16 returning starters, a team that
was ranked in the top five in preseason polls, and was expected to
show these Eastern plodders some West Coast offensive pyrotechnics.
Instead, from the moment Penn State touched the ball, it was clear
that these weren't your father's _ or Papa Joe Paterno's _
predictable old Nittany Lions.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, some old standbys were employed _ a smothering defense,
running plays between the tackles and a blocked punt. But how about
wide receiver reverses, rotating quarterbacks and the return of the
effectively thrown, quick-strike forward pass?
</P>
<P>
   On the very first drive _ a comparatively eternal 80-yard, 2
minute 56-second march _ the Nittany Lions surprised the Wildcats,
as well as the 97,168 on hand, by running a reverse on
third-down-and-2. Chafie Fields danced it 20 yards to the Penn
State 40-yard line. Four plays later, quarterback Kevin Thompson
found him crossing the middle at the 22-yard line, delivered it and
the senior receiver shed Arizona linebacker Scooter Sprotte and
headed to the end zone for a 37-yard touchdown play.
</P>
<P>
   When the Wildcats got the ball for the first time, it looked as
if they were ready for a shootout. Quarterback Keith Smith needed
just three consecutive passes to drive Arizona 62 yards to the
Nittany Lions' 19.
</P>
<P>
   But after Penn State's all-America linebacker LaVar Arrington
dumped Trung Canidate for a 5-yard loss on third-and-2, Arizona
kicker Mark McDonald missed a 40-yard field goal.
</P>
<P>
   And from there the East-West shootout turned one-sided.
</P>
<P>
   On second-and-3 from the Penn State 30, Fields took an inside
reverse from quarterback Rashard Casey, turned it up the middle and
blurred 70 yards down the middle of the field. Two plays, 46
seconds, and the Nittany Lions were up 14-0.
</P>
<P>
   Last season, the Wildcats averaged 38 points a game. This year,
they brought back a 1,200-yard plus rusher, Canidate, who is a
Heisman Trophy hopeful and figured to be in the title hunt. But
none of that talent was on display Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Arrington and his fellow Butkus Award candidates, Mac Morrison
and Brandon Short, hounded the Wildcat quarterback duo of Smith and
Ortege Jenkins all day. The tandem combined for 182 yards passing,
and Canidate was held to 31 yards on 10 carries. The Wildcats
didn't score until Leo Mills' 1-yard plunge with 47 seconds
remaining.
</P>
<P>
   In the first half, Penn State outgained Arizona, 361 to 183
yards, with Canidate rushing for just 30 yards. A Wildcat defense
that gave up only 18 points a game in 1998 was down 31-0 at the
half. Poor tackling and turnovers helped the much-maligned Nittany
Lion offense dominate the highlight reels.
</P>
<P>
   Travis Forney kicked a 31-yard field goal that was set up by
Eric Sturdifen's block of a punt by Arizona's Chris Palic, and Penn
State was off and passing.
</P>
<P>
   Starting quarterback Kevin Thompson, who was booed at a Penn
State basketball game last winter after a 9-3 season, swung a pass
into the flat for tailback Larry Johnson, and Johnson motored
70-untouched yards for a touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson's second touchdown pass not only gave the Nittany Lions
a 24-0 second-quarter lead, but got him one-third of the way to his
touchdown total for 1998. Last year, Thompson threw just six
touchdowns against eight interceptions. He finished the day 5-for-8
for 135 yards.
</P>
<P>
   Casey, who pushed Thompson last year and again this summer, led
the Nittany Lions to 24 points. In the second quarter, he directed
a five-play, 61-yard drive that was capped by a 15-yard rumble on a
draw play by Aaron Harris.
</P>
<P>
   In the third, he led drives that set up a 47-yard field goal by
Forney to stretch the score to 34-0, as well as a 65-yard march
that was completed by Omar Easy's 1-yard run. Casey finished
6-for-10 for 107 yards.
</P>
</TEXT>
