u f BC-LUMBER-SHORTAGE-REAL-     08-28 0641
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LUMBER-SHORTAGE-REAL-590(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REAL ESTATE: LUMBER SHORTAGE RAISES COST OF BUILDING A HOUSE
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: Calif., Fla., Conn., Hawaii, Ore., R.I., Wash.)  (rk) 
 By ELEANOR CHARLES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   All set to sign that contract to build your new home? Don't be
surprised if your builder has inserted a clause saying that if the
price of lumber goes up during construction, so will the price of
your house.
</P>
<P>
   Shortages of lumber in the Northeast, caused in part by a
home-building boom that put demand far ahead of supply, resulted in
a 30 percent rise in prices from January to July of this year.
</P>
<P>
   For an average 2,000-square-foot home the increase in the cost
of lumber is about $4,000, according to Joanne Carroll, a director
of the Connecticut Home Builders' Association and president of JMC
Resources, a housing research firm. The increase for a trophy house
in a swank Connecticut suburb can spiral up by $10,000 or more.
</P>
<P>
   ``A 6,000-square-foot house can take six months to build and
make the buyer a victim of the market,'' said Norton C. Wheeler,
lumber buyer for United Builders' Supply in Waterford and Niantic,
Conn., and in Richmond and Westerly, R.I. ``But at the lower end,
even though a small house goes up faster, a sharp rise in lumber
costs can knock a first-time buyer out of the box.''
</P>
<P>
   In recent years shortages have been exacerbated by cutbacks in
Canadian lumber, the primary source for homes in the Northeastern
United States, that began in 1996 when a quota on importing
Canadian lumber was imposed to protect U.S. prices. Shipments fell
from 16.2 billion to 14.7 billion board feet annually, said Nsimba
Kinuani, chief economist for the Quebec Lumber Manufacturers'
Association.
</P>
<P>
   Other cutbacks resulted from a series of federal logging
restrictions that began in 1990, when 40 percent of American lumber
came from federal forests. Today the figure is down to 10.7
percent, said Butch Bernhardt, spokesman for the Western Wood
Products Association in Portland, Ore. ``Production in 1987 was
23.9 billion board feet,'' he said. ``Last year it was 16.8 billion
board feet.''
</P>
<P>
   Increasing volatility in the price of lumber has led developers
and builders to seek more stability in overall expenses by focusing
on eliminating waste and reducing labor costs. Labor has been a
problem anyway. What had been a large pool of skilled construction
workers has shrunk to a puddle. Builders believe that the men are
finding less stressful jobs in a robust economy that in Connecticut
has resulted in a 3 to 4 percent unemployment rate.
</P>
<P>
   An enormous time and labor saver is the truss _ for floors and
roofs. Manufactured of middle- and lower-grade woods under extreme
pressure and delivered ready to install, it uses leftover wood and
is stronger than conventional framing lumber. Trusses do not pop
nails and they can be fabricated to lengths of as much as 80 feet.
Floor trusses render floors virtually squeak proof and they have no
need for supporting cellar beams and columns.
</P>
<P>
   Another improvement in construction efficiency is panelization _
in which complete sections of framing that can extend to a width of
22 feet and a height of 12 feet are delivered ready to install,
with exterior sheathing attached if desired. They require one or
two unskilled laborers to set in place, rather than half a dozen
experienced carpenters to build them from scratch.
</P>
<P>
   While these elements are more expensive than traditional lumber,
the extra cost is compensated for by savings in labor, construction
time and even paperwork. A few bills for completed trusses and
panels cover what hundreds of invoices for dozens of types and
sizes of lumber, nails and other hardware cover in conventional
construction.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Carl Kuehner, president of Building &AMP; Land Technologies in
Wilton, builders of subdivisions and custom homes, has been using
trusses for a few years, but just started panelization. He
enumerated some of the advantages.
</P>
<P>
   ``Panels are numbered in sequence so you can't make a mistake,''
he said. ``You don't have deliveries of 2-by-4s that are wrong and
have to be returned, or wood that's cut wrong by a carpenter on
site. Every nail is in place so there are no worries about lazy
laborers skimping on nails. There is much less time for the
building to be exposed to the elements, and you don't have to pick
up leftover lumber.''
</P>
<P>
   A company in Shelton called BT Building Systems produces
trusses, panels and a complete line of components for houses. The
year-old firm describes itself as the only fully automated building
component manufacturer on the East Coast. Named for its owners,
Arnold Van H. Bernhard and Harold C. Thomas 3rd, it is also a home
builder.
</P>
<P>
   In executing what it calls its Fast Frame system, it can produce
the framing, roof and floor trusses for a home or apartment complex
to precise measurements in record time. The blueprints are entered
into a computer and the building is produced by the stroke of a
button that sets computerized saws and assembly machines in motion.
</P>
<P>
   ``The factory can do from four to six 3,000-square-foot homes in
a single eight-hour shift,'' said Duffy Sasser, plant manager.
``Where a crew of five carpenters might take 20 minutes to make and
stand a wall, we can run 20 walls in that time. Framing is the
biggest time consumer,'' he said. The words wall or panel in this
context mean a ``wall'' of preassembled framing for a house.
</P>
<P>
   For some developers and builders, taking the sting out of
skyrocketing lumber prices can be accomplished by playing the
commodities market.
</P>
<P>
   William A. Ferrigno, owner-president of Sunlight Construction in
Avon, Conn., builder of homes priced from $250,000 to over $1
million, invests in lumber futures. ``We bought a 5-month lumber
futures contract in February and made about $20,000 when prices
peaked in July, but we spent $16,000 on product for three houses,''
he said, resulting in a modest $4,000 profit minus a $100 brokerage
fee. Better than nothing, or a total loss in a down market, he
said. While there is risk involved, most big builders have their
sources within the industry for predicting major price swings.
</P>
<P>
   Kuehner is also ``hedging the market,'' he said, ``either by
buying lumber futures or getting the vendors to lock in the price
for a certain period _ maybe six months. We don't sell any houses
beyond that. In five months we reset the price based on the
market.'' He noted that small builders don't have those options.
</P>
<P>
   Wheeler believes that in the next few weeks distributors will
begin to ship lumber ordered at the lower price. And what that
means, he said, ``is that prices will trickle down to the builder
and home buyer in September.''
</P>
<P>
   A strong competitor for wood trusses, as well as an alternative
to conventional framing lumber, is steel. Popular in California,
Florida and Hawaii, it has not caught on in the Northeast.
</P>
<P>
   ``There have been a few custom homes in Connecticut and Long
Island, and it is being used in the Nehemiah projects _ subsidized
low cost housing in Brooklyn and the Bronx,'' said John Pugliese,
technical engineer at Super Stud Building Products in New York
City.
</P>
<P>
   Its advantages are its light weight and strength that is as
great or greater than lumber. Greater truss spans can be produced
simply by changing the gauge. ``Steel doesn't burn, so insurance
costs are lower, and steel prices are a lot more stable than
lumber,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But builders resist having to train crews in steel, teaching
them to use screws instead of nails, eliminate saw cutting, and
builders face higher plumbing and electrical costs because those
trades won't work on steel-framed jobs at regular prices.
</P>
<P>
   Steel's acceptance in other regions, said Lisa Stevens,
marketing director for the North American Steel Framing Alliance in
Washington, is based on practical considerations. It is impervious
to Hawaii's hordes of termites, resistant to earthquake damage in
California and it withstands Florida hurricanes.
</P>
<P>
   Hurricanes also have a more direct effect on the lumber market.
Lumberyards and construction companies in locations that are
susceptible to hurricanes stock up on half-inch plywood, which is
American made and now sells wholesale for about $2.88 for a
4-by-8-foot sheet. ``Hurricane season shoots up the price of
plywood,'' said Wheeler.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
