u s BC-BBO-MINOR-LEAGUE-GM-N     08-28 0741
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-MINOR-LEAGUE-GM-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOOKING FOR A BIG LEAP FROM BRIDGEPORT'S MINOR LEAGUE CLUB TO THE
MAJORS
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Conn.)  (rk) 
 By ANDREW R. TRIPALDI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Charlie Dowd knows what he wants in life and what it will take
to get there. But he also knows that achieving his lifelong dream
of becoming the general manager of a major league baseball team
will not be an easy task.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have an uncle or father who owns a major league
team,'' Dowd said. ``So I have to work my way up.''
</P>
<P>
   Dowd, 37, is the general manager of the Bridgeport (Conn.)
Bluefish, one of six teams in the independent Atlantic League.
Chiefly responsible for the daily business and baseball operations
of the team, Dowd hopes to enhance his organizational skills and
establish a reputation for himself as a capable executive.
</P>
<P>
   Over the past year and a half, Dowd's Bluefish have established
their own reputation as the model franchise in the Atlantic League.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, the first season of the Atlantic League, Bridgeport
finished with an overall record of 64-36 before losing to Atlantic
City, 3-2, in the League Championship Series. This season, the
Bluefish got off to a 68-32 start in a schedule that has been
expanded to 120 games.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody loves a winner,'' Dowd noted, and the Bluefish have
the attendance to prove it.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout Fairfield County, interest in Bridgeport has soared.
Upward of 3,000 people flock to Harbor Yard, home of the Bluefish,
for every game. Dowd attributed the team's commercial success to
its reputation for providing a family atmosphere at a reasonable
cost, with tickets selling for $4 to $10.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have made tremendous strides over the last year and a half
in attracting fans,'' Dowd said. ``We are not fully there yet,
because we get more people by word of mouth than by advertising,
but we still have been able to attract a lot of fans. Kids have a
good time here and businessmen can bring their clients.''
</P>
<P>
   Before being hired in Bridgeport by the team's founder and
president, Mikey Herbert, Dowd was the general manager of the New
Haven Ravens, the Double-A affiliate of the Colorado Rockies at the
time.
</P>
<P>
   Leaving a team that had a major league affiliation may seem
risky to some, but Dowd never wavered in his decision; he was
determined to elevate his status. But he knew that he was facing a
huge challenge.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one ever thought that there would be professional baseball
in Bridgeport,'' Dowd said.
</P>
<P>
   The first task Dowd faced after becoming Bridgeport's general
manager was finding a field manager that could effectively run the
team and help promote the product to the Fairfield County
community.
</P>
<P>
   Already having a few candidates in mind, Dowd was introduced by
the ownership group to Willie Upshaw, a former major league player
and coach who lives in Fairfield, Conn. After meeting for only a
few minutes, Dowd realized he had found his man.
</P>
<P>
   ``Willie Upshaw will be a big league manager someday,'' Dowd
said. ``He is a quiet, unassuming man, but has an amazing ability
to teach the game of baseball. He has been an invaluable employee
to us.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Dowd has the final say on personnel decisions, he
consults Upshaw before making any decision. ``It's been a real
pleasure working with Charlie,'' Upshaw said. ``He's so personable,
he makes it real easy to work together. For the past two years,
we've gotten along like brothers. He's so knowledgeable about the
game, you respect everything he says.''
</P>
<P>
   Dowd is trying to establish a player-friendly organization that
helps the players achieve their goal of making or returning to the
major leagues.
</P>
<P>
   Mariano Duncan, a former Yankee, spent time with the Bluefish
before signing with Edmonton, Florida's Triple-A affiliate. Kinnis
Pledger, a former first baseman, recently signed with Seattle's
Triple-A affiliate, Tacoma. This season, former major leaguer Alex
Cole is playing center field for Bridgeport.
</P>
<P>
   Dowd hopes that the former Bluefish players spread the word that
Bridgeport can help resurrect careers.
</P>
<P>
   A native of Staten Island, Dowd and his wife, Dawn, have three
children: Casey, Conor and Tristan. But Dowd's personal life would
not stop him from moving his family to another part of the country
if he was offered a job in the major leagues. ``None of us want to
be Bluefish all of our lives,'' Dowd said. ``I have always wanted a
championship ring.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
