<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CANE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Residents from Florida to North Carolina not 'off the hook' as
Dennis strengthens
 &HT;    By Mike Williams
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   COCOA BEACH, Fla. _ A strengthening Hurricane Dennis continued
its maddeningly slow and unpredictable trek toward the Southeast
Saturday as edgy coastal residents of Florida, Georgia and the
Carolinas scrambled to prepare for a landfall without having any
idea where it might occur.
</P>
<P>
   The storm added muscle Saturday while taking its own sweet time
moving through the northern Bahamas, where it knocked down trees
and sank a few boats but caused no apparent major injuries.
</P>
<P>
   The National Hurricane Center in Miami said Dennis' course was
uncertain, but it could affect the coast of the Carolinas late
Monday or Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully, before they have to do evacuations and that sort of
thing, we'll be able to clear up things,'' said Jerry Jarrell,
director of the hurricane center. ``Right now I can't let anybody
from Georgia to North Carolina off the hook.''
</P>
<P>
   At 5 p.m. Dennis was centered about 180 miles east of Cape
Canaveral, Fla., with sustained winds of 105 mph. It was moving
northwest at 6 mph, and was expected to gradually turn toward the
north today.
</P>
<P>
   The hurricane was expected to strengthen into a Category 3
storm, with winds of 111 mph to 130 mph. That would make Dennis
capable of major damage.
</P>
<P>
   Tropical storm warnings and a hurricane watch were in effect
Saturday for the Florida coast north to the Georgia state line, and
the hurricane center said the watches and warnings would be
extended northward as the storm moved. But Dennis appeared most
likely to brush past Florida and Georgia on its way to landfall
somewhere further north.
</P>
<P>
   A heavy surf advisory was posted for the coast of Georgia. Some
people called resorts to cancel their reservations while others
went to the beach to surf in the high waves.
</P>
<P>
   Predictions about the storm's path were complicated by its slow
movement, coupled with uncertainty over the impact of weak
upper-level weather systems that could even kick the hurricane out
to sea.
</P>
<P>
   Some hurricane center computer models suggested Dennis might
veer away from land.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's some glimmer of hope,'' Jarrell said Saturday
afternoon. ``Some of the models are beginning to show that it may
miss the coast.''
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Jarrell and other storm trackers worried that
Dennis might stall again as it did Friday, giving it the chance to
grow even stronger while making its track even less predictable.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fear of a stall is that it makes the storm surge much
larger because it sits there and pushes water up onto the coast for
a long period of time,'' Jarrell said.
</P>
<P>
   As it moved northward off the coast of South Florida, Dennis
became more organized with a more defined eye.
</P>
<P>
   The hurricane center said coastal Florida could have gale force
winds by this morning, and that by South Carolina could expect
tropical storm winds by Monday. If Dennis continues it's current
track, hurricane-force winds would belt the Carolinas by Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Cheryl Woods-Flowers, the mayor of Mount Pleasant, S.C., just
east of Charleston, said people should at least get ready for
protective measures such as covering windows.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm probably not going to start putting my husband on a ladder
until tomorrow,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   About 1,000 South Carolina National Guardsmen were on alert
upstate and some 600 law enforcement officers were on the coast in
case they are needed to direct traffic in the event of an
evacuation.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Jim Hodges met with emergency officials early Saturday to
be briefed on the storm. ``At this point we are still not talking
about any evacuation, we are simply taking the normal precautions
that should be taken,'' Hodges said.
</P>
<P>
   Winds along Central Florida beaches gusted to 40 mph Saturday
afternoon as Dennis' outer bands blew ever closer. Six-to-ten-foot
waves pounded the beaches, eroding sand dunes and keeping all but
adventurous surfers out of the water.
</P>
<P>
   In the Bahamas, many residents felt they dodged a bullet even
after taking a direct hit from Dennis, which toppled trees and
pounded beaches on the islands of Great Abaco and Grand Bahama, as
well as several smaller keys.
</P>
<P>
   ``The seas were very bad,'' said Martin Havill, manager of the
Bluff House Beach Hotel on Green Turtle Cay just off Great Abaco.
``But it really was not a problem. We had a couple of roofs with
some shingles off, a lot of trees down and our pool is full of
leaves. But we had everybody up for breakfast.''
</P>
<P>
   Early reports indicated some damage to buildings in Marsh
Harbour, Great Abaco's largest town, where two buildings under
construction had collapsed walls. But there were no early reports
of injuries.
</P>
<P>
   Dennis packed sustained winds of about 80 mph when it roared
over Great Abaco, with gusts as high as 115 mph and huge waves
pounding the outer reefs of several smaller islands that lie just
off Abaco's shores.
</P>
<P>
   ``The seas on the outer reef were unbelievable,'' Havill said.
``The waves were probably 20 feet plus.''
</P>
<P>
   Before the storm reached the Bahamas, Allan Bachewicz flew to
Great Abaco from his home in Fort Lauderdale to secure his 50-foot
sailboat, which he keeps at the Treasure Cay Marina.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been through several hurricanes here and this was the
worst because the eyewall passed right over us,'' he said. ``My
wife was scared. Last night you had to hang onto stuff when you
were walking.''
</P>
<P>
   Others said that while the winds were powerful, the damage
remained surprisingly light.
</P>
<P>
   ``It could've been much worse,'' Havill said. ``We'll have
everything cleaned up in a day or two.''
</P>
<P>
   Mike Williams writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga. Jack Warner and the Associated Press contributed to
this article.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
