<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-28 18:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2903 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-N.Y.-INTERNET-EXPLOSI     08-28 0829
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-N.Y.-INTERNET-EXPLOSIVES-400&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EX-OFFICER ARRESTED ON EXPLOSIVES CHARGES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ky.) (js) 
 By KIT R. ROANE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A former New York City police officer who tried to
trade explosives over the Internet was arrested on federal firearms
charges late Friday after the authorities found disassembled guns
and explosives in his Brooklyn home, federal officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The suspect, Maurice Brunet, 37, also known as Brunet Maurice,
spent 11 years on the police force before going on medical leave
last year. Police and federal officials said the leave stemmed from
an unspecified mental illness.
</P>
<P>
   Brunet had been on restricted duty in the police motor pool in
Woodside, Queens, since 1993 when he was ordered to give up his gun
after threatening a supervisor, the police said.
</P>
<P>
   Federal officials said Brunet drew their attention after he
tried to make a trade over the Internet with a Kentucky sheriff,
offering to swap two grenades for some blasting caps, small
firecrackerlike devices used to detonate explosives.
</P>
<P>
   ``When they started to talk and the law enforcement source
figured out what was happening, he led Brunet on and called us,''
said Joe Green, a spokesman for the federal Bureau of Alcohol,
Tobacco and Firearms. ``The explosives could have leveled his
building and done extensive damage to the surrounding ones.''
</P>
<P>
   Brunet could also be indicted on federal charges that he
possessed explosives and sought to deal both them and the firearms
_ two machine pistols and an AR-15 rifle, a civilian version of the
M-16 assault rifle _ without a license, Green said. Noting that the
firearms charges were drawn up to get an arrest and search warrant
for Brunet's basement apartment at 182 E. 32nd St., in the Flatbush
section of Brooklyn, Green said, ``We now know the material found
in a shoe box are C-4 explosives and the grenades are live.''
</P>
<P>
   According to the Police Department, Brunet spent four years in a
Marine Corps artillery unit before joining the police force in
1987.
</P>
<P>
   Brunet's lawyer, Michael Hardy, who is also representing him in
a civil suit against the Police Department, said Saturday that his
client was forced to retire from the department after police
officials claimed he was a paranoid schizophrenic.
</P>
<P>
   After a hearing on the firearms charges was postponed Saturday,
Hardy said he could not comment on Brunet's arrest other than to
say that his client, who is black, ``wasn't building a black
militia or anything out there in Brooklyn.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Although it remains unclear what Brunet intended to do with the
blasting caps, federal officials said he seemed excited to make the
trade when he struck up a conversation last month with a sheriff in
Ashland, Ken., in a chat room for gun buffs.
</P>
<P>
   The sheriff immediately contacted the firearms bureau, the
authorities said. Brunet continued to communicate with the sheriff
in Internet chat rooms and through e-mail, with the sheriff feeding
the information to federal agents.
</P>
<P>
   In one of their last Internet correspondences, Brunet gave the
sheriff his telephone number _ giving federal agents a way to find
out his address _ and tried to set up a meeting to do the trade.
</P>
<P>
   ``During the e-mails he told the sheriff that he was a retired
police officer and that he wanted to trade two hand grenades for 20
blasting caps and 250 feet of military fuse,'' said Capt. John
Murphy, the commanding officer of the New York City Police
Department's Organized Crime Investigative Division. He said that
Brunet complained of being short of money but said that he would
come up with enough to also purchase parts to make his guns fully
automatic.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then in the telephone conversation, he actually claimed to
have a small amount of C-4 plastic explosives and various amounts
of automatic weapons,'' said Murphy. ``Due to public safety
concerns, we decided to go ahead and move in.''
</P>
<P>
   Local and federal officers raided Brunet's apartment at 10:30
p.m. Friday, the police said. Two agents who had been conducting
surveillance grabbed him as he walked out to run an errand and then
dozens of other officers rushed inside.
</P>
<P>
   Murphy said Brunet denied having any weapons. But the apartment
was strewn with magazines about guns, hunting and the lifestyle of
soldiers of fortune. No guns were seen until an agent noticed what
looked like a hidden compartment above a radiator.
</P>
<P>
   According to the police, the compartment was full of gun parts
and grenades, only one of which was active. They said another agent
searching a closet found a shoe box containing bricks of a white,
claylike substance that later turned out to be C-4, a powerful
military explosive.
</P>
<P>
   ``It appears all of the weapons were send through UPS,'' Murphy
said. ``We are now going though his computer, his bank statements
and correspondences we found from different firearms dealers.''
</P>
</TEXT>
