<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-GIANTS-NUMBERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR THE GIANTS' RECEIVERS, PICKING A NUMBER IS AN ART
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By BILL PENNINGTON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was an unexpected and startling announcement when the Giants
cut venerable wide receiver Chris Calloway in February. A savvy
leader of the receiving corps, Calloway was esteemed and admired by
his peers, regarded as a helmsman for the team's younger receivers.
</P>
<P>
   Calloway's departure was like a thunderbolt for the five
remaining Giants receivers.
</P>
<P>
   Brian Alford, a second-year receiver, immediately called the
team. He wanted Calloway's No. 80 for the 1999 season.
</P>
<P>
   It's not that Calloway's veteran presence will not be missed
this season, but a favorite jersey number is important.
</P>
<P>
   ``Your favorite number is like a good pair of house slippers,''
said Alford, who wore 80 at Purdue, in high school and on his first
pee-wee football team. ``I called the day Chris was let go because
I knew 80 was open. I didn't know the procedures for asking for a
number, so I asked.''
</P>
<P>
   David Patten wanted the number, too. ``But I thought I'd wait at
least a couple days before I called,'' he said. ``I kind of wanted
to let people get over Chris' exit.''
</P>
<P>
   Bad move.
</P>
<P>
   First come, first served. Alford, who wore No. 84 last season,
is wearing No. 80 this season.
</P>
<P>
   That did not stop Patten. He changed his number anyway, from 83
to 85. And there was a domino effect as Joe Jurevicius changed his
number from 86 to 84.
</P>
<P>
   The trend is one started by Amani Toomer a year ago. He went
from No. 89 to No. 81 and had a breakthrough 1998 season. Toomer is
now a starter with a new $11.2 million contract extension.
</P>
<P>
   Giants fans tuning in to watch their team for the first time
this season are going to need a scorecard to know who is who. It
can get confusing. A uniform number is more than two digits on a
synthetic jersey. It is a player's identity. Just ask Patten.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had family members and friends calling me after the two
preseason games asking me if I'm still on the team,'' said Patten,
who has four catches and a touchdown reception during the
preseason. ``They called and said, `I saw an 83 on TV, but that's
not you.'''
</P>
<P>
   Pete Mitchell, the Giants' new tight end is wearing No. 83, his
old number with the Jacksonville Jaguars. Mitchell is 6 foot 2, 245
pounds. Patten is 5-9, 190 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, `I hope that 83 doesn't look like me,''' Patten said.
</P>
<P>
   Family members had a role in Jurevicius' decision to switch
numbers.
</P>
<P>
   ``My family told me I looked too fat in 86,'' he said. ``They
said I looked like a big old tight end. So I went back to my glory
days. I wore 84 in high school.''
</P>
<P>
   The player who started this trend, Toomer, said he changed from
No. 89 to 81 last year because 81 was the reverse of his number at
Michigan.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's makes you feel better, but let's be serious. It's still
you in there whatever the number,'' Toomer said. ``The thing is
they just hand you a number when you're a rookie. Guys feel like
changing.''
</P>
<P>
   But it takes a certain status.
</P>
<P>
   Patten did not think to complain about his No. 83 in his first
two years with the Giants. An undrafted free agent coming out of
the Arena League, Patten accepted whatever they gave him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was so happy to be getting any number,'' Patten said.
</P>
<P>
   But he wore No. 5 at Western Carolina and when Alford beat him
to No. 80, Patten thought 85 would be at least a piece of his
college number. He sees the number change as a new beginning.
</P>
<P>
   ``The story on me used to be that I was trying to stay on the
team,'' Patten said. ``That was 83. Now when people see 85,
hopefully they'll see a new person, a receiver who's taking it up a
level. I'm not just trying to stay with the team, I'm here to make
big plays.''
</P>
<P>
   In any case, as comfy slippers or good-luck charms, jersey
numbers define the player in football, where helmets and face masks
make it harder to identify a player's face. But the changing
numbers had autograph-seeking fans at the Giants' training camp
this summer befuddled.
</P>
<P>
   Fans often come to camp with trading cards for players to sign.
The pictures are all from the past season, so this year, the fans
came with pictures of Patten in No. 83, Jurevicius in No. 86, and
so on.
</P>
<P>
   That meant that the rookie tight end Dan Campbell, the Giants'
new No. 86, was asked to sign Jurevicius' trading card. Campbell
would then have to send the fans over to Jurevicius, who fans
mistook for Alford, since he was wearing No. 84, Alford's old
number.
</P>
<P>
   ``It can take some explaining,'' Patten said.
</P>
<P>
   So far, quarterback Kent Graham has not thrown to the wrong
receiver, bewildered by all the number changes in his receiving
corps.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, no way,'' Graham said, smiling. ``I study those things at
night: you know, go over the names, go over the numbers like flash
cards. You know, `Jurevicius, 84. Patten, 85. Alford 80.' I've got
that down cold.''
</P>
</TEXT>
