<SLUG> BC-NY-MEATDISTRICT-REAL-730(3TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REAL ESTATE: IN MANHATTAN'S WEST VILLAGE, A DEVELOPERS' GOLD RUSH 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By DAVID W. DUNLAP   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A grove of feathery Chinese scholar trees took root
this year in what was once a realm of meathooks and stiletto heels
at Washington and Jane streets in the far West Village. A nearby
sign, ``Please keep out of fountain,'' does not wholly discourage
young waders.
</P>
<P>
   Fifteen years ago, another sign hung at this intersection:
``Hookers and johns beware. We take your numbers.'' Overhead,
casting a perpetual shadow, was the abandoned freight railroad
viaduct known as the High Line.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, Rockrose Development Corp. has dismantled the High
Line and built 265 apartments _ and the public plaza at 99 Jane St.
where the scholar trees stand _ along the viaduct route. ``The day
it was removed, it was like lifting a weight off the West
Village,'' said K. Thomas Elghanayan, the president of Rockrose.
</P>
<P>
   That the lid is off, there is no doubt. Besides 99 Jane St., at
least eight other apartment buildings and two hotels are newly
completed, under construction or being planned from Hudson Street
to the Hudson River.
</P>
<P>
   The question is whether this physical transformation will
fundamentally alter the character of the West Village, a
rough-edged amalgam of 19th-century industry and 20th-century
artistry, of iconoclasm and neighborliness, of creative freedom and
sexual license. New Yorkers who fled there to escape crush and buzz
are distressed to see taxis full of fashionistas rumbling over the
Belgian block paving, with construction cranes on the horizon. What
Jane Jacobs called an ``intricate sidewalk ballet'' is turning into
a duel for the future of the Village waterfront.
</P>
<P>
   ``This whole area, in theory, can look like New Jersey east,''
said Arthur W. Strickler, the district manager of Community Board 2
and a West Villager for two decades, referring to the
concrete-and-glass palisades on the opposite shore. ``My prediction
is that there's not going to be an empty lot anywhere on West
Street.''
</P>
<P>
   Not if the experience of Tamarkin Co. is any barometer. Buyers
have already claimed seven of the nine floor-through lofts in its
11-story condominium, which is still under construction at 495 West
St., near 12th Street. Among the quick sellers: two duplex
penthouses with 16-foot-high steel casement windows overlooking the
waterfront, priced at $4.2 million. For raw space.
</P>
<P>
   Now that it is possible to find boutiques in the meat market, a
boutique hotel seems the natural next step. Madison Equities and
Broadway Management are planning just that at Hudson and 13th
streets: the 16-story, 195-room, $52 million Greenwich Village
Hotel, which is to open in 2001. Designed by Frank Williams &AMP;
Associates, its two-story open arcades recall the voids in nearby
factories through which the High Line tracks once ran.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Meier, the architect who converted the Bell Telephone
Laboratories at West and Bethune streets into the Westbeth artists
housing complex, is returning to the West Village after 30 years.
He is designing a project for the restaurateurs Jean-Georges
Vongerichten, Phil Suarez and Bob Giraldi and the hoteliers Richard
Born and Ira Drukier. They plan a condominium of up to 15 stories
on the north corner of West and Perry streets and a two-story
restaurant on the south corner, connected to a six-story garage
that will be turned into a 75-room hotel and gain a six-story
addition with condos. The project could cost as much as $60 million
and take two years.
</P>
<P>
   One block east, the two-story garage at 132 Perry St. that has
housed the Cooper Classics automobile dealership since 1978 is to
make way for an 11-story condominium developed by Axel Stawski,
Anthony Paul Leichter and Estera Lisker and designed by Lee Harris
Pomeroy Architects.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, a scarlet 1959 Cadillac convertible and a black 1960
Corvette were all that remained on the floor at Cooper. Elliot
Cuker, the founder, confessed that it was a poignant moment,
although Cooper will reopen across the street as a combination
showroom and art gallery.
</P>
<P>
   Cuker is indirectly fueling the transformation of the
neighborhood with the sale of his building, but he believes the
essence of the West Village _ what he called ``a ghetto of the
spirit'' _ will survive.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not going to change because the people aren't going to
change,'' he said. ``There's something about the West Village that
draws a certain kind of person.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Four of the seven purchasers at 495 West St. already live in the
West Village, said the broker, Jan Hashey, a senior vice president
of Douglas Elliman. Buyers are in the fine arts, publishing and
entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   Imagination helps. ``I'm creating blank, raw shells for people
to create their own vision,'' said Cary Tamarkin, the architect and
developer of the $13.5 million project, who took the same approach
in the renovation two years ago of 140 Perry St.
</P>
<P>
   That is also the plan for the 132 Perry St. project. Nine
full-floor units of 3,000 square feet will come largely unfinished,
to give buyers the greatest flexibility in layout. It will include
20,000 square feet of commercial space, ideally for ``arts-related
enterprises,'' Stawski said. Demolition is to begin next month,
with completion late next year. About the design of the brick
building, he said, ``I've always believed you fit into the
neighborhood and this will fit in.''
</P>
<P>
   Significantly, however, it is not required to fit into the
neighborhood, since the south side of Perry Street between
Washington and Greenwich Streets _ unlike the north side _ lies
outside the 30-year-old Greenwich Village Historic District.
Therefore, the design is not subject to review by the Landmarks
Preservation Commission.
</P>
<P>
   The western boundary of the district, excluding everything
between Washington Street and the river, has long been a sore point
for preservationists and many Villagers. ``It's outrageous that the
Landmarks Commission, then and now, has refused to bring the
landmark district all the way over to the waterfront,'' Strickler
said.
</P>
<P>
   Most development is occurring outside the district.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll regret it in years to come when we see a waterfront that
becomes almost like a checkerboard of foreign pieces,'' warned Ben
Green, executive director of the Federation to Preserve the
Greenwich Village Waterfront and Great Port.
</P>
<P>
   Jennifer J. Raab, the chairwoman of the commission, said the
boundaries had been drawn thoughtfully and that the ensemble of
riverfront blocks was not sufficiently coherent for historic
designation.
</P>
<P>
   ``A wholesale extension, with all of the vacant land and
noncontributing buildings, is not something we would be interested
in pursuing,'' she said. ``But we'd be very interested in looking
at pockets of historic properties that should be protected.''
</P>
<P>
   To that end, the Greenwich Village Society for Historic
Preservation, which conducted a building-by-building survey 10
years ago, will compile a list of exceptionally significant
buildings and blocks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our ideal is to protect as much as possible,'' said Kimberly
Stahlman Kearns, executive director of the society. ``But we're
trying to look at smaller pockets in response to the fact that we
haven't been getting anywhere. Time is of the essence here.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the obvious candidates are the tiny Charles Lane alleyway
and Weehawken Street, a one-block stretch of the 19th century with
a red-brick stable built in 1836 and a clapboard oyster house from
1849.
</P>
<P>
   The society will also be looking at the meat market, Ms. Kearns
said. The meat industry has shrunk drastically in recent years,
leaving behind its distinctive cold storage houses with their long,
deep canopies over sidewalk loading platforms.
</P>
<P>
   Fresh carcasses are no longer shipped to the market for cutting
and packing, so there is no need for much of that space, said Noel
L. Berk, an associate director of Cushman &AMP; Wakefield. She recently
sold a row of warehouses on 10th Avenue, between 13th and 14th
streets, to William Gottlieb, perhaps the largest landowner in the
West Village.
</P>
<P>
   Several big wholesalers are holding the fort. ``It's shrinking,
but there's still a lot of meat handled out of this market,'' said
Hank Guerra, vice president of Maggio Beef Corp., which has
operated at Washington and Gansevoort streets for 28 years.
</P>
<P>
   Maggio has 75 employees and offers a full line of meats and
poultry to supermarket chains, mom-and-pop stores, caterers,
restaurants and even individual shoppers with carts. Guerra said
the market is in a perfect spot from which to reach customers
around the metropolitan area.
</P>
<P>
   Allowing that galleries will pay higher rents, Guerra added, ``I
don't think an art exhibit is going to employ as many people as we
do or feed as many people.''
</P>
<P>
   Easily the highest-profile newcomer to the meat market will be
the Greenwich Village Hotel. One of the developers, Robert
Gladstone of Madison Equities, and the architect, Frank Williams,
are already collaborating on the Planet Hollywood Hotel under
construction in Times Square.
</P>
<P>
   The Hudson Street hotel will have duplex suites with terraces
behind the open arcades, which resemble the buttresses atop Raymond
Hood's Tribune Tower in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   Gladstone believes the offbeat location will be a draw itself.
``New York has been synthesized into a city more like London, Paris
and San Francisco, where people are going to stay in
neighborhoods,'' he said. ``To me, what's called the meat market is
a neighborhood that's becoming more neighborly every day.''
</P>
<P>
   The fashion photographer Albert Watson and his wife and agent,
Elizabeth, moved to the neighborhood in 1985, when the ``hookers
and johns'' warning was on display.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't see them here anymore,'' Mrs. Watson said. ``Now I'm
seeing a lot of children, which is lovely. I see families with
young children and dogs going down to the river for skateboarding
and Rollerblading and all the stuff that goes on down there.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
