<DOCNO> NYT19990828.0216 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-28 18:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2922 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-NY-MEATDISTRICT-REAL-     08-28 1202
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-MEATDISTRICT-REAL-3RDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 NEW YORK: down there.''  
<TEXT>
<P>
   A seven-lane boulevard, Route 9A, with planted medians and a
paved pathway for bicyclists, joggers, skaters and pedestrians, has
replaced the open scar left by the demolition of the West Side
Highway in 1982.
</P>
<P>
   Another verdant patch is the public plaza known as Washington
Commons at 99 Jane St. It resulted from negotiations between
community leaders and Rockrose, which needed a variance to build a
parking garage on the site. ``My big joy is to see it used as I
envisioned it,'' said the designer of the plaza, Marie
Drews-D'Angelo. ``Children make a beeline to sit by the fountain
and play with the water.'' Or in it.
</P>
<P>
   Ten years ago, there were almost no youngsters across the street
in the West Coast Apartments, said Sofia Estevez, director of
operations at Rockrose. Today, she said, half the families there
have children.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm astonished just standing in the lobby and seeing all the
strollers, nannies and dogs,'' Ms. Estevez said. A children's play
area has been added on the rooftop.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, families in the West Village come in all varieties.
Richard Cantor of Cantor-Pecorella, who was the sales agent at 99
Jane St., said one gay and one lesbian couple had bought large
apartments because they planned to adopt children.
</P>
<P>
   Long a haven for gay men and lesbians, the West Village assumed
an even greater role with the arrival of the Lesbian and Gay
Community Services Center, which is operating at 1 Little West 12th
St. while its permanent home at 208 W. 13th St. is undergoing
extensive renovation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Five thousand people a week are coming through the doors,''
said Richard D. Burns, the executive director.
</P>
<P>
   The center's temporary home is in a corner property owned by
Gottlieb, around which Madison Equities will build its hotel.
Gottlieb, who declined to be interviewed for this article, has a
reputation as an owner more interested in acquiring property than
in selling or developing it. He has some 50 parcels in the West
Village.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can sell to him, but you can't buy from him,'' said
Elghanayan of Rockrose, which sold Gottlieb an entire blockfront
along Gansevoort Street, between Greenwich and Washington streets.
``I'm glad he's there. He keeps it gritty.''
</P>
<P>
   Grittiness is a prized quality in the West Village and a number
of the new projects consciously employ the idiom of 19th- and early
20th-century factories, warehouses and commercial buildings.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Himmelstein has designed a six-story home at 399 West St.,
near 10th Street, for a family that wishes not to be named,
although Himmelstein said they had spent a long time in Hong Kong
and were accustomed to life on a busy waterway. He said his design
is meant to be a ``muscular maritime facade, an old building left
from a thriving commercial port.''
</P>
<P>
   The 495 West St. project bears a strong enough kinship to the
Starrett-Lehigh Building of 1931 that one has to look twice to
realize that it is a brand new condo.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a rough and tough quality to the edge of the city,''
Tamarkin said. ``The piers. The smokestacks of the old sanitation
facility. There's something beautiful and monumental about that. I
wanted to capture something of that.''
</P>
<P>
   Rockrose, too, sought to emulate the past at 99 Jane St.,
designed by Fox &AMP; Fowle. ``We wanted it to look like a loft
building that had been converted into an apartment house,''
Elghanayan said. ``In this neighborhood, people prefer that
product.''
</P>
<P>
   And if anyone knows the neighborhood, it is Rockrose, having
built or renovated 1,333 housing units there since 1979.
</P>
<P>
   Rockrose is a triumvirate of brothers: Thomas, 54, who was
trained as a businessman at Harvard; H. Henry, 59, who was trained
as a lawyer at New York University; and Frederick, 51, who was
trained as an engineer at Cornell University.
</P>
<P>
   In 1969, Henry and Thomas formed an investment fund for wealthy
Iranians that put some money in Manhattan real estate. Needing a
name for the fledgling company, the Elghanayans borrowed the
``Rockrose'' from Rockrose Place in Forest Hills Gardens, Queens,
where their father lived.
</P>
<P>
   After an unhappy experience with a small-time renovator on the
Upper West Side, the Elghanayans decided to get into the renovation
and redevelopment business themselves. Frederick joined Rockrose,
as did a fourth brother, Jeffrey, an architect. (He has since moved
to California.)
</P>
<P>
   Their first projects were scattered through Manhattan and
Brooklyn, but in the late '70s, they began focusing on the West
Village. ``This was a grungy neighborhood adjacent to a very good
neighborhood,'' Thomas Elghanayan recalled. ``The buildings were
cheap. It was not zoned for residential but there were plans to
rezone it.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1977, they bought a 12-story warehouse at Washington and 10th
streets and turned it into the Shepherd House apartments. It opened
in 1979, the same year that Rockrose paid $325,000 for the
blockfront parcel on which 99 Jane St. would later rise.
</P>
<P>
   A year later, the last load of freight _ three boxcars of frozen
turkeys _ rolled down the High Line and into the meat market. The
southern end of the market was rezoned for residential development
in 1984.
</P>
<P>
   During the late '80s, Rockrose opened the West Coast, at 95-97
Horatio St.; the Archive, at 666 Greenwich St. and 110-14 Horatio
St. Then it bought a five-block stretch of the High Line from
Conrail and, in 1991, demolished it from Bank to Gansevoort
streets. Where the tracks had run through the West Coast, Rockrose
filled in the structure with 33 apartments.
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere on the High Line, it built 100 Jane St. as an
``80-20'' project, with 20 percent of the apartments for
lower-income tenants, and 99 Jane St. as a condominium, selling for
about $600 a square foot. It sold out before it opened.
</P>
<P>
   The Elghanayans have now turned their attention to the
renovation of 252 Seventh Ave., between 24th and 25th Streets, as
the Chelsea Mercantile condominium.
</P>
<P>
   They are finished with development in the West Village. ``We
were all young men when we started this,'' Elghanayan said of their
adventures along Washington Street. ``Today, sitting where I am, I
wouldn't have started it. It was too ambitious. There were too many
risks and uncertainties.''
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, he said he is proud of Rockrose's role. ``What we
did there was the equivalent of what a municipality would do as
urban redevelopment,'' Elghanayan said, ``and probably more
efficiently and artistically than government could do.''
</P>
<P>
   From the other side of the bargaining table, Green, of the
waterfront preservation group, offered this assessment of Rockrose:
``They were forthcoming. This didn't happen without a lot of
pressure but they certainly did keep channels open.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think they wanted to disturb the context of the
neighborhood,'' he said. ``We didn't always agree on what that
was.''
</P>
<P>
   At Maggio Beef, Guerra has his own notion of context. ``They
build these very expensive condominiums and then complain that the
refrigeration on our trailer trucks keeps them awake,'' he said.
``We tell them, `Our trailer trucks were here before your
condominiums.' ''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
