<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Andretti agrees to extension
 &HT;    By Michael Carvell
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRISTOL, Tenn. _John Andretti will be driving the famous No. 43
car for three more seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Andretti, 36, and Petty Enterprises announced an extension
through 2002 on Saturday at Bristol Motor Speedway.
</P>
<P>
   ``Having John with us for at least the next three years
continues our work toward taking Petty Enterprises back to the top
of NASCAR racing,'' said Kyle Petty, who owns the team along with
his father, Richard Petty.
</P>
<P>
   Andretti is in his sixth full season of Cup racing, boasts two
career victories, and ranks 13th in the points standings this year.
</P>
<P>
   Musical chairs
</P>
<P>
   With Andretti agreeing to an extension, Robert Yates Racing has
one less driver to consider for the No. 28 car, which will be
vacated by Kenny Irwin after the season. Ricky Rudd, Wally
Dallenbach, and Joe Nemechek, among others, are candidates for the
car.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are several guys I'd like to work with, but I can't put
a percentage on how close we are with anybody,'' Yates said
Saturday. ``Probably the only percentage I could tell you is that
I'm going to go 100-percent crazy if I don't figure out something
soon.''
</P>
<P>
   2000 Monte Carlos
</P>
<P>
   The 2000 Chevy Monte Carlo will have its first extensive test
run Monday and Tuesday at Gateway International Raceway in Madison,
Ill. Bobby Hamilton, Sterling Marlin, Ken Schrader, David Green,
Jerry Nadeau, Geoffrey Bodine, Dale Earnhardt and Mike Skinner are
scheduled to drive the NASCAR-approved cars at the 1.25-mile track.
Chevy will have the cars tested again in late October.
</P>
<P>
   Another night race?
</P>
<P>
   Night races are the latest craze on the Cup circuit, and the
Southern 500 may start after sundown in the near future. Darlington
Raceway is studying the idea, and has received permission from its
parent company, International Speedway Corp., to use $3 million for
lights.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to see if it makes fiscal sense,'' Darlington Raceway
president Jim Hunter said. ``But I'm the wrong person to ask
because I really want them here.''
</P>
<P>
   Bristol, Charlotte, Daytona and Richmond are the four tracks
that already play host to night races.
</P>
<P>
   ``That would be wild (having the Southern 500 at night),'' Jeff
Gordon said. ``Seeing the walls is pretty important, and if we put
the Darlington stripes up on the walls at night, that would be
interesting.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have been amazed with the lighting systems. Most places we
go, (drivers) see better at night than we do in the day. I'm for
it, but I've also heard (others) say they'd rather see one pit row
(at Darlington) before we see lights, which I don't think is a bad
idea.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael Carvell writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
