<P>
   (NYT6) JERSEY CITY, N.J. -- Aug. 28, 1999 -- SENIOR-KAYAKER-2,
8-28 -- Leonard LeShay, 80, and a fellow member of the Metropolitan
Association of Sea Kayakers, get ready for a 10 hour trip around
the island of Manhattan. As a senior Kayaker, LeShay has several
decades on other kayakers who paddle around Manhattan on the
33-mile trips. But don't tell him that. ``If anyone says, 'Pop,' I
kill them,'' he says. ``I'm in there as an equal. I help them. They
don't help me.'' (Suzanne DeChillo/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) NEW YORK -- Aug. 28, 1999 -- SENIOR-KAYAKER-1, 8-28 --
Leonard LeShay, 80, is an old hand in a thriving pastime of
kayaking around the New York region. Nearly every weekend for the
past 12 years, through sweltering summers and shivering winters,
LeShay has hauled a kayak from his home in Fresh Meadows, Queens,
to rivers and bays around the Northeast. For LeShay, kayaking was a
natural evolution in his life. He was born in the Bronx to a family
of ``water people.'' He says his mother swam regularly in the
Atlantic Ocean until she was 86. His father was an avid fisherman.
(Suzanne DeChillo/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) NEW YORK -- Aug. 28, 1999 -- TEN-VECSEY-COLUMN, 8-28 --
Judy Levering, the first female president of the United States
Tennis Association, persuaded the association's board that the new
stadium at the National Tennis Center should be named after the
late Arthur Ashe. In her first Open as president of the USTA,
Levering now has another challenge -- filling the ludicrously
oversized 21,000-seat stadium with actual tennis fans. ``If you put
the stars in the stadium court, very often they have easy matches
in the early rounds,'' says Levering. ``People might go to the
hotly contested matches, and the stadium is one-third empty.''
(Angel Franco/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) NEW YORK -- Aug. 28, 1999 -- NY-REFUGEES-COLLEGES, 8-28
-- Milot Hajzeraj, 21, right, and his cousin, Mentor Ferataj, 23,
center, refugees from Kosovo, with Doris Hohman of the Refugee
Resettlement Program of Catholic Charities. The two men have been
given full scholarships to Hartwick College in Oneonta, N.Y. In
Kosovo, Albanian students were not allowed to attend classes on
campus or study in the Albanian language. ``When I used to go to
school, I never took a bag with me because if the police would find
our books, they would beat us and say: 'Why are you studying in
Albanian? This is a Serbian land.''' (Linda Rosier/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) MILWAUKEE -- Aug. 28, 1999 -- WELFARE-SURPLUS-2, 8-28 --
Tanya Moore talking with Dennis Dietz, a financial planner, found a
part-time job and got day care for her daughter, Michaela, 1, after
joining the Wisconsin Works program. Wisconsin has doubled the size
of its child care program, in part by tapping its welfare money.
And using other pools of state and federal money, it offers
low-wage workers subsidized health care and annual wage
supplements. (Nicole Bengiveno/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) MILWAUKEE -- Aug. 28, 1999 -- WELFARE-SURPLUS-1, 8-28 --
After joining the Wisconsin Works program, Tanya Moore found a
part-time job and got day care for her daughter, Michaela, 1. No
one would accuse Wisconsin of ending welfare on the cheap. But even
the state's famously expensive program finished last year with an
eye-popping surplus -- nearly $350 million in unspent federal
money. Wisconsin has also increased its spending on other needy
families, to reward them for staying off the rolls. (Nicole
Bengiveno/New York Times Photo)
</P>
