<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-MONEY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLAIMS AND COUNTERCLAIMS FLY IN MONEY LAUNDERING CASE
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRIAN WHITMORE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ What happened to our money? This is the question that
many Russians would like answered.
</P>
<P>
   Cynicism about public finances runs high in Russia, where state
employees like teachers and doctors, many of whom earn less that
$20 a month, go unpaid for months, and where currency devaluations
that wipe out the savings of ordinary citizens occur frequently.
</P>
<P>
   But as Boris N. Yeltsin's turbulent presidency enters its
twilight, questions about what really happened to Russia's public
purse over the past decade are finally finding answers _ sort of. A
series of Western media reports in the last 10 days have alleged
theft and graft on a shocking scale. Most notable are reports that
billions of dollars in pilfered public and corporate funds,
possibly including loans to Russia from the International Monetary
Fund, were laundered by Russian mob bosses through the Bank of New
York.
</P>
<P>
   But like most scandals reported in this country's opinionated
media, the Bank of New York money laundering case has become just
another weapon in the clan warfare here.
</P>
<P>
   Media loyal to Moscow Mayor Yuri Luzhkov, for example, are
spinning the scandal as another example of Kremlin corruption,
pointing the finger at Luzhkov's archrival, politically connected
tycoon and Yeltsin confidant Boris Berezovsky. Media loyal to
Berezovsky on the other hand, are reporting that the man behind the
money laundering is Luzhkov.
</P>
<P>
   The Moscow mayor and Berezovsky have been at each other's
throats for months.
</P>
<P>
   Luzhkov would like to become Russia's next president. He
recently assembled many of the country's powerful regional leaders
in a electoral bloc that could put him in the Kremlin when
Yeltsin's term expires next summer. That is a terrifying thought
for Berezovsky and a group of Kremlin insiders, darkly referred to
here as ``The Family,'' who fear the reckoning and possible
prosecutions that could result should forces hostile to them win
the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   In Russia, most major media are linked in some form to one or
the other of the country's competing political clans. ``Everybody
is trying to use this scandal to advance their own political
agendas,'' said Radik Batirsin, an adviser for the powerful
Media-Most company, which manages the popular NTV commercial
television station and the daily newspaper Segodnya, both widely
seen as sympathetic to Luzhkov.
</P>
<P>
   The scandal broke on Aug. 19, when The New York Times reported
that Russian organized crime groups had laundered as much as $10
billion through accounts in the Bank of New York. The report, which
cited unidentified law-enforcement officials, linked the accounts
to reputed Russian mobster Semyon Mogilevich and claimed the funds
were used for activities including contract murders, narcotics
trafficking, and prostitution. Saturday, Mogilevich denied
involvement.
</P>
<P>
   The bank has suspended one employee, Natasha
Gurfinkel-Kagalovsky of New York, and fired another, Lucy Edwards
of London. Both handled the bank's Eastern European accounts and
both are married to Russian businessmen. Gurfinkel-Kagalovsky is
the wife of Konstantin Kagalovsky, who from 1992 to 1995 was an
adviser to Russia's government and its representative to the IMF.
He now is vice president of Yukos, one of Russia's biggest oil
companies. The Kagalovskys have denied any wrongdoing, and called
the whole affair ``an anti-Russian campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   The Wall Street Journal later reported that IMF loans to Russia
may have been among the laundered funds, a claim the IMF is
denying. Later reports in USA Sunday claimed that as much as $15
billion may have passed through the accounts, that food aid funds
to Russia may also have been pilfered, and that former and current
members of the Russian government were implicated.
</P>
<P>
   Federal lawmaker Vladimir Lukin, a former ambassador to the
United States, called the scandal ``the big one.'' Regarding how it
has been played in the Russian media, Lukin said, ``This is the
reality of our oligarchic semifeudal system where practically
everybody belongs to somebody else.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It is very important that every one of these allegations be
investigated thoroughly by American and other law-enforcement
bodies,'' Lukin said.
</P>
<P>
   The FBI will not say publicly whether it is investigating the
money laundering claims, although Britain's National Crime Squad
has confirmed that it is cooperating with the bureau on the matter.
</P>
<P>
   The federal Securities and Exchange Commission announced
Saturday it would investigate 33 Russian companies that deal with
Bank of New York.
</P>
<P>
   Congress is also getting into the act. A spokesman for Iowa
Republican Representative James Leach, chairman of the House
Banking Committee, said hearings on the money laundering scandal
will be held next month.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Berezovsky and Luzhkov exchanged public insults
Friday over an entirely different scandal. The Italian newspaper
Corriera della Sera reported last week that a Swiss company that
had won lucrative Kremlin renovation contracts had paid Yeltsin and
his two daughters an estimated $1 million. Berezovsky said that
``Luzhkov and his henchmen'' were behind that report. Luzhkov hit
back with a sarcastic statement saying he was happy to hear that he
was ``strong enough to run and command not only the Moscow press,
but foreign publications as well.''
</P>
<P>
   And Russians are still left wondering what happened to their
money.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-28-99 1912EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
