<HEADER>
A2944 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-TIMOR-ELECTION-BOS &LR;      08-28 0918
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TIMOR-ELECTION-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EAST TIMOR TO VOTE ON INDEPENDENCE PLAN
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By INDIRA A.R. LAKSHMANAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DILI, East Timor _ After centuries of colonial oppression
followed by years of civil war and unsettled peace, a single day at
the ballot box Monday will determine the future of this disputed
territory at the eastern edge of the Indonesian archipelago.
</P>
<P>
   More than half of East Timor's 800,000 residents are registered
to vote in a United Nations-sponsored referendum that will allow
self-determination for the first time _ a choice between autonomy
under Indonesia or independence.
</P>
<P>
   But if the tense and bloody seven-month lead-up to the ballot is
any indication, Monday's vote could well be disrupted or even
skewed by outbreaks of violence and intimidation at any of 200
polling stations.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday, pro-Indonesia supporters fired shots in the air in one
tense suburb of Dili, prompting hundreds to flee their homes and
others to take up machetes, axes, and sticks.
</P>
<P>
   In clashes on Thursday and Friday, at least 10 people were
killed in a ``last attempt to destabilize the situation before we
go to the polls,'' said David Wimhurst, spokesman for the UN
mission here.
</P>
<P>
   But leaders of both sides, as well as the UN and international
observers, called for the balloting to go forward, saying a delay
would only exacerbate a precarious situation.
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, many residents interviewed said that after being
deprived of a say for so long, they fully intend to exercise their
vote.
</P>
<P>
   Postponing the vote ``is not fair to East Timor because they've
been suffering for quite a long time,'' said a spokeswoman for the
Asian Network for Free Elections, one of numerous nongovernmental
groups that have deployed a total of 1,500 observers here from
around the world.
</P>
<P>
   East Timor was a distant and neglected Portuguese colony from
the early 18th century until 1975, when a socialist government in
Lisbon was making plans to withdraw. A civil war erupted between
independence seekers and those who wanted to join neighboring
Indonesia, a nation of more than 200 million people.
</P>
<P>
   Indonesia invaded in 1975 and annexed East Timor the next year,
triggering years of guerrilla war and abuses.
</P>
<P>
   Early this year, President B.J. Habibie of Indonesia pledged to
let East Timorese settle the question themselves. But since then,
violence has claimed scores of lives, most of the strife stoked by
those who want to remain part of Indonesia and fear a vote for
separation.
</P>
<P>
   Jakarta fears a vote to separate here could encourage three
other restive provinces _ Aceh, Irian Jaya, and Ambon _ to break
away.
</P>
<P>
   Delaying the ballot would ``not increase the safety and security
of East Timor people, because there are no guarantees from the
international community of better security in future,'' said Saskia
Kouwenberg of the International Federation for East Timor Observer
Project.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Kouwenberg said that violent incidents of the last week
``throw into question the legitimacy of the ballot.''
</P>
<P>
   International observers and the UN have condemned the Indonesian
military and police, who are responsible for keeping peace, for
failing to intervene to stop clashes, and, worse, aiding
pro-Indonesia civilian militias.
</P>
<P>
   Kouwenberg's group reported seeing Indonesian riot police
distributing automatic weapons to pro-autonomy militia members in
the town of Maubisse.
</P>
<P>
   In the town of Maliana, Indonesian military personnel are among
leaders of the local militias, the group said.
</P>
<P>
   Other groups reported police carrying pro-autonomy paraphernalia
at rallies, and failing to stop militias on rampages.
</P>
<P>
   Independence leaders called on the UN to send peacekeepers in
before the vote _ an impossibility at this stage, and a move that
Indonesia has consistently opposed. The UN has only 280 unarmed
police here.
</P>
<P>
   There were also reports of local authorities copying
registration lists and voter cards and telling people that
officials will know how they vote.
</P>
<P>
   An Indonesian government spokesman, Dino Djalal, defended the
security and secrecy of the vote, saying one Indonesian police
officer would be deployed for every 100 people, with three manning
each polling station.
</P>
<P>
   He also said it is the job of the UN Mission in East Timor to
convince people that ``no one will ever know how any person or any
village voted.''
</P>
<P>
   Djalal said he was optimistic that the vote will be ``a clean
and fair process. . . . The whole point about this process is to
let the vote kill the violence, not let the violence kill the
vote.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If autonomy is rejected,'' he said, ``people will say, `You
had it coming.' If autonomy wins, people will say it's because of
intimidation. So it's a no-win situation'' for the Indonesian
government.
</P>
<P>
   Scores of families who fled deadly clashes in Dili neighborhoods
Thursday and Friday were sheltering Saturday in a school complex
adjoining the UN mission. But many insisted they could not be
deterred from voting.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not scared by this,'' said Maria Soares, 47, a farmer
whose husband was shot during the Indonesian invasion in 1975. ``If
I die, that is God calling me to death. I feel it's my duty to
vote.''
</P>
<P>
   Her neighbor, Antonio Dacosta, 30, was not so sure.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there's this much violence, how can you expect us to be
brave enough to vote? People are fleeing one another. We need UN
security forces to guarantee our safety,'' Dacosta said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-28-99 1914EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990828.0228 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-28 19:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2945 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-FBC-ARIZONA-PENNST-CO     08-28 0580
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-ARIZONA-PENNST-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Making 41-7 Penn State-ment
 &HT;    By Tony Barnhart
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   STATE COLLEGE, Pa. _ They call it a ``statement'' game _ one of
those special afternoons where a team steps up and defines what it
is and what it ultimately hopes to be. No. 3 Penn State made an
emphatic statement about its national championship aspirations
Saturday by destroying No. 4 Arizona 41-7 before 97,168 happy but
somewhat disbelieving fans at Beaver Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Penn State (1-0) gave every indication that it's a legitimate
contender by rolling up 361 yards in the first half and taking a
31-0 halftime lead. That made the second half a moot exercise
filled with the penalties and mistakes that come with a first game.
Arizona's only score came against Penn State's third-team defense
with 47 seconds left.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just told our guys to go out and have fun and let's just see
how good we are,'' said Joe Paterno, who got his 308th win as Penn
State's coach. ``We sort of fooled them a little bit by showing
them some things they hadn't seen. Then once they got down, it was
hard for them to come back.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the things Arizona, or any other team, had not seen from
Penn State was Paterno's willingness to open up the offense and use
Chafie Fields as his primary weapon. A senior flanker, he scored
Penn State's first touchdown on a 37-yard reception and then three
minutes later took an inside reverse handoff around his left end
for a 70-yard score. Penn State also had a 60-yard touchdown catch
and run by reserve tailback Larry Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coach just kind of took the reins off the offense so we could
really show what we could do,'' said Fields, who caught three
passes for 76 yards and ran three times for 110 yards. ``Man, this
definitely sets the tone for the season.''
</P>
<P>
   As impressive as Penn State was, the Nittany Lions were aided by
an Arizona team that failed to back up its credentials as a
national power. With countless missed tackles and missed
assignments, the Wildcats looked like anything but a prohibitive
favorite to win the Pac-10. Penn State took the opening possession
and drove 80 yards for a touchdown in seven plays. It was never a
game after that.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Dick Tomey tried hard to put the best spin on what was an
ugly afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this was good for us,'' said Tomey, whose team had won
16 of its past 17 games. ``This doesn't have to be the death knell
for us. This needed to happen. And it's a helluva lot better that
this happen now than against Stanford in the conference.
</P>
<P>
   ``If this . . . is part of the development of our team during
the course of the year, it will be worth it.''
</P>
<P>
   For Penn State, the road ahead is promising. It should cruise in
its next two games with Akron and Pittsburgh. Then comes an
interesting trip to improved Miami on Sept. 18. The big ones, Ohio
State and Michigan, are both at home.
</P>
<P>
   In short, Joe Paterno's 50th year at Penn State has a chance to
be special. His team had that look Saturday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just one game and I really don't think it proves
anything,'' said Paterno, 72. ``If we keep getting better, then
maybe we have a chance to be pretty good.''
</P>
<P>
   As Arizona began the long trek home, it was already persuaded.
Penn State is more than pretty good.
</P>
<P>
   Tony Barnhart writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
