<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-28 19:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2947 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-TEXAS-LONGDISTANCE-CO     08-28 0887
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-LONGDISTANCE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    New utility laws could put money in your pocket
 &HT;    By Bruce Hight
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Texans who make a lot of in-state long-distance
telephone calls should see prices coming down in the next few
months, thanks to a rewrite of the state's phone laws by the
Legislature this spring.
</P>
<P>
   And those who find themselves in a billing dispute with their
long-distance provider no longer will risk losing their local
telephone service for refusing to pay a long-distance bill.
</P>
<P>
   Many Texans, meanwhile, can expect to see big changes in how
they buy electricity when the market is opened up to competition
Jan. 1, 2002. The new electric law does not apply to Austin Energy,
Pedernales Electric Cooperative Inc. and other municipally owned
utilities and cooperatives. But their prices may decline if their
customers see electricity prices falling elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Utility law is not an exciting subject _ at least not until the
monthly electric bill arrives.
</P>
<P>
   But in its 1999 session, the Legislature made two landmark
changes: It lifted many government restrictions from Southwestern
Bell Telephone Co. and opened the electric utility industry to
competition.
</P>
<P>
   The new laws take effect Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Customers are still protected, but there's a recognition that
the market, in the next couple of years, will be a much more
effective protector of the customer than the regulatory state has
been so far,'' said Pat Wood, chairman of the Public Utility
Commission.
</P>
<P>
   The PUC will become more of a market cop _ taking complaints,
levying fines and, if necessary, revoking the certificates of
utility companies.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Bill 560 by Sen. David Sibley, R-Waco, capped
Southwestern Bell's prices for basic local residential telephone
service until 2005 but allowed it to change its prices for many
other services. Long-distance phone companies also will have to pay
less to access Southwestern Bell's networks.
</P>
<P>
   The changes were expected to result in more competition for
local phone service and lower prices for in-state, long-distance
calls.
</P>
<P>
   But the Consumers Union and other consumer advocates say
residential consumers won't necessarily benefit because there's
virtually no competition now for their business. Instead, the
consumer advocates said, competition will focus on business
customers.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation also cleared the way for long-distance companies
such as AT&AMP;T Corp. and MCI Worldcom to slash the 12 cents a minute
they now must pay Southwestern Bell to complete their in-state,
long-distance calls.
</P>
<P>
   The PUC estimates that the cost of an in-state, long-distance
call should drop by about 5 cents a minute. It could drop by
another 2 cents a minute July 1, 2000, or whenever Southwestern
Bell gets into the long-distance business.
</P>
<P>
   The cuts will cost Southwestern Bell an estimated $200 million a
year _ savings that long-distance companies must pass on to their
customers.
</P>
<P>
   But Texans may not clearly see the changes on their bills,
because long-distance companies can apply the savings in a variety
of ways. The two biggest companies, AT&AMP;T and MCI Worldcom, have not
announced their intentions.
</P>
<P>
   The long-distance cut comes at a price. The access charge
subsidized expensive or specialized customer services, such as
those for rural communities and for deaf people.
</P>
<P>
   The Universal Service Fund, which will cover those costs, is
going up in September from the current 0.787 percent of a monthly
bill to 3.579 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The bottom line: People who make a lot of in-state,
long-distance telephone calls probably will save money, but for
those who make few such calls, the main difference might be a
slight increase in their monthly local bill.
</P>
<P>
   The PUC, under Senate Bill 86 by Sen. Jane Nelson, R-Flower
Mound, also will get much tougher enforcement powers on Sept. 1
against slamming and cramming. Slamming is changing a customer's
long-distance provider without permission; cramming is charging a
customer for a service neither ordered nor wanted.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can move more quickly, and we have some new tools,'' said
Saralee Tiede, the PUC's chief of customer protection. ``And we
have an ability to deal with the scams we haven't seen.''
</P>
<P>
   Starting Jan. 1, local phone companies will not be able to cut
off service to customers who don't pay their long-distance charges.
Such cutoffs now can occur for long-distance companies that bill
through a local provider, such as Southwestern Bell.
</P>
<P>
   A study done several years ago indicated that two-thirds of
Texans who did not have telephones said the reason was previous
problems paying long-distance charges, Wood said. Breaking the link
between local and long-distance charges, he said, may help poor
Texans afford minimal telephone service.
</P>
<P>
   The monthly electric bill likely won't change much for a few
years.
</P>
<P>
   Rates for investor-owned electric utilities, including TXU
Electric, effectively have been frozen until Jan. 1, 2002, when
they will be cut 6 percent.
</P>
<P>
   At that point, other companies can begin competing for the
utility's customers _ and presumably offer lower prices.
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Hight writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
