<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-28 19:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2960 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-BBN-BRAVES-CARDS29-CO     08-28 0812
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-CARDS29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Millwood lasts 10 as Braves streak goes to 9
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS _ The lengths the Braves have gone to keep their
tentative hold on the NL East going are beginning to border on the
absurd.
</P>
<P>
   Take, for example, Saturday's 10 shutout innings from Kevin
Millwood and a 3-0 13-inning win over the Cardinals.
</P>
<P>
   It was the 1,500th victory of manager Bobby Cox's career, the
Braves' ninth consecutive win to match the longest winning streak
of last season, and most important, maintained at least a 1
1/2-game lead on the Mets.
</P>
<P>
   But wait, there's so much more.
</P>
<P>
   Millwood became the first pitcher in baseball this season to
throw 10 innings, the first Braves pitcher to throw 10 innings in a
game since Greg Maddux did in a 3-2 11-inning win over the
Cardinals on April 30, 1993 and the first Braves pitcher to throw
10 scoreless innings since Frank LaCorte on Sept. 17, 1976 in a 1-0
win over the Dodgers.
</P>
<P>
   He did it without getting a win.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I could I'd give all six of mine to him, I would,'' said
Mike Remlinger, who took the win after working two scoreless
innings in relief. ``Guy pitches 10 shutout innings, he deserves a
win.''
</P>
<P>
   Millwood's problem was Cardinals pitcher Darren Oliver. Those
two duked it out to an 0-0 draw through nine innings by allowing a
total of seven men to reach base _ on two hits and a walk against
Millwood, four hits and a walk on Oliver, who bowed out after nine
innings.
</P>
<P>
   Not before Eddie Perez doubled past St. Louis third baseman
Fernando Tatis, Walt Weiss bunted the pinch-running Ozzie Guillen
to third, and Gerald Williams drove him in with a single to center
was there such a thing as a lead in this game.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're all tired, we had to do something,'' Perez said
afterward before pointing postgame buffet table. ``The
food's cold.''
</P>
<P>
   The Braves padded the lead with two more runs on a couple of
Cardinal errors, and John Rocker collected his 30th save after
loading the bases in the 13th and leaving them that way on an Edgar
Renteria groundout. The game, which had flown for the first nine
innings, lasted 3 hours and 40 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Millwood) was out there for a minute, I was out there for
about two minutes,'' Oliver said. ``If somebody would have scored,
it would have been a two-hour game. You could have 1,000 starts and
never have that happen.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals haven't scored on the Braves in the last 19
innings of this series and find themselves down 2-0 with one game
to play despite allowing only five runs in two games.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why do writers always want to write it was the hitters'
fault?'' said Mark McGwire, who is now 1 for 9 in the series with
five strikeouts. ``Those guys over there are paid a lot of money to
get you out.''
</P>
<P>
   Millwood might give a little back for a couple runs here lately.
The Braves have scored Millwood only seven runs in his last three
starts, six of them in his win over Reds. Otherwise he's taken two
no-decisions after throwing a eight innings of one-run ball in
Colorado and his shutout work Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm really nice to those guys,'' Millwood joked about his
teammates. ``I try to be a good guy, but I'm not going to be
anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Millwood looked like he was going pitch on into the night as he
headed back out for the 10th inning, something he could afford to
do after using only 106 pitches to pitch the first nine innings.
</P>
<P>
   He threw 119 pitches in all, struck out nine, and walked one. He
allowed only two hits for the fifth time this season, including two
other no-hit bids against Boston and Houston, eight shutout innings
against the Mets, and his two-hit dandy in Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   He saw this particular no-hit bid end on an Edgar Renteria
groundball that Chipper Jones had skip off the heel of his glove
with two outs in the sixth inning. Jones hopped up and threw to
first on a play the Braves in the field thought was an out. The
play was ruled a hit, though opinions varied in the clubhouse
afterward.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had it going there for a while,'' Millwood said. ``But
there's no reason for me to let up and lose concentration just
because I give up one hit.''
</P>
<P>
   He didn't allow his first legitimate hit of the game until
giving up a hard single to center by pinch hitting Craig Paquette
in the ninth inning. After a failed attempt to advance Paquette on
a bunt, J.D. Drew and McGwire took Millwood deep in the outfield
for flyball outs. That was as much noise as the Cardinals would
make on him in a game that featured plenty of good defense for
Millwood.
</P>
<P>
   ``Man, he was unbelievable,'' Perez said. ``His high cheese was
getting everybody out. That was the key.''
</P>
<P>
   Carroll Rogers writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
