<SLUG> BC-FBN-FALCONS-FOLO-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Falcons fret little things
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ As the Falcons head into the final week of the
preseason, they ought to be fine-tuning a few things, tweaking the
roster and getting ready for bigger and better things.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, despite losing three starters from last year's NFC
Championship team, it's the little things _ a lot of them _ that
are irking the Falcons.
</P>
<P>
   Injuries continue to be a giant pain.
</P>
<P>
   Starting quarterback Chris Chandler's sore right hamstring kept
him out of Friday night's 17-3 loss at Tennessee, although coach
Dan Reeves said Chandler should practice Monday.
</P>
<P>
   As the Falcons prepare to trim their roster from 70 to 65 by 4
p.m. Tuesday, here are other hang-ups:
</P>
<P>
   _ The competition between Danny Kanell and Tony Graziani for the
backup quarterback job has been fouled up. Injuries to Graziani,
who had an MRI exam on his hyperextended right knee Saturday, have
limited him to two quarters. Kanell has played about eight.
</P>
<P>
   _ There are still too many questions at wide receiver, where the
release of Tony Martin and the sprained ankle of Chris Calloway
have caused problems.
</P>
<P>
   _ Offensive execution has been poor _ the team has scored nine
points in the past two games _ and penalties have been plentiful.
</P>
<P>
   _ The defense has been fairly solid the past two games, giving
up 34 points, and 10 Tennessee points were set up by two of the
Falcons' five turnovers. Tennessee averaged 2.5 yards per rush
Friday, but the Falcons are getting beat in the passing game.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps most alarming, Kanell and Graziani are behind where they
should be.
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons are 19-5 when Chandler starts and finishes games,
including the postseason, and 3-7 otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   Kanell has completed 32 of 68 passes for 367 yards, one
touchdown and four interceptions for a 44.2 passer rating.
</P>
<P>
   Graziani has completed 8 of 16 for 139 yards and one
interception for a 53.9 passer rating.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tony is throwing to the right people more, making the right
reads,'' Reeves said. ``Danny did some good things, too, but he
took three of the toughest shots I've seen in awhile.''
</P>
<P>
   Second-year wide receiver Tim Dwight, who started at split end
in place of Calloway, caught three passes for 48 yards Friday night
and threw a nice downfield block on O.J. Santiago's 22-yard
reception.
</P>
<P>
   But other teams are passing the ball better.
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons gave up passing plays of 48 and 36 yards to set up
the Titans' two touchdowns. In last Saturday's 19-6 loss to
Baltimore, a 57-yard pass set up one Ravens touchdown, and the
other score came on an 81-yard pass.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the quarterback has enough time to throw it, he's going to
make plays,'' said Falcons cornerback Ray Buchanan, who was not
involved in any of those.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the ball is floating up there, we've got to go get it
like we did last year.''
</P>
<P>
   Matt Winkeljohn writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
