<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-NATIONAL-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BREWERS SEEK MINORITY HIRE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Omar Minaya has friends in high places, but will
it be enough to get the general manager's job with the Milwaukee
Brewers?
</P>
<P>
   Minaya, the one-time Texas scout who signed fellow Dominican
Sammy Sosa back in 1986, is the assistant GM with the New York Mets
and was a finalist for the Dodgers job last summer.
</P>
<P>
   National League president Leonard Coleman is seeking to boost
minority representation in baseball's upper management and wants
Minaya for the job Sal Bando gave up when manager Phil Garner was
fired.
</P>
<P>
   Club president Wendy Selig-Prieb also is interested in a
minority hire for the job and is considering her farm director
Cecil Cooper, a member of the Brewers' only World Series team in
1982.
</P>
<P>
   Although former Dodgers GM Fred Claire recently appeared on a
list of 12 candidates, he is a long shot. Blue Jays assistant GM
Dave Stewart, however, is considered a front-runner. Other names
include Dan Evans of the White Sox, Dean Taylor of the Braves and
Dan O'Dowd, formerly of the Indians.
</P>
<P>
   High-yield Bonds: The Giants' Barry Bonds took Friday off after
one of the hottest stretches of his career. In the previous nine
games Bonds went 18 for 41 (.439) with nine homers and 18 RBI.
Included were three home runs in a doubleheader sweep of the Cubs
that ran the Giants' winning streak to seven games. Bonds, who
missed two months with a torn left bicep, entered Saturday with 25
homers and 68 RBI in just 72 games. This season he has homered
every 9.9 at-bats and collected an RBI every 3.6 at-bats, both
career bests.
</P>
<P>
   Money talks: Phillies first baseman Rico Brogna has been on fire
since signing a one-year, $4million contract extension last week.
In eight games since the deal was done, Brogna hit .571 with three
homers and 15 RBI. Now if Philadelphia can get something done with
right fielder Bobby Abreu, who is second in the league in hitting
to Colorado's Larry Walker. Abreu, traded two years ago by
expansion Tampa Bay before the Devil Rays even played a game, last
winter rejected a contract offer by the Phillies, who had just
signed third baseman Scott Rolen to a four-year, $10 million deal.
Abreu will be eligible for salary arbitration this winter.
</P>
<P>
   A.J. is back: Remember when Florida right-hander A.J. Burnett
was sent down after beating the Dodgers 11 days ago in his
major-league debut? Well, after getting roughed up in a Double-A
start, he returned to the big leagues Saturday and started against
the Astros. His biggest problem so far has been getting out
minor-league batters. Burnett entered his start against the Dodgers
6-12 with a 5.52 ERA at Double-A Portland. When he returned he
allowed 10 hits. ``He's a guy we think is in the mix for next
year,'' said Marlins manager John Boles, who could start Burnett
next week against the Dodgers in Miami. ``So we'll give him the
ball and get him out of that tough Eastern League.''
</P>
<P>
   Great matchups: Last week's series between the Reds and Braves
and Mets and Astros will be repeated beginning Monday in Cincinnati
and Houston. The Reds, baseball's best road team at 40-20, were
swept by the Braves and went 0-5 this season at Turner Field. They
hit .123 and averaged two runs a game. The Braves, however, could
be without starter Greg Maddux for a couple of starts with a bone
chip in his right wrist. Atlanta also lost valuable setup man Rudy
Seanez this past week with elbow problems that might require
surgery. The Braves already have lost Andres Galarraga and Javy
Lopez. The underrated Seanez was the bridge between the starters
and closer John Rocker. A weak bullpen has hurt the Braves in the
postseason the past few years.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
