<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-28 19:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2963 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-TEXAS-DUI-LAWS-COX     08-28 1205
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-DUI-LAWS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    This week, 'one for the road' gets riskier
 &HT;    By Scott Greenberger
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Services
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Don't tell Peggy Floyd that lowering the
blood-alcohol levels for drunken driving to 0.08 percent from 0.10
percent won't make a difference.
</P>
<P>
   Almost two years ago, Floyd's 24-year-old daughter Kayla was
killed when a drunken teen-ager in a pickup ran a red light and
plowed into her Pontiac Firebird.
</P>
<P>
   The teen-ager had a blood-alcohol level of 0.08 percent when he
was tested about 90 minutes after the accident.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning Sept. 1, Texas will join 16 other states in enforcing
a 0.08 standard. Critics of the new law point to a recent federal
study that questioned the effects of lowering the blood-alcohol
limit alone. But Floyd and other supporters cite medical research
showing that alcohol begins to impair coordination and vision at
levels less than 0.08 _ and she knows better than most that in an
accident, inches and split-seconds count.
</P>
<P>
   ``Drinking even one beer can make us less alert and less
responsive to any problems,'' said Floyd, who is featured in radio
spots publicizing the new law. She said witnesses testified that
the teen-ager who killed her daughter ``didn't tap the brake; he
didn't turn. If he had tilted his wheel just a little bit, just
jerked a little bit, she would have been out of there.''
</P>
<P>
   The new 0.08 rule is just one of about 900 new laws that will
take effect Wednesday, but few of them have the potential to affect
as many Texans: About half of Texas' adults are regular drinkers,
according to a recent Texas Poll. And about 40 percent of those
regular drinkers admitted there have been times they might have
failed a sobriety test if they had been stopped after drinking.
</P>
<P>
   On average, according to the National Highway Traffic Safety
Administration, a 170-pound man reaches a 0.08 blood-alcohol level
after five drinks (one drink equals one 12-ounce can of beer, a
5-ounce glass of wine or a shot of liquor)over two hours. A
120-pound woman reaches that level after consuming three drinks in
the same time period. The difference between 0.08 and 0.10 is one
drink over two hours for a 170-pound man and half a drink over two
hours for a 120-pound woman.But individuals metabolize alcohol
differently, and the agency's formula also doesn't account for
factors such as age.
</P>
<P>
   Critics of the 0.08 standard say it will net social drinkers who
aren't a danger on the roads.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will be a spate of news stories about 0.08, and it will
frighten some people. But the effect is not long-lasting, and the
alcohol abusers aren't the ones who are going to be cutting back on
drinking,'' said John Doyle of the American Beverage Institute, a
Washington-based group that lobbies for restaurants on
alcohol-related issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``Millions of people drive responsibly and reach levels of
0.08,'' Doyle said. ``You're destroying people's lives by arresting
them for behavior which is not contributing to the problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Doyle and other opponents use a recent report by the General
Accounting Office, the research arm of Congress, to buttress their
case.
</P>
<P>
   When Texas lawmakers debated the change last spring, supporters
pointed to a half-dozen studies showing a reduction in
drunken-driving accidents in states with the 0.08 standard. But
about a month after the Legislature approved the lower limit, GAO's
review of the data concluded that ``the evidence does not
conclusively establish that 0.08 BAC (blood-alcohol content) laws,
by themselves, result in reductions in the number and severity of
alcohol-related crashes.''
</P>
<P>
   GAO investigators said some of the studies were flawed because
additional anti-drunken-driving laws went into effect about the
same time as the 0.08 limit, and the researchers didn't isolate the
effects of the tougher blood-alcohol standard. Other studies used
time frames that were too short to determine trends or yielded
mixed results.
</P>
<P>
   Critics also say few drinkers will know what the new standard
means in terms of their own consumption.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can only drink about three an hour, right?'' said Yogi
Patel, 22, as she sipped a Dos Equis at a bar in downtown Austin.
The Southwest Texas State University student said she heard about
the new law on the radio.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not going to change the way I drink _ it's not going to
change the way anyone drinks. They know how much they can handle,
so I don't see why they'd change,'' Patel said.
</P>
<P>
   Rob Rodriguez, 41, a Dell employee who was drinking a Bass a few
feet away, described 0.08 as ``an abstract concept.'' He, too,
questioned the impact of the change.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know when I need to stop _ usually, three's the limit. I
don't know what that is on the scale they're talking about,''
Rodriguez said. ``I think that for anyone who's conscientious about
their drinking, the new law won't make any difference. And people
who don't give a crap will continue to do their thing, too.''
</P>
<P>
   But supporters of the change note that the GAO review also said
there are ``strong indications'' that if the 0.08 standard is
combined with other measures such as strict license revocation laws
and public education campaigns, lives will be saved.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just because the law is changed doesn't mean that crashes and
fatalities go down if the public is not made aware, if enforcement
is not maintained _ or increased _ and if people's general behavior
and attitude are not changed,'' said Sue Bryant, traffic safety
director at the Texas Department of Transportation.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, the most recent year for which statistics are
available, Texas led the nation in alcohol-related traffic
fatalities with 1,748, according to the National Highway Traffic
Safety Administration. About half of Texas' traffic fatalities were
alcohol-related, compared with the national average of 39 percent.
Only Alaska, Rhode Island and the District of Columbia had a higher
rate.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the radio spots featuring Floyd, the
transportation agency is hanging 0.08 signs in stores that sell
liquor and putting stickers on cases of beer to get the message
out. The department still is working on signs for bars and
restaurants, Bryant said.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Lewis, the legislative liaison for the Texas chapter of
Mothers Against Drunk Driving, said public awareness of a tougher
standard _ even if it's fuzzy _ is ``probably the main rationale
for lowering the BAC to 0.08.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Most folks don't have any idea what 0.08 means. What they do
know is that it's lower, so people who may be tempted to drink too
much before they drive may cut themselves off sooner because they
know there's some tough, new law out there,'' Lewis said.
</P>
<P>
   Heather Sentell, who tends bar at The Gingerman a few doors down
from Fado, said she hopes the new law will make people nervous.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm terrified of drinking and driving myself. Anything they
have to do to crack down on it is fine with me,'' said Sentell, 23.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it makes people one ounce more paranoid to get in a car
drunk, it's worth it.''
</P>
<P>
   Scott S. Greenberger writes for the Austin American-Statesman,
Austin, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
