<HEADER>
A2978 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BBA-DETROIT-WEAVER-LA     08-28 0792
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-DETROIT-WEAVER-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEAVER ADJUSTING TO BIG-LEAGUE LIFE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HEATHER GRIPP  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Jeff Weaver isn't used to seeing himself on
television.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's strange when you go home and sit in bed and turn on
SportsCenter, the highlights of the game and there you are,'' said
the Simi Valley High graduate, who has received plenty of air time
since being called up to the Detroit Tigers in April. ``It's
definitely a change. Hopefully you only catch the good highlights.
It is pretty strange.''
</P>
<P>
   Weaver's professional career spans a little more than a year.
He's adjusted to the travel, attention and what he calls an overall
``pretty cool'' life of a major-leaguer, a life remarkable for
someone who failed to be drafted out of high school yet became the
14th pick overall in 1998 out of Fresno State.
</P>
<P>
   How far he's come hit Weaver when he turned 23 last weekend and
he couldn't think of anything to ask for.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've pretty much got everything I could want,'' said Weaver,
who was in town for a series against the Anaheim Angels.
</P>
<P>
   ``How about some wins,'' suggested a teammate.
</P>
<P>
   Weaver hopes for better results soon _ ``I definitely want to be
part of a winning team,'' he said _ but not even playing for the
team with the worst record in the American League can ruin the
6-foot-5, 200-pound right-hander's first experience in the majors.
</P>
<P>
   ``It makes it tough to come to the yard sometimes,'' Weaver
said, ``not feeling like you want to go through another big loss.
But you've got to remember you're still pitching in the big leagues
and you're still at the top of the levels. Sometimes it just makes
it a longer season being on a losing team, but they're making
changes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it really matters where you're pitching. The
first time you're still kind of nervous, how you're going to fit
in, how well you'll do. I don't think it would have mattered if I
was pitching for Cleveland or pitching for Detroit, it still would
have felt the same, I think.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never really thought I'd be in this position, so every time
I go out there it's a great feeling.''
</P>
<P>
   Returning to Southern California and seeing his friends and
family for the first time since his major-league debut was another
great feeling.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being home was a big boost,'' Weaver said. ``Just getting off
the plane, getting on the bus, getting on to a familiar highway,
seeing familiar places, it made you feel like you're back home and
you have your feet on the ground ... It gives you an attitude you
want to perform at your best and thank God it went that way.''
</P>
<P>
   Weaver gave up three hits in seven innings and had a season-high
seven strikeouts in the win against the Angels, his first victory
since May 27.
</P>
<P>
   His fast start _ a 6-3 record and 2.89 ERA through May _ put him
in early contention for Rookie of the Year honors. Then he went 13
starts without a win.
</P>
<P>
   A longer season than he's ever experienced could be one reason
for Weaver's slump. The mental aspect of playing so many games is a
bigger factor than fatigue, according to Weaver. However, his
coaches noticed a slight change in his delivery as the season
progressed. He began using a higher release point, forced pitches
and wasn't able to work the outside edge the way that made him
effective early in the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing about this is you can lose just a little bit, you
won't even hardly feel it,'' Tigers manager Larry Parrish said,
``but at this level they let you know. A good hitting club will
just wear you out.''
</P>
<P>
   On a team with a better record, Weaver's spot in the rotation _
and in the majors _ could have been in jeopardy. The Tigers never
considered sending him down.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think he's got a bright future,'' Parrish said. ``Sometimes
you've got to test a guy to see how he handles things. Anybody can
handle things when they go good. You want to see what a guy does
when he struggles a little bit. It really shows what kind of
character he has.
</P>
<P>
   ``It tested him a little bit. That's a long dry spell. For a
young kid, that's like eternity.''
</P>
<P>
   That's how long it could take Weaver to think of himself any
differently than a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``Out of spring training they said you'll have five or six
starts at Double-A and get reevaluated,'' Weaver said. ``I had one
start and they were like, `Uh, we're calling you up.' I was really
surprised, everything happened so fast. I mean, I played with guys
in the minor leagues that had been at that level for three or four
years, so it's something you don't take for granted.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to remember where you came from. That's what everyone
says, but it's true. It keeps you grounded.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
