<HEADLINE>
CONE'S GAME HAS SLIPPED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Five weeks after pitching his perfect game, David
Cone is a big part of a big problem with the New York Yankees'
starting rotation.
</P>
<P>
   Since shutting down Montreal on July 18, Cone is just 1-3 with
three no-decisions. Last week against Kansas City, his fastball was
clocked at 83 mph. It improved to 87 on Tuesday in Texas, but he
was ripped for six runs and seven hits in 12/3 innings, his
second-shortest outing since 1989.
</P>
<P>
   All this comes at a time when the Yankees have the league's best
record, but remain uncertain who will pitch in the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Although Roger Clemens pitched eight scoreless innings Friday
against Seattle, the five-time Cy Young Award winner has won two
straight only once. Hideki Irabu hadn't lost since May 25 before
getting routed Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   No chance: Mike Mussina's bid to win 20 games for the first time
in his career ended last Sunday when he took a Brook Fordyce line
drive off his pitching shoulder. He has eight starts to win five
more games, but there is enough discomfort in the shoulder to
wonder about future problems. ``At this point in the season,
considering where we are, there's no reason to push it,'' Mussina
said of his team, which is 21{ games back after losing its third
straight Friday night. Mussina, who said Wednesday he would miss
one and maybe two starts, has flirted with 20 two other times. He
had 16 victories in 1994 when a strike wiped out the final two
months of the season. In 1996, Mussina whiffed on four chances to
win his 20th.
</P>
<P>
   Staying healthy: Oakland's feel-good run at the AL wild-card
spot is happening despite a very busy trainers' room. John Jaha
(sore ribs) and Matt Stairs (knee) couldn't play earlier this week.
Veteran leaders Tony Phillips and Tim Raines already are gone for
the year. Perhaps most worrisome is right-hander Kevin Appier, who
pitched so well after coming over from Kansas City. Appier is
expected to make today's start against the White Sox in Chicago,
but he lasted just 32/3 innings last time out due to a sore right
leg. Any leg injury can throw off Appier's delicate mechanics,
which is troublesome for his surgically repaired right shoulder.
Appier was outstanding in his first two starts with the A's. But in
the past three he is 1-2 with an 8.34 ERA. He has allowed eight
homers in 301/3 innings after giving up 19 in 167 innings with the
Royals.
</P>
<P>
   Reborn Ranger: The Texas Rangers ran away with the Western
Division, but they never seem to have enough pitching to move
beyond the first round of the playoffs. But the resurgence of
right-hander Esteban Loaiza gives them a third solid starter after
Rick Helling. After a dreadful first half that included a stint on
the disabled list and a move to the bullpen, Loaiza is back in the
rotation and 6-0 with a 2.82 ERA in seven starts, including a 7-3
victory over the Yankees on Wednesday. The Rangers, who could face
the Yankees in the playoffs, have gotten 12 victories out of former
Dodger Mike Morgan, but he is 1-2 with a 10.80 ERA in his last five
starts.
</P>
<P>
   Twins hurting: The Minnesota Twins rebounded for two straight
wins late last week, but using 17 rookies this season often has
left manager Tom Kelly angry and frustrated. The Boston Red Sox did
not arrive in Minneapolis on Monday until 5 a.m. after experiencing
plane trouble. They had a four-game losing streak and canceled
batting practice. Then they went out and beat the Twins, who struck
out 11 times and stranded 12 baserunners, nine in scoring position.
``I hope the fans don't take it too personally, but it was awful,''
Kelly said. ``They ought to get their money back.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-28-99 2028EDT &QL; 
