<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-28 21:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2993 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-FBN-GALLOWAY-COLUMN-T     08-28 0785
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-GALLOWAY-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DON'T PANIC, COWBOYS, SEASON STARTS SEPT. 12
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY GALLOWAY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Not yet. It's not time. Stay calm. Don't join the panic.
</P>
<P>
   As pathetic as the Cowboys have looked in the exhibition season,
it doesn't matter. Why? Because it doesn't matter.
</P>
<P>
   Never allow yourself to be mistaken for someone who actually
cares about preseason football. It's uncool.
</P>
<P>
   On your schedule, circle Sept. 12 in Washington. Anything that
happens on that date, and the 15 games beyond that date, feel free
to react accordingly.
</P>
<P>
   If it's consistently bad for the Cowboys, panic is OK. If it's
real bad, then go ahead and take advantage of the new open-flame
policy for tailgating on the Texas Stadium parking lots. Throw
yourself into a fire.
</P>
<P>
   But for now, be relaxed. Be like Jerry Jones.
</P>
<P>
   ``There seems to be a lot of concern about our team, but I don't
share that,'' the owner said Friday at Valley Ranch. ``I look more
at what's gone right for us than what's gone wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   It wouldn't exactly be un-Jerry-like for him to ignore football
reality, but Jones has a point here.
</P>
<P>
   In the three exhibition losses thus far, the highlights have
been, well, brief. And coach Chan Gailey is hoping all that changes
tonight when Denver visits Texas Stadium. The first half, and maybe
part of the third quarter, will be a full dress rehearsal for the
regular season opener, Sept. 12. This is the only exhibition game
where meaningful applies.
</P>
<P>
   But thus far, the Cowboys' messy preseason has had more to do
with who doesn't play as who does. Injuries have caused a multitude
of loose ends that remain untied. Gailey keeps saying, ``we're not
where we want to be, but we've still got time to get there.''
Maybe, maybe not. The answer, however, won't come for another
couple of weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the team's medical staff is more important than the
coaching staff.
</P>
<P>
   Over the last year, the Cowboys have added eight veteran
newcomers, hoping they could overcome those three draft wipeouts of
the mid-'90s. For example, Jones said Friday, ``Alonzo Spellman, if
he works out like we think he will, can be what we wanted Shante
\RCarver\S to be.''
</P>
<P>
   But the three key free agents from last season _ Ernie Mills,
Chris Warren and Everett McIver _ all were sidelined with injuries
in '98. McIver finally returns to the field tonight at offensive
guard, but Warren is once again a major health worry. As as
nickel-package back and Emmitt Smith's caddie, Warren figured
prominently in Gailey's offensive plans. For now, that's on hold.
</P>
<P>
   Jones outdid himself for this season in bringing in experienced
help. But one of those players, free-agent linebacker Quentin
Coryatt, might never play a down here due to yet another injury
(''I'm worried,'' Jones acknowledged). On the plus side, receiver
Rocket Ismail finally finds the field tonight after missing the
first three games with a training camp injury.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys traded for receiver James McKnight, planning to twin
his speed with Ismail's, but McKnight blew a knee early in training
camp. He will be back in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``I agree that injuries have caused question marks,'' said
Jones, ``but we have offset our negatives with the positives. Many
of our positives are just starting to surface.''
</P>
<P>
   Such as?
</P>
<P>
   Tight end David LaFleur, who figures into the offensive package
much more than Gailey admits, is back on schedule for the regular
season. LaFleur broke his ankle in a May minicamp.
</P>
<P>
   There's also the continuing recovery of Nine-Toed Deion. ``He's
another one right on schedule, maybe even for the opener,'' added
Jones, although he did admit Kevin Smith's ailing back leaves an
uncertainty in the cornerback rotation.
</P>
<P>
   ``McIver is returning at the right time, and maybe Chan won't
agree, but I'm not sure Ismail missing the first three
\Rpreseason\S games doesn't work to our advantage,'' said Jones.
``Rocket is fresh, and ready to go.''
</P>
<P>
   To hear Jones tell it, all those loose ends will be tied down by
Sept. 12.
</P>
<P>
   And although Jerry wouldn't and couldn't comment, there is also
new Valley Ranch speculation that Leon Lett might be receiving a
break from commissioner Paul Tagliabue. It seems very far-fetched
that Tags won't suspend Lett for any regular season games, but
that's the speculation.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, however, Lett remains absent while the Cowboys juggle
bodies in the middle of the defensive line.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've very optimistic over how everything is coming together,''
added Jones.
</P>
<P>
   It would be best not to join Jerry on the edge of that
particular cliff. But the time is also not right for any panic
plunges. Not yet.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-28-99 2103EDT &QL; 
