<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-BRONCOS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COWBOYS FACE BRONCOS AS PRESEASON TESTS CONTINUE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RAY BUCK 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   What better scenario for the Cowboys' dress rehearsal for the
1999 season than a preseason meeting against the two-time defending
champion Denver Broncos at Texas Stadium tonight?
</P>
<P>
   Here are the last two teams to win back-to-back Super Bowls and
leading candidates for Team of the '90s, who are now set to meet in
a nationally televised, next-to-last preseason game for both teams.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys are 0-3; the Broncos are 2-1. Kickoff is 7 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's important for us to have a good showing against
Denver,'' said Cowboys fullback Daryl Johnston, a member of all
three Super Bowl teams of the '90s for the Cowboys. ``We really
haven't put together anything consistently. We need something to
build on \Rnow\S ... it's time to start building some postive
momentum.''
</P>
<P>
   It's time indeed. The Sept. 12 season opener at Washington is
two weeks away.
</P>
<P>
   In three preseason starts so far, Troy Aikman and the Cowboys'
first-team offense have been on the field for the first quarter of
each game. They've had the ball for nine full possessions, and have
managed 10 points.
</P>
<P>
   They've had three turnovers (two Aikman interceptions and one
fumbled center exchange), and Johnston spared them a would-be
fourth when he recovered an Emmitt Smith fumble against New
England.
</P>
<P>
   They've had four penalties (two false starts, two holding), and
two more penalties were declined.
</P>
<P>
   Injuries are part of football. But the Cowboys have yet to have
their starting offense on the field for one snap. This week will be
different.
</P>
<P>
   Wide receiver Raghib ``Rocket'' Ismail and right guard Everett
McIver make their first preseason appearances, but now the Cowboys
will be without veteran Ernie Mills (strained hamstring) in the
four-wide receiver set.
</P>
<P>
   Ismail is coming off a slightly separated shoulder, which he
injured diving for a pass in practice Aug. 4, and McIver hasn't
suited up for a game since he underwent knee surgery last November.
</P>
<P>
   Mills' left hamstring bothered him early in camp, quieted down,
then flared up again during last weekend's loss at New England. The
nine-year veteran knows the importance of this game for a
struggling Cowboys offense, but he won't allow a dress rehearsal
pressure him into putting his season in jeopardy.
</P>
<P>
   Mills battled a similar hamstring injury to the same leg while
with Pittsburgh in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   ``I missed only one game that season,'' said Mills, ``but the
\Rinjury\S never completely healed until after the season. That
just makes me more conscious of the fact that I need to get it
right.''
</P>
<P>
   With Mills out, rookie Wane McGarity and vastly improved
second-year player Jeff Ogden will get more playing time with the
first team.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to take advantage of every opportunity,'' said
McGarity, who leads all Cowboys receivers with six receptions.
``Denver will have its first defense out there probably the whole
first half. We have to be ready to go against that.''
</P>
<P>
   Jason Tucker, MarTay Jenkins and John Washington will continue
to get long looks. All three have distinguished themselves, but
Tucker is the hot receiver. The former TCU player is trying to
force the coaches into keeping six receivers, not just five.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys' starting offensive line is intact for the first
time. McIver returns to right guard and will play 12 plays. Rookie
Solomon Page started at right guard in each of the first three
games.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Warren is still nursing a recurring groin injury that took
the 10-year running back away from camp for a week] to see a
specialist for treatment in Colorado Springs, Colo. Warren returned
to practice this week, but isn't sure how much he will play against
Denver.
</P>
<P>
   Plans to get Warren in the same backfield with Smith, so far
only shown in practice, are predicated on Warren's health.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because of guys missing \R with injuries\S, we really haven't
been able tell much about where we are,'' Aikman said. ``Hopefully,
we can keep everybody healthy during the season. I think if we're
able to do that, we'll have a pretty good football team offensively
this year.''
</P>
<P>
   Aikman said that continuity and timing are important elements to
attain in preseason, although coach Chan Gailey's offense doesn't
have the timing routes that the offense had when Ernie Zampese was
Cowboys offensive coordinator.
</P>
<P>
   ``Timing is alway important with the receivers,'' Aikman said,
``but probably not as important in this offense as what it was in
the previous offense. So getting out on the field and spending time
with the receivers probably isn't quite as critical, but it's
always important.''
</P>
<P>
   Aikman has been enthusiastic about the young receivers in camp,
saying that McGarity ``just needs to keep doing what he has been
doing ... and do it in games,'' and that Tucker ``has done
everything possible to make this team'' although that still may not
be enough when it comes down to numbers.
</P>
<P>
   ``\RTucker\S has made a lot of plays over the last six or seven
practices ... \Rand\S shown a real ability to make the tough
catches,'' said Aikman of Cincinnati's 1998 sixth-round pick (167th
overall) who was released on injury settlement last August, then
later cut from Green Bay's practice squad.
</P>
<P>
   What better scenario for so much to be determined than in the
Cowboys' first home preseason game, dress rehearsal, against the
two-time defending Super Bowl champs.
</P>
<P>
   Does this provide added pressure on the Cowboys in '99?
</P>
<P>
   ``Not really,'' said Aikman, ``there's enough pressure on us
every year.''
</P>
<P>
   And it starts up again at Texas Stadium tonight.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-28-99 2105EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
