<HEADLINE>
BRUINS OK DESPITE THIN, YOUNG LINE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Few things make offensive-line coach Mark Weber
happier than the new blocking sleds dotting the northeast corner of
Spaulding Field. But the play of UCLA's young linemen has Weber
smiling like a proud papa.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Bruins lack depth and experience, Weber believes
this is the most athletic group he's coached in three seasons at
UCLA. Yes, more athletic than last year's group, which featured
three All-Pacific-10 performers.
</P>
<P>
   Sophomore center Troy Danoff is more mobile than his
predecessor, Shawn Stuart. Freshman right guard Mike Saffer has the
quick feet, fluid stride and knee bend not found in Andy Meyers.
And freshman Blake Worley, from what he's shown so far, appears
worthy of succeeding Outland Trophy winners Jonathan Ogden and Kris
Farris at left tackle.
</P>
<P>
   ``Blake has excellent pass-blocking skills,'' Weber said. ``He's
ahead of most redshirt freshmen, but he has a ways to go. All the
young guys do, and that's why we're giving them so many repetitions
in practice.''
</P>
<P>
   Weber has no choice. In the last year, he's lost seven linemen:
Stuart and Meyers graduated; Farris bolted for the NFL; Jeff Wright
and Scott Wiegand quit; David Wilford failed out; and Steve Morgan
switched to defense.
</P>
<P>
   Add the season-ending shoulder injury to reserve Josh Webb and
the two-game suspensions of Oscar Cabrera and Jim Ghezzi, and the
Bruins have just eight healthy linemen. They're one injury _ or
heat-related illness _ from using true freshman Bryce Bohlander,
who was expected to redshirt.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've talked about it,'' Saffer said. ``Coach Weber told us
not to worry about who we've lost and just do what we can to get
ready for the opener. If we can get through the first two games,
then we get Oscar and Jim back and we'll be OK.''
</P>
<P>
   His turn, finally: Danoff played just 60 snaps as Stuart's
backup last season, but the coaches were impressed enough to hand
him the starting job for the next three seasons. So far, he's
everything they expected.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stuart said many times that Troy was going to be much better
than he ever was,'' Weber said. ``Troy spent a lot of time with
Stu, trying to emulate him. In fact, he spent so much time with
Stu, the guys used to joke with him about it.''
</P>
<P>
   How they stand: The Bruins will face Boise State with Worley at
left tackle, senior Matt Phelan replacing Cabrera at left guard,
Danoff at center, Saffer at right guard and steady junior Brian
Polak at right tackle.
</P>
<P>
   Ed Anderson is the third guard. Tony Ippolito is the backup
center and, if needed, the fourth guard.
</P>
<P>
   Micah Webb is the third tackle. If needed, Bohlander's ready as
the No. 4 tackle.
</P>
<P>
   ``It'd be nice to be able to redshirt both freshmen,'' Weber
said of Bohlander and guard Shane Lehmann. ``But we're getting them
ready like we'll need them to play. It's such a big adjustment from
high school, not only physically but mentally.''
</P>
<P>
   Change of pace: The Bruins gathered Saturday at 10 a.m. for a
pre-practice film session. When it ended, UCLA coach Bob Toledo
canceled practice and let the players watch the Arizona-Penn State
game. There's no practice today, either. Toledo hopes the relaxing
weekend will energize his weary players, who don't have a bye until
Nov. 6.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-28-99 2116EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990828.0244 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-28 21:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3003 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a BC-ALABAMA-POLL-HNS &LR;      08-28 0975
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALABAMA-POLL-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
ALABAMA REPUBLICANS REWARD KEYES FOR SHOWING UP AT STRAW POLL THAT
MOST CANDIDATES SKIPPED
<TEXT>
<P>
   By CRAGG HINES &QL;
</P>
<P>
   C. 1999 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Houston Chronicle &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BIRMINGHAM, Ala. _ Hell hath no fury like a straw poll scorned.
</P>
<P>
   None of the major Republican presidential contenders bothered to
come Saturday for a nonbinding preference vote sponsored by the
Alabama GOP, so more than half the 1,700 party faithful, who paid
$35 a person to participate, cast their ballots for two lagging
candidates who did show up.
</P>
<P>
   Former diplomat Alan Keyes, a fiery conservative orator, won
with 29 percent of the vote, edging Sen. Orrin Hatch, R-Utah, who
had 27 percent. Neither is seen as a major force in the Republican
race.
</P>
<P>
   Among the absent candidates, Gov. George W. Bush of Texas ran
far ahead of the pack. His 25 percent of the vote was more than
three times that for the next nearest no-show.
</P>
<P>
   Even as the voting continued at the Birmingham-Jefferson
Convention Complex, Alabama Republican Chairman Winton Blount III
guessed that Bush would win. Blount might not have voiced that view
if he had talked with voters as they filed out of the curtained-off
polling area.
</P>
<P>
   ``I voted for Orrin Hatch because of his respect for Alabama by
coming,'' said Betty Botts, a Pike County housewife in a sequined
stars-and-stripes vest. Botts said she was not firmly committed in
the race for the Republican presidential nomination but liked Bush
a lot.
</P>
<P>
   Even Ginger Austin, who was wearing two Bush buttons, said she
voted for Hatch ``just because he came. People who came today ought
to have a little boost.''
</P>
<P>
   But Austin, a long-time Republican activist from Union Springs,
expressed confidence that Bush, the national polling leader,
ultimately will be the GOP nominee: ``I'm not worried about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, some Bush backers in Alabama, who had been confident of
winning the straw poll even without their candidate present, were
stung by the result, with one complaining the campaign's high
command ``didn't want to do anything.''
</P>
<P>
   After Keyes, Hatch and Bush, the order of finish was
conservative activist Gary Bauer, 7.26 percent; former Cabinet
official Elizabeth Dole, 4.16 percent; magazine publisher Steve
Forbes, 2.52 percent; conservative commentator Pat Buchanan, 2.46
percent; former Vice President Dan Quayle, 1.29 percent; Sen. John
McCain, R-Ariz., 1.23 percent; and Angel Rocker, an education
reform advocate from Florida who also spoke to the GOP session,
0.35 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Alabama Republicans, looking for a little national attention,
whipped up the straw poll after the state's Democrat-dominated
Legislature refused to move the presidential primary from June to a
date earlier in the campaign calendar. Most candidates, however,
refused to play along with the upstart Southern contest, preferring
to concentrate their organizing and funding on the hard-fought Iowa
straw poll two weeks ago _ which Bush won.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Neeley, executive director of the Alabama GOP, sought to
invest the outcome of his state's exercise with some significance,
arguing: ``It shows we've got a competitive race.'' But even local
media have made light of the homegrown GOP effort. The Birmingham
Post-Herald on Friday set the stage for the event by calling it a
Republican ``pep rally'' and offering this headline: ``Analysts:
Results not significant.''
</P>
<P>
   The campaigns of Keyes and Hatch are so thin on the ground that
they apparently did not have aides present after the vote to
inflate any significance of the result. The Bush folks, however,
were omnipresent and ready to spin out a tale of ``victory.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There's one candidate who did nothing and still got a great
vote,'' said Alabama Lt. Gov. Steve Windom, a state Bush campaign
co-chairman. ``This doesn't change the fact that all the polling in
Alabama shows Governor Bush is in a commanding lead.''
</P>
<P>
   The most recent scientific sampling of political sentiment in
the state, conducted last month for the Mobile Register by the
University of South Alabama, found that among Republicans, Bush
held a 65 percentage point lead (71-6 percent) over his nearest
opponent, Elizabeth Dole.
</P>
<P>
   In that survey, Bush led Vice President Al Gore, the leading
Democratic contender, among the general electorate in Alabama by
61-32 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Hatch's campaign had phoned delegates and mailed them
literature, said Ragan Ingram, a Windom aide.
</P>
<P>
   R.C. Cox, a Republican activist from suburban Birmingham, said
Keyes' appeal was based on both the fact that he showed up and his
strong conservative message.
</P>
<P>
   Keyes was introduced by Roy Moore, the Etowah County circuit
judge who became a hero of the religious right-wing after posting
the Ten Commandments in his courtroom.
</P>
<P>
   Keyes repeatedly had the conservative audience hooting approval
of his attacks on abortion, the federal income tax and ``educrats''
whom he seemed to link to the ``soul-less evil that is stalking our
schools.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd rather be elected to nothing than stand for nothing,''
Keyes declared as he urged delegates from the state's 67 counties
to ``vote your conscience as God would have you vote.''
</P>
<P>
   In the great tradition of political orators, Keyes raised one of
his opponents' problems by questioning why it had become an issue.
Keyes brought up the recent attention paid to Bush's refusal to say
if he used illegal drugs as a young man _ but turned to the issue
by chiding the news media.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have been more willing to talk about something, as far as
I can tell, that (has) no basis in a specific allegation or
credible allegation,'' Keyes said. ``They've been more willing to
spread that all over the newspapers about G.W. Bush than they were
to examine the witnesses and facts and the evidence against Bill
Clinton.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-28-99 2117EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990828.0245 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-28 21:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3005 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a BC-ENDANGERED_RIVER_AZR &LR;      08-28 2123
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ENDANGERED_RIVER_AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SE ARIZONA POPULATION RISE THREATENING SAN PEDRO'S EXISTENCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By KATHLEEN INGLEY  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SIERRA VISTA, Ariz._ One of the last free-flowing rivers in the
Southwest, the San Pedro, with its rare stands of cottonwoods and
willows, could be sucked dry.
</P>
<P>
   The growing population of southeastern Arizona is pumping out
groundwater faster than snow and rain can replace it. As the water
table falls, the river may no longer run year-round.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bottom line is they're using more water than nature is
providing, and the river is going to go dry,'' said Robert MacNish,
a hydrology professor at the University of Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   The lush corridor of the San Pedro runs north like a green
ribbon from its headwaters in Mexico until it empties 140 miles
later into the Gila River. An oasis in an arid land, it is among
the biological treasures of North America, with one of the largest
varieties of creatures on Earth. Millions of migrating birds depend
on the San Pedro for food and shelter.
</P>
<P>
   Nearby Fort Huachuca and Sierra Vista are trying to take the
pressure off the river with everything from flushless urinals to
putting treated wastewater back into the ground.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our goal is to balance our economic growth with protecting the
river, recognizing it is part of the reason people come here,''
said Chuck Potucek, Sierra Vista city manager.
</P>
<P>
   But critics say that the tactics are too little too late, and
they argue that unfettered development in Cochise County is
undermining the gains.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you look through the smoke screen, you see the guaranteed
demise of the river,'' said Robin Silver, a Phoenix doctor and
environmentalist who owns property along the San Pedro.
</P>
<P>
   On a summer morning, as thunderheads piled higher and higher on
the horizon, Holly Richter walked gingerly along the slick, muddy
banks of the river, near Sierra Vista. A spate of rain had sent tan
water swirling through bulrushes, carrying the new sediment crucial
for cottonwoods and willows to sprout.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looks like cappuccino,'' observed Richter, a biologist with
the Nature Conservancy, an environmental group that buys land for
conservation.
</P>
<P>
   A frog hopped past her feet, grebes paddled upstream and
countless other birds, hidden in the trees, twittered and trilled.
</P>
<P>
   The key to keeping this complex world alive, said Richter, is
maintaining the stream flow at the driest times of the year, from
April through June.
</P>
<P>
   If the underground water table near the San Pedro drops too low,
the river will cease to flow above the surface and, like other
depleted rivers in Arizona, will flow only beneath a dry riverbed,
if at all.
</P>
<P>
   And competition for the river's water is increasing.
</P>
<P>
   On the Mexican side of the border, people are pumping water for
household use, farming and mining.
</P>
<P>
   There's less agriculture on the U.S. side, but the population is
growing faster. Cochise County, through which the San Pedro runs,
has 120,000 people, a 22 percent jump from 1990. All their water
comes from wells.
</P>
<P>
   The result is a bit like starting off with a fat checking
account. You deposit money every month, but write checks for more
than you put in. You can operate in the red for years, but someday,
your checks will bounce.
</P>
<P>
   Environmentalists say the river's bank statement is looking
ominous. Gauges on the San Pedro show that flows during the dry
season have declined steadily since 1940.
</P>
<P>
   Each year, by one estimate, wells around the river are pumping
7,000 more acre-feet of water out of the ground than nature puts
back in, enough to fill 3,000 Olympic-size swimming pools.
</P>
<P>
   Hydrologist MacNish predicts that in the next three or four
years, the river will flow intermittently rather than year-round in
the stretch around Arizona 90.
</P>
<P>
   That doesn't mean all the faucets will go dry in Cochise County.
Paradoxically, there's a huge supply of underground water.
</P>
<P>
   The problem comes from a complex bit of hydrology. As a well
uses up more water than nature can replenish, the entire water
table doesn't drop at once. Instead, a ``cone of depression''
forms: The water disappears across a wide area near the surface,
tapering down to a small point by the base of the well.
</P>
<P>
   Think of drinking a flavored Sno-Cone drink through a straw.
You'll notice that the colored liquid disappears from the ice at
the top, while you're still sipping plenty from the bottom.
</P>
<P>
   As the cones of depression spread out, they'll intercept the
river's water long before any consumers run short.
</P>
<P>
   The push to keep the San Pedro alive is spurring a dizzying
number of studies, conferences, reports and partnerships. Many
questions remain about how the river system works, especially in
Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   But there are basically just two approaches to saving the San
Pedro: Use less water or put water back into the ground.
</P>
<P>
   Under those simple headings, there are dozens of ideas.
</P>
<P>
   Congress took a big step in 1988 by establishing the San Pedro
Riparian National Conservation Area, which protects a 40-mile
stretch of river from near the Mexican border, north to St. David.
</P>
<P>
   There's no more farming or grazing in the area. That means less
groundwater pumping and more native plants, which reduce runoff and
allow more rain to seep into the earth.
</P>
<P>
   In June, the federal government announced a push to buy more
land and water rights in the area, plus a partnership with Mexico
to study and protect the San Pedro.
</P>
<P>
   Sierra Vista, the largest city in the area, and Fort Huachuca,
the mainstay of employment, are both promoting conservation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It costs a whole lot less not to use it in the first place,''
said Gretchen Kent, environmental policy coordinator at the Army
fort.
</P>
<P>
   Tactics there range from strict irrigation limits at base
housing to low-flow plumbing fixtures. Many of the men's rooms have
waterless urinals, which use a chemical trap in the drain.
</P>
<P>
   ``At a gallon and a half a flush, it adds up,'' Kent said.
</P>
<P>
   Sierra Vista has an aggressive public education program called
``Waterwise,'' City Manager Potucek said. It's been effective
enough for one local water company to notice usage has gone down,
he added.
</P>
<P>
   Voters there also passed a referendum authorizing the city to
buy the two private companies, both owned by developers, that
provide most of the city's water. If that happened, Potucek says
the city would get a better handle on water use, including the
possibility of mandatory conservation.
</P>
<P>
   For now, when the two developers want to build, ``they just
extend their own waterlines,'' Potucek said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The city's not really a player,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   On the supply side, the main strategy is recharge _ finding ways
to get treated wastewater and more storm water to sink into the
aquifer.
</P>
<P>
   Fort Huachuca, for instance, is putting wire baskets filled with
rocks, known as gabions, into washes to slow down and capture storm
water.
</P>
<P>
   Sierra Vista is planning a big project to recharge wastewater,
although a hang-up in federal funding has delayed it.
</P>
<P>
   Potucek also sees promise in an ambitious proposal for recharge
projects at the base of the Huachuca Mountains, with the goal of
capturing more storm runoff. For now, though, it's unclear how much
such a project would accomplish and who would pay for it.
</P>
<P>
   Silver, the environmentalist, sees one fatal flaw in all the
conservation and recharge projects.
</P>
<P>
   ``They do nothing in terms of solving the big picture,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The culprit is excess, uncontrolled growth.''
</P>
<P>
   Ane, he added, the main force driving it is Fort Huachuca.
</P>
<P>
   As conservation chairman of the Center for Biological Diversity
of Tucson, Silver has helped file a series of lawsuits seeking to
force the base to do a full environmental impact statement showing
the cumulative effects of its operations.
</P>
<P>
   His biggest complaint: Although Fort Huachuca has cut staff on
base, it has let out local contracts that employ hundreds of
people.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't matter if they're conserving some water on the
base,'' Silver said, ``if all these folks go home and water their
lawns.''
</P>
<P>
   A review of the base's impact would show that it should either
shrink its operations dramatically, Silver argues, or the local
authorities should control water pumping.
</P>
<P>
   Other environmental groups take a less militant view. Richter,
of the Nature Conservancy, figures that even if Fort Huachuca
closed today, ``the water budget would not be balanced.''
</P>
<P>
   People are drawn to southeastern Arizona to retire and to take
jobs unrelated to the military. Tourism, much of it focused on bird
watching, is a $6 million-a-year local business.
</P>
<P>
   ``Growth is not going to go away,'' Richter said. ``We need to
use our best sicence and our best technology to allow the growth
the community desires.''
</P>
<P>
   She sees hope in cooperative efforts among government, citizens
and advocacy groups.
</P>
<P>
   Richter also duels with growth advocates, who object that the
plants along the San Pedro guzzle more water than any development,
accounting for half of local water use.
</P>
<P>
   That may be true, Richter said, but it's circular logic.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be silly to cut down the trees to save the water,''
she said, ``if the reason we're saving the water is the trees.''
</P>
<P>
   Local officials complain that other parts of Arizona are growing
faster, using more water and getting less criticism.
</P>
<P>
   ``The amount of water used in the San Pedro Valley is about what
is used on the golf courses in Scottsdale,'' said Rick Koehler, a
hydrologist for Cochise County.
</P>
<P>
   Not that he doesn't think the river is in peril. But Koehler is
optimistic about a combination of tactics that local governments
agree on: water recharge, promoting or requiring water-efficient
development and planning open space.
</P>
<P>
   So far, there's little appetite for putting tight reins on
growth.
</P>
<P>
   Cochise County's Board of Supervisors ``has taken a posture that
responsible development for the area should occur,'' county
Administrator Jody Klein said.
</P>
<P>
   In July, Sierra Vista's City Council approved a land annexation
and a controversial 6,400-home project to be built there. Opponents
last week turned in petitions to put the issue to a vote.
</P>
<P>
   City spokeswoman Marie Hansen said the development would have
gone ahead with yet more homes and fewer conditions if the property
had remained in the county. The subdivision won't be built out for
years, she added, because Sierra Vista, with 40,000 people, is
growing more slowly than most Arizona cities. Nevertheless, it has
grown 21 percent since 1990.
</P>
<P>
   Southeastern Arizona is home to some staunch advocates of
private property rights, who are skeptical about whether the San
Pedro has a problem at all.
</P>
<P>
   Rachel Thomas, president of Arizona People for the USA, has
lived in the area for 35 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``When it rains, that river's got water in it,'' she said.
``When it doesn't, it doesn't.''
</P>
<P>
   Harold Vangilder, a Sierra Vista councilman, contends that the
steps taken so far to mend the San Pedro are already succeeding.
</P>
<P>
   ``The river is in the best state it's ever been since the
riparian area was established in 1988,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Despite all the talk about water in southeastern Arizona, the
state has not declared it an Active Management Area, where pumping
of groundwater is restricted.
</P>
<P>
   Some environmentalists say the state is shirking its duty.
</P>
<P>
   But Steve Olson, spokesman for the Arizona Department of Water
Resources, said an AMA isn't justified because there's no evidence
of regionwide declines in the water table.
</P>
<P>
   And he argues that the AMA authority is too broad to help the
San Pedro.
</P>
<P>
   ``To maintain the flow in the river,'' Olson said, ``you're
going to need some very targeted controls on groundwater pumping.''
The spacing and location of wells could be critical, while the AMA
is aimed at ensuring an overall water supply.
</P>
<P>
   The threat to the San Pedro is no phantom to Jack Pfister,
former chief of the Salt River Project water and electric utility.
He was co-chairman of a panel that looked at the river for the
Commission for Environmental Cooperation, a group that's an
outgrowth of the North American Free Trade Agreement.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can peer into the future by looking at what's happened in
Arizona's past,'' he said. ``Every time we have let development
occur near a riparian area or a free-flowing stream, we end up
drying it up.''
</P>
<P>
   Cochise County must find ways to offset or reduce water use,
Pfister said.
</P>
<P>
   Otherwise, he can show what's ahead: Just look at the barren bed
of the Salt River in Phoenix. &QL; 
Kathleen Ingley can be reached at (602) 444-8171 or at
kathleen.ingley(at)pni.com. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
