<HEADLINE>
PACIFIC CLASSIC COULD BE BIG BOOST FOR GENERAL CHALLENGE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Will the Pacific Classic be remembered for the
horse who wins or the horses who didn't run?
</P>
<P>
   That's up to General Challenge and jockey David Flores.
</P>
<P>
   If any excitement remains in Del Mar's $1 million race, weakened
by injuries to a succession of favorites, it resides in the
muscular body of General Challenge, the flashy but flighty gelding
who faces older horses for the first time today.
</P>
<P>
   A victory would _ if it's done in style _ revive the
``rising-star'' talk that followed his Santa Anita Derby victory in
April.
</P>
<P>
   A victory would make him the first 3-year-old to win the Pacific
Classic _ or even finish in the money _ since Best Pal won the
first running in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   And a victory would be very popular at Del Mar, since he is bred
and owned by track chairman John Mabee and his wife Betty, who also
bred and owned Best Pal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Best Pal was a little ahead of General Challenge in
development at the same point in their careers,'' John Mabee said
this week. ``(But) General Challenge has greater potential.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, it's unfulfilled potential.
</P>
<P>
   After winning the Santa Anita Derby by 3{ lengths, he joined the
Mabees' filly Excellent Meeting in the Kentucky Derby, and together
they were favored on the morning line. General Challenge ran into
severe traffic in the first turn and finished 11th.
</P>
<P>
   Skipping the rest of the Triple Crown, he came home and stepped
down in class to win the Affirmed Handicap at Hollywood Park. Back
in the big leagues in Hollywood's Swaps Stakes, he was out-gamed at
1-2 odds by habitual runner-up Cat Thief.
</P>
<P>
   Handicappers who'd questioned General Challenge's brain power _
he's easily rattled by crowds and on-track adversity _ started to
doubt his heart as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's still got something to prove in that department to me,''
Mabee said.
</P>
<P>
   Today he'll start from the potentially troublesome post 1 as he
tries 1\ miles for the second time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not happy with the post position,'' Flores said.
</P>
<P>
   To stay in the clear early, Flores might have to shoot for the
lead. That would mean out-breaking Malek and Alex Solis, who start
from post 7.
</P>
<P>
   But trainer Bob Baffert said he'll tell Flores to ``let him lope
away from (the gate).''
</P>
<P>
   Malek is an 8-5 morning-line favorite over 2-1 General
Challenge.
</P>
<P>
   When the Pacific Classic was made the climactic event in the
inaugural, 11-race ``NTRA Champions on Fox'' series for 3-year-olds
and up, Del Mar salivated at the thought of hosting Horse of the
Year contenders from across the nation.
</P>
<P>
   But series leader Behrens stayed in the East to prep for the
$4million Breeders' Cup Classic Nov. 6 at Gulfstream Park near
Miami, his connections passing up a chance to pocket a $330,000
bonus by winning the Pacific Classic. And injuries sent 1998
Belmont Stakes winner Victory Gallop and record-setting speedster
Mazel Trick into retirement and '98 Kentucky Derby and Preakness
winner Real Quiet to the sidelines for the rest of '99.
</P>
<P>
   Remaining is a field of California-based horses, with only
General Challenge, Malek and Baffert-trained River Keen having won
stakes on U.S. dirt tracks. Unbelievably, Malek is the only NTRA
series points-earner in the race.
</P>
<P>
   If Malek wins, he'll receive a series bonus of $140,000 as well
as $600,000 of the Pacific Classic purse, pushing his season total
to $2,005,570 and trailing only Kentucky Derby and Preakness winner
Charismatic in '99 earnings.
</P>
<P>
   But none of that would thrill a crowd expected to top 25,000.
Six-year-old Malek's frequent second- and third-place finishes _ in
races as prestigious as the Dubai World Cup _ have given him a
reputation as a high-priced trial horse.
</P>
<P>
   Malek's big victory came in the '98 Santa Anita Handicap
remembered for barnmate Gentlemen's shocking last-place finish and
Silver Charm's race-eve injury. A win today might get the same
``yeah, but...'' reaction.
</P>
<P>
   It's up to younger, more promising General Challenge to save the
day for Del Mar.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
