<SLUG> BC-RAC-TRAVERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE BELMONT STAKES WINNER AND RUNNER-UP DUEL ANEW IN THE SUMMERTIME
DERBY  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOSEPH DURSO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SARATOGA SPRINGS, N.Y. _ Lemon Drop Kid supplied a smashing
encore to his victory in the Belmont Stakes Saturday when he won
the 130th running of the Travers and raced to the head of this
season's class of 3-year-olds.
</P>
<P>
   The bay son of Kingmambo actually rewrote the climax to his June
script in which he held off the long shot Vision and Verse by a
head before a record Belmont crowd of 85,818. This time, running
against three of his Triple Crown rivals and four other colts with
championship ambitions, he finished three-quarters of a length in
front of Vision and Verse before a record Travers crowd of 51,371.
</P>
<P>
   Then came the warriors: Menifee, the 9-5 favorite, got trapped
on the inside and ran third in front of his stablemate, Ecton Park,
while the star of the D. Wayne Lukas barn, Cat Thief, finished
seventh with breathing problems.
</P>
<P>
   So, in million-dollar landmark races less than three months
apart, Lemon Drop Kid staked his claim to the leadership of the
class. It was once held by Charismatic, who won the Kentucky Derby
and the Preakness before running third in the Belmont, which he
finished with a fractured leg that forced his retirement.
</P>
<P>
   And Lemon Drop Kid's jockey, Jose Santos, was quick to assert
the claim.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is one of the best, if not the best 3-year-old,'' Santos
said. ``He won the Belmont, beat Charismatic, and now he's won the
Travers. Maybe now he'll get the respect he deserves.''
</P>
<P>
   Scotty Schulhofer, who trains Lemon Drop Kid for Jeanne Vance
and her husband, Laddie, remembered that his horse had run second
to Ecton Park in the mud in the Jim Dandy Stakes earlier this month
and said he had been sweating out the weather here all week. But
the rain left, the sun returned and the track was rated fast by
post time.
</P>
<P>
   ``He doesn't like running on a sloppy track,'' Schulhofer said,
``and I was afraid for a while this morning that we might have an
off track. But he still has a lot to do. We'll see how he does the
next two or three races. He'll have to beat Behrens and some of
those older horses.''
</P>
<P>
   The race, celebrated as ``the summertime Kentucky Derby,''
provides a second chance for horses who do not win the Kentucky
Derby. It also sets up a ranking for 3-year-olds as they head into
the homestretch of a season that ends in November with the $4
million Breeders' Cup Classic.
</P>
<P>
   And it prompts expressions of regret by the losing trainers and
jockeys.
</P>
<P>
   Jerry Bailey, the rider on Unbridled Jet and the nation's
leading jockey, finished last in all three stakes on Saturday's
program, then said after the Travers, ``I had good position, but
when I pulled the trigger, Unbridled Jet didn't shoot.''
</P>
<P>
   Elliott Walden, who trains Menifee and Ecton Park _ who won the
Haskell and Jim Dandy at different tracks on the same day earlier
this month _ lamented the slow pace of the Travers. ``When they go
that slow, it's hard to make up ground,'' he said. ``Lemon Drop Kid
ran a great race, and we just didn't get lucky. Menifee ran well,
but he just couldn't get out from the inside, and that might have
cost him the race.''
</P>
<P>
   Lemon Drop Kid stalked the slow pace set by Cat Thief, running
third for the first mile. Then, as they turned for home, Santos
nudged him up to second place behind Vision and Verse and they
dueled the rest of the way while Menifee and Ecton Park gave their
finishing kicks, too little, too late.
</P>
<P>
   Lemon Drop Kid ran the mile and a quarter in 2:02, paid $9.30
for a $2 bet to win and earned $600,000 for the second time in
three months.
</P>
<P>
   The stage for the Travers was set by two other stakes with
all-star casts, the King's Bishop and the Fourstardave. And
Forestry, who ran third behind Menifee and Cat Thief in the
Haskell, won the $200,000 King's Bishop by a length and a half
after a dazzling speed duel with Five Star Day, with Successful
Appeal and Vicar next.
</P>
<P>
   The winner, owned by Marie and Aaron Jones and trained by Bob
Baffert with Chris Antley riding, ran the seven furlongs in 1:21,
record time for the stakes, and returned $5.60 to win for a $2 bet.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't want to run him in the Travers,'' Baffert said.
``He's not ready for that. But that was world-class speed you saw
today.''
</P>
<P>
   In the $150,000 Fourstardave, a mile and one-sixteenth on the
grass, Neil Howard's Commic Strip scored by 2{ lengths over Divide
and Conquer with Bomfim third.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-28-99 2158EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
