<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-28 22:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3013 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BKW-COMETS-SPARKS-HNS     08-28 0821
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKW-COMETS-SPARKS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Comets put home superiority to the test
<TEXT>
<P>
   By W.H. STICKNEY JR.
</P>
<P>
   Houston Chronicle
</P>
<P>
   Comets coach Van Chancellor isn't known for his reticence.
Thrust a microphone near his mouth or turn on the TV camera lights,
and he's liable to talk into the wee hours of the morning.
</P>
<P>
   But Chancellor was succinct Saturday describing the plight of
the Comets, who trail the Los Angeles Sparks 1-0 entering today's
Game 2 of the best-of-three WNBA Western Conference finals.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our whole season is tomorrow,'' he said. ``We're going to put
it all on the line. Every bit of it.''
</P>
<P>
   For three years, the Comets have defined what it means to be the
best in the WNBA. Just mention ``two-time defending champion,'' and
the subject is clear.
</P>
<P>
   But for the second time in as many summers, the Comets are
facing a backs-to-the-wall situation in the playoffs. Lose to the
Sparks for the fourth time this summer, and there is no tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
   But for the Comets, there couldn't be better walls to be pressed
against than those of Compaq Center, site of today's game and, if
necessary, Game 3 on Monday night. Over the last two years, the
Comets have posted a 32-2 record at home (including the playoffs),
by far the best in the WNBA.
</P>
<P>
   ``Really?'' forward Tina Thompson, said. ``That's pretty
impressive, huh? I didn't know that.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think you find, I guess, a state of comfort at home. It's
definitely fun being at home. You get to sleep in your own bed;
you're in a relaxed and familiar situation. We have our fans behind
us, and they're great.''
</P>
<P>
   It was by virtue of their 26-6 regular-season record that the
Comets earned home-court advantage throughout the playoffs. It was
clearly the difference last year when the Comets ran up a 27-3
mark, opened at Phoenix in the WNBA Finals and fell behind 1-0 to
the Mercury. Upon coming home, they staged a comeback and repeated
as champs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we understand the situation we're in,'' forward Sheryl
Swoopes said. ``We know if we lose we're finished, and there's no
chance for the three-peat.
</P>
<P>
   ``And right now, that's not even what we're really focusing on.
We just want to come out and play hard and win the game. I think if
we win, we will be very confident in feeling like we can win again
on Monday. But the most important thing is that we stay focused
(today) and play really well, tough and hard for 40 minutes.''
</P>
<P>
   In finishing 15-1 at Compaq Center this year, the Comets won
their last 12 regular-season games at home, a league record, and
are 5-0 all-time there in postseason games.
</P>
<P>
   The expansion Orlando Miracle planted the only blemish on this
year's home record with a 68-64 win June 18 that kept the Comets
from an 8-0 start, which would have been an all-time WNBA best.
</P>
<P>
   But playing in Compaq Center never has been a pleasant task for
the Sparks. In eight visits, including two this season, LA never
has beaten the Comets here.
</P>
<P>
   But there's a first time for everything. And Los Angeles coach
Orlando Woolridge will lead a confident, loose group onto the court
today.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have nothing to lose,'' said center Lisa Leslie, who
torched the Comets for 23 points in the Sparks' 75-60 victory at
Los Angeles on Thursday night. ``They're the defending champions.
Nobody expects us to win anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps. But on three occasions in LA this season, the Sparks
have proved the Comets aren't invincible.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Chancellor says it won't be for lack of confidence if the
Comets fall a fourth time to LA.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll always believe we're going to win,'' he said. ``I think
what we did Thursday night was give LA a big boost of confidence.''
</P>
<P>
   The Comets were ineffective in all phases of the game. The
Comets shot poorly (41.2 percent), were outrebounded 30-21,
committed 18 turnovers and twice fell behind by as many as 17
points in the second half.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that was the one game that everyone was just
emotionally drained,'' said guard Cynthia Cooper, who was 4-for-16
from the floor and scored 12 points, 10 below her average. ``We
were emotionally drained from everything that had been going on all
season, and certainly in the last couple of weeks (surrounding the
death of Kim Perrot).
</P>
<P>
   ``We were just flat. Mentally and physically, we were not there.
That coupled with the fact that they (the Sparks) played well.''
</P>
<P>
   Woolridge is bracing for a potential haymaker from the Comets in
response.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're the type team that takes it personally when you beat
them,'' he said. ``We know we're going to face their best effort.
And we have to raise the bar. We have to play twice, three times as
good as we did in LA, because they're tough to beat here.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, said Leslie, if there's pressure, it's on the Comets.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're the defending champion. We're just here to win a
ballgame,'' she said. ``Simple as that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
