<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HILLARY-SPEECH-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTONS HUNT FOR A HOUSE AND CAMPAIGN FUNDS
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)
<TEXT>
<P>
   By NANCY MATHIS &QL;
</P>
<P>
   c. 1999
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Houston Chronicle &QL;
</P>
<P>
   HAUPPAGE, N.Y. _ At President Clinton's urging, New Yorkers
opened their checkbooks Saturday for first lady Hillary Rodham
Clinton and Democrats as a vacation gave way to campaign fund
raising in the Hamptons.
</P>
<P>
   The president joined top Democrats in making the most direct
appeals yet on behalf of his wife's unannounced, and unprecedented,
candidacy as the first lady herself maintained there is still work
to be done in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you want somebody that's thought about this stuff (issues)
and worked hard and always tried to do it for other people for 30
years, who has more heart, more intelligence, more ability and more
commitment than any person I have ever known ... then you ought to
send her to the Senate and give her a chance to serve,'' Clinton
told 300 well-heeled New Yorkers.
</P>
<P>
   Although Hillary Clinton has yet to declare her candidacy, her
Senate exploratory committee was sharing in the $300,000
fund-raising event at the East Hampton home of Washington lobbyist
Liz Robbins. The Democratic Party and the Democratic Senatorial
Campaign Committee also were each receiving a third of the
proceeds.
</P>
<P>
   It was the first fund-raising event held for the first lady in
which reporters were allowed to hear the remarks. Hillary Clinton
has held fund-raising events in New York, Texas and Massachusetts.
Today, the fashion designer Vera Wang will hold another
money-raising luncheon for her in the Hamptons. The president
intended to raise money for the Democratic Party at a late evening
event and at a dinner Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Robert Torricelli, D-N.J., chairman of the DSCC, said, ``We
need this woman in the United States Senate. We need her strength,
we need her intellect, we need her convictions.''
</P>
<P>
   There was little pretense that her ``exploration'' was still
under way. However, there still is no date for her formal
announcement.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm considering this because I really believe in public
service,'' the first lady said, adding that ``even after, yes, the
last six and a half years I still believe in public service.'' She
said she had long supported other people's campaigns ``and now I'm
stepping forth and asking you for your support and your help.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I like the progress we've made in the last six and a half
years and I want to be a part of continuing that,'' Hillary Clinton
said. But she also added there was still work to be done to spread
the economic prosperity to even the poorest Americans, to provide a
first-class education for all children and to ensure health care
for those who can't afford it.
</P>
<P>
   The president told the New Yorkers that he and Hillary Clinton
are still debating the policy issues of the day, just as they did
when the first met in 1971.
</P>
<P>
   He told them about a walk he and the first lady took Friday,
their last full day of vacation in Martha's Vineyard. ``I said, you
know, I hope you're not tired of this after all these years and she
said, `No, it's still very interesting to me.' She said, `You may
be a lot of things but you're not boring.' ''
</P>
<P>
   The crowd howled at the last line. Only months ago Clinton
survived an attempt to remove him from office, impeached for
denying a sexual affair with a young White House intern that he
eventually admitted. It was during the year-long sex scandal that
the first lady's popularity, enhanced perhaps by the image of a
suffering spouse, hit new highs and helped inspire her quest for
the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   The president also championed the cause of all Democratic office
seekers. ``I'm not running for anything, but I don't want to see
all this work we've done derailed. And I don't want to see all the
progress my country has made sacrificed. And believe me, there is
still a war going out there for the conscience, the soul and the
future of this country,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   The Clintons will continue their vacation when they leave Monday
for the Skaneateles, Finger Lakes resort near Syracuse.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, the first family resumed their hunt for a house in
Westchester County where the first lady wants to establish her
official residency. The Clintons own no property, accept for a
share of the first lady's mother's home in Arkansas.
</P>
<P>
   The family spent two hours looking over one four-story home in
Chappaqua, a five-bedroom, $1.7-million Georgian colonial. Bill
Clinton told reporters there had been no decision on a home
purchase.
</P>
<P>
   Asked what kind of home they were looking for, he said, ``some
place nice and airy that will make Hillary happy _ that's all I
want.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
