<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-BLUE-JAYS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RANGERS FIND POP IN CLUTCH TO BEAT BLUE JAYS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHNNY PAUL 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TORONTO _ Two-out, run-scoring base hits will demoralize an
opponent.
</P>
<P>
   See Blue Jays, Toronto, for the nearest Canadian example.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers _ thanks to a barrage of clutch, two-out hits _
moved 26 games above .500 for only the second time in the
franchise's 28-year history with yesterday's 9-7 victory at
Skydome.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers lowered the boom on left-hander David ``Boomer''
Wells by scoring seven runs in his four-inning appearance, and five
of those crossed the plate with two outs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those are big hits,'' said first baseman Rafael Palmeiro, who
drove in the Rangers' first-inning run with a two-out single that
scored second baseman Luis Alicea. ``It just demoralizes a team. I
know. I've been there when it's been done to us.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers kept doing it, and right-hander Aaron Sele
benefited. Sele (15-7) pitched six effective innings for the
victory and improved to 62-10 for his career when given five or
more runs of support.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers scored their fourth and Sele's magical fifth runs on
a two-out, second-inning home run by designated hitter Juan
Gonzalez, who deposited an 0-2 delivery from Wells into the Blue
Jays' left-field bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   Manager Johnny Oates turned to pitching coach Dick Bosman in the
visitors' first-base dugout.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, `Boz, the odds are in our favor,' '' Oates recalled.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez's two-run homer wrapped up the Rangers' four-run second
inning, but perhaps the most significant at-bat belonged to Rusty
Greer earlier in the frame. Ivan Rodriguez stranded Tom Goodwin and
Alicea at second and third base, respectively, with his second
strikeout in as many at-bats.
</P>
<P>
   That brought Greer to the plate in search of a momentum-changing
hit. Wells (12-9) worked the count in his favor and then lost his
advantage when Greer stroked a two-strike pitch into center field
for a two-run single.
</P>
<P>
   Those two-out, run-scoring base hits discourage opponents, who
are on the verge of escaping an inning unscathed with one more
pitch.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those are big for your ballclub, and it might take a little
air out of them,'' Greer said. ``I know I don't like to see two-out
base hits when I'm on defense.''
</P>
<P>
   Sele departed after the sixth inning with an 8-4 lead intact,
but the Blue Jays put a mild scare into the Rangers with their
ninth-inning uprising. Left-hander Jeff Fassero, acquired Friday
from the Seattle Mariners, surrendered three consecutive hits
without recording an out after pitching a scoreless eighth.
</P>
<P>
   Manager Johnny Oates summoned closer John Wetteland from the
bullpen after a run-scoring single by right fielder Shawn Green
pulled the Blue Jays within four runs.
</P>
<P>
   The first two batters Wetteland faced were first baseman Carlos
Delgado and third baseman Tony Fernandez, two of the American
League's more dangerous hitters. However, neither Delgado (0-for-6)
nor Fernandez (0-for-7) have a career base hit against Wetteland,
``and they still don't have a hit off of him,'' Oates said.
</P>
<P>
   Delgado, though, drove in a run with a sacrifice fly, and Darrin
Fletcher drove in another with his two-out double before Wetteland
retired Tony Batista on strikes for his 35th save.
</P>
<P>
   Yesterday's triumph provided the Rangers an opportunity to
finish this 13-game stretch against Cleveland, Boston, New York and
Toronto with a 10-3 record if they win today.
</P>
<P>
   ``This ballclub,'' Oates said, ``has responded to the challenge
very well.''
</P>
<P>
   Two-out base hits always help.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
