<SLUG> BC-FBN-PENN-STATE-ARIZONA-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PENN STATE CLOBBERS ARIZONA
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WENDELL BARNHOUSE 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   STATE COLLEGE, Pa. _ The Pigskin Classic was supposed to
showcase a team that wins with two quarterbacks sharing the load.
It did. But the successful, share-the-wealth quarterbacks played
for Penn State, not Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   The third-ranked Nittany Lions started their national
championship chase with yesterday's 41-7 shellacking of
fourth-ranked Arizona, which plays at TCU next Sunday. Penn State
had 504 yards in offense (its highest total since 1997), with
senior Kevin Thompson and junior Rashard Casey each playing six
possessions.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd heard all about Arizona and their two-headed monster at
quarterback,'' Casey said. ``We wanted to show that we've got two
pretty good quarterbacks, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Paterno's system rewards seniors, and he had named Thompson the
starter even though the fans are behind Casey, who has a strong arm
and can scramble for big plays. Before the game, he gave no
indication that he would play Casey. But after Thompson drove the
Nittany Lions to a touchdown on their first drive, Casey came in
for the next two series.
</P>
<P>
   Both Penn State quarterbacks ran an offense that was a bit more
freewheeling. The Nittany Lions even confused Arizona, which had
six months to prepare for the game. Cornerback Kelvin Hunter said
the Wildcats had prepared for most of Penn State's plays _ like
Chafie Fields' reverses (three times for 110 yards). But linebacker
Scotter Sprotte said the Nittany Lions surprised Arizona with their
single-back, spread-the-field sets.
</P>
<P>
   The wide(r)-open offense allowed Penn State to breeze to a 31-0
halftime lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's great to see those offensive guys out there running
free,'' said Penn State junior linebacker LaVar Arrington, who had
seven tackles, three for losses, and broke up a pass. ``We feed off
each other. To have an offense like that, it's a new dimension for
our team.''
</P>
<P>
   Thompson and Casey, who combined to complete 11-of-19 passes for
242 yards and two touchdowns, overshadowed their Arizona
counterparts. The Wildcats' Keith Smith and Ortege Jenkins combined
to complete 25-of-35 passes for 232 yards, but Arizona's only
points were from a touchdown with 47 seconds remaining.
</P>
<P>
   ``Penn State gave us a reality check; they handed it to us,''
Smith said. ``They beat us every which way.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-28-99 2219EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
