r s BC-BBA-REEVES-COLUMN-TEX     08-28 0904
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-REEVES-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LONG BLAST SHOULD SERVE AS REMINDER OF JUAN GONZALEZ'S VALUE TO
RANGERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM REEVES 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TORONTO _ Twenty-four hours after the event, Johnny Oates was
still talking about it yesterday afternoon at Skydome.
</P>
<P>
   A professional stadium tour director couldn't have done a better
job.
</P>
<P>
   ``Did you see where Juan hit that ball?'' the Rangers' manager
said to anyone who would listen in the Rangers' dugout.
</P>
<P>
   He was pointing to a red tarpaulin-covered section of seats in
the third deck, high above the two lower decks ``and'' the
double-decked luxury suites in left field.
</P>
<P>
   Any closer to the Skydome Hotel, with its rooms overlooking the
playing field, and you'd need a major credit card.
</P>
<P>
   This was one of those flights that normally comes with two
meals, a movie and four-digit frequent-flier miles.
</P>
<P>
   It landed halfway up the third-deck seating area, a full section
to the right and five or six rows higher than the spot marked with
the No. 29, where Joe Carter smashed a 483-foot home run two years
ago.
</P>
<P>
   The list of those who have had their passports stamped for trips
to that remote area _ Carter, Jose Canseco, Mark McGwire _ is a
short one.
</P>
<P>
   ``At least 500 feet, probably more,'' a Blue Jays' official said
of Gonzalez's prodigious rocket launch.
</P>
<P>
   Only the giants walk there, proving yet again that Gonzalez is
the rock upon which this team should be built, now and far into the
future.
</P>
<P>
   All that said, Oates will happily take yesterday's far more
pedestrian 378-foot line drive into the Blue Jays' bullpen in the
second inning.
</P>
<P>
   The monster blast Friday _ and another just like it yesterday _
came during batting practice and, while awe-inspiring, means
absolutely nothing in the grand scheme of things. Nobody will be
rushing out to paint Gonzalez's No. 19 at the distant spot where it
landed.
</P>
<P>
   Yesterday's two-run blow, however, broke Toronto starter David
Wells' back and helped carry the Rangers to a
closer-than-it-should-have-been 9-7 victory over the Blue Jays,
their 10th win in their past 13 games as they sprint toward
September's pennant-race stretch run.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez's game-breaking home run was a reminder that while the
two-time MVP may be taking a backseat to the grand seasons being
enjoyed by teammates Rafael Palmeiro and Pudge Rodriguez, he is
still a mighty force in the middle of the Rangers' batting order.
</P>
<P>
   How many players can hit .310 with 29 homers and 106 runs batted
in with 32 games to go and say they're having an ``off year?''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm waiting for my month,'' Gonzalez said. ``Maybe
September.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe September ``and'' October, a sobering thought for American
League pitchers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he's getting ready,'' Oates said. ``You can see it
coming. You can see that power stroke coming around.''
</P>
<P>
   All the more reason for the Rangers to recommit themselves _
both on the field and off _ to this powerful, talented and
enigmatic slugger.
</P>
<P>
   His brief ``misunderstanding'' with Oates a few weeks ago has
faded away and didn't amount to much of anything in the first
place. It did, however, bring Gonzalez to general manager Doug
Melvin's office for a very beneficial face-to-face meeting.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe that was something he needed,'' Melvin said. ``Not so
much to be talked to as it was having someone to listen. He wanted
assurance from the general manager that he wasn't being perceived
as a bad guy or some sort of malcontent.
</P>
<P>
   ``And he wanted to let me know how much he enjoys playing in
Texas.''
</P>
<P>
   The feeling should be mutual.
</P>
<P>
   Since the meeting, Gonzalez has hustled and worked hard on
defense. He has smiled. He has accepted the Rangers' team-first
concept, never seeming to be concerned that Palmeiro and Rodriguez
are enjoying the attention he usually commands at this time of the
season.
</P>
<P>
   ``He seems happier and he looks like he's having more fun,''
Melvin said. ``At one point he looked like it was bothering him
that he wasn't hitting more home runs, but I don't think that's the
case any more. That was one of the things I told him, not to worry
about home runs and to just go out and be a good hitter.''
</P>
<P>
   No problem there.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's been much more consistent with what I expect of him since
the meeting,'' Oates said. ``It's rubbing off on the players, too.
Everyone around him feels more at ease. I know I do.''
</P>
<P>
   As the Rangers and their expanding marketing staff contemplate
new strategies for the future, they should build their campaign
around the team's key players, starting first and foremost with
Gonzalez.
</P>
<P>
   And please, don't give me the language barrier as an excuse.
We've learned enough by now to understand that there doesn't have
to be a lot of chit chat to make an effective and dramatic
television spot. The one with Gonzalez swinging a bat in his
bathrobe on the front porch is a perfect example.
</P>
<P>
   The next step, since he can become a free agent after the 2000
season, is to get Gonzalez's signature on a new long-term contract.
He should never, ever play a single day in another uniform.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the season's over, we'll sit down and talk,'' Melvin
said. ``We have some other free-agent questions to address first,
but we'll put together a timetable.
</P>
<P>
   ``It all comes down to trying to put a good team on the field.''
</P>
<P>
   Here's a thought: Build it on your biggest, strongest rock.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-28-99 2223EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990828.0253 </DOCNO>
