r s BC-FBC-CSUN-LADN     08-28 0481
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-CSUN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NORTHRIDGE DEFENSE STRIKES BACK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHRIS BRANAM  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ After watching the Cal State Northridge
quarterbacks and receivers dominate most of the last week of fall
camp, the defense struck back.
</P>
<P>
   The Matadors offense managed just two touchdowns in Saturday's
final scrimmage before the season opener next weekend against
Western Oregon.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were getting after them a little bit,'' said linebackers
coach Terrance Johnson. ``I think our defense responded.''
</P>
<P>
   Wide receiver Aaron Arnold caught Marcus Brady's quick slant
pass and raced 65 yards for a touchdown on the offense's second
series. Last Tuesday, the quarterbacks and receivers damaged the
defense, completing 19 of 22 passes in a 7-on-7 drill.
</P>
<P>
   With pride at stake, the CSUN defense forced fumbles and picked
up sacks. The offense didn't score until late in the scrimmage on a
25-yard pass from Mitch Ryerson to Ryan Beckwith.
</P>
<P>
   ``The defense, to me, has been as solid this camp as any since
I've been here,'' said CSUN interim head coach Jeff Kearin, who had
been a Matadors assistant since 1995 before taking the head job in
July. ``They got after us (today). They got it done.''
</P>
<P>
   Working for a Cos: Saturday's opener at North Campus Stadium
will mark sophomore linebacker Cos Abercrombie's first start in
almost a year. He broke his jaw in the fourth quarter of the
Matadors' 41-10 win over Northern Arizona last September and never
returned.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been hungry,'' said Abercrombie, speaking of his desire
but also remembering how he lost 15 pounds when his jaw was wired
shot. ``They've had to put a muzzle on me. I know I worked extra
hard to come back.''
</P>
<P>
   Abercrombie had 17 tackles, including eight solo, in just 1{
games last year before getting hurt. He was one of the best
performers in camp, which ended Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cos adds a lot of life to the defense,'' Johnson said. ``He's
young, but he's a proven veteran. He's aggressive. I know he's
excited. It's been a long time coming for him.''
</P>
<P>
   Waiting game: Senior linebacker Kaleon Green, whom CSUN coaches
are counting upon as an important contributor, still hasn't gotten
approval from the NCAA for a rare sixth year of eligibility.
</P>
<P>
   Green said he talked to Tom Shannon, CSUN's interim compliance
director, last Thursday about his appeal. He said he's ``nervous''
about not being eligible to play in the season opener.
</P>
<P>
   ``This should have been done five or six months ago,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Getting the punt: Freshman walk-on Scott Talamantes punted in
Saturday's scrimmage, but incumbent punter Ethan Beck said he
expects to be back in action this week.
</P>
<P>
   Beck, a first-team All-Big Sky Conference selection last year,
has been nursing a sore groin muscle. He hasn't practiced in almost
two weeks.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
