<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MILLIONAIRE-SHOW-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHO WANTS TO BE A MILLIONAIRE?' CASHES IN ON '50S GAME SHOW
FORMULA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By AARON BARNHART  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   At this point, Regis Philbin ought to be saying: Who doesn't
want to be a millionaire?
</P>
<P>
   In the 14 days since the game show ``Who Wants to Be a
Millionaire?'' made its premiere, with Philbin hosting nightly, it
has turned into a ratings phenomenon for ABC.
</P>
<P>
   With its garish special effects and graphics, suspense-building
tricks and unprecedented cash payout of $1 million, ``Who Wants to
Be a Millionaire?'' instantly cut through the late-summer clutter
of reruns. It has been TV's most-watched program nearly every night
for the past two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   The program comes to an end with an hourlong finale at 8 tonight
on KMBC, Channel 9. ABC already has promised that the show will be
back, possibly in November, for another short run.
</P>
<P>
   ``Millionaire,'' patterned on the 1950s hit ``The $64,000
Question,'' may have single-handedly revived the genre of
prime-time game shows. Networks avoided them for decades after the
1959 congressional investigation into cheating on ``Dotto,''
``Twenty-One'' and other big-money quiz shows.
</P>
<P>
   But now other networks are planning to imitate ABC's example,
and the ``Millionaire'' format, already a smash in Great Britain,
is being exported to more than 120 countries, according to its
executive producer, Michael Davies.
</P>
<P>
   So far, ``Millionaire'' hasn't made anyone a millionaire, and
the tapings have not been glitch-free. But nothing has stemmed the
growing enthusiasm for the show.
</P>
<P>
   On tonight's finale _ expected to draw as many as 20 million
viewers _ a contestant who was wrongly eliminated will be invited
back to resume his game at the $125,000 level. On the show that
aired Aug. 19, David Honea correctly identified Lake Huron as the
second-largest of the Great Lakes; the answer used on the show was
Lake Michigan.
</P>
<P>
   Two other contestants have stopped just short of the $1 million
summit, taking home prizes of $500,000 (the biggest single payout
in TV history) and $250,000. Each player must answer 15 questions
to reach $1 million, roughly doubling their money with each right
guess. A single miss ends the game, though players are allowed
three ``lifelines,'' or requests for help.
</P>
<P>
   ``Millionaire's'' popularity and the traditional low production
costs of game shows have created a hugely profitable hit _ the
``Blair Witch Project'' of this summer's TV schedule.
</P>
<P>
   And the show has another revenue stream: a nationwide 900 number
that viewers call to qualify to be on it. The preliminary phone
game, which cost $1.50 a play, featured three sets of items that
had to be placed in order using the telephone keypad. Call-in
players who correctly arranged the items fastest then competed in a
telephone playoff against other callers. The 10 finalists, plus two
alternates, were flown to New York for the taping.
</P>
<P>
   Joanne Roberts of Paola, Kan., went to Monday's taping as an
alternate and was named a contestant after a finalist had to drop
out.
</P>
<P>
   ``It happened so fast,'' Roberts recalled. ``I wasn't nervous
during the taping. It was like a carnival, it was so unreal.''
</P>
<P>
   That day Roberts competed against other finalists in one last
round of ``the fastest finger.'' Asked to arrange four dolls in the
order in which they came on the market, Roberts was correct but
wasn't the fastest.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a great time and I was really glad I went, but then in
the last 24 hours it's begun to sink in. I didn't get a shot at the
money,'' said Roberts with a laugh. ``All those things I could've
done, even with $32,000.''  &LR; brk:Unbeatable formula
</P>
<P>
   Describing what made ``Who Wants to Be a Millionaire?''
profitable is easier than explaining why audiences have been so
taken by it.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly ABC's nonstop promotion campaign helped, as did the
lack of competition on other networks.
</P>
<P>
   Others say that for sheer drama, ``Millionaire'' is in a league
by itself: the music, the lighting, the moment of indecision
brought on each time Philbin asks the contestant, ``Is that your
final answer?''
</P>
<P>
   ``This show is light years above any other format of this kind
that has been even remotely attempted over the past 30 years,''
said Steve Beverly, a broadcast professor at Union University in
Jackson, Tenn., and historian of game shows.
</P>
<P>
   ``The college professors here where I teach, normally when you
talk about something like this show, they hold their nose. They're
watching this show.''
</P>
<P>
   The origins of ``Millionaire'' are found in the quiz show craze
that started 44 summers ago when ``The $64,000 Question'' became an
immediate hit. That fall it bumped Edward R. Murrow's news program,
``See It Now,'' off the air and went on to be the No. 1 rated show
of the 1955-56 season.
</P>
<P>
   Viewers tuned in to see familiar personalities struggle with the
questions _ usually no more than four or five per broadcast _ as
they climbed the tortuous money ladder.
</P>
<P>
   One of the best-known ``$64,000 Question'' winners was Teddy
Nadler, an eccentric $50-a-week postal clerk with an eighth-grade
education. Nadler made four appearances on ``Question'' and its
companion show, ``The $64,000 Challenge,'' winning big all four
times.
</P>
<P>
   Nadler walked away with $264,000 and never worked another day in
his life.
</P>
<P>
   ``He grew up in a shelter home, an orphanage, as did all the
males of his family,'' said Teddy's nephew Rich Nadler, publisher
of KC Jones. ``He was a voracious reader, particularly in history
but a variety of subjects as well. He had a romantic attachment to
books, possibly to relieve the grimness of his life.''
</P>
<P>
   Teddy Nadler kept getting asked back because the Revson brothers
_ who not only were the show's sole sponsor (Revlon lipstick) but
controlled every aspect of its production _ considered him a
``proletarian hero.''
</P>
<P>
   ``People were coming on the show with master's degrees,'' said
Rich Nadler. ``Teddy was this little postal clerk from nowhere who
didn't know how to pronounce any of the names because he'd never
heard them pronounced. But he was always right, and he'd always say
the answers fast.''
</P>
<P>
   Many of the contestants on this summer's ``Millionaire,''
however, don't exactly inspire memories of Nadler's run. One could
not remember the capital of Iraq. Another, a man, did not know
which article of clothing used French cuffs. A stock trader missed
his first question, which is always easy.
</P>
<P>
   There have been other problems. Nearly all of the finalists have
been men. Many finalists have come from the nine states where it is
illegal to dial a 900 number to play a game of chance. In those
states, callers are referred to a toll-free 888 number. On some
nights, eight of the 10 finalists on ``Millionaire'' have come from
the nine toll-free states; one state, Florida, turns up two
finalists practically every night.
</P>
<P>
   A source at the program acknowledged the problem Friday, saying
more viewers probably were competing in states where the calls were
free than in those where they had to pay.
</P>
<P>
   Above all, ABC and the staff of ``Millionaire'' have kept
security tight behind the scenes, according to several familiar
with the show's production.
</P>
<P>
   Historian Jeff Kisseloff, who interviewed most of the principals
in the quiz show scandals, says that he admires ``Millionaire'' but
that the events of the '50s have made him suspicious of any
big-money quiz show.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just don't trust these people,'' Kisseloff said.
</P>
<P>
   Beverly teaches the history of the early quiz shows in his
broadcast ethics course.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of my students have never heard it before. I tell them,
`You think it's an innocuous little game, but it almost brought
down an entire industry.'''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-28-99 2237EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
