<DOCNO> NYT19990828.0256 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-28 22:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3199 &Cx1f; kan-z
r w BC-ANTHRAX-MILITARY-KAN &LR;      08-28 1555
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANTHRAX-MILITARY-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOME IN THE MILITARY REFUSE TO GET REQUIRED ANTHRAX VACCINE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SCOTT CANON  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Armed with government research, filled with suspicion about
military medicine, convinced her health is at risk, Air Force Capt.
Cyd Birns is disobeying orders.
</P>
<P>
   She refuses to take a vaccine, even though the Pentagon insists
it could save her life against the most likely of biological
weapons _ anthrax.
</P>
<P>
   ``(The Department of Defense) has a history of lying to
people,'' said the grounded reconnaissance jet pilot based near
Omaha, Neb. ``I'm a very healthy person. ... I'd like to stay that
way.''
</P>
<P>
   Birns is part of a small and stubborn minority of troops alarmed
by the anthrax inoculation, the first vaccine ever given to protect
a fighting force against germ warfare. These troops are so worried,
they're willing to forfeit military careers rather than submit to
the vaccine.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, America's military command characterizes the
resistance as so much Internet-driven hysteria about a vaccine used
safely and effectively for almost 30 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anybody who has an open mind to the science and the evidence
reaches the conclusion that we've reached,'' said Lt. Col. John
Grabenstein, a pharmacist, epidemiologist and the deputy director
of the Army Surgeon General's anthrax vaccine immunization program.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is safe.''
</P>
<P>
   By the hundreds of thousands, America's military personnel have
rolled up their sleeves for yet another needle poke. They've
submitted to anthrax vaccinations because the Pentagon insists the
threat of germ warfare is grave and growing. Military doctors have
assured them that the vaccine will work and work safely. Besides,
it's an order.
</P>
<P>
   By the hundreds _ estimates range from less than 200 to more
than 400 depending on who is asked _ rebellious troops see the
vaccine as dangerously untested and probably harmful. Birns, for
instance, thinks the myriad symptoms of Gulf War syndrome all can
be traced to anthrax inoculations.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the conflict stems from the military's spotty record of
looking out for the long-term health of its forces.
</P>
<P>
   At the dawn of the atomic age, the government conducted human
radiation testing later linked to cancer. During the Vietnam War,
the military used the defoliant Agent Orange and created various
maladies among its troops. And Gulf War veterans complaining of a
range of sickness remain at odds with Pentagon brass over whether
there is a connection between their service and their poor health.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a group of people that doesn't trust the
government,'' Grabenstein said.
</P>
<P>
   The conflict also partly stems from the glimpse it reveals of
the battlefield of the future. Before the anthrax vaccine, no
military ever tried to immunize itself against biological attack.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are having a hard time adjusting to this new threat,''
said Mayer Nudell, a former diplomat and counterterrorism
consultant to corporations and various government agencies. ``It's
difficult because it's something you can't reach out and touch.''
</P>
<P>
   Bacillus anthracis exists among livestock around the world,
although it is most common in the least developed areas of Central
and South America, Southern and Eastern Europe, Asia, Africa, the
Caribbean and the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
   Infection from the bacteria causes anthrax. If the infection
comes through a cut or scrape of the skin, there's a 20 percent
chance of death. Cases of intestinal infection, usually by way of
contaminated meat, are fatal 25 to 60 percent of the time. Anthrax
infection of the lungs has a death rate of 95 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The bacteria, which can survive years in the soil in its
protective spore form, are durable little things. They can
withstand relatively high temperatures and are not easily damaged
in something like a bomb detonation.
</P>
<P>
   They come in a compact package. The death caused by chemical
weapons measured in tons could be matched in anthrax weighed in
kilograms.
</P>
<P>
   Anthrax could be dumped on a city or battlefield with anything
that would suspend it in the air _ a bomb that detonates before
hitting the ground, a cruise-type missile, a low-flying aircraft
with crop-dusting equipment.
</P>
<P>
   Testing of a vaccine for anthrax began in the 1950s. The
substance, licensed by the U.S. Food and Drug Administration in
1970, is created by nurturing cultures of the bacteria and then
killing them with formaldehyde. The process produces an ostensibly
harmless remnant of the microscopic organism. Introducing that into
the body gives birth to antibodies that can fight off otherwise
lethal forms of anthrax.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be better if we didn't have to take any vaccines _
measles, whooping cough, polio _ because you're injecting a foreign
substance into the body,'' said David Huxsoll, the former commander
of the U.S. Army Medical Research Institute of Infectious Diseases.
``But it's important to protect ourselves from these diseases.''
</P>
<P>
   For years, the vaccine was given mostly to civilians. Some
veterinarians used it for protection, and it was given to mill
workers handling the carcasses of imported animals.
</P>
<P>
   In the early 1900s, about 130 cases of anthrax were reported in
the United States each year. By the 1990s, entire years passed
without an American anthrax infection.
</P>
<P>
   For those without vaccination, treatment can prove nearly
impossible. Doctors can fight the disease if they know about the
infection within 48 hours by hooking the patient up to intravenous
antibiotics coupled with doses of vaccine.
</P>
<P>
   But the first signs of anthrax appear much like the common cold.
Only after several days _ when treatment would be too late _ do
acute symptoms such as severe breathing problems provide a clue of
how serious the illness is.
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon contends that treating large numbers of
nonvaccinated troops exposed to anthrax spores would be a
logistical nightmare with horrifying casualty rates.
</P>
<P>
   It also asserts that countries and terrorists operating in the
Persian Gulf region and on the Korean Peninsula pose a real threat
to use anthrax weapons against American troops.
</P>
<P>
   More than 150,000 military personnel received the anthrax
vaccine _ a treatment of six shots over 18 months _ during the Gulf
War. In late 1997, Defense Secretary William Cohen ordered the
inoculation of any troops deployed to Korea or the Middle East. So
far more than 326,000 have started inoculation. By 2005, all new
recruits will receive the vaccine.
</P>
<P>
   The side effects of vaccination are a point of fierce debate.
The Defense Department says most people feel the sort of temporary
tenderness in their arm typical of most vaccines. Small numbers of
people have swelling in their arms and, Defense officials say, 0.2
percent complain of flulike symptoms.
</P>
<P>
   Skeptics, however, suggest that adverse reactions come far more
often. Troops who take the vaccine, they say, often suffer tremors,
fever, sleepiness, exhaustion and serious muscle pain.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people talk about getting grayouts, where they feel
fuzzy-headed,'' said Mark Zaid, a Washington lawyer who has
represented about two dozen persons who refused the vaccine.
``That's the last thing a reserve officer whose day job is flying a
727 or a 737 or 747 wants to experience.''
</P>
<P>
   Even those nuisances will pass, Zaid said, but a greater threat
looms from the unknown long-term effects.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody knows the long-term effects because nobody has followed
up the people who have taken the vaccine over the years,'' the
lawyer said.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters note that vaccines have existed since a prevention
for smallpox was discovered in 1796, yet not one has been proved to
cause birth defects, sterility, cancer or other fears raised in
various quarters about anthrax vaccine.
</P>
<P>
   ``What they're saying,'' said the Army's Grabenstein, ``isn't
even biologically plausible.''
</P>
<P>
   Critics also suggest the stuff might not work.
</P>
<P>
   Medical ethics prevent intentionally exposing a vaccinated
person to anthrax. So the tests of the vaccine have all been on
animals.
</P>
<P>
   What's more, Russians scientists in the city of Sverdlovsk
created an artificial strain of anthrax. That has prompted
speculation that even vaccinated troops might be defenseless
against designer germs.
</P>
<P>
   Birns, the Air Force captain, has heard these worries and more.
Researching congressional reports and government agency reports on
the Internet, she has filled one loose-leaf binder five inches
thick and is about an inch deep into a second.
</P>
<P>
   She is primarily concerned that the vaccine can cause serious
damage to her immune system, something she's not willing to risk in
return for protection against a threat she sees as remote.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people who are pushing this just want you to be ready for
battle,'' she said. ``They don't care about what happens to you
after you retire.''
</P>
<P>
   Birns is waiting for the final disposition of her case, but she
fully expects to be kicked out of the Air Force. Everyone else who
has refused anthrax vaccination _ a private in Georgia went AWOL
when his sergeant threatened to hold him down for a shot _ has seen
his or her military career ended.
</P>
<P>
   ``They don't think the vaccine is worth their risk,'' said Zaid,
the vaccine-battling lawyer. ``They're scared.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-28-99 2239EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990828.0257 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-28 22:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3200 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a BC-FISHER-COLUMN-KAN &LR;      08-28 1164
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FISHER-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MILO, MO., POWWOW UNLOCKS THE RHYTHM OF THE EARTH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM FISHER  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MILO, Mo. _ Last weekend, east of here at the end of a rough
gravel road that traverses ripening fields but only an occasional
dwelling, there was a singular sight.
</P>
<P>
   Indians.
</P>
<P>
   And tepees, headdresses and the sound of drums.
</P>
<P>
   Roughly 500 American Indians were on hand, some from as far away
as Florida and Arizona. All were here for the 37th annual Clear
Creek All Nations Indian Powwow, the biggest and oldest such event
in Missouri.
</P>
<P>
   A thousand or more non-Indians each day found their way to a hay
field turned parking lot, then made their way into a grove of oaks
and firs where booths and tepees were set up, Indian-made goods
were sold, and the aroma of barbecued pork, hominy, and beans
wafted amid the trees.
</P>
<P>
   The big attraction, of course, were the twice-daily gourd dances
with their beating drums, cadenced steps and chanting dancers _ the
keystone of any Indian powwow.
</P>
<P>
   Yet what made the event unique was its location near, of all
places, Milo, Mo., one of 17 so-named places in the United States,
a designation that could be a surrogate for rural life. Seven of
the eight states abutting Missouri _ Nebraska is the exception _
have Milos of their own.
</P>
<P>
   Milo conjures up visions of russet grain atop dark green plants;
combines sweeping through autumnal fields; and a feed that, oddly,
is still sold by the hundredweight, not the bushel.
</P>
<P>
   That reverie, somehow, never even hints at Indians.
</P>
<P>
   Nor, on the surface, does surrounding Vernon County. Nevada was
burned to cinders during the Civil War, a college for women has
thrived, an insane asylum was once one of the largest employers, a
four-lane highway now splits the county, and a handful of farmers
now manage fields with the aid of ground positioning satellites.
</P>
<P>
   But look closer, said Ed Woodington, owner of the land and the
spark plug behind the powwow for its entire existence, and this
place is absolutely perfect for a gathering of Indians.
</P>
<P>
   Why?
</P>
<P>
   ``Osages,'' Woodington said.
</P>
<P>
   Until almost 200 years ago, this small part of Missouri was
literally the land of milk and honey as the hereditary home of the
Great and Little Osage tribes, an intensely spiritual people who
hunted and cultivated crops, believed in selective breeding (6 feet
6 inches was not an uncommon height for an Osage male), and utterly
controlled most of what is now Kansas, Missouri, Arkansas and
Oklahoma through their ``Arabic fervency in their military
aggression.''
</P>
<P>
   Those last words were written by John Joseph Mathews, a
quarter-blood Osage himself and author of the 1961 classic, The
Osages, Children of the Middle Waters.
</P>
<P>
   The ``Middle Waters'' were the present day Osage River and its
tributaries, the Marmiton, the Little Osage and the Marais des
Cygnes. Meaning Vernon and southern Bates counties.
</P>
<P>
   Among those streams dwelt the Osages, finding, as Mathews put
it, that ``they lived in a region that had long periods of lush
tranquility, and that water fowl and water animals abounded; that
they lived at the contact line between the prairie-plains and the
woodland.
</P>
<P>
   ``For food they had abundant white-tail deer, wild turkeys,
prairie chickens, wapati (elk), buffalo, skunk, fish, lotus,
pawpaws, grapes, persimmons, hickory nuts, walnuts, hackberries,
pecans, and acorns, beside their cultivated crops of varicolored
maize, squashes, beans, pumpkins and the wild potato.
</P>
<P>
   ``In all the regions of the Western Hemisphere where there were
indigenous peoples, there could not be found a more fortunate tribe
than ... the Children of the Middle Waters.''
</P>
<P>
   Woodington, 72, himself part Ottawa Indian, said the Osage
connection wasn't lost on him when he established the first powwow
in 1962.
</P>
<P>
   ``I used to dance down in Oklahoma at lot,'' he said. ``People
there were always saying we should have dances up here with all the
history. So we started this one. Used to be at the fairgrounds in
Nevada, but the people there talked about charging. We don't
charge. It's all free.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's simple. It keeps our traditions and culture alive. It's
friends getting together. And what better place. This was Indian
land.''
</P>
<P>
   But not for a long time. From here the Osage were first moved,
by treaty, to southeast Kansas, then given what the government
considered wasteland in northern Oklahoma. Under that soil,
however, were vast pools of oil and subsequent riches for the
tribe.
</P>
<P>
   ``A few years ago the state put in a little park up near
Harwood, where the Osage villages were,'' Woodington said. ``They
had a ceremony, invited some Osage leaders for the dedication. But
they don't come to this powwow often. Or any other. They pretty
much stay down home.''
</P>
<P>
   Gene Red Bear, 52, a Lakota-Cherokee artist who came to the
powwow from his home in Poteau, Okla., said Indian history in
Missouri, while a mystery to most white people, was real to a lot
of Indians. It's fitting, he said, that there should be a powwow
here.
</P>
<P>
   Tribes are important, he said. But a powwow _ which you can hold
anywhere if you have Indians _ puts the brotherhood of all Indians
out for people to see.
</P>
<P>
   Plus, he said, they're fun to attend, to get away for a weekend.
The idea, he said, is to sell enough to cover expenses.
</P>
<P>
   Yet what Red Bear especially enjoys is the irony he sees all
around him _ buyers of Indian goods demanding absolute assurance
that their purchase isn't some Asian knockoff, the fact that the
heads of some of the tomahawks being sold are made by pacific
Mennonites, and the profusion of signs accepting credit cards.
</P>
<P>
   ``Indians are learning,'' Red Bear said. ``They're taking what
they need from the white man's world, using it to their advantage
and not worrying about the rest.
</P>
<P>
   ``Take me. I sell my art all over the world. How? Easy. I've got
a 26-page Web site. I also pull a 1959 trailer to these things.
It's all a matter of priorities.''
</P>
<P>
   John Cornsilk of Tahlequah, Okla., went along with Red Bear.
Cornsilk represents 20 Indian artisans, one of whom designs sweat
shirts with Cherokee, Choctaw and Comanche on their fronts. The
lettering makes them appear, from a distance, like the distinctive
script of a well-known soft drink.
</P>
<P>
   ``At a powwow in Oklahoma City, Coke came down and looked them
up one side and down the other,'' Cornsilk said. ``But what could
they do? They didn't say Coca-Cola. They spelled out an Indian
tribe.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the essence of the powwow was the dancing, in the hot
afternoon and the falling dusk, and where spectators sat
transfixed, not unlike all those years ago, nearby, when the Osages
danced. Mathews wrote:
</P>
<P>
   ``The rhythm was the rhythm of the earth as if the drum beats
were heart beats, and the songs the drummers sang all seemed to
have an (oratorical) quality, as if the centuries-old prayer songs
had colored their voices.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
