<HEADLINE>
WHIPPED ARIZONA TURNS ITS ATTENTION TO HORNED FROGS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WENDELL BARNHOUSE 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   STATE COLLEGE, Pa. _ Arizona woke up Saturday morning in Happy
Valley, ranked No. 4. The Wildcats arrived home Saturday night in
Tearful Tucson hoping to still be ranked in the top 10 when they
play at TCU next Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   All you needed to know about the Pigskin Classic] the 97,618 at
Beaver Stadium told you with 5:13 remaining in the first half.
After Penn State scored to take a 31-0 lead, the fans started
chanting: ``Over-rated, over-rated. Arizona got the message. After
yesterday's 41-7 embarrassment, the Wildcats hope to make a
rebuttal statement at Amon Carter Stadium in eight days.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel disgusted, violated and what we've got to do is take
this whipping and learn from it,'' said Arizona linebacker DaShon
Polk, who talked better than he tackled \Rthree, total\S .''We've
got to take the hurt that's built up in us and bring it to the next
game. I hope this will make us stronger, because right now, we're
not a good team.
</P>
<P>
   ``TCU is no pushover. That's a big game. We're really going to
have to show the character of this team.''
</P>
<P>
   Are the Wildcats as bad as they appeared? Probably not. But they
might not be as good as they were expected to be. Arizona had
pointed to and prepared for the Penn State game, a game it
volunteered to play. Because the Wildcats appeared so overmatched,
it will be difficult to convince the poll voters any different.
Arizona's season goal has changed from ``Sugar Bowl'' to ``Rose
Bowl.''
</P>
<P>
   But even a first trip to Pasadena might rest on a trip to Fort
Worth.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're looking at TCU now,'' Arizona junior quarterback Ortege
Jenkins said. ``It will be a huge test for us mentally. Hopefully
this team will bounce back next week. If not, we're in a load of
trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   The third-ranked Nittany Lions might be the nation's best team.
They looked that way razing Arizona, which had that
``deer-in-the-headlights'' look about them. The Wildcats are
celebrating their 100th year of football and an Arizona team had
never ventured this far East. They probably won't make a similar
trip for another 100 years.
</P>
<P>
   The preseason hype generated by a 12-1 season that ended with a
Holiday Bowl victory over Nebraska disappeared quicker than Penn
State could score. And that was fast. The Nittany Lions' longest
scoring drive was their first, a plain-as-their uniforms 80-yard
effort in seven plays. Penn State's other first-half scores
required possessions of 12 seconds, 46 seconds, 1:32 and 2:17.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona started the game with four linebackers. The Wildcats
needed 11 tacklers. The Wildcats perpetuated the image of the
Pacific-10 as a touch-football conference. Chafie Fields' first
touchdown, a 37-yard reception, came when he broke a Pee Wee
Herman-like tackle by Arizona cornerback Kelvin Hunter. Two
possessions later, Penn State's Aaron Harris ran through another
Hunter arm tackle. And on Harris' 15-yard touchdown run, he blasted
past and through three Wildcats.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got our butts kicked. We got beat as bad as we could get
beat,'' Arizona coach Dick Tomey said. ``It was one of those games
that was a nightmare. We were poor in the kicking game, poor in
tackling, they outhit us, they were tougher than we were, more
physical. Everything you want to be in football, they were better
than us.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to find out who we are. Right now, we don't like
what we see. We need to take the hurt and the pain from this game
and transfer that into positive energy.''
</P>
<P>
   And that New Age form of football preparation will be aimed full
force at TCU.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
