<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-LYONS-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DISTRESS IS IN THE AIR AROUND NFL CAMPS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN LYONS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Soundcheck 1: ``Anytime you bring in a lot of new people, your
execution is going to be bad. ...every time we got going, we were
set back by something we did wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   Soundcheck 2: ``We stink. It was horrible. I'm sick.''
</P>
<P>
   Soundcheck 3: ``We have to step it up. If we don't, it's going
to be a long year. We really stunk it up. It's not a good
feeling.''
</P>
<P>
   Soundcheck 4: ``We didn't do anything well out there. We just
have to come out and regroup. We have to get our focus back. We
didn't look like a team that's supposed to be in the playoffs. We
didn't look like a team that would even have a winning record.''
</P>
<P>
   Soundcheck 5: ``Right now, this team is like a dark comedy. Just
when you think it can't get worse, it gets worse.''
</P>
<P>
   The mood of those quotes from the past week could certainly come
from Camp Cowboys, for this has been a summer they would like to
forget. They have had enough injuries to merit team trainer Jim
Maurer a bigger office. The first-team offense has scored but one
touchdown, and the first-team defense was bombed last week in New
England.
</P>
<P>
   Truth is, however, the poor-mouthing did not come from the
Cowboys. In the first soundcheck, Dan Reeves bemoans the fate of
his defending NFC champion Falcons, who can't seem to get it going
consistently this summer with so many rookies. In a preseason game
against the Ravens a few days earlier, the Falcons lost, 19-6, when
two rookie cornerbacks were beaten on long touchdown passes.
</P>
<P>
   In the second soundcheck, Bill Parcells, coach of a Jets team
that lost in the AFC Championship Game last season, sounds as if he
needs to see a doctor. Parcells' special teams were anything but
special in a one-point victory against the lowly Philadelphia
Eagles last week.
</P>
<P>
   In the third soundcheck, Broncos running back Terrell Davis,
whose club is trying to become the first team to win three
consecutive Super Bowls, can't stand the smell of his team after
the Broncos were blown out by the Green Bay Packers on Monday Night
Football.
</P>
<P>
   In the fourth soundcheck, Jaguars cornerback Aaron Beasley
worries that his team won't make the playoffs. A few days earlier,
Jacksonville had dropped a 27-20 decision to the New York Giants,
who didn't make the playoffs in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   And in the fifth soundcheck, Cardinals offensive lineman Matt
Joyce curses the luck of his club, which this summer has seen
injuries on the offensive line and quarterback Jake Plummer, three
players injured in a near fatal car accident and three players who
remain holdouts.
</P>
<P>
   The point is this: Nobody is looking good in the preseason. Not
even the so-called ``elite'' or the ``up-and-coming'' teams.
Rookies still don't know the plays. Veterans are injured or out of
shape. A new coaching staff hasn't had time to adapt. The
temperature is too hot.
</P>
<P>
   Cowboys coach Chan Gailey has been around this game too long to
get too low about a preseason loss, or too high about a preseason
win. (OK. In two years, Gailey has never had a preseason victory.
But you get the point). Broncos coach Mike Shanahan, whose club
faces the Cowboys tonight in an exhibition game at Texas Stadium,
is also keeping things in perspective.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been through it a number of years, and preseason never
changes,'' Shanahan said. ``If you win, it was a preseason game. If
you lose, that's the end of the world. That's just the nature of
this business.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe the Cowboys will be terrible in 1999. But if we use only
the preseason to make such an assumption, then there will be a lot
of disappointment for a bunch of good teams this year.
</P>
<P>
   \Nsubheds:SPOTLIGHT: 49ers defensive end Charles Haley
Bob Galbraith Charles Haley, center, is showing a change of
attitude, and the 49ers hope it will help them when they face Brett
Favre and the Packers this season.
</P>
<P>
   Haley's behaving well, helping 49ers defense
Since he resumed his career by re-signing with the San Francisco
49ers, defensive end Charles Haley, 35, has been a model citizen.
According to his coaches and teammates, Haley's attitude this
summer has been a 180-degree turnaround from the one thatsaw him
have emotional outbreaks, and wild mood swings when he played with
the 49ers (1986-1991) and Cowboys (1992-1996).
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he's gotten a lot more mature. I think he's a lot more
in control of his emotions and his composure,'' 49ers linebacker
Ken Norton told the San Francisco Chronicle last week. Norton was a
teammate of Haley's in Dallas from 1992-1994. ``I think in the
past, \RHaley\S was a little more out of control. But truly, I
think life has brought these experiences to him, and he's
undoubtedly matured a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   Haley was forced to retire from the Cowboys following the 1996
season because of back problems. While out of football, he led the
search for a compatible marrow donor for his daughter,
five-year-old Brianna, who has leukemia. Haley's fourth child,
Madison, born last October, was a perfect match and the leukemia is
in remission.
</P>
<P>
   Haley signed with the 49ers after the 1998 regular season and
was active for their two playoff games. This summer, his back has
held up. And he has taken the time to pass on his supreme
pass-rushing skills to younger players.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think there's any question, Charles makes our
defensive line better,'' Norton said. ``Just his presence, and I
think everybody really respects the way he plays. Everybody knows
that off the field, you've got to have this tolerance and patience
with him, but everybody also knows that once he straps it up on the
field, you're getting everything he's got.''
</P>
<P>
   \Nsubheds:Quick hits
</P>
<P>
   \Nsubheds:Nice draft, Jerry Remember the April draft? The
Cowboys seriously considered trading up to get Louisiana Tech wide
receiver Troy Edwards before picking North Carolina defensive end
Ebenezer Ekuban with the 20th pick. Right now, it's a good thing
the Cowboys stuck with Ekuban. Word out of Pittsburgh, where
Edwards was drafted at No. 13, is that Edwards has been slow to
pick up the pro passing game and won't beat out Courtney Hawkins or
Hines Ward for either of the starting wide receiver spots. Ward, in
his second season out of Georgia, caught 15 passes last season.
Hawkins caught 66 for 751 yards and 1 touchdown. If Edwards
couldn't beat out Hawkins and Ward, how could he have played much
for a Cowboys team with Michael Irvin, Raghib Ismail, and Ernie
Mills.
</P>
<P>
   \Nsubheds:QB or not QB Even though Doug Flutie came off the
bench to lead the Bills to the playoffs last season, head coach
Wade Phillips is not ready to name Flutie as his starting
quarterback for 1999. This summer, Flutie has been sharing snaps
with Rob Johnson, who was the club's starting quarterback before he
injured his ribs last year. Johnson and Flutie, both of whom make
about $5 million a year, have played so well this summer that
Phillips has thought about rotating them during the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are all kinds of possibilities,'' Phillips said. ``I
think we have to wait until the preseason is over, see where we are
and how they fit in.''
</P>
<P>
   While Phillips is noncommittal, Johnson has an opinion.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we had to start a game tomorrow, Doug would start,''
Johnson said Friday. ``Like I've said a million times, Doug played
well last year and nothing's changed. So I wouldn't figure they
would make a change right now in the preseason.''
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
