<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-KAHN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HARRY KAHN, 82, A COLLECTOR OF ART  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Harry Kahn, a retired New York investment adviser,
art collector and philanthropist, died on Aug. 20 at Lenox Hill
Hospital. A resident of Manhattan's Upper East Side and Truro,
Mass., he was 82.
</P>
<P>
   The causes were pneumonia and congestive heart failure, his
family said.
</P>
<P>
   Kahn retired in 1990 as a partner in the brokerage firm of
Neuberger &AMP; Berman. He joined the firm in 1963 after 10 years as a
researcher and partner in Bache &AMP; Co.
</P>
<P>
   Long a supporter of the Brooklyn Museum of Art, he served on its
board until 1997. He was a founder of its Contemporary Arts Council
and, at his death, was a member of the Acquisitions Committee.
</P>
<P>
   As an art collector in his own right he was widely known for the
self-portraits by 20th-century American artists he gathered with
his companion, Ruth Bowman, an art historian.
</P>
<P>
   Born in Manhattan, Harry Kahn graduated from Harvard College in
1937 and earned a master's in public administration from Harvard
University in 1948. In between, he served in the Army and held
posts in the Treasury Department and the Office of Strategic
Services. After the war, he was on the staff of the Marshall Plan
Administration in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Besides Ms. Bowman, a resident of Manhattan, Kahn is survived by
a daughter, Dr. Jenny Elizabeth Kaufmann of Manhattan; two
stepdaughters, Susan and Evelyn London of Cambridge, Mass.; and two
granddaughters. His wife, Margery Guiterman Kahn, died several
years ago.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
