<SLUG> BC-BKL-SPARKS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPARKS GET TWO CHANCES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By PAMELA LEWIS  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Now comes the tricky part for the Los Angeles
Sparks. They've had no problem handling the Houston Comets in the
comforts of the Forum, where they have won all three games against
the two-time WNBA champions, including the opener of the Western
Conference finals.
</P>
<P>
   But can they win just one before an emotional, capacity crowd of
16,285 in Houston's Compaq Center?
</P>
<P>
   That is the challenge the Sparks will have to answer today or
Monday as the Western Conference finals continue. The Sparks and
Comets square off at 1 p.m. in Game 2 of the three-game series. If
they lose, the series will be decided Monday at 5 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   The Comets don't give up too much at home, where they are 39-7
and 5-0 in the playoffs after three years. They lost only one of
their 16 home games this season, a 68-66 decision to Orlando.
</P>
<P>
   Then consider the Comets haven't played at home since Aug. 18 _
the day before their point guard, Kim Perrot, died from lung cancer
_ and one has to figure they will be backed by an emotionally
charged home crowd.
</P>
<P>
   Despite an 0-6 record at Compaq, the Sparks feel extremely
confident, especially after their front court of Lisa Leslie,
DeLisha Milton and La'Keisha Frett combined for 50 points in the
team's 75-60 series-opening victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we would have lost that game it would have been very
difficult going into Houston needing two (wins),'' Sparks coach
Orlando Woolridge said. ``We feel like we have a very good
chance.''
</P>
<P>
   It was Mwadi Mabika's defensive work on Houston leader Cynthia
Cooper and Frett's denial defense on Sheryl Swoopes that made the
difference. Cooper, the three-time league scoring champ, was held
to her lowest output of the season, 12 points on 4-of-16 shooting.
Frett, who has become known for her defensive prowess, had the
primary job of guarding of Swoopes, holding her to only 10
field-goal attempts. Although Swoopes scored 17 points, she shot
five below her average.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to have the same defensive effort that we had
(Thursday), and come aggressive from the beginning,'' Mabika said.
``I think that we can do it.''
</P>
<P>
   That sentiment is shared by the Sparks, but they know it will
take their very best effort to pull if off.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to go in there and fight for our lives,'' backup point
guard Penny Toler said. ``We have a golden opportunity here. We
have to get them now. They have to have a little pressure being
down 0-1, but I still say that they have the heart of a champion.
When we come out, we just have to play like there is no tomorrow.
We have to play like the series is 1-1.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
