<SLUG> BC-FBC-NOTREDAME-KANSAS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IRISH TAKE ADVANTAGE OF HISTORY AND TURNOVERS  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By ANDREW BLUTH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SOUTH BEND, Ind. _ The historians among the Notre Dame faithful
_ which is almost all of them _ have been looking forward to the
1999 season for a long time. Not because this year's version of
their beloved Irish football team is particularly loaded with
talent, and not because the team is coming off an extraordinarily
satisfying 1998 season. But because the history books tell them
that this is their year.
</P>
<P>
   Armed with those history books, these fans point out that Notre
Dame has won a national championship in 1966, 1977 and 1988. They
expect nothing less in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Still on track for that championship, Notre Dame opened the 1999
season Saturday at home in the Eddie Robinson Classic, beating
Kansas, 48-13, on a hot, humid and hazy day, in a game named after
the legendary Grambling coach.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Davie, beginning his third season as Notre Dame coach, has
been quick to calm the perhaps unrealistic expectations, pointing
out that this year's team is a young one, and that it must face a
difficult schedule, traveling to Michigan next week and to
Tennessee, the defending national champion, later in the season.
</P>
<P>
   However, despite a periodically shaky offensive performance
before the 142nd consecutive sellout at Notre Dame Stadium, a
bruising Irish defense overwhelmed Kansas. The defense wasted no
time flexing its muscle, causing a Kansas fumble in the first
series of the game, the first of four Jayhawk turnovers. The fumble
recovery led to a 38-yard touchdown scramble by the senior
quarterback Jarious Jackson just three plays later and a 7-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had some big hits out there,'' Davie said after the game,
acknowledging his team looked sloppy on occasion. ``As the game
went on I think we got a little bit stronger.''
</P>
<P>
   On the Jayhawks' first play from scrimmage following the
touchdown, Irish cornerback Deveron Harper intercepted a Zac Wegner
pass and returned it 22 yards for a touchdown. By the time the
first quarter ended, Notre Dame had built a 20-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   But Irish kickers missed two field goals and an extra point in
the first half, and the offense could not put Kansas away. Notre
Dame did not score in the second quarter, giving up two touchdowns,
and Kansas pulled within 20-13. The second Kansas touchdown came
after a Jackson interception, helping to set up a 30-yard touchdown
pass from Wegner to Termaine Fulton with two seconds left in the
half.
</P>
<P>
   The Irish graduated almost all of their offensive line from last
season and lost both starting running backs. Jackson is returning
after limping through the end of the 1998 season. He looked more
comfortable running out of the option, exploding for several long
runs and rushing for 85 yards on the day, but he threw for only 89
yards and 3 interceptions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully it's out of my system,'' Jackson said of his
turnovers. ``But we won the game, and to me that's all that
matters.''
</P>
<P>
   One of those interceptions came on just the third play of the
second half, giving Kansas the ball on Notre Dame's 33-yard line
trailing by 20-13. But a blocked field goal by Irish cornerback
Clifford Jefferson led to a short touchdown run by Tony Fisher to
give Notre Dame a 27-13 lead. Fisher gained a game-high 111 yards
on 13 rushes.
</P>
<P>
   On the Jayhawks' next possession, Irish lineman Andy Wisne
knocked the ball loose from Wegner, allowing linebacker Anthony
Denman to pick up the loose ball and scamper 31 yards for a
touchdown and a 34-13 lead. Fisher broke free for a 46-yard
touchdown run in the fourth quarter, and the sophomore backup
quarterback Arnaz Battle added a 74-yard touchdown run late in the
game to extend the lead to 48-13.
</P>
<P>
   ``We cannot afford to spot Notre Dame a 20-point lead and be
successful,'' Kansas Coach Terry Allen said. ``They are too good.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
