<SLUG> BC-GIULIANI-POLITICS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIULIANI GETS WARM RECEPTION FROM HOMOSEXUAL REPUBLICANS' GROUP  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By THOMAS J. LUECK   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, delivering what has become a
stump speech focused on his conservative Republican credentials for
national office, Saturday night received a lavishly supportive
reception from the nation's largest organization of homosexual
Republicans, the Log Cabin Republicans, at the group's annual
convention in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   But while the mayor was cheered on in a ballroom at the
Roosevelt Hotel in Midtown Manhattan, a melee broke out afterward
in the hotel's elegant lobby when a small group of protesters
entered to criticize the mayor and the Log Cabin group.
</P>
<P>
   Before the protest ended shortly before 10 p.m., the police had
arrested five demonstrators.
</P>
<P>
   In his remarks, the mayor sought to cast his administration's
success in reducing crime, cutting taxes and reducing the welfare
rolls as the result of a personal political philosophy that would
be well-suited to national politics.
</P>
<P>
   He also praised those at the meeting as representing a bold
cutting edge in national politics that has successfully undermined
popular stereotypes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Your presence in the Republican Party keeps pushing us all to
be the very best we can,'' said Giuliani.
</P>
<P>
   Officials of the Log Cabin Republicans, which was formed in 1978
in California, said in interviews that their group overwhelmingly
supported Giuliani in his expected bid for the U.S. Senate.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, Frank Ricchiazzi, who is one of the founders of
the group, which says it has 10,000 members, said he expected at
least part of the money raised to be set aside for Giuliani's
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The small group of protesters who gathered outside the hotel
Saturday night sought stridently to make a point that Giuliani was
not supported by all homosexuals.
</P>
<P>
   ``We find this whole event repulsive,'' said Sue King, a
spokesman for the protesters, who she said belonged to a group
called Fed Up Queers. ``Giuliani is not a friend of gays and
lesbians,'' Ms. King said.
</P>
<P>
   After the mayor had finished his remarks, a small group of other
protesters, who apparently had bypassed a phalanx of police
outside, screamed obscenities as the police tried to remove them
from the hotel lobby.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-28-99 2322EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990828.0272 </DOCNO>
