<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-ARIZONA-RUNNING-BACK-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STATE SCHOOLS' BACKS MOVE TO THE FRONT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By KENT SOMERS  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Arizonans are accustomed to seeing the unusual. We have watched
governors be impeached and convicted, the Cardinals make the
playoffs and cotton fields transform seemingly overnight into
neighborhoods of stucco and red-tiled roofs.
</P>
<P>
   So perhaps it's fitting that this college football season also
brings us something unique: Three premier running backs at three
different schools, separated only by a few hundred miles of
interstate, not by talent and potential.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe no other state can boast that each of its football-playing
universities has an electrifying running back capable of dominating
a game.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona has Trung Canidate, who rushed for 1,220 yards last year
as a junior. His 15 career rushing touchdowns have come from an
astounding average of almost 52 yards out.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona State has J.R. Redmond, who can break open a game
running, receiving or returning punts and kicks.
</P>
<P>
   Northern Arizona has Ronney Jenkins, a transfer from Brigham
Young University who could put up silly numbers at the Division
I-AA level.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's amazing,'' said Arizona Coach Dick Tomey, who hasn't seen
a more talented trio in his 12 years in Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   ASU Coach Bruce Snyder agreed. He knows first-hand what the
running backs can do.
</P>
<P>
   He's coached Redmond, a senior. Last season he watched as
Canidate shredded ASU for 288 rushing yards, including touchdown
runs of 80, 66 and 48 yards. And he knew of Jenkins, a junior, even
before he gained 171 yards against ASU in Brigham Young's 26-6
victory last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I recruited Ronney Jenkins out of high school (in Oxnard,
Calif.) and watched him gain 600 yards in a game,'' Snyder said.
``It was against nobody, but do you know how much 600 yards is? So
I know just how good he is.''
</P>
<P>
   Of the three schools, Arizona State has the best reputation for
turning out running backs, dating back to the Frank Kush era, when
the likes of Art and Ben Malone and Woody Green ran wild. Arizona
has a less illustrious history of producing runners. Its all-time
leading rusher is Ontiwaun Carter (3,501) followed by the ``Cactus
Comet,'' Art Luppino, who played in the mid-'50s.
</P>
<P>
   NAU, a member of the pass-happy Big Sky Conference, had Archie
Amerson, who gained nearly 3,200 yards in the 1995 and '96 seasons,
and Allan Clark, who finished with 2,723 yards.
</P>
<P>
   Canidate, Jenkins and Redmond each has a resume that keeps
opposing defensive coordinators in the office late at night.
Canidate is a threat to score each time he gets the ball. Redmond
might be the best multipurpose back in the college game. And
Jenkins has sprinter's speed and a receiver's hands.
</P>
<P>
   But what should really scare defensive coordinators is that none
of the three running backs has been healthy for an entire
collegiate season in which they've been a starter.
</P>
<P>
   Jenkins gained 1,307 yards and scored 12 touchdowns at BYU last
season, even though he never felt in shape after sitting out the
previous season because of violating the school's honor code.
</P>
<P>
   Canidate missed the first game of last season while recovering
from a broken foot and wasn't 100 percent until the end of the
year. Still, he gained 1,220 yards to lead the Pac-10 and set a UA
single-season rushing record.
</P>
<P>
   And Redmond missed one game last year and was limited in at
least two others by toe and ankle injuries. &QL; 
One wise guy &QL; 
Canidate needs 1,280 yards rushing to break the school's career
record, which shouldn't be a problem if he stays healthy.
</P>
<P>
   Foot and ankle injuries have hampered him the last two seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``Trung is healthier than he's been the last couple years,''
Tomey said in preseason camp. ``He played at less than 100 percent
for most of the last year and a half.''
</P>
<P>
   Canidate, from Central High, said he was in agony when last
season started. He's not preoccupied, how ever, with the statistics
he could compile if he stays healthy, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess some people might be curious, but I just know I can do
more,'' he said. ``You have to remember where you came from and I
know where I cam from. I came from a lot of hard work. There are
many days I thought `This just isn't right and it might not happen
for me.' But I kept working hard and kept believing in myself and
took advantage of the opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   Canidate has been mentioned as a Heisman candidate, partially
because of his big-play capability and, of course, his last name.
</P>
<P>
   Tomey doesn't think that will bother the 5-foot-11, 199-pound
senior.
</P>
<P>
   ``Understand this, there are not a lot of people like him,''
Tomey said. ``He understands that a lot of this is catchy because
of his last name. I promise you, if there is anybody who can handle
something like that, he can. He has more wisdom in his little
finger than most people do in their entire body.''
</P>
<P>
   Pro scouts love Canidate's penchant for big plays, but there are
concerns about his durability.
</P>
<P>
   ``The kid has an uncanny ability to break long runs for
touchdowns,'' said Joel Buchsbaum of ``Pro Football Weekly.''
``He's the type of runner who when he gets the ball, you hold your
breath.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The War Room,'' a respected scouting publication, said
Canidate is an athletic back but a bit undersized. It projects him
as a top third-down back at the NFL level.
</P>
<P>
   Canidate could change that with a big year.
</P>
<P>
   The Wildcats love to use Canidate on runs inside the tackles
because he hits the line so quickly and has the entire field to
maneuver once he clears traffic.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's not an outside runner; he's an inside runner,'' Tomey
said. ``He's one of those runners that people always say, `What are
you running up the middle for?'
</P>
<P>
   ``Because if you keep going there with a guy like that, you're
going to break it. You're liable to make one (yard), make none,
make two and then make 50.'' &QL; 
Zoning out &QL; 
When Redmond talks of being in ``the zone,'' he's not referring to
the end zone, although that's where he would like to end up.
</P>
<P>
   No, Redmond is talking about reaching that magical place where
every move he makes is the right one.
</P>
<P>
   ``What it is, is when your body reacts quicker than your mind,''
he said. ``Like sometimes, you'll see something and move toward it.
In my case, I move toward it before I see it.''
</P>
<P>
   Redmond has only been in the zone once in college, he said,
against Stanford last season. He scored three touchdowns in just
over one quarter before suffering toe and ankle injuries. He missed
most of the next two games.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a patient runner, waits for blocks to develop and shows
good field vision,'' according to ``The War Room.'' ``He doesn't
have great burst or breakaway speed, but his quickness and feel for
the game make up for it. He's also proven himself as a quality
return man and a blocking back, which makes him a more interesting
player on the NFL draft boards.''
</P>
<P>
   Redmond, 6-foot and 210, reminds Snyder of Ahmad Rashad, whom he
coached at Oregon. Like Rashad, Redmond has an infectious appetite
for the game.
</P>
<P>
   Redmond would abhor becoming strictly a running back. In his
perfect world, he would play running back, wide receiver and return
kicks and punts.
</P>
<P>
   But he plays in Snyder's world. Redmond likely won't play
defense this year, and Snyder is thinking of limiting his kick
return duties.
</P>
<P>
   Redmond understands, but he never wants to be just a running
back, not even in the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   ``It takes away your spirit for the game,'' he said. ``And it
takes away from your drive. Everyone should strive to play more,
get more snaps.''
</P>
<P>
   He believes that if a team has a dominating player, it shouldn't
try to limit him.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kind of like the game of checkers,'' he said. ``You have
the king, the most powerful piece on the board. When you get your
king in a power position, you have to use it. Or else you really
don't want to win.'' &QL; 
Give him the ball
</P>
<P>
   They will hand it, pitch it and pass it to him and maybe use him
on kickoff returns.
</P>
<P>
   And if the NAU Lumberjacks can figure out another way for
Jenkins to touch the ball, they'll try that, too. Coach Jerome
Souers joked that his staff might set an NCAA record for creative
ways to put the ball in Jenkins' hands.
</P>
<P>
   NAU coaches would like opponents to be uneasy about where
Jenkins might line up.
</P>
<P>
   NAU, has a new offensive coordinator, Brent Pease, who spent
time looking at tape of Jenkins playing at BYU.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to put him situations he feels comfortable in and in
other things that fit into our schemes,'' Pease said. ``He has so
much talent and so much ability. But it also comes down to 10 other
people doing their jobs.''
</P>
<P>
   Few running backs in the country face the expectations that
Jenkins does at Northern Arizona. He is one of the most talented
backs to ever play in the Big Sky Conference, and longtime NAU
observers haven't seen his kind of ability in Flagstaff since Pete
Mandley played in the late 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   Coming out of high school, Jenkins was recruited by Arizona
State and Southern California, among others, but chose BYU, in part
because his grandmother liked the family atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
   But Jenkins was suspended after his freshman year for violating
the honor code and was expelled after the 1998 regular season for a
second violation. Both transgressions were for engaging in sexual
relations outside of marriage, which is forbidden.
</P>
<P>
   By transferring to a Division I-AA school, Jenkins was
immediately eligible.
</P>
<P>
   The quiet and modest Jenkins doesn't necessarily buy into the
high expectations. There are good players in the Big Sky, he said,
and football is full of uncontrollable variables.
</P>
<P>
   ``I expect a lot out of myself, regardless of what people expect
out of me,'' he said. ``That's why I've worked so hard in the
off-season.''
</P>
<P>
   The 5-11 Jenkins is listed at 175 pounds, but he said he bulked
up to 190 pounds without losing speed. He has been timed in the
40-yard dash in under 4.4 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   He's in far better shape today than he was a year ago at BYU, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt horrible,'' he said. ``I'm much better now. Totally
different. I had 1,300 yards for the season, and I don't know how I
did it. I felt out of shape, sluggish and I had little nagging
injuries throughout the season. I was never at my best. Never.''
</P>
<P>
   Many people are assuming that Jenkins will leave for the NFL
after this season. But he said he plans to stay for his final two
years, which is a good move, according to Buchsbaum.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's probably better off staying, maturing and growing,''
Buchsbaum said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
