<SLUG> BC-FBC-ASU-OVERVIEW-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEVILS ARE BACK FROM NEAR DEATH  
 KEALY IS STILL READY WITH PADDLES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PAOLA BOIVIN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Beep. Beep. Beep. Beeeeeeeeeeeeee . . .
</P>
<P>
   Midway through the 1998 season, the Arizona State football team
flat-lined. Back-to-back losses to Southern California and Notre
Dame put the Sun Devils at 2-4, an unlikely predicament for a
program projected to finish in the Top 10.
</P>
<P>
   But a team on the verge of spinning out of control never did,
and that final surge is the foundation on which the 1999 Sun Devils
are built.
</P>
<P>
   Ryan Kealy was the defibrillator. The pulse of the program
returned when the young quarterback began playing as he did as a
freshman: relaxed, poised and confident.
</P>
<P>
   ``He looks great,'' ASU Coach Bruce Snyder said. ``When Ryan
remembers why he's out there, to have fun and play football, he's
just fine.''
</P>
<P>
   Kealy's potential is a big reason the Sun Devils find themselves
back in most Top 25 polls, despite last season's 5-6 record.
</P>
<P>
   In his final four games of 1998, he completed 72 of 110 passes
for 1,100 yards, 11 touchdowns and two interceptions. When
confident and healthy, he is arguably the Pac-10's best
quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   But as Kealy goes, so does the team. The offense's chemistry
last season was affected, in part, by the quarterback's brief exits
from the lineup because of a concussion, a sprained right knee and
a mid-season slump.
</P>
<P>
   ``Guys were getting frustrated,'' he said. ``There was a little
bit of finger-pointing. I think this team has really come together
over the summer.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite last season's crash, there's every reason to believe the
Sun Devils are close to returning to pre-1998 form (the 1996 and
1997 teams were a combined 20-4).
</P>
<P>
   Tailback J.R. Redmond is a big reason. The Heisman Trophy
candidate can take over a game when healthy, with ``when'' being
the operative word. He was slowed for part of the season with ankle
injuries but still managed to rush for 883 yards.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be a mistake not to design our running game around
him,'' offensive coordinator Dan Cozzetto said. ``When you have
that type of a player on your team, you have to take advantage of
the situation.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sun Devils have never led the Pac-10 in rushing. Could this
be the season?
</P>
<P>
   ASU is also optimistic about 1999 because of an offensive line
that features tackles Marvel Smith and Victor Leyva and freshman
All-America Scott Peters, who likely will start at center. The trio
will help provide ample protection for Kealy.
</P>
<P>
   Cozzetto wants to see the group open more lanes for runs. He
believes if the Sun Devils had done that better last season, ``we
would have won more games.''
</P>
<P>
   ASU will need a strong running game while it tries to determine
how effective its wide receivers can be.
</P>
<P>
   The season-long suspensions of Justin Taplin and Joey Graves as
well as an assortment of injuries have left the Sun Devils
depleted. Snyder knows what junior Tariq McDonald can do, but how
will junior college transfers Ryan Dennard, Richard Williams and
Royce Coachman perform in front of crowds of 60,000?
</P>
<P>
   None have the connection with Kealy that McDonald does. The two
have played together since Pop Warner days.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not concerned,'' Kealy said. ``We brought in some really
talented players who will get the job done. I'm not worried at
all.''
</P>
<P>
   He knows that Todd Heap, as well as several other talented tight
ends, will be in the lineup on a regular basis. When Heap got the
ball last season, he performed magic, and the Sun Devils need
someone in the lineup with big-play capabilities.
</P>
<P>
   Big plays are something the defense lacked last season. Only two
Pac-10 teams had fewer interceptions than ASU's 12. Only two
recovered fewer fumbles than the Sun Devils' 9. Only one team had
fewer quarterback sacks than ASU's 24.
</P>
<P>
   ``You'll see a difference in how guys perform this year because
they know what they are doing,'' defensive coordinator Phil Snow
said. ``There were a lot of question marks last year because of the
new people we had in place.''
</P>
<P>
   Two of those question marks were linemen Junior Ioane and Erik
Flowers, who blossomed as the season progressed.
</P>
<P>
   Although the secondary is inexperienced, the Sun Devils aren't
worried.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's funny, because I think the perception of that part of our
team is that it's a concern,'' Snyder said. ``But I don't see it
that way at all. I think it's something we addressed in the
off-season, and I feel very comfortable with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Strong safety Willie Daniel was thrown into the fire last
season, and his two starts will benefit him this year. Redshirt
freshman Alfred Williams may be the best-kept secret on the team.
</P>
<P>
   A former linebacker, Williams emerged in the spring as the top
candidate to start at free safety. The two will rotate with junior
college transfers Craig Koontz and Monte' Franks and possibly
redshirt freshman Brandon Falkner.
</P>
<P>
   Like their wide receivers, the Sun Devils have some serious
questions about their linebackers. Stephen Trejo has returned to
the outside. Eric Fields is in the middle, a position he has never
played before. Adam Archuleta is back at the other outside spot,
but he has missed the majority of practices the last few weeks with
a hamstring injury.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not where we need to be,'' Snyder said. ``And we're not
very deep.''
</P>
<P>
   That's not the case with the kicking game. Stephen Baker's
45.7-yard punting average set an ASU record. The Sun Devils also
have place kicker Mike Barth and punter Nick Murphy on scholarship,
giving Snyder choices in both areas.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's nice to have options,'' he said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
