r s BC-FBC-USC-LADN     08-28 0506
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-USC-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
USC DOES SOME POSITION SHUFFLING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The addition of JC transfer Markus Steele at
linebacker has caused some position shuffling, most notably the
move of true freshman Troy Polamalu, who switched from safety to
linebacker.
</P>
<P>
   Polamalu was a star in USC's first scrimmage, recording eight
tackles and forcing two fumbles. He also scored a touchdown on a
fumble recovery.
</P>
<P>
   Polamalu was switched to weakside linebacker, where he and
sophomore Darryl Knight will back up Steele. Sophomore Henry
Wallace, who was playing weakside linebacker, is now playing the
middle and strongside positions.
</P>
<P>
   USC needs someone to back up strongside linebacker Sultan
Abdul-Malik because junior Jason Steen will miss the Hawaii game
with a neck injury. True freshman Chris Prosser was his only backup
before Wallace switched positions.
</P>
<P>
   The much-heralded Steele needed less than two days of practice
after arriving late to training camp to claim the starting weakside
position.
</P>
<P>
   MacKenzie improving: Tailback Malaefou MacKenzie has been
brought along slowly in his recovery from season-ending knee
surgery, but USC coach Paul Hackett believes the sophomore made
significant strides this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's had by far his best days,'' Hackett said. ``I might say
by game time he'll be in there. He's a little behind the others
still.''
</P>
<P>
   Penalty problems: Although the offensive line has struggled with
penalties in USC's two scrimmages, assistant coach Steve Greatwood
said the first team showed improvement in the Trojans' second
scrimmage.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first unit was much better than (in the first
scrimmage),'' Greatwood said. ``The second unit still had some
problems. The situation is never as bad as it looks or good as it
looks.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's something we're trying to address. We somewhat revert.
The defense knows us like a book. I'm not concerned about that.
It's our own mistakes that are concerning me and all the offensive
coaches. If I'm disappointed in anything, it's in the lack of poise
when a guy flinches because a linebacker is coming at him.''
</P>
<P>
   Number changes: Freshman tight end Norman Katnik has switched
from No. 62 to 96. Fullback Chad Pierson is wearing 34 instead of
47 and tackle Matt Welch will wear 98 in addition to his regular
72, when he is a tackle-eligible in goal-line situations.
</P>
<P>
   Rest day: USC took Saturday off. The Trojans will hold a night
practice today, then take Monday off before holding heavy practices
Tuesday and Wednesday. The team leaves for Hawaii on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   School starts: USC begins classes Monday, something Hackett
expects will affect the team as it returns from training camp and
begins preparing for Saturday's game against Hawaii.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now we go through a re-entry process,'' Hackett said. ``The
ability to manage time and be successful is the key. Notoriously,
the first week a team starts school they don't play very well.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
