<HEADER>
A3227 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s BC-FBC-ASU-CASSTEVENS-AZ     08-28 0741
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-ASU-CASSTEVENS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO ONE COULD STEP INTO SNYDER'S SHOES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID CASSTEVENS  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, Ariz. - Kevin, say Bruce came to you at the end of the
season and said he wanted to retire.
</P>
<P>
   If he quit, what would you do?
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Snyder is under contract through 2004. The Sun Devils
football coach hasn't even hinted that he might give up his labor
of love before age 65. But to humor me, Athletic Director Kevin
White considered the hypothetical question.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin, what would you do after a search committee _ which sounds
like three guys with flashlights and a fourth with a divining rod _
met and drew up a list of qualifications (winning record,
experience, name recognition, West Coast ties, etc.) and a wish
list of candidates?
</P>
<P>
   Who would ASU hire?
</P>
<P>
   Joe Paterno? Bobby Bowden? Steve Spurrier? They wouldn't come to
ASU. Mack Brown wouldn't leave Texas, not with that school's money
and facilities.
</P>
<P>
   Would the Sun Devils take a chance on a former NFL head coach or
pro assistant or some rising star at a smaller school?
</P>
<P>
   Kevin, who ``would'' you hire? &QL; 
Hard at work
</P>
<P>
   ASU's athletic director gazed out at the field where his
59-year-old coach was directing a spirited practice. The Sun Devils
open at home Sept. 6 against Texas Tech. Since the end of last
year's 5-6 season, Snyder has eagerly awaited the day when he can
return to the field and begin again. His resolve is not unlike a
clench-jawed prizefighter who gets knocked down and then hops to
his feet and impatiently takes a mandatory standing eight count.
</P>
<P>
   During the summer Snyder met twice a week with his seniors and
selected underclassmen. They discussed the importance of
leadership, a missing ingredient last year. Snyder thought about
the opening game. He knows (remember Washington?) that the opener
can set the tone for the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm reading everything I can about Texas Tech on the
internet,'' Snyder said before the workout. The ASU coach sat
behind the wheel of a cart, smiling into the morning sunshine. ``I
figure half of it's true.''
</P>
<P>
   Always organized, the clock always ticking in his head, Snyder
can't stop wondering what other coaches are up to. ``I check
(Tech's) practice schedule. I see they're scrimmaging on Tuesdays
and Saturdays. I'm thinking, `Why are they doing ``that''?' ''
</P>
<P>
   Kevin, who would you hire?
</P>
<P>
   Coach and athletic director share a mutual admiration and
respect. They were together that night in Houston when Snyder won
the 1996 national Coach of the Year award. The Devils had gone 11-0
and were headed to the Rose Bowl. White heard the pride and
conviction in his coach's voice as Snyder, dressed in a tuxedo,
told the audience that coaching is ``the single-best profession in
the world.''
</P>
<P>
   In the what-have-you-done-for-me-lately world of sports, fans
have short memories. Some ASU supporters grouse to White about last
season. Some question Snyder's coaching.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like he never knew Xs and Os,'' White said. ``It borders
on the comical to me.''
</P>
<P>
   So who would fill Snyder's shoes? &QL; 
Kind words
</P>
<P>
   White answered not with a name but a glowing testimonial. ``I
don't think Bruce ``is'' replaceable,'' he said. ``We've won 25
games the last three years. That puts us tied (in the Pac 10) with
UCLA. . . . With Bruce I believe we have a chance to finally turn
the corner and have a lot of fun in the next decade and make a lot
of noise.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bruce is at the top of his game right now. He is
task-oriented. Steady. Unflappable. Experienced. I appreciate his
vision. He is proud. Thoughtful.
</P>
<P>
   ``He does things his way, but he's also flexible. . . . He
relates to every generation and every situation. And I don't know
anyone more passionate about the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Work ethic? ``Check our parking lot,'' White said. ``His is the
first car in and the last car out. I'm impressed with what he has
created the last six months. If you're around him you know he has
strong focus, and a sense of urgency.''
</P>
<P>
   Kevin White will tell anyone who asks that his man is the right
man for the job, now and for a long, long time. But
``irreplaceabl''e? Goodness, how often does a college athletic
director say that, for the record, about his coach?
</P>
<P>
   If I were Bruce, I would clip out the quote.
</P>
<P>
   And save it. &QL; 
David Casstevens can be reached at (602) 444-8635 or at
david.casstevens(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-28-99 2324EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
