<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-28 23:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3228 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s BC-FBC-ARIZONA-OVERVIEW-     08-28 1008
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-ARIZONA-OVERVIEW-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOOTBALL AT UA FIGHTS FAMILIAR FOE  
 BASKETBALL IS STILL KING IN TUCSON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By NORM FRAUENHEIM  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TUCSON - In various preseason polls, Arizona was ranked high
enough to believe it has a shot at being No. 1.
</P>
<P>
   In the nation.
</P>
<P>
   But in Tucson?
</P>
<P>
   The Wildcats' chances at being No. 1 in the football nation
might be a lot less daunting than their hopes of ever being tops in
Pima County, basketball country.
</P>
<P>
   Fair or not, Tucson is labeled a basketball town. Arizona
Athletic Director Jim Livengood argues that the label isn't
incorrect so much as it is incomplete.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think Tucson is a basketball town,'' he said before
the fourth-ranked Wildcats tested their preseason credentials at
third-ranked Penn State on Saturday in the Pigskin Classic. ``It's
a success town.''
</P>
<P>
   The city got hooked on basketball simply because of consistent
brilliance under Coach Lute Olson. The Wildcats won the national
title in 1997. They've been to the Final Four three times. The
school and the town have taken on the basketball identity because a
tradition is firmly in place.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, Livengood and others are convinced there is room
for more than one.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before the great run of success with Coach Olson, Tucson was
always a football town,'' said Don Harris, a former Maricopa County
Attorney who holds undergraduate and law degrees from Arizona.
``When I was down there in the early 1960s, football was the going
thing.''
</P>
<P>
   The bet is that football can equal basketball's popularity with
a 1999 season that would build on last year's surprising 12-1
record, including a Holiday Bowl victory over Nebraska.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Livengood says he detects that the city is poised to
embrace Arizona football as it has basketball for more than a
decade. Season-ticket sales are reported to be good by UA
standards: more than 24,000.
</P>
<P>
   The record is 27,700, which was set in 1994 when the Wildcats
graced ``Sports Illustrate''d's cover as the magazine's No. 1
preseason pick. Arizona officials hope to surpass the 1994 mark by
the Sept. 11 home opener against lightly regarded Middle Tennessee
State.
</P>
<P>
   Average attendance last year _ Arizona's finest football season
ever _ was 50,206, which ranks fifth on the school's all-time list.
The top four: 56,562 in 1994, 54,074 in 1990, 51,749 in 1995 and
50,761 in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   The optimism is not without caution. A couple of losses against
Penn State and then Texas Christian on Sept. 5 would probably blow
a hole in attendance projections. Unlike the basketball
congregation, Arizona football is followed by the hopeful, yet
skeptical.
</P>
<P>
   There was disappointment in 1994 when the Wildcats did not live
up to impossible expectations. And there is still that elusive Rose
Bowl. Arizona is the only Pacific-10 Conference school that hasn't
made the postseason trip to Pasadena.
</P>
<P>
   There is no magic marketing that can dispel the lingering
skepticism, according to junior quarterback Ortege Jenkins, who
spent a couple of seasons on the basketball roster. Jenkins agrees
that the basketball aura is hard to overcome.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's true,'' he said. ``We had a great football season last
year, but it was kind of overshadowed because of the national
championship and then the Pacific-10 Conference titles in
basketball.''
</P>
<P>
   Tucson's ambivalence toward football was unmistakable after the
Wildcats fell to UCLA in their lone loss before a sold-out Arizona
Stadium crowd of 58,738.
</P>
<P>
   Despite a quick turnaround the next week at Oregon State, empty
seats became the norm at Arizona Stadium. There were more than
12,000 empties for an impressive victory over Oregon, then
nationally ranked, in a battle for second place in the conference.
</P>
<P>
   The Oregon game happened to coincide with Halloween. Arizona
Coach Dick Tomey, pragmatic as ever, said he wasn't surprised at
the crowd. He said he would have watched the game on television and
taken his kids trick-or-treating, too.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it's hard to imagine empty seats at McKale Center for a
basketball game on any day. Tomey bristles at attendance
comparisons. Arizona Stadium has between four and five times as
many seats as McKale Center.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, Livengood is convinced the larger number of
football seats can become as valuable as the ones for basketball.
On the one hand, Livengood says, there's an increase in interest
because Arizona has discovered an offense with Jenkins, fellow
quarterback Keith Smith and running back Trung Canidate.
</P>
<P>
   Defense might win games, but points on the scoreboard win at the
box office. It's no coincidence, perhaps, that ads in Arizona's
sales pitch this summer have featured one defensive player,
linebacker Marcus Bell, alongside Jenkins, Smith and Canidate.
</P>
<P>
   Livengood also is borrowing from professional sports, which have
turned to a variety of ways to sell the product. The game is just
part of a package that includes music, fireworks, food and a
variety of other bells and whistles.
</P>
<P>
   ``In this day and age of discretionary income, people want to be
entertained,'' said Livengood, who is looking forward to the
unveiling of a $2.9-million, state-of-the-art scoreboard at the
Sept. 11 home opener.
</P>
<P>
   But Jenkins remains convinced that, in the end, only one formula
works:
</P>
<P>
   Win, and they will come.
</P>
<P>
   ``From this point on, I really believe we will be a
well-balanced school between football and basketball,'' he said.
``In football, we've got a lot of young guys who are just getting
started. Coach Tomey and this team are on the rise.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're starting to set a standard. In Tucson, people are just
used to winning in basketball. It's something that's been a pattern
for so many years. But for as long as I'm here and Keith is here,
we're going to try to set the standard.
</P>
<P>
   ``By doing that, we can let our friends, younger players and
recruits know that something is going on.''
</P>
<P>
   By doing that, more than just something goes on. It becomes
tradition. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
