<SLUG> BC-FBC-NAU-OVERVIEW-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LUMBERJACKS READY TO MAKE A NEW START 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By AL TOBY  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   FLAGSTAFF, ARiz. - If imitation is the best form of flattery,
then the football officials at Montana might blush when they look
at NAU.
</P>
<P>
   Much of NAU's coaching staff has ties to the Big Sky perennial
power. NAU second-year Coach Jerome Souers, offensive coordinator
Brent Pease and co-defensive coordinator Corey Batoon spent a total
of 21 years in Missoula. Running backs coach Josh Branen didn't
coach there but starred in the Grizzlies' backfield as the school's
third all-time leading rusher.
</P>
<P>
   Souers will be the first to admit that he isn't trying to turn
NAU into Montana but he does want to bring its winning tradition to
Flagstaff.
</P>
<P>
   He appears to have the Lumberjacks poised to make a
full-throttle run at the Grizzlies, the preseason favorite to win
the conference for a second straight year. The Lumberjacks were
projected to finish second in the same media/coaches poll.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're excited about this season for a lot of reasons,'' Souers
said. ``We're looking forward to having some fun.''
</P>
<P>
   The fun began for Souers and the Lumberjacks when running back
Ronney Jenkins transferred to NAU from Brigham Young. Jenkins was
Flagstaff-bound after he got kicked off BYU's team for violating
the school's honor code.
</P>
<P>
   With new scenery and a fresh start, Jenkins should make a
significant impact in the backfield alongside Marcus King. In his
last year at BYU, Jenkins rushed for 1,307 yards. It was the second
highest output in school history.
</P>
<P>
   Jenkins, a soft-spoken 22-year-old whom Souers describes as a
silent leader, said he hasn't noticed the change in level of play
from Division I-A to I-AA.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not that big of a difference,'' Jenkins said. ``They have
good athletes on both ends. I see the same ability on this team as
I did at BYU. (The lineman) are just as big as the linemen I played
with at BYU.''
</P>
<P>
   Conference defensive coordinators will have their targets locked
on Jenkins. This should free up senior quarterback Travis Brown, a
four-year starter and one of 17 returning starters. In his freshman
and sophomore seasons, Brown threw for a combined 6,793 yards,
breaking Steve McNair's record for combined passing yardage in his
freshman and sophomore seasons.
</P>
<P>
   But last year's coaching change from Steve Axman to Souers and
an elbow injury took their toll. Brown threw for a career-low 1,550
yards and 12 touchdowns as NAU fell to a tie for seventh in the Big
Sky (3-5, 6-5 overall).
</P>
<P>
   Souers said the onus will fall on Brown to rebound in order to
free up some running room for Jenkins.
</P>
<P>
   Although the offense will get most of the headlines, Souers
wants his defense to personify the team's overall blue-collar
attitude.
</P>
<P>
   That attitude begins with the team's new uniforms. The
Lumberjacks changed their traditional yellow helmets to a solid
dark blue with a black trim.
</P>
<P>
   ``Black and blue, that's how we want to leave them,'' said
defensive end Lynne Ray Smith.
</P>
<P>
   The defense has nicknamed themselves ``The Family.'' Their
familial resolve was displayed at NAU's football media day. When
asked who the head of the clan was, Smith replied, ``No one, it's a
family.''
</P>
<P>
   While Smith did most of the talking, the unit's de facto
patriarch may have been one of its quietest members, senior
linebacker Afa Faraimo. After posting a team-high 118 tackles, 6{
sacks, five fumble recoveries and an interception last year, he was
being touted as a Buchanan Award candidate, given to I-AA's best
defensive player.
</P>
<P>
   But Faraimo's play this season will reflect his quiet mood at
media day. The Lumberjacks lost their best defensive player for the
entire season when Faraimo tore his anterior cruciate ligament at
practice.
</P>
<P>
   Souers said, ``We expect Afa to contribute to our program in
other ways, such as serving in a mentorship capacity with our young
linebackers, and I know he will be well-received in that role.''
</P>
<P>
   The Lumberjacks, who last qualified for the playoffs in 1996,
garnered a No. 22 ranking in the preseason Sports Network Top 25
poll for I-AA teams, but Souers isn't interested in the ranking.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll just as soon have our pads do the talking,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
