<SLUG> BC-FBC-PAC10-OVERVIEW-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIME FOR PAC-10 TO PROVE WORTH  
 CHANCE TO MAKE NATIONAL SPLASH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PAOLA BOIVIN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, Ariz. - It has been victimized by an East Coast bias and
its own competitive balance. But the Pac-10 Conference hasn't done
itself any favors recently in the quest for national respect.
</P>
<P>
   It's a put-up-or-shut-up year for the league.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona's meeting with Penn State isn't the only opportunity for
the Pac-10 to test its mettle nationally. Arizona State and
Southern California get a shot at Notre Dame; UCLA visits Ohio
State; Washington hosts Colorado; and California travels to
Nebraska.
</P>
<P>
   In 21 years, the league has had just one national champion, the
1991 Washington Huskies. The Trojans alone won five titles from
1962 to 1978. And the Pac-10 has lost six of the past nine Rose
Bowls.
</P>
<P>
   The last Heisman Trophy winner was  &UR; Marcus Allen in 1981. In the
two previous decades, the conference contributed seven: &UR; O.J.
Simpson, &UR; 
 &UR; Charles White,  &UR; Mike Garrett,  &UR; Jim Plunkett,  &UR; Gary Beban,  &UR; Terry
Baker and Allen.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's important for the conference to keep putting
itself in a situation to win games against nationally recognized
opponents,'' Golden Bears Coach  &UR; Tom Holmoe said. ``It's doesn't
make any sense to shy away from the challenge.''
</P>
<P>
   The expectations have been there. ASU made the top 10 of several
preseason polls in 1998 but couldn't even break .500. The Wildcats
were ``Sports Illustrated's'' No. 1 team in 1994 yet finished 8-4.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins blew their chance last season by wiping out everyone
on their schedule except Miami in the regular-season finale.
</P>
<P>
   ``No excuses,'' UCLA Coach  &UR; Bob Toledo said. ``We could have won
the game and didn't. Although our priority was our team and our
fans, it reflected on the conference.'' &QL; 
He looks familiar . . .
</P>
<P>
   Quick, name the starting quarterbacks for Oregon, UCLA,
California and Washington State.
</P>
<P>
   What? Having trouble? You're not alone. All are new starters and
most weren't named until this week.
</P>
<P>
   One of the biggest surprises is the Golden Bears'  &UR; Samuel
Clemons, who didn't allow freshman prodigy  &UR; Kyle Boller to unseat
him. It probably will happen in the future, but for California's
opener against Rutgers on Saturday, Clemons will start.
</P>
<P>
   The hype surrounding Boller, who was ranked as the No. 1 high
school player by several recruiting services, proved to be too much
for the Bears' other scholarship quarterbacks _ freshman  &UR; Ryan
Sorahan and redshirt freshman  &UR; David Page _ and they left the
program.
</P>
<P>
   Clemons felt it was worth sticking around. Although he passed
for just 2 yards in his college career, he is beginning his third
year with the program and is comfortable with the system, even
though new coordinator  &UR; Steve Hagen has abandoned the West Coast
offense.
</P>
<P>
   UCLA's Toledo said he has settled on junior &UR; Drew Bennett for the
Bruins' Saturday opener against Boise State.  &UR; Cory Paus was named
the backup although he is expected to play in UCLA's first two
games.
</P>
<P>
   Bennett came to Westwood as a walk-on who had been recruited by
Princeton and a handful of Division III schools. Although he threw
only 11 passes as &UR; Cade McNown's backup, his athleticism and
knowledge of the offense made the difference.
</P>
<P>
   Oregon's  &UR; Mike Belotti named junior &UR; A.J. Feeley as his starter
for Friday's game at Michigan State but said sophomore  &UR; Joey
Harrington will take snaps as well.
</P>
<P>
   And Washington State has settled on  &UR; Steve Birnbaum, who shared
time with  &UR; Paul Mencke last season, but word is Coach  &UR; Mike Price
has not discounted the more mobile  &UR; Jason Gesser, a redshirt
freshman. &QL; 
DeShaun's de man &QL; 
Remember all that talk about  &UR; DeShaun Foster being the Bruins' No.
3 tailback? Forget about it.
</P>
<P>
   The move was an obvious attempt by Toledo to take pressure off
his sophomore sensation. But the coach recently gave in and named
him the starter. With good reason.
</P>
<P>
   Remember what he did as a freshman in Tucson last season? He
rushed for 118 yards, including a 37-yard scoring run, and returned
a kickoff 45 yards that set up the drive that won the game.
</P>
<P>
   Quick hits
</P>
<P>
   The Pac-10 has four candidates for the Jim Thorpe Award, which
recognizes the nation's premier defensive back: ASU's  &UR; Courtney
 &UR; Jackson, USC's &UR; Antuan Simmons, Stanford's  &UR; Tim Smith and Washington
State's  &UR; Lamont Thompson. The league has had two winners: Arizona's
 &UR; Darryl Lewis in 1990 and USC's  &UR; Mark Carrier in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   The league returns 64 percent of last season's starters. It
averaged 58 percent the past three years.
</P>
<P>
   New Washington Coach &UR; Rick Neuheisel still holds the NCAA
single-game record for highest percentage of passes completed: 25
of 27 for UCLA in 1983.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
