<HEADER>
A3233 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s BC-FBC-PAC10-CAPSULES-AZ     08-28 1581
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-PAC10-CAPSULES-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PAC-10 CAPSULE PREVIEWS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PAOLA BOIVIN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Team-by-team look at the Pac-10, in predicted order of finish: &QL; 
 &UR; Arizona Wildcats
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COACH:  &UR; Dick Tomey
</P>
<P>
   &UR; 1998 RECORD: 12-1 overall, 7-1 Pac-10
</P>
<P>
   &UR; STARTERS RETURNING: Six offense, nine defense.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE GOOD: The Wildcats return the heart of their offense:
quarterbacks  &UR; Ortege Jenkins and  &UR; Keith Smith, wide receiver
 &UR; Dennis
 &UR; Northcutt and running back  &UR; Trung Candidate, the Pac-10's leading
rusher with 1,220 yards. Nine starters return from a defense that
ranked second in the conference.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE BAD: He's just one player, but All-America cornerback
 &UR; Chris
 &UR; McAlister will be missed. The Wildcats start a new left tackle and
lack depth at wide receiver.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE UNKNOWN: Can returning place kicker  &UR; Mark McDonald improve
on his 8-of-17 success rate on field goals? How will Arizona handle
all the preseason hype that seemed to undo its neighbor to the
north a season ago? &QL; 
 &UR; USC Trojans
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COACH:  &UR; Paul Hackett
</P>
<P>
   &UR; 1998 RECORD: 8-5 overall, 5-3 Pac-10.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; STARTERS RETURNING: Nine offense, six defense.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE GOOD: The entire offensive line returns. The Trojans have
the depth at tailback for which they're known;  &UR; Chad Morton and
 &UR; Sultan
 &UR; McCullough are a dangerous one-two punch. All Pac-10 pick  &UR; Ennis
Davis is back at defensive tackle.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE BAD: Lack of depth at wide receiver. The loss of  &UR; Chris
Claiborne at middle linebacker will hurt more than most think. The
secondary features three new starters.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE UNKNOWN: How will the Trojans respond to Hackett's plan to
open up the offense? If quarterback  &UR; Carson Palmer plays to his
potential, USC will be dangerous. But if he makes some of the
mistakes he did as a true freshman last season, he could cost the
Trojans a game.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; UCLA Bruins
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COACH:  &UR; Bob Toledo
</P>
<P>
   &UR; 1998 RECORD: 10-2 overall, 8-0 Pac-10
</P>
<P>
   &UR; STARTERS RETURNING: six offense, eight defense.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE GOOD: UCLA's receivers are among the best in the nation,
and senior flanker  &UR; Danny Farmer is as sure-handed as they come.
The Bruins are deep at tailback. Their top three are back, with
hotshot sophomore
 &UR; DeShaun Foster jumping from No. 3 to starter.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE BAD: The Bruins must fill the big shoes left by
quarterback &UR; Cade
 &UR; McNown. An inexperienced offensive line will not make it any easier
for the new starter. UCLA will miss  &UR; Chris Sailer, who was a
standout punter and place kicker.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE UNKNOWN: Eleven players are suspended for the first two
games. How much will this set back the team against Boise State and
Ohio State? UCLA's defense struggled often last season. Is new
coordinator
 &UR; Bob Field the answer?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Arizona State Sun Devils
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COACH:  &UR; Bruce Snyder
</P>
<P>
   &UR; 1998 RECORD: 5-6 overall, 4-4 Pac-10
</P>
<P>
   &UR; STARTERS RETURNING: Seven offense, eight defense.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE GOOD: The Sun Devils return one of the league's best
quarterbacks,  &UR; Ryan Kealy, and running backs,  &UR; J.R. Redmond.
Experience on the defensive front should make ASU more effective
rushing the passer. The Sun Devils seem confident, but without the
swagger of last season.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE BAD: Injuries and suspensions have depleted the team at
wide receiver. Questions remain about how effective the linebackers
can be.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE UNKNOWN: How quickly can ASU's junior college transfers
make an impact? Have the Sun Devils shaken off the effects of last
season's disappointing finish? &QL; 
 &UR; Oregon Ducks
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COACH:  &UR; Mike Bellotti
</P>
<P>
   &UR; 1998 RECORD: 8-4 overall, 5-3 Pac-10.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; STARTERS RETURNING: Six offense, seven defense.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE GOOD: The Ducks return seven starters (all juniors and
seniors) on defense. Tailback  &UR; Reuben Droughns is back after
missing the last six games of 1998 because of a broken leg.  &UR; Nathan
Villegas came out of nowhere to be one of the nation's top kickers
last season.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE BAD: Quarterback  &UR; Akili Smith is long gone, and his
replacement was up for grabs until junior  &UR; A.J. Feeley got the nod
late in camp. It's not a good sign when you're closing in on your
opener and you're not sure who your top tight end and one of your
two receivers are going to be. Valley product  &UR; Rashad Bauman went
down with a knee injury during spring practice and is expected to
miss the season, making the Ducks suddenly inexperienced at
cornerback.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE UNKNOWN: The Ducks have a killer stretch of
back-to-back-to-back road games at Washington, UCLA and Arizona.
How they fare during that stretch could determine whether they
attend a bowl game again.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; Washington Huskies
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COACH:  &UR; Rick Neuheisel
</P>
<P>
   &UR; 1998 RECORD: 6-6 overall, 4-4 Pac-10.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; STARTERS RETURNING: five on offense, eight on defense
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE GOOD:  &UR; Jabari Issa and  &UR; Mac Tuiaea, two of the better
tackles in the league, anchor the Huskies' new 3-4 defensive front.
Three returning defensive backs should make this group better than
the one that managed only five interceptions last season.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE BAD: The offense will be loaded with new faces. The biggest
concern is the offensive line, where three new starters must be
replaced. Most of the backfield, including the quarterback, is new
as well.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE UNKNOWN: Neuheisel is a big fan of quarterback &UR; Marques
 &UR; Tuiasosopo. If the junior plays to his potential, the coach likes
their chances. How will Neuheisel and his team respond to playing
Colorado, the school he left for Washington, three weeks into the
season?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; COACH:  &UR; Tom Holmoe
</P>
<P>
   &UR; 1998 RECORD: 5-6 overall, 3-5 Pac-10.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; STARTERS RETURNING: Seven offense, seven defense.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE GOOD: The Bears may have one of the best defenses in the
conference. They get a lot of mileage out of linebackers  &UR; Sekou
Sanyika and  &UR; Matt Beck. Three starters return on the offensive
line, which should be improved. The players seem to believe in
Holmoe.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE BAD: Cal scored an average of only 16.6 points last season
and with a rookie quarterback set to take over, it's hard to
believe much will change early on. The Bears also need to replace
standout receiver
 &UR; Dameane Douglas.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE UNKNOWN: The impact new offensive coordinator  &UR; Steve Hagen
has on this team could go a long way in determining its success. If
freshman quarterback sensation  &UR; Kyle Boller blossoms early, the
Bears could be in great shape.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; Stanford Cardinal
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COACH:  &UR; Tyrone Willingham
</P>
<P>
   &UR; 1998 RECORD: 3-8 overall, 2-6 Pac-10.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; STARTERS RETURNING: Nine offense, 10 defense.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE GOOD: With 19 starters returning, the Cardinal will win
games because of its experience. Willingham is encouraged by the
improvements senior quarterback  &UR; Todd Husak made in the off-season.
Stanford's arsenal of receivers, led by &UR; Troy Walters, who caught 52
passes in only six full games last year, heads a top-flight
receiving corps, will be hard to defend.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE BAD: There is no convincing argument that the Pac-10's
worst running team will be any more effective this season. The 19
returning starters led Stanford to a 3-8 record last season. The
schedule is a killer, especially three of the first four games: at
Texas, Washington State, at Arizona and UCLA.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE UNKNOWN: Will the defensive changes that the Cardinal made
be for the better?  &UR; Riall Johnson, the top pass rusher last season,
has moved from defensive end to outside linebacker. Standout &UR; Tim
Smith moves from free to strong safety. Willingham has managed just
eight wins the past two seasons. Is his job in danger?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; Oregon State Beavers
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COACH:  &UR; Dennis Erickson
</P>
<P>
   &UR; 1998 RECORD: 5-6 overall, 2-6 Pac-10.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; STARTERS RETURNING: Six offense, five defense.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE GOOD: &UR; Ken Simonton came out of nowhere last season to be
one of the Pac-10's top rushers. A strong group of junior college
transfers will help plug some holes. Free safety  &UR; Terrence Carroll
is one of the better defensive backs in the conference. Erickson's
presence has been a boost for team morale.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE BAD: The defense needs to replace its starting ends and two
linebackers. Depth is a concern on the offensive line and at
cornerback.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE UNKNOWN: What will starting the season against Nevada,
Fresno State and Georgia Southern do for the team's confidence?
Help it? Give it a false sense of security? How will sophomore
 &UR; Jonathan Smith, who stepped in late last season, fare now that
he's been handed the reins?
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COACH:  &UR; Mike Price
</P>
<P>
   &UR; 1998 RECORD: 3-8 overall, 0-8 Pac-10.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; STARTERS RETURNING: Seven offense, nine defense.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE GOOD: It's hard to find a better group of receivers in the
league.  &UR; Nian Taylor and  &UR; Leaford Hackett combined for 99
receptions and 1,527 yards last season. JC transfer  &UR; Milton Wynn is
expected to find his way into the lineup as well. Junior free
safety  &UR; Lamont Thompson had four interceptions last year.
Linebacker  &UR; Steve Gleason, who had 70 tackles last season, has
lived through this team's highs and lows.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE BAD: The Cougars will start the season with quarterback
 &UR; Steve
 &UR; Birnbaum, who wasn't particularly convincing in that spot last
season, throwing 11 interceptions vs. six touchdowns. The team
lacks depth at cornerback. Keeping players eligible and out of
trouble may prove the coach's biggest challenge.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE UNKNOWN: The difference this season could be two young
players: redshirt freshman quarterback  &UR; Jason Gesser and freshman
tailback  &UR; Dion
 &UR; Burnett. If both manage to work their way into the lineup, the
Cougars' chances improve. Washington State needs to take advantage
of seven home games.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
