<SLUG> BC-FBC-NATIONAL-OUTLOOK-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
QB OR NOT QB: COACHES ARE SCRAMBLING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By KENT SOMERS  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   From Los Angeles to Ann Arbor, Mich., to Manhattan, Kan., so
many coaches spent this preseason searching for starting
quarterbacks that they could have formed a support group.
</P>
<P>
   UCLA is trying to replace &UR; Cade McNown. Michigan Coach &UR; Lloyd Carr
is deciding between veteran  &UR; Tom Brady and sophomore hotshot  &UR; Drew
 &UR; Henson. Kansas State Coach  &UR; Bill Snyder is evaluating four
contenders to replace  &UR; Michael Bishop. Oregon is trying to survive
life without
 &UR; Akili Smith.
</P>
<P>
   The coaches' decisions could well determine the outcome of the
season. Get a guy with a little magic, like Tennessee's  &UR; Tee
Martin, McNown or Bishop, and he can make up for a lot of other
weaknesses.
</P>
<P>
   Pick someone whose knees start knocking in the fourth quarter,
and the alumni are handing you Realtors' business cards. But just
because a quarterback starts the season doesn't mean he'll be there
for every game. At Penn State, Alabama and Texas, phenoms wait just
off stage. Sophomore  &UR; Austin Moherman will start at quarterback
today for Ohio State when it meets Miami, but that doesn't mean
Coach  &UR; John Cooper will hesitate using  &UR; Steve Bellisari, another
sophomore, if the need arises.
</P>
<P>
   ``I cannot tell you right now in my mind who I think the best
quarterback is, but we think the one who deserves to start in this
first ballgame is Austin,'' Cooper said.
</P>
<P>
   Cooper has played two quarterbacks before.  &UR; Joe Germaine and
 &UR; Stanley Wilson shared the job for the two seasons prior to last
year. Cooper is not entering the season thinking the pair will
share the job.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of it will be based on feel, a gut decision that you
make during the ballgame,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Snyder hasn't picked a replace ment for Bishop, although junior
 &UR; Jonathan Beasley from Glendale Cactus High is regarded as the
front-runner.
</P>
<P>
   Four players are auditioning for the job, but Beasley doesn't
sound worried about the possibility of replacing Bishop, a junior
college transfer who led the Wildcats to the Big 12 championship
game last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Michael was a great athlete, what can I say?'' he said. ``He
could run and throw and do it all. But he wasn't here in the
program as long as we've been. We've got a better feel for the
offense.'' &QL; 
No fashion sense
</P>
<P>
   BYU has redesigned its uniforms and altered the school colors,
upsetting some fans. Gone is the white helmet and the blue decal.
The school has gone to a deeper shade of blue, accented by tan.
</P>
<P>
   Linebacker  &UR; Rob Morris was listening to fans complain on a radio
talk show and was irritated. He did an interview with the station
later that day and said fans should realize times have changed.
</P>
<P>
   `` &UR; Jim McMahon's not coming back. &UR; Steve Young's not coming back.
Get over it,'' he said. &QL; 
Strange bedfellows
</P>
<P>
   Washington Coach  &UR; Rick Neuheisel is a free thinker, but it still
seems strange that the two college coaches he admires most are Penn
State's  &UR; Joe Paterno and Florida's  &UR; Steve Spurrier. Those two
couldn't be more different, but Neuheisel has his reasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``Paterno is like royalty,'' Neuheisel said. ``Maybe it's the
way he embraced me the first time I met him. He made me feel such a
part of the game. It validated me.
</P>
<P>
   ``Spurrier . . . I love his bravado. I love the way he trusts
himself. If there is one thing that sets him apart from most
coaches is that he doesn't worry about what anyone else thinks.
</P>
<P>
   ``You look at his offensive schemes, they weren't a product of a
lot of staff time. They are a product of him saying, `I'm going to
do this,' and cutting through all the red tape.'' &QL; 
Quiet life
</P>
<P>
   Wisconsin running back  &UR; Ron Dayne needs 1,717 yards to become
college football's all-time leading rusher, surpassing &UR; Ricky
Williams' mark of 6,279 yards. But that's not the reason Dayne
decided to stay for his senior year.
</P>
<P>
   Dayne, who is from the southern part of New Jersey, stayed
because he likes Madison, Wis., and is no hurry to join the
high-pressure world of the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   ``My freshman year, my friends from Jersey stopped at a light to
ask for directions,'' Dayne told the ``Philadelphia Inquirer.''
``They had tinted windows on their car. There was an old lady
walking by. They let the windows down, and she came right up to the
car and said, `Hey, guys, how ya doing?'
</P>
<P>
   ``They came to me and said, `Yo, this lady told us where you
stayed, where you were at, how to get there.' That shocked me. In
Philly, you don't walk up to a car with tinted windows. You walk
backwards.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-28-99 2338EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
