A3235 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BBO-BASECOL-LADN     08-28 0598
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-BASECOL-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THROW IN THE TOWEL ON PARK? NOT JUST YET
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ So he hit two batters in the first four innings
and occasionally looked as lost as he has at any time during this
difficult season.
</P>
<P>
   Chan Ho Park won a game at Dodger Stadium on Saturday. That is
big news around here.
</P>
<P>
   Not only did he come in with an 0-6 record and a 5.86 ERA at
home, Park was doing it in a climate where no one's job is safe for
next year.
</P>
<P>
   Park, who won 29 games the past two years, could be traded for a
Jeromy Burnitz or for part of a bigger deal that could include
Florida's Cliff Floyd. Park so often has suffered from
inconsistency and self-doubt that many think he has gone from star
to fourth starter overnight.
</P>
<P>
   The offers will be good this winter and a fresh start might be
helpful to both sides.
</P>
<P>
   That's a trigger the Los Angeles Dodgers shouldn't pull.
</P>
<P>
   When he retired Jeff Reed and struck out Jose Nieves with the
bases loaded to end the eighth inning, he made that point. For all
his problems this year, Park's 4-3 victory over the Chicago Cubs
proved he is a keeper.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody wants Eric Young or Davon White. There is minimal
interest in Eric Karros. Gary Sheffield has a contract laced with
concrete. Raul Mondesi needs a wakeup call before he gets on with
his career.
</P>
<P>
   As poorly as Park has pitched, he represents an anchor for the
Dodgers. When you think about how bad the club's starters have done
this season, remember that the 4.54 team ERA is only
middle-of-the-road in the National League.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers were spoiled by great pitching over the years. They
had a big ballpark with distant power allies and vast foul
territory. And at night, when the air gets heavy, a team of Sammy
Sosas couldn't hit one out.
</P>
<P>
   If someone has to go it needs to be Ismael Valdes, who has
improved his standing this year even though he went seven starts
without a victory before Friday.
</P>
<P>
   When you are dealing with Park you aren't talking about
potential. You are looking at an established pitcher who has
stumbled. Some think his throwing during last January's Asian Games
after a long season was damaging.
</P>
<P>
   He came back this year a different pitcher, rarely trusting his
95 mph fastball. He often seemed timid in tight spots.
</P>
<P>
   And though he bristles at every mention of the four-year, $32
million contract he turned down last spring, Park left an obscene
amount of money on the table that could take years to recoup.
</P>
<P>
   He is making $2.3 million this season and probably won't do
better than $4 million next February in arbitration.
</P>
<P>
   But it should never come to that.
</P>
<P>
   At the top of GM Kevin Malone's long to-do list should be
repairing the damage Park did to himself and the team this year.
</P>
<P>
   Malone, who has a good rapport with players and agents, should
not punish Park by letting the contract talks get to arbitration.
</P>
<P>
   Malone, despite all the Fox resources, was wise not to bite at
Park's outrageous contract proposal of four years for $40 million.
</P>
<P>
   But now comes the hard part.
</P>
<P>
   It is still hard to imagine Park, the same pitcher who went 8-1
last July and August, could be available. But teams were asking
about him at the trade deadline and they will be asking again in
the offseason.
</P>
<P>
   Any team that is 10 games under .500 and didn't compete all
season has to return phone calls.
</P>
<P>
   Malone cannot afford to let Park's fragile psyche reach next
season.
</P>
<P>
   But he can't afford to lose him, either.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
