<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-28 23:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3237 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s BC-FBC-REPUBLIC-TOP-25-A     08-28 1580
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-REPUBLIC-TOP-25-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE ARIZONA REPUBLIC'S TOP 25 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By KENT SOMERS  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; Florida State
</P>
<P>
   As usual, Coach  &UR; Bobby Bowden has more NFL prospects than
anyone. Unfortunately, they don't hand out championship rings for
that. It gnaws at Bowden that he's had all that talent and only one
dad gum national title to show for it. That will change this season
if the Seminoles don't have their usual slip-up.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Florida State lost early (N.C. State) and late
(Tennessee in the Fiesta Bowl). The common thread was that
quarterback &UR; 
 &UR; Chris Weinke didn't play well (N.C. State) or at all (Tennessee).
If Weinke can successfully come back from a neck injury, and if the
'Noles find some corners who don't get beat deep, Bowden will get
his other ring. &QL; 
 &UR; Tennessee
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Coach  &UR; Philip Fulmer sold the Vols on the belief that
no one outside the state thought they had a chance to win the
national title. The Vols bought into it like a hot mutual fund and
beat Florida State in the Fiesta Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Quarterback  &UR; Tee Martin and tailback  &UR; Jamal Lewis return.
 &UR; Peerless
 &UR; Price is gone, but Tennessee has a factory out back where it
produces big-play receivers. What really hurts, however, is the
loss of middle linebacker &UR; Al Wilson, their spiritual leader.
National title hopes, again, will rest largely on the ability to
beat Florida and win the SEC. &QL; 
 &UR; Florida
</P>
<P>
   The Gators weren't good enough to play ball the way Coach &UR; Steve
 &UR; Spurrier wanted last year. The passing game didn't scare anyone,
and word is that some of the defensive starters were saving
themselves for the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   Don't look for this to happen again. Spurrier has tightened his
visor, and with games against Tennessee and Florida State at home,
the Gators could be primed for another national title run. &QL; 
 &UR; Penn State
</P>
<P>
   They say you win championships with defense, and  &UR; Joe Paterno
has the country's best this season: Nine seniors starting on that
side of the ball.
</P>
<P>
   But can the Nittany Lions score enough to contend for a title?
Somewhere along the line, the quarterback usually has to win a game
late. Senior  &UR; Kevin Thompson hasn't inspired confidence in Penn
State followers. &QL; 
 &UR; Texas A&AMP;M
</P>
<P>
   The Aggies lost the opener last year to Florida State and
quietly were shoved out of the national championship picture. But
they salvaged the season, finishing 11-3 and winning the Big 12
title.
</P>
<P>
   Linebacker  &UR; Dat Nguyen, who played college ball for what seemed
like 24 years, is gone. But 18 other starters are back, including
QB  &UR; Randy
 &UR; McCown, who has a knack for making big plays. &QL; 
 &UR; Arizona
</P>
<P>
   Coach  &UR; Dick Tomey was adamant that the Wildcats didn't schedule
Penn State in the opener with an eye toward a national title run.
Maybe not, but this was a win-win situation for the Wildcats.
</P>
<P>
   Win and the Wildcats could move into the top 2 in the polls.
Lose and you still have 11 more games to play, plenty of time to
recover. Tomey has his best offensive team in years, with QBs
 &UR; Keith Smith and
 &UR; Ortege Jenkins, running back  &UR; Trung Canidate and receivers  &UR; Dennis
 &UR; Northcutt and  &UR; Brad Brennan. The key will be avoiding injuries and
having the corners hold up. &QL; 
 &UR; Nebraska
</P>
<P>
   The temptation is to blame injuries for last season's 9-4
record, and there is some validity to that. Quarterback  &UR; Bobby
Newcombe and I-back  &UR; DeAngelo Evans were healthy for all of about
five minutes.
</P>
<P>
   But some long-time Husker observers think the talent level in
the program has dropped over the past few years. By midseason last
year, no one was afraid of Nebraska. Newcombe and Evans are back,
and the Cornhuskers have something to prove. We'll see if they're
good enough to do it. &QL; 
 &UR; Ohio State
</P>
<P>
   Winning 11 games last season wasn't good enough for the
Buckeyes, who failed once again to win a national title under
Coach &UR; John Cooper. They spent more than two months ranked No. 1
before blowing a lead, and their title hopes, against Michigan
State.
</P>
<P>
   The losses were heavy. Gone are quarterback  &UR; Joe Germaine and
receiver  &UR; David Boston. But no team in the country has replaced
talent as successfully as the Buckeyes, so don't look for them to
slip out of the top 10. They will be tested today by Miami. &QL; 
 &UR; Wisconsin
</P>
<P>
   Give Coach  &UR; Barry Alvarez a devastating running game and a
veteran defense and he'll give you double-digit victories. That's
what the Badgers have this year with running back  &UR; Ron Dayne, who
stayed for his senior year, and a defense that returns eight
starters.
</P>
<P>
   Wisconsin has to figure out a way to replace quarterback  &UR; Mike
 &UR; Samuel, who never put up great numbers but was efficient. If  &UR; Scott
 &UR; Kavanagh or  &UR; Brooks Bollinger comes through, the Badgers could
contend for a Sugar Bowl berth. &QL; 
 &UR; Virginia Tech
</P>
<P>
   The Hokies are perennially one of the nation's best-kept
secrets. Coach  &UR; Frank Beamer continually turns out exceptional
teams, and this year's model could be his best.
</P>
<P>
   Fifteen starters return from a club that went 9-3 last season.
Miami is expected to make a resurgence in the Big East, but the
Hokies have to be favored to win the league and earn a BCS berth. &QL; 
 &UR; Michigan
</P>
<P>
   The Wolverines, still giddy from their share of the 1997
national title, lost their first two games last season. They did a
nice salvage job, finishing 10-3, and are vowing to start this
season differently. Senior  &UR; Tom Brady and phenom &UR; Drew Henson, a
sophomore, are battling for the quarterback job. Eight starters are
back on defense. &QL; 
 &UR; Georgia Tech
</P>
<P>
   Quarterback  &UR; Joe Hamilton enters his fourth year as a starter
and is a legitimate Heisman candidate. But if Georgia Tech is to
make any noise this year, it has to find a way to improve
defensively. The secondary has been porous, and Coach &UR; George
O'Leary is relying on several young players at key spots. &QL; 
 &UR; Southern California
</P>
<P>
   Last year, USC had one of the Pac-10's best defenses but
struggled offensively. The opposite could be true this year as the
Trojans return nine starters on offense but only six on defense.
Coach  &UR; Paul
 &UR; Hackett thinks sophomore QB  &UR; Carson Palmer is special. He'll have
to be if the Trojans are to make a run for the league title. &QL; 
 &UR; Georgia
</P>
<P>
   QB  &UR; Quincy Carter was sensational last season, setting nearly
every freshman record for passing at the school. He doesn't have
much experience around him, however, so Coach &UR; Jim Donnan's highly
rated recruiting classes had better produce. &QL; 
 &UR; Colorado
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Rick Neuheisel packed up his guitar and split town, accepting a
$1 million offer at Washington. He didn't leave the program void of
talent, however, and new Coach  &UR; Gary Barnett should have a decent
first year in Boulder. &QL; 
 &UR; Alabama
</P>
<P>
   The Crimson Tide has a talented running back ( &UR; Shaun Alexander),
an exciting quarterback ( &UR; Andrew Zow) and a beleaguered head coach
( &UR; Mike
 &UR; DuBose) who spent the off-season dealing with sexual-harassment
charges. The talent is there for a big improvement over last year's
7-5 mark. &QL; 
 &UR; Miami
</P>
<P>
   It's popular to predict this as the year of the Hurricanes'
resurgence. Seventeen starters return and Coach  &UR; Butch Davis
finally some depth. Still, this was the team that gave up 111
points in its last two regular-season games, and quarterback  &UR; Kenny
Kelly has never started a game. &QL; 
 &UR; Notre Dame
</P>
<P>
   Coach  &UR; Bob Davie is entering his third year, which is a
milestone for Notre Dame coaches.  &UR; Frank Leahy,  &UR; Ara Parseghian,
 &UR; Dan Devine and &UR; Lou
 &UR; Holtz each won a share of a national title in his third season as
head coach of the Irish. QB  &UR; Jarious Jackson is dangerous, but the
Irish still lack big-play threats. The defense should be solid,
though. &QL; 
 &UR; UCLA
</P>
<P>
   Quarterback &UR; Cade McNown is gone and so are those nifty
handicapped parking passes. Life will be a little tougher in
Westwood this season, especially if the Bruins don't improve
defensively. Sophomore RB
 &UR; DeShaun Foster should be a star, and receivers  &UR; Danny Farmer,
 &UR; Brian
 &UR; Poli-Dixon and  &UR; Freddie Mitchell are dangerous, provided someone
can get them the ball. &QL; 
 &UR; Virginia
</P>
<P>
   This is usually a safe place to pick the Cavaliers, who have
underachieved the past few seasons. Coach  &UR; George Welsh has a nice
core of players back, but they aren't good enough to challenge
Florida State for the ACC title. &QL; 
 &UR; Texas
</P>
<P>
   Running back  &UR; Ricky Williams is gone, pushing the Longhorns into
the post-dreadlocks era. Only 11 starters return. Quarterback
 &UR; Major
 &UR; Applewhite will have to carry more of a load, but if he struggles,
fans will be calling for freshman  &UR; Chris Simms to play. &QL; 
 &UR; Marshall
</P>
<P>
   Don't laugh. The Thundering Herd has won 22 games since moving
to Division 1-A two years ago. All but one starter is back, and
quarterback  &UR; Chad Pennington could be one of the best in the
country. &QL; 
 &UR; Purdue
</P>
<P>
   The Boilermakers are pumping quarterback  &UR; Drew Brees for the
Heisman, and it's not just hype. Brees threw for 3,983 yards and 39
touchdowns last season. But life will be tougher this year with
Ohio State and Michigan back on the schedule after a hiatus. &QL; 
 &UR; Louisville
</P>
<P>
   Coach  &UR; John L. Smith worked wonders in his first season last
year, guiding a team that had gone 1-10 to a 7-5 record.
Quarterback &UR; Chris
 &UR; Redman is a potential first-round draft choice, and 10 defensive
starters are back. &QL; 
 &UR; Arkansas
</P>
<P>
   The Razorbacks were one of the major surprises in the country
last season, narrowly missing a chance to play for the national
title. The offensive skill positions are stocked, but Coach
 &UR; Houston Nutt has a rebuilding job on defense.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
