r s BC-FBC-FIESTA-OVERVIEW-A     08-28 0691
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-FIESTA-OVERVIEW-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIESTA REMAINS A BIG BOWL PARTY  
 NO TITLE GAME, BUT ATTRACTIVE OPTIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By KENT SOMERS  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, Ariz. - Scouting college football games has never been
tough duty for bowl officials. After choosing a tie to match their
loud sports coats, the toughest remaining decision is whether to
skip breakfast and gamble that there will be a nice buffet in the
press box.
</P>
<P>
   Fiesta Bowl officials had it even easier last season. They
played host to the first national championship game under the new
Bowl Championship Series. While other bowls worried about
entertainment value, ticket sales and how many fans a team would
bring, Fiesta officials only had to wait and watch.
</P>
<P>
   Its matchup was determined by the final BCS poll. That ended up
being Tennessee and Florida State, with the Volunteers beating the
Seminoles, 23-16, for the national title.
</P>
<P>
   Things have changed dramatically this year, however, and
although Fiesta officials won't be breaking their backs on scouting
trips, they have more to do than last year.
</P>
<P>
   The Sugar Bowl has the national title game, while the Fiesta
falls back into a tier with two other BCS bowls: the Orange and the
Rose.
</P>
<P>
   Many fans are assuming, wrongly, that because the Fiesta had the
national championship game last year, it will fall to the back of
the BCS line and have the final two choices of the four bowls.
</P>
<P>
   Bowl officials answer the selection question wherever they go.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we have some work to do,'' said John Junker, the
bowl's executive director. ``I think people had just grown used to
the old system. When we present them with what the situation is,
they are always excited about it. While there might be some
education, the punch line is always a good one.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe, but it's one that's not easy to explain or understand.
</P>
<P>
   Under the simplest scenario, the Fiesta Bowl will have an anchor
team, the Big 12 champion. Five other conference champions are
guaranteed places in the BCS. That leaves two at-large teams, of
which the Fiesta Bowl gets first pick, by virtue of its high bid
when the BCS was formed.
</P>
<P>
   But the situation can be much more complicated than that given
the myriad possibilities. What if, say, the Big 12 champion plays
for the national championship in the Sugar Bowl? The Fiesta Bowl
would then get first pick of a replacement team, after the other
bowls took their anchor teams, and then the first at-large choice.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've gone through lots of yellow pads (predicting
scenarios),'' Junker said. ``We couldn't pay for all the
mathematicians or anything. We've run it many, many ways and we
come up with a good game the vast majority of the time.''
</P>
<P>
   The possibilities are intriguing to the bowl's officials. They
could end up with Nebraska, bouncing back from a disappointing
season, or Texas A&AMP;M, predicted by many to make a run for the
national title.
</P>
<P>
   For an at-large pick, they could select Wisconsin, if the
Badgers don't play for the national title or in the Rose Bowl.
Wisconsin has running back Ron Dayne, who could break the NCAA's
all-time rushing mark and a huge fan following willing to travel
and spend money.
</P>
<P>
   Those possibilities don't hold the interest that a national
title game has, but bowl officials aren't complaining.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, it's expected that within the next year the BCS
agreement will be extended through the 2005 bowl games. That
probably will give the Fiesta Bowl the top two teams again in 2003.
</P>
<P>
   For this year, however, the bowl is worried about having an
entertaining game and selling out Sun Devil Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Ticket prices have been lowered for this season. A majority of
the seats are $75, with premium seats ranging from $100 to $125 and
loge seats from $160 to $180. Last year, a majority of the tickets
cost $135, while prime seats went for up to $195.
</P>
<P>
   ``This year is a different kind of excitement because of
flexibility we'll have,'' Junker said. ``It's quite a difference to
our people on the road. We're emphasizing to them that it's a much,
much different deal.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
