<HEADLINE>
WILL ABC EGOS UPSTAGE THE GAMES? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM GINTONIO  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The biggest battle of the college football season won't be
taking place on the football field. Who's the best team? Who cares?
</P>
<P>
   No, the real fight will be the clash of egos at ABC.
</P>
<P>
   In an ideal world _ that's one where  &UR; Brent Musburger never
meets a camera _ ABC would have named  &UR; Brad Nessler its No. 1
football broadcaster the day after  &UR; Keith Jackson retired. But in
an odd twist of events, Jackson returned, and Nessler and Musburger
share the highest rung, according to  &UR; John Filippelli, the vice
president for ABC Sports.
</P>
<P>
   Filippelli failed to mention where Jackson, who will do only
West Coast games, falls in the ratings game, so we'll help him out:
Jackson should have stayed retired, but since he's back, there's no
doubt in the mind of any college football fans about the identity
of the star of the trio.
</P>
<P>
   Nessler and Musburger, however, will be getting the top games
throughout the season, and with ABC's regionalized concept, having
a different top dog on different weeks makes sense.
</P>
<P>
   Nessler is an underrated play-by-play man who seems to appeal to
a wide audience. Musburger offers no middle ground. Fans hate him,
management loves him.
</P>
<P>
   During a recent conference call, everyone was sticking to the
script. In fact, one of Nessler's remarks could have come from
central casting: ``Keith is in the Hall of Fame, and Brent will be,
so I'm in good company.''
</P>
<P>
   Nessler said he was disappointed when Jackson decided to curtail
his duties.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was his biggest fan,'' he said. ``There's not a competition
among the three of us, but we are pretty competitive people.''
</P>
<P>
   Musburger seemed a bit subdued during the call; the bombastic
style that people have come to expect was missing. Perhaps he's
decided that he's not bigger than the sport, and if so, it will be
a welcome change.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was lucky to have  &UR; Dan Fouts with me for two years,'' he
said. ``It was a great two years. I hope I continue being lucky. In
many cases, you're no better than the game you're broadcasting. If
we get a good game, fine. There's plenty of good games for Brad and
me.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's great to have Keith back. I told him he'd never retire.
It's ideal for us to have him in the Pac-10.''
</P>
<P>
   Filippelli said he would leave it to others to overanalyze the
No. 1 scenario.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is what it is,'' he said. ``We have fabulous people and a
great schedule of games.''
</P>
<P>
   Musburger will again work with Fouts, and Nessler teams with
 &UR; Gary
 &UR; Danielson. &QL; 
Double-edged tube
</P>
<P>
   While television exposure has been a tremendous ally of college
football, two high-profile coaches,  &UR; Joe Paterno of Penn State and
 &UR; Butch Davis of Miami, discussed another side of the issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a little more hoopla than some kids can handle,''
Paterno said. ``And their families might have more of a problem
than the kids. Parents envision their kids getting this and that.
</P>
<P>
   ``And some of the comments made by some people (commentators) on
how coaches do things, when they get critical of coaches, I don't
think they're doing much good. I think sometimes coaches get blamed
more than they should. I think overall we're doing a great job.''
</P>
<P>
   Paterno and Davis agreed that they want to give players the
opportunities to enjoy college life, and Paterno said, ``I don't
think any coach has complete control over 120 kids who are normal,
young adults. Some are going to slip at times.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis said living in the college football fishbowl can be
hazardous.
</P>
<P>
   ``The exposure today is enormous,'' he said. ``It's very
difficult when you have 110, 115 kids in a program to monitor them
24 hours a day, seven days a week. That's ridiculous. I do think
kids need to learn some respect and responsibility.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do think a whole lot more coaches are doing the right things
than the other way.'' &QL; 
Jim Gintonio covers sports media. He can be reached at (602)
444-8380 or at jim.gintonio(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
