u s BC-FBC-FLORIDASTATE-LATE     08-28 0752
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-FLORIDASTATE-LATECH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEMINOLES EVENTUALLY TO TOUGH FOR TEACH  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By CHARLIE NOBLES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TALLAHASSEE, Fla. _ By opting not to turn professional in April,
Peter Warrick passed up riches to be an impact player at Florida
State this season.
</P>
<P>
   He is 1 for 1.
</P>
<P>
   Warrick Saturday helped turn a close game into a rout, as the
No.1 ranked Seminoles rolled over spunky Louisiana Tech, 41-7,
before 72,702 at Doak Campbell Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   The flanker caught 9 passes for 121 yards and rushed twice for
41 yards, including a 20-yard touchdown that will be a highlight
film clip.
</P>
<P>
   With the game tied at 7-7 late in the first half, Warrick,
heading right, took a handoff from quarterback Chris Weinke but
found his path blocked. He cut left and kept zigzagging as several
defenders flailed at him. Suddenly, he bolted back to the right,
evading all defenders. He was so open that he trotted into the end
zone with 39 seconds left in the half.
</P>
<P>
   ``That even surprised me,'' Warrick said. ``I thought I'd get
some yards, but I didn't expect to get to the house.''
</P>
<P>
   FSU Coach Bobby Bowden said with a chuckle, ``I'd hate to have
to draw that thing up and run it again.''
</P>
<P>
   The marquee matchup in this game had been two quarterbacks _
Louisiana Tech's Tim Rattay, the two-time national total offense
leader, and Weinke, FSU's strong-armed 27-year-old who is
rebounding from a neck injury last season.
</P>
<P>
   Weinke went on the field Saturday with a titanium plate, four
screws and some cable wire in his neck. That didn't seem to faze
him as he completed 20 of 32 passes for 242 yards and 2 touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt at times like I was rushing the ball and didn't need
to,'' said Weinke, who came out of the game early in the fourth
quarter when his team had a big lead. ``This was about what I
expected after being out.''
</P>
<P>
   Rattay didn't fare as well, though Weinke clearly had the
superior supporting cast. The senior from Phoenix, completed 28 of
48 passes for 240 yards, with a touchdown and two interceptions.
</P>
<P>
   And he left FSU's defense panting.
</P>
<P>
   ``For sure, they run you,'' Florida State nose guard Corey Simon
said. ``But I thought we improved as the game went on. Everybody's
not like Penn State _ coming out like they did. We had some things
to work out.''
</P>
<P>
   The Seminoles' talent edge became more pronounced as the day
wore on. Rattay often was under siege from their pass rush,
particularly early in the fourth quarter when linebacker Theon
Rackley returned an interception 10 yards for a touchdown and a
38-7 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Louisiana Tech left Bowden shaking his head.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I saw the final score, I'd take that,'' he said. ``Now if I
look at the way we did it, I was very disappointed.''
</P>
<P>
   In the Bulldogs' first series, Rattay connected on four of his
five passes for 44 yards. And later in the first half, he led an
impressive drive that took 12 plays, went 89 yards and consumed 4
minutes 57 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   Rattay's first two passes fell incomplete, but the third was a
laser to Sean Cangelosi for 15 yards. Rattay went on to complete
six of his next seven passes, the finale a beauty between two
Seminole defenders in the end zone's right corner for a 13-yard
touchdown to tailback John Simon.
</P>
<P>
   A season ago, when the Seminoles were in contention for the
national title, they allowed opponents to convert third down plays
just 33 times in 173 tries, a 19.1 success rate that was among the
country's best.
</P>
<P>
   By halftime, Rattay had converted five of eight third-down
attempts. He finished with 7 seven of 15.
</P>
<P>
   The Bulldogs, 7-5 last season, were in good position to take the
lead in this game late in the second quarter. Weinke had just
thrown his first interception after a string of 237 completions
over two seasons _ beating the Atlantic Coast Conference record of
Virginia's Matt Blundin. After rover Bobby Gray cradled the errant
ball at the FSU 25, Louisiana Tech promptly moved inside the host's
10, on 9- and 12-yard completions to Cangelosi. But on the second
completion, Cangelosi was hit by cornerback Clevan Thomas and
fumbled. It was scooped up by free safety Sean Key, who was tackled
at his 5.
</P>
<P>
   With just 2:56 remaining before halftime, it was soon to be
Warrick's time. His 21-yard run gave FSU life, and Weinke found
split end Talman Gardner for 33 yards to the Bulldogs' 20.
</P>
<P>
   That was where Warrick unleashed his highlight play, and it
enabled the Seminoles to take a 14-7 lead into intermission.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
