<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-POLITICS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTONS TAKE LONG LOOK AT 1889 HOUSE IN CHAPPAQUA  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By PAUL ZIELBAUER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHAPPAQUA, N.Y. _ Continuing their search for a house after the
White House, President Clinton and Hillary Rodham Clinton spent two
hours Saturday inspecting a 110-year-old home on a secluded
cul-de-sac here before flying to the Hamptons for a fund-raiser.
</P>
<P>
   The Clintons spent far more time at the white, two-story
wood-frame home at 15 Old House Lane than they have at other homes
they have visited since beginning their search for a house in
Westchester County. But they did not indicate if they were
seriously considering buying it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very nice house, but we don't have an announcement to
make,'' Clinton said after the visit, as he emerged from a gray
Chevrolet Silverado to shake hands with local residents a few yards
from the house. ``Nice people,'' he added. ``Nice neighbors.''
</P>
<P>
   The 5,200-square-foot home, shrouded from easy view by towering
fir and maple trees, sits on 1.1 acres set off from the cul-de-sac,
and is listed for $1,695,000, according to real-estate brokers. The
house, which has a master bedroom with a wrap-around deck that
overlooks a pool and a wooded backyard, has been on the market
since Aug. 16, said Wayne Crosby, an agent with Houlihan/Lawrence
Inc., the real-estate agency that is listing the house.
</P>
<P>
   The house is an 11-room Dutch Colonial that was built in 1889,
he said. It has five bedrooms, four bathrooms and a separate barn
that serves as a two-car garage, Crosby said. A white picket fence
encloses the backyard.
</P>
<P>
   The house's owners, Dr. Jeffrey Weisberg and his wife, Cheryl,
have lived there for more than a decade, the neighbors said. Its
property taxes last year were $25,900, Crosby said.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday's three-hour trip to Westchester was the Clintons'
second visit in two weeks. After their arrival at Westchester
County Airport at 12:40 p.m., the Clintons climbed into the back of
the Silverado and, trailed by nine vehicles carrying staff members,
Secret Service agents and reporters, drove up Route 120, past IBM's
headquarters in Armonk, to Chappaqua.
</P>
<P>
   On Old House Lane, the motorcade waited as the Clintons visited
with the Weisbergs for two hours and inspected their home. Along
the 200-yard-long lane, lined with large homes surrounded by
manicured lawns and weedless shrubbery, neighbors emerged and stood
along the road in curious clumps, waiting for a peek at the
Clintons and mulling the prospect of having a retired president as
a neighbor.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's better to have the president than someone else,'' said
one neighbor, Osman Osmani, 53, who immigrated from Kosovo 11 years
ago and works as a real-estate agent in the Bronx. ``I like him now
more than ever before. He saved my people.''
</P>
<P>
   Across the street stood Curt Stewart, 54, a close friend of the
Weisbergs, who had just arrived on his sleek racing bicycle to
visit them but found hordes of reporters and Secret Service agents
blocking his way.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart, a corporate consultant, called the Weisbergs' home
``one of the most beautiful houses you'll ever see.'' He said he
recently went out to dinner with the Weisbergs and, mindful of the
Clintons' house search, asked if they would consider showing their
house to the president. ``They joked about it and said, `No, no,'''
he recalled.
</P>
<P>
   Some neighbors seemed more uneasy about what would happen if the
Clintons moved in.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a little exciting that they would want to live here, but
I'm not sure,'' said Michele Neufeld, who, along with her husband,
Todd, an investment banker, moved into a house nearby three months
ago. ``This is the busiest I've ever seen this neighborhood,''
Neufeld said, looking slightly concerned.
</P>
<P>
   The Clintons lived in the Arkansas Governor's Mansion before
moving to Washington. They have no home to return to when the
president leaves the White House in early 2001, and they intend to
find a house in affluent Westchester County.
</P>
<P>
   If Mrs. Clinton is to run for the U.S. Senate next year, she
must live in New York state by Election Day. After the house visit
and five minutes of shaking hands with neighbors and their
children, the Clintons left, returning to Westchester County
Airport.
</P>
<P>
   By 3:35 p.m., their plane was en route to an airport in West
Hampton, where a helicopter was scheduled to fly the Clintons to a
Democratic fund-raiser Saturday evening.
</P>
<P>
   Now the Clintons will go about deciding whether they want the
house, said Kathy Sloane, a Westchester County real-estate agent
who is aiding the Clintons in their home search.
</P>
<P>
   She would not speculate on how much the Clintons liked the house
they saw Saturday. But Crosby said two hours was an exceptional
amount of time for any home buyer to spend at one dwelling. ``Most
people are in a house for 20 minutes if they're not interested,''
he said in a telephone interview Saturday afternoon. ``I'd say they
are interested in the house.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-28-99 2349EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
