<SLUG> BC-CHESS-MATCH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A CIRCUMSPECT DRAW BRINGS CHESS DUEL TO A SHOWDOWN  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By ROBERT BYRNE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   After playing guardedly to a draw on Friday night, Alexander
Khalifman of Russia and Vladimir Akopian of Armenia no doubt spent
most of Saturday deep in private strategy sessions for what could
be the finish of their tense, six-game match for the International
Chess Federation's World Championship. Khalifman retained a
one-point lead, at 3-2, and needed only a draw to win the title.
</P>
<P>
   To keep the match alive, Akopian had to win Saturday. He was
facing a dilemma familiar to boxers: to land a decisive blow he
would have to leave himself open to a decisive counterblow.
</P>
<P>
   In Game 5 on Friday, he tried to win without taking any risk and
found that those two objectives don't mix very well. With the
conservative formation he put on the board, he was not able to gain
any advantage. Khalifman met caution with caution, and the point
was halved after 49 moves.
</P>
<P>
   As White, Akopian has a marked preference for queenside
openings, but he won the second game with 1 e4 and decided to give
it another whirl here. He was very likely looking forward to facing
a Sicilian Defense again, which he had confronted in good style in
Game 2. But Khalifman crossed him up by using 1 ... e5.
</P>
<P>
   Akopian's quiet, inoffensive 5 d3 indicates that he probably did
not want to be tested by one of the sharp defenses to the Ruy
Lopez, like the Open Defense with 5 O-O Ne4 or the Marshall Gambit.
</P>
<P>
   With 10 ... c5, the Chigorin Defense appeared; it is designed to
diminish the effect of aggression in the center by White.
</P>
<P>
   After 14 ... Bf8, Akopian played 15 d4, even though it brought
about a well-known position in which White is a tempo down, the
pawn having taken two moves to reach d4.
</P>
<P>
   After 18 Qd4, the previous exchanges gave White a preponderance
of central space and Black a vulnerable d6 pawn. But Khalifman's
free development of pieces nullified that to a considerable extent.
</P>
<P>
   After 22 ... Re6, attempting aggression with 23 e5 would only
have dissipated Akopian's strength when Khalifman replied 23 ...
Qe8! Moreover, 23 Nf5 is rebuffed by 23 ... Rc4.
</P>
<P>
   After 35 ... Qb3, the game was equal, but Akopian, desperate to
catch up in the series, tried a last hope, 36 f5, to open lines
against the black king. Khalifman, not willing to risk anything,
forced a technically drawn ending by sacrificing a pawn with 36 ...
Qe3 37 Kh2 Qc5.
</P>
<P>
   After 49 Rb3, a dead draw arises from 49 ... Rh7 50 Kg3 Kf6,
which the players acknowledged by shaking hands.
</P>
<P>
   RUY LOPEZ
</P>
<P>
   White Black
</P>
<P>
   Akopian Khal'an
</P>
