<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DBACKS-CASSTEVENS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BASEBALL BRINGS BACK BOYHOOD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID CASSTEVENS  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - The Little League World Series championship game was
under way. Seated at his desk, Buck looked at the TV screen and
smiled.
</P>
<P>
   For a moment he forgot about the New York Mets.
</P>
<P>
   For a few sweet seconds Saturday afternoon, Buck Showalter _ age
43, manager, husband, father _ became a kid again.
</P>
<P>
   He was Bill Showalter's boy.
</P>
<P>
   Little League second baseman.
</P>
<P>
   Buck's memories took him home. He was back in Century, Fla., a
10-year-old gazing beyond his back yard at the local ball field
glowing under the lights on a warm summer night.
</P>
<P>
   That field was his whole world. Worse than any whipping was the
threat from his mom or dad. ``Nat, if you don't . . . you're
``not'' playing tonight!''
</P>
<P>
   What else do you remember?
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything,'' Buck said.
</P>
<P>
   Showalter remembers the joy of winning and how much losing hurt.
When his Little League team won, each player earned a hot dog and a
Coke. When they came up short, the post-game treat was a snow cone.
</P>
<P>
   Buck remembers trudging home, walking in the house, glove in
hand. He remembers his sister looking at the telltale blue syrup
stains circling his mouth and announcing, ``Y'all lost, didn't
you?''
</P>
<P>
   He remembers the first time he struck out.
</P>
<P>
   That awful sound of the ball hitting the catcher's mitt. Strike
three! The umpire, Mr. Leahy, who went to the Baptist church,
called him out.
</P>
<P>
   He remembers the pitcher. Ronnie Wedgworth.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ronnie,'' Buck said, ``had facial hair.''
</P>
<P>
   He remembers feeling like the whole world was staring as he
returned to the dugout. He sat there, embarrassed and angry. ``I
cried my eyes out.''
</P>
<P>
   After the game, he heard his name announced as the league's Most
Valuable Player. He felt better, but to this day he can see Ronnie
Wedgworth on the mount, triumphant.
</P>
<P>
   He remembers his new bat, a 28-inch Eddie Mathews model .
</P>
<P>
   He remembers how good it felt in his hands the night he swung
and hit the ball flush. Dropping the bat, he lifted his eyes,
watching the ball rise and sail into deep center field.
</P>
<P>
   He remembers the magical moment when he hit his first home run
at age 10. In his mind's eye, he can see the man beyond the fence
rising from his lawn chair. He reached out and caught the ball with
his bare hand.
</P>
<P>
   The man was his father.
</P>
<P>
   He remembers being 12, and the pride he felt wearing the gray
flannel pinstripes of the Tri City All-Stars.
</P>
<P>
   His mother still has his cap.
</P>
<P>
   The kids from Florida went to the playoffs. If they beat a team
from Miami, they were going to the Little League World Series in
Williamsport, Pa. Buck got his team's only hits, three of them. ``I
had a snow cone that night.''
</P>
<P>
   He remembers the field behind the house where his mother lives.
It is still there. So is the billboard honoring his team, state
champions.
</P>
<P>
   He still can see his teammates, Jim Mathis and the others, their
faces frozen in time, smiling, forever young. Their names _ and his
_ are listed on the sign.
</P>
<P>
   He remembers it all. The fun. The excitement. The cheers. The
bond he felt when he played catch with the man who years later told
him he wanted him to have something he had put away for
safekeeping. He produced a Little League baseball. On it he had
written, ``Nat's first home run, 1966.''
</P>
<P>
   He remembers the joy of being a boy playing a game he loves. The
memories are forever, as dear to him as the abiding love for a man
who, two weeks before he died, learned that his boy, the Little
Leaguer, was the new manager of the New York Yankees. &QL; 
David Casstevens can be reached at (602) 444-8635 or at
david.casstevens(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
