<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-28 23:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3263 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s BC-FBC-ARIZONA-PENNST.-A     08-28 0832
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-ARIZONA-PENNST.-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ZIP - ARIZONA PRODUCES NOTHING IN LOSS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By NORM FRAUENHEIM  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   STATE COLLEGE, Pa. _ Penn State Coach Joe Paterno said he would
have preferred Akron. He didn't get the school. But he got the
nickname right.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona was a collection of Zips.
</P>
<P>
   In an embarrassing 41-7 loss Saturday to the Nittany Lions in
the Pigskin Classic, the Wildcats had no zip and were left with zip
as they now sift through the rubble in an attempt to restore all
the promise that they seemed to possess.
</P>
<P>
   If anything was proven by the rout, it is simply that preseason
pollsters don't know zip. Just 48 hours ago, the Wildcats were
ranked among the nation's top five teams in virtually every poll.
</P>
<P>
   According to the rankings that are supposed to serve as the
season's road map, the Wildcats were going to challenge Penn State
en route to a Pac-10 championship.
</P>
<P>
   But these particular mapmakers might as well be the same people
who thought the world was flat. Penn State simply pushed the
Wildcats over the edge. During 11 games over the next three months,
the Wildcats will discover whether oblivion is their fate.
</P>
<P>
   Within a subdued dressing room after a very long afternoon at
Beaver Stadium, the Wildcats already were talking resurrection.
Miracles do happen. But they also had to confront the fact that on
this day, they were overwhelmed and overrated.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not the best in the Pac-10,'' Arizona quarterback Ortege
Jenkins said to a circle of reporters. ``We're not No. 3. Their
fans said we were overrated. That's a fact. It's true, and you guys
know it's true.''
</P>
<P>
   It's too bad no points are given for honesty. The Wildcats would
have scored plenty of them in the locker room after the game. Other
than a meaningless touchdown in the closing moments, they couldn't
score from anywhere else or at any other time.
</P>
<P>
   ``They beat us as bad as a team can be beat,'' said Arizona
Coach Dick Tomey, whose team was ranked No. 4 by the Associated
Press and No. 3 by the coaches who vote in the ESPN/USA Today
version. ``It was one of those games. It was a nightmare.''
</P>
<P>
   Signs of a rout were abundant when Penn State took the opening
kickoff and marched 80 yards in seven plays. The Nittany Lions'
initial score summed up the game. On the drive, at least three
tackles were missed by an Arizona defense that has no replacement
for last year's All-America cornerback, Chris McAlister.
</P>
<P>
   On the touchdown itself, Arizona cornerback Kelvin Hunter didn't
pursue Penn State flanker Chafie Fields so much as bump into him.
Fields had just caught a pass from Kevin Thompson at about
Arizona's 25-yard line. He bounced off Hunter and raced, untouched,
for the end zone.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were a poor tackling team,'' said Tomey, who endured more
of the same until the half ended with Penn State leading, 31-0.
``They outhit us. They were tougher, more physical.''
</P>
<P>
   Penn State's defense was expected to be tough. On that one, at
least, the prognostication crowd was right on the mark. With
linebacker LaVar Arrington setting the tone, the Nittany Lions shut
the door on Arizona. It was as if last year's explosive offense had
imploded.
</P>
<P>
   Trung Canidate, an explosive runner most of last season, was
virtually stopped by a swarming defense that probably stopped his
Heisman Trophy campaign as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their defense did a lot of talking coming into this game,''
said Canidate, who was held to 31 yards on 10 carries. ``Give them
credit. They did what they said they were going to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Above all, the Nittany Lions made an important defensive
adjustment in the early going. The surprise was an inability to
counter by an Arizona offense that suddenly looked dull. For the
most part, this is the same Arizona offense that was so dynamic
last year.
</P>
<P>
   The Wildcats had some success moving the ball on their first
possession. Keith Smith, the starter at quarterback, found Dennis
Northcutt for consecutive completions of 29 and 26 yards.
</P>
<P>
   They drove 63 yards to the Penn State 18 when the offense
stalled. Canidate couldn't find an opening behind an offensive line
that was overmatched. Then Tomey ordered a 40-yard field goal
attempt. Mark McDonald's kick went awry, and the rest of the
offense soon followed.
</P>
<P>
   A key, Jenkins said, was Penn State's decision to double-team
Northcutt.
</P>
<P>
   ``They dropped in a safety on Dennis and that took away our best
option,'' he said. ``We didn't create anything after that. They
made us play their game.''
</P>
<P>
   Penn State's game might prove to be its very best this season.
If the polls were so woefully wrong about Arizona, they might be
absolutely right about the Nittany Lions, who were ranked No. 3 by
the Associated Press and No. 1 by ``Sports Illustrated''.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope they're a great team,'' said Tomey, whose team really
is in for a nightmare if the pollsters are as wrong about Penn
State as they were about the Wildcats. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
