<HEADER>
A3266 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s BC-FBC-ARIZONA-BICKLEY-A     08-28 0702
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-ARIZONA-BICKLEY-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIONS EXPOSE ARIZONA AS PAC-10 WIMP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN BICKLEY  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   STATE COLLEGE, Pa. - What a lovely display of cotton candy
football.
</P>
<P>
   What a terrible way to meet the nation.
</P>
<P>
   Penn State 41, Arizona 7.
</P>
<P>
   Pffffft.
</P>
<P>
   So the Wildcats came to Linebacker U. hoping to make a lasting
impression, and boy, did they ever. In the same manner that
Limburger cheese adds presence to a refrigerator.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, Arizona only strengthened the perceptions that the
Pac-10 is all tofu, no steak. A conference for sissies.
</P>
<P>
   The Wildcats may recover from their trip to the shed, but their
image will not. No matter what they accomplish this season, most of
the nation will scoff. This sorry afternoon in the spotlight will
be a reference point that will not go away.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it's not fair. But it's the way things work.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the Big Ten, we try to get it done by bullying people,''
Penn State linebacker LaVar Arrington said. ``The West Coast uses a
lot of trickery.''
</P>
<P>
   Which is a nice way of saying the Lack-10 is soft. And when the
league's overwhelming favorite simply rolls over, who's to argue?
</P>
<P>
   Field goals were missed. A punt was blocked. In the first half,
Penn State averaged 11.6 yards every time it snapped the ball. And
in a massive show of disrespect, Arrington was signing autographs
for the Penn State faithful with three minutes left in the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure, I'm embarrassed,'' receiver Dennis Northcutt said. ``It
hurts. All this talk about Arizona is going to do this, Arizona is
ranked here . . . We didn't show up, and the whole country was
watching.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, you don't give Joe Paterno eight months to prepare
for a home game and expect things to go smoothly. But Arizona boss
Dick Tomey had time as well, only to emerge as an overmatched
pretender.
</P>
<P>
   The play calling was both terrible and tentative in a few clutch
situations during the opening quarter. And the way the Wildcats
reacted on defense, you wonder whether they practiced tackling in
training camp. In fact, you wonder whether they practiced at all.
</P>
<P>
   Penn State functioned like a machine. Arizona's performance was
ragged and rough. Both are reflections of the men in charge.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were just better prepared,'' quarterback Ortege Jenkins
said. ``They came out and punished us like we were a Pop Warner
team.''
</P>
<P>
   While admitting that he and his staff did a bad job, Tomey tried
to put a positive spin on the horrific effort. He claimed that the
pain will serve as a valuable lesson, that character will emerge
from the rubble.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe, maybe not.
</P>
<P>
   The temptation is to think that Penn State is in a class by
itself, but it won't be long before Paterno's crew is winning games
21-10 and 17-3. The offense is still suspect . . . an offense that
gained more than 500 yards against the Wildcats.
</P>
<P>
   So Arizona has many holes to address, and this platoon system at
quarterback is still a bad idea. Jenkins is a wonderful athlete and
adds a different dimension to the offense, but Keith Smith is too
good to spend time on the sidelines. Especially in big games.
</P>
<P>
   Case in point: On Saturday, Smith was yanked after starting the
game with nine consecutive completions.
</P>
<P>
   ``You guys may turn on us,'' Smith said. ``But we're going to do
the job. I think this is a good check for us. To see who will come
with us and who won't.''
</P>
<P>
   Surely, Arizona State fans had a wonderful time watching the
debacle. But before the gloating gets out of control, give Tomey
credit for pursuing this game. It was a risk that took courage, and
a contrast to ASU's decision to duck an invitation from Florida
State last season.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, a huge opportunity was squandered. The previous
impression of the Wildcats was a big-time victory over Nebraska in
the Holiday Bowl. Had Arizona lived up to the hype, it would have
become a player. A national presence.
</P>
<P>
   The Wildcats didn't have to win. They just had to compete.
</P>
<P>
   Alas, it was too much to ask.
</P>
<P>
   Some bubbles are burst. This one was blown away. &QL; 
Dan Bickley can be reached at (602) 444-8253 or at
dan.bickley(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
